[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction "]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. --
{ Hello! I am Catalan Grandmaster Àlvar Alonso Rosell and I wish you a happy stay in this course. As a brief introduction of mine, I have been Absolute Spain Champion and 5th in a World Under-12 Championship, ahead of Wesley So and Fabiano Caruana, and behind Ding Liren.  I have been a coach and columnist for many years, achieving very good results and titles with my students. I especially wanted to take a course on Catalan for several reasons:  - It is an opening that I have played since I was very young.  - I have always been excited that it is the opening of my homeland.  - I want to share my vision of chess through this course.  A favorite anecdote of mine: during the 2017 Individual European Championship, in Minsk, I was paired as White against Peter Leko  (a serious World Championship Candidate at his peak and someone I was a big fan of, growing up)  .   I prepared the Catalan Opening, since he had been entering it without hesitation for 15 years. But when I got to the board, he played the Grunfeld! He had allowed the Catalan against the elite with no exception but changed against me! In the postmortem he told me that he thought I played the Catalan very well and that's why he changed...   1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  we will enter the Catalan from this move-order and I'll explain why below  3...d5  4.g3  .   The story behind the Catalan Opening is well-known: on the occasion of the 1929 International Exhibition, held in Barcelona, an international chess tournament was organized in Sitges, which was attended by most of the great players of the time. One of its organizers, Francesc Armengol, wanted that there was a Catalan Opening in chess. Thus, he called the chess players to a contest to create a new opening. Polish GM Savielly Tartakower's invention won, pocketing him 150 pesetas.  The Catalan's basic idea is to attack the center and queenside with the fianchettoed light-squared bishop. Tartakower's original move-order was  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  , but the one we follow in this course is much more popular with about 75,000 games in my database, to 25,000 with the old one. For this reason, it seemed more relevant to me to cover it.  So, the obvious question is: how does  3.Nf3  benefits me instead of  3.g3  ? Let's go step by step.  1. The first reason is that after  3.g3  I consider  3...c5  very good for Black. The Benoni Defense was my main weapon against d4 from age 12 until 16-17 and I got especially good results against the 3.g3 Variation. In fact after 2010's book on the Catalan for White by GM Boris Avrukh was published, I got back to the Benoni, since 3.g3 became very fashionable and I still had very good results with it.  The bishop on g2 does not coordinate well with the pawn on d5 and the rest of the pieces and plays a secondary role unlike the main lines of the Catalan. Also, the positions are extremely unbalanced and it is very difficult to be 'in control'. Most lines work for very specific reasons, have no 'rules of thumb' and are very volatile  (we can get a losing very quickly)  .  The Catalan is characterized by positions with initiative and play by general concepts,  (strong bishop on g2, fight for the center, control of weak squares)  that are repeated throughout the course. For this reason I believe it is appropriate to focus on these values as much as possible.  To mention one line in particular, the Re8 and Bf5 variation of the Benoni discussed in GM Narayanan's course would seem like a very good answer to me.  2. Reti's players:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  and  1...--  2.c4  , will have a nicer transition to 1. d4. In an era characterized by constantly changing repertoires and openings, playing 3.Nf3 allows us to start from the Reti or even 1.d4 & 2.Nf3 in case we want to avoid aggressive lines like the Benko Gambit:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  , or having something more flexible against critical lines such as the King's Indian Defense or the Grunfeld:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  g6  .   Another fashionable variation is the Orthodox:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  which allows us to transpose to the Catalan too.	  So for the small price of avoiding the Queen's Indian, 3.g3 forces us to jump right into the most critical variations against 1.d4 and we lose move-order flexibility. The initial idea of the course was to discuss the subtleties of each move-order, but the scope and nuances to keep in mind has made it too extensive.  3. I have extensively played the Reti:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  and  1...--  2.c4  , the King's Indian Attack:  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  and  1...--  2.g3  , Zukerkot system:  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  e6  3.e3  , openings that have many synergies and similarities with the Catalan, either in terms of move order or the spirit of the position. Even London System players will have a more comfortable transition. For example  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  and if Black replies  2...d5  , they can play the London, and if  2...e6  , then play the Catalan.  I think I can summarize my approach to creating this course in four key ideas:  1. Progressive learning: having safer and simpler lines to cover large aspects of the theory and being able to put the course into practice while learning all the main variations.  2. Everyone forgets the theory, so much of my effort has been to find harmony between the variations I recommended  and making them understandable through very simple concepts. It's been challenge since the material  had to be of high level.  3. That you can play the Catalan all your career and still be unpredictable. The course provides you with numerous alternatives and reasonable options to the mainlines, since I consider it vital to have a certain variety so that the repertoire can last you a lifetime and you don't get bored.  4. In the same way that I have found many novelties and new ideas, I encourage you to look for little-explored paths or reuse old ideas. The classics are so underrated!  We will start by covering the Catalan Main Line, so that you get acquainted with the spirit of the Catalan. From there, we will go back and look at all the options with 1...Nf6, explore Black's most peculiar first moves, the many ways to enter the Dutch, and then we will look at 1...d5, from the early branches till the main lines.  Where I could, my approach was to recommend lines where White can fianchetto, so that the entire repertoire is as coherent as possible. In some cases  (such as the Queen's Gambit Accepted, for example)  , this is not recommended. Even so, I have tried to make my proposals fit the spirit of the Catalan: a combination of active play and the search for small opening advantages.  My goal with this course is that you enjoy learning the Catalan and its main lines and that at the same time you have many secondary weapons to be able to use depending on your opponent.  I hope I achieved it, and without further ado, I invite you to study the Quickstarter Guide! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grünfeld with ...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3
{ I wanted my recommendations to keep the maximum flexibility possible according to what I recommend in the Catalan chapters.   There are quite a few players who opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  and if Black plays  2...d5  , they go  3.Bf4  and if they continue  2...g6  they can already play the King's Indian.   It is very important to be aware of our memory and mastery of the openings and these little shortcuts or tricks in the move orders that allow you to 'close' one way while you are learning another.   It is better to have a simpler path than to go into main lines with everything half done. For all these reasons, I continue with this move order, which will also benefit Reti players  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  --  2.c4  and you will be able to appreciate Black's numerous reactions. At the top level it is considered that the most precise move order is  3.g3  delaying as much as possible the move Nf3 to keep the dxc5! option open in case Black wants to transpose to Benoni positions by going ...c7-c5.   The move 3.g3 allows certain move order pluses against the Grünfeld in some concrete variations.   The point is that, in exchange for these small details, we lost a lot of move order flexibility, and we did not avoid the most relevant variations with ...d6 or ...c6-d5. So consistently with the rest of this course and the Part 1 we will go for this move order and give an answer to all Black's alternatives. }
3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions. After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively.   We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c6 6. Nc3
{ Here we can continue with  6.O-O  and 7. Qb3, as I recommend as an alternative, or 6. O-O and 7. Nc3, which will lead to the same variation to the one that will be our weapon. }
6... d5 7. O-O
{ Carlsen has once again popularized this typical 'Catalan' sacrifice, and it will be our main option, being very similar to the positions seen in the Catalan.   As a first big difference, we have to talk about the bishop on g7. In the Catalan, Black has less activity with the bishop on the f8-a3 diagonal, and that is why this variation against the Grunfeld is considered somewhat risky. }
7... dxc4 { Black should take the pawn, otherwise will be in trouble. } 8. e4
{ It is very important that you know the peculiarity of these positions.   The g7-bishop allows Black to meet our typical move in the Catalan,  8.Ne5  , with  8...Ng4!  , and the d4-pawn is exposed. This resource is very common, and it is important to keep it in mind. }
8... b5 9. Qe2 Bg4
{ This pin is Svidler's recommendation. Black is looking for the typical theme of playing ...e5!, so we do not have much choice. }
10. e5 Nd5 11. a4
{ We take advantage of the fact that the long h1-a8 diagonal is more vulnerable. }
11... Bf5 { With this move, Black aims to take advantage of the d3-square. }
12. axb5 Bd3 13. Qd1 e6 { Svidler end up recommending this move. } 14. Ng5
{ This novelty is intended to delve into the theme of our strong h1-a8 diagonal and also into some hidden ideas. }
14... Bxf1 15. Qxf1
{ Our threat is Be4!, followed by Qh3. Suddenly, the black king is in trouble. }
15... h6
{ The only move that does not seem obvious to me if Black does not know the attacking plan.   After  15...cxb5  16.Nxb5  the ideas are the same. }
16. Nge4 cxb5 { Black did not have many more moves. } 17. Nxb5 Nc6 18. Qxc4 Qb6
{ Other moves are somewhat weaker, and we would continue with Ned6. } 19. Ned6
{ Our minor pieces are annoying for Black and the d5-square is quite weak. }
19... Rad8 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Qa4
{ We can continue with Be3 and aim to take on d5 with Nc3.   Also, after Bf4, it does not seem easy for Black to get rid of the uncomfortable knights. Both of Black's minor pieces would like to be on other squares, and the rooks do not have much play. }
