{ Carlsen has once again popularized this typical 'Catalan' sacrifice, and it will be our main option, being very similar to the positions seen in the Catalan.   As a first big difference, we have to talk about the bishop on g7. In the Catalan, Black has less activity with the bishop on the f8-a3 diagonal, and that is why this variation against the Grunfeld is considered somewhat risky. }
7... dxc4 { Black should take the pawn, otherwise will be in trouble. } 8. e4
{ It is very important that you know the peculiarity of these positions.   The g7-bishop allows Black to meet our typical move in the Catalan,  8.Ne5  , with  8...Ng4!  , and the d4-pawn is exposed. This resource is very common, and it is important to keep it in mind. }
8... b5 9. Qe2 b4 10. Nd1
{ Black's most direct option. Our knight will be weird on d1, but Black's queenside pawn structure will not be so stable. }
10... Ba6 11. Re1 { Black wanted to go ...c4-c3 winning the exchange. } 11...
c5 12. d5 Nbd7 13. e5
{ I like the idea of that the main theme in most lines is the e5-e6 push. }
13... Nxd5 14. e6 N7b6 15. exf7+ Rxf7 16. a3
{ This awkward move allows us to activate our rook or force Black to destroy their strong pawn structure. We continue to threaten Ng5 and Ne6 or Qe6+ at convenience.    If Black wishes to play h6, then Ne5 will be very strong. It's a position with two pawns down in which Black's pieces are very uncoordinated and it's roughly equal because we have so much counterplay. }
