1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3
{ I wanted my recommendations to keep the maximum flexibility possible according to what I recommend in the Catalan chapters.   There are quite a few players who opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  and if Black plays  2...d5  , they go  3.Bf4  and if they continue  2...g6  they can already play the King's Indian.   It is very important to be aware of our memory and mastery of the openings and these little shortcuts or tricks in the move orders that allow you to 'close' one way while you are learning another.   It is better to have a simpler path than to go into main lines with everything half done. For all these reasons, I continue with this move order, which will also benefit Reti players  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  --  2.c4  and you will be able to appreciate Black's numerous reactions. At the top level it is considered that the most precise move order is  3.g3  delaying as much as possible the move Nf3 to keep the dxc5! option open in case Black wants to transpose to Benoni positions by going ...c7-c5.   The move 3.g3 allows certain move order pluses against the Grünfeld in some concrete variations.   The point is that, in exchange for these small details, we lost a lot of move order flexibility, and we did not avoid the most relevant variations with ...d6 or ...c6-d5. So consistently with the rest of this course and the Part 1 we will go for this move order and give an answer to all Black's alternatives. }
3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions. After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively.   We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... c5 7. O-O Nc6
{ This is the best move order, which is recommended by Gawain Jones. Other moves aren't as good.   If  7...a6  we play  8.dxc5!  and 9.Be3 would be a terrible version for Black. Against a move such as 7...a6 we could continue our development with b3-Bb2 and the knight would be out of play if the center is not closed. }
8. d5 Na5
{ Black's key point. He wants to take advantage of the threat on c4 to look for a6-b5 and crack open the queenside. The usual price for Black is to have a knight that is a bit out of play and that can become a real problem if he does not get enough counterplay. }
9. Nd2 e6
{ In general, in this course we have avoided the Benoni, but the knight on a5 drastically changes all the approaches we take because it is an easy target to focus our plans on. }
10. Rb1
{ Going off the long diagonal and having the option of playing b2-b4 is the usual modus operandi. }
10... exd5
{ Against  10...Re8  we would continue with b4, as we will usually do in this variation. Gawain considers this capture as best and it seems the most natural move as well. }
11. cxd5
{ Ideally in these pawn structures we would have the c4-square for our knight. In this case it is covered by the knight on a5.    The big difference, having the knight on a5, is that the usual plans with ...a6-...b5 are not so useful and in case of b2-b4, the knight can end up relegated to b7, where it would have no circuit to activate. }
11... Bd7
{ Black wants to play ...b5 as efficiently as possible: developing the pieces. Against 11...Re8 12.b4 cxb4 13.Rxb4 b6 and we will meet this line with Bb2-a4-Nb5. }
12. Nde4
{ We want to expose the knight on a5, so we aim to make ourselves stronger in the center. At the moment Bg5 and Nxd6 are serious threats and Black has to react. }
12... Ne8
{ The move recommended by Gawain. Black wants to take advantage of the situation of White's knights in the center @@StartBracket@@they take squares away from each other and cover less space@@EndBracket@@ with an eventual f5 or ...b5-b4. }
13. Qd3
{ We deviate from the variations discussed by Gawain Jones. We want to play b4 and take advantage of the misplaced knight on a5. }
13... a6
{ WATCH OUT against this move!! Now b4 would be a terrible blunder. After14.b4 cxb4 15.Rxb4 Rc8! we cannot go for the typical jump Nb5 and the knight saturation is working against us. 13...f5 In King's Indian positions, this move usually does not work if Black has not prevented Ng5 first. The e6-square is very weak, and our knight coordinates very well with the bishop on the long h1-a8 diagonal, which is waiting for its turn.14.Ng5 Nc7 15.Bf4 now our whole position makes sense, and we will simply accumulate troops in the center with Re1-e4 and Rad1. Against h6, we would jump to e6 and continue with Rad1. When in a position, where natural moves are very powerful, it becomes difficult for our opponent to defend. }
14. Bf4
{ Against the common 14.Bg5 aiming to force ...f6, Black can play 14...Qc7! and 15.Be7 is impossible due to 15...Bb5!. Besides, f6 is not a drama or substantially changes the game for Black, so it is not worth the risk. }
14... Bf5
{ Now we had freed up space to be able to threaten b4 properly and have Rc1 in case of what was mentioned a couple of moves ago. }
15. h3
{ Pushing the bishop away and bringing the queen on g3 is extremely pleasant in terms of coordination. }
15... Qe7
{ A bit far-fetched Black alternative, increasing the pressure on e4. } 16. g4
{ I did not like the fact that after 16.a4 Black can activate the knight with 16...Nb3! }
16... Bd7
{ For Black to come up with this wonderful move, he must have foreseen that after 21. Qg3 b5! 22. Nxd6 g5!!, is the necessary reply that would win for Black. Quite unnatural. In general, it is always a disaster for Black to exchange on e4 and help white make space for the remaining knight. }
17. Rbc1
{ Let's say that this move improves the position in most future situations. The most obvious would be to unpin the knight on e4 against an eventual f5 and another would be to have the knight on c3 overdefended to be able to play b3 without problems. }
17... f5 18. gxf5 Bxf5
{ The pawn capture would be met with the typical Ng5!, invading Black's white squares with Ne6. }
19. Qg3 Nc4 20. b3 Ne5 21. Bg5
{ Our plan is aiming for f4, most likely meeting Nf7 with Bh4 and then Nf2-e4. I like it because all our pieces pursue the common goal of pushing in the center.  For example, if Black wanted to play b7-b5 we would see that our e4-e5 break has pluses, as the g2-a8 diagonal is open. }
