[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Benko Gambit "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... c5 3. d5 b5
{ The Benkö @@StartBracket@@or Volga@@EndBracket@@ Gambit is a very frequent weapon at upper beginner level and which guarantees a quite easy practical game for Black in exchange for a pawn.   I have always had issues facing this variation, as it is extremely easy to make a small positional inaccuracy and being punished by our opponent's solid pawn structure. In general, White is considered to be better, but I would be very careful with this variation if you haven't faced it in the past.   I believe that this is a dangerous weapon in rapid time controls. Besides, even Magnus Carlsen has often played it. Black's goal is to open the a and b-files in exchange for a pawn and put pressure on our queenside with the help of a strong bishop on g7. }
4. cxb5
{ I have played the alternative move  4.c2  is several games, but I consider the text move easier to play. I prefer to justify an alternative in which we enjoy having an extra pawn. }
4... a6 5. e3
{ This move invites Black to take on b5 so we can develop our light-squared bishop on the f1-a6-diagonal. The main line with bxa6-g3-Bg2 I don't like for similar reasons to what happens with the Benoni with g3.   Our bishop on g2 does not fit as well as it should with a pawn on d5 and requires a very precise play by White to be able to answer the different plans that Black can go for. The alternative 4. bxa6 g6 5.Cc3 Ba6 6.e4 allows Black to take our f1-bishop.   Although I also have played this line, it also requires a very precise play if we do not want to end up in practical problems. }
5... g6
{ Black usually gives priority to their piece development. One of Black's ideas will be to delay taking on b5 until we move the f1-bishop to force us to lose a tempo. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. a4 { Supporting our b5-pawn. } 7... O-O 8. e4
{ Once b5 is better defended, we can start our central expansion. } 8... Bb7
{ Black seeks to put pressure on the center and maintain the tension with ...a6-...b5. }
9. Bc4
{ The premature development of White's bishop is justifiable as Black has invested a tempo playing ...Bb7. In this case we want to play Nge2. }
9... axb5 10. Bxb5 e6 11. Nge2 exd5 12. exd5 Na6
{ Black's aim is to increase the pressure against our d5-pawn. } 13. O-O
{ After Bc4 and Rb1 we will have very good control of the center and we have neutralized Black's counterplay. Then we could continue with Bf4-Qd2.   The knight on e2 is important because, in case of ...Re8, the move Ng3 would be our reply to prevent Black from gaining presence in the center with ...Ne4. }
