[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Budapest Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e5
{ I have used the Budapest Gambit as a weapon on several occasions, but lately seems not to be so safe and sound anymore. This defense requires only a little degree of preparation from Black's point of view, so it is important to have an adequate reply against it.   Black sacrifices a pawn momentarily to break our center and activate his minor pieces. As I said, I played it on several occasions, but since a 2500-player beat me without a chance, I preferred to opt for more consistent variations. }
3. dxe5
{ There are 3 usual replies to this move, divided into 2 concepts.   1@@EndBracket@@ The move Bf4 would belong on the first concept, which would consist of defending the e5 pawn. Black usually ends up playing f6, getting positions with relative compensation and hard to materialize from our point of view.   2@@EndBracket@@ Nf3 and e4 belong on the second concept, which would be to give priority to our development.   White is happy that Black will lose time with the knight and will give up the center for our pawns. The move I propose is along the lines of the second group, but is somewhat more aggressive. }
3... Ng4 4. e3
{ When creating this courses, my aim is also to update my way of approaching the game of chess and also my point of view on how the openings are played nowadays.   I would usually recommend the classical  4.Bf4  or  4.Nf3  , but I like you to see the more modern variations and the style of play that predominates in the era of neural networks. }
4... Nxe5 5. f4
{ Asking Black's knight whether it prefers to hinder the development of the queenside or to return to the kingside. }
5... Ng6 6. h4
{ There is a concept that is repeated in many, many positions. The knights on g6 or b6 are vulnerable to either h4 or a4 pushes, respectively. By extension, it is often strong to play h4 or a4 when the knights are on e7 or d7, so I hope that by the study of this course you will also be able to extrapolate ideas like this to other openings.   Moreover, this pawn sacrifice to open the h file is very common in hypermodern chess and so we get used to consider h4-h5 in many positions. Finally, we will also add that playing 6 pawn moves in a row is very cool :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7
{ Black aims to put pressure on the key e3-square and develop quickly. } 8. Kf2
{ With h4 we have bet on having the rook on h1, so we will probably not castle. }
8... Bxd2 9. Qxd2 Nxh4 10. Nc3
{ Our next moves will likely be Bd3-Nge2-Ng3 and Black's position is excessively delicate. Castling short is unthinkable and castling long will be met with a quick attack with Nd5-b4. This is a very good example of the usefulness of the h-pawn sacrifice ideas. }
