1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5
{ The Benoni has always been special in my bond with chess. It was the first defense that I played since I was 11 years old until I was 15-16 exclusively and it gave me very good results.   Its main virtue is that, even knowing that it is objectively weak, the answers to the different problems posed by Black are quite specific. White has to be constantly in a balance between controlling Black's counterplay and expanding by taking advantage of his central pawn majority.   While I try to explain each line, my main intention is to equip you with all the 'issues' we have to watch out for and that you can use them to counter the Benoni. }
6. cxd5 g6 7. h3
{ Preventing Bg4 and preparing the development of the bishop on c1. With this move we open a safe square on h2 for the bishop in case Black plays Nh5.   7.Nd2  , covered by Shankland, seems to me a very good alternative. However, there are certain variations which I find them too technical for White, so I preferred this alternative. }
7... Bg7 8. Bf4
{ 8.e4  probably has been tried in 20 games, but the amount of variations you have to learn, and, especially the variation  8...O-O  followed by  b5  , make me inclined to recommend this variation. }
8... O-O 9. e3
{ The key of this setup is that the bishop on f4 will eternally harass d6. Also, the bishop on c8 has no comfortable square to develop to due to the lack of space.   That is the reason why this will always be an unresolved issue for Black. The little price we pay is that we are not in time to play e4, as Black can continue with moves like Nxe4 and Re8. For this reason, we will regain the space in the center as soon as we have the chance to do so. }
9... a6
{ In the Benoni there is always the doubt whether the moves a6-a4 should be included or it is better to wait. In general, taking into account my personal experience, the differences are minimal. }
10. a4 Ne8
{ Black has maximum flexibility and wants to develop the knight on b8, as d6 is defended. However, this also allows a very interesting, yet little explored move. }
11. e4
{ This move has not been played in any of the 500 games that have reached this position. As Black does not have any presence in the center anymore, We take advantage of this to gain space there before finishing the development.   In general, it is not advisable to move the same pawn twice in the opening, but we will have already surprised the opponent and the position is easier to understand, in my opinion, with this pawn structure. }
11... f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Be2
{ The hole on e6 is very weak and the bishop on f5 is still very vulnerable to g4. }
13... Nf6 14. O-O Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. g3
{ We want to play Ng5 and Ne6. The b2-pawn is relatively important, and this is because the knight on b8 and the rook on a8 are not playing and Black is in trouble due to the fact that the pawn on d6 is vulnerable. }
16... Bxb2 17. Ra2 Bf6 18. h4
{ Intending Ng5 and again Black will struggle to find a safe square for the light-squared bishop. }
18... Bxf3 19. Bxf3
{ We will enter on e6 and Black will be very vulnerable to ideas like Bh6-f4-f5 or simply h5. Black's extra pawn is futile agsinst White's attack, that can be combined with some pressure along the b and e-files, depending on the situation. }
