[Black "Queen's Indian Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6
{ Black wants to put pressure on c4 and a range of interesting possibilities opens up now for White. }
5. Nbd2
{ Although ideally we would like to develop the knight on b2, we have to keep in mind that the bishop on a6 will most likely relocate to b7 once its function of pressing c4 is over.   A very substantial plus of this move is that it requires very little knowledge to have a playable game while the others may be affected by more incisive variations. Another very interesting option if our opponent plays exclusively this variation is to try to play the Catalan by delaying 2.c4.   I recently encountered a student who did not have an alternative planned for it and had to play Bb7 straight. I always encourage to be demanding with the move order, you can win many points this way. }
5... Bb7 6. Bg2 c5
{ At last it seems that Black, once he has put our knight on d2, will be able to play c5 in good conditions. Here we have a different idea to what we have seen }
7. e4 cxd4 { 7...Nxe4  is impossible, as it loses after  8.Ne5  . } 8. O-O
{ 8.e5  would be met by  8...Ne4!  , and complications balance the scales. }
8... Nxe4 { It fails once again } 9. Ne5 d5 10. cxd5 exd5
{ 10...Nxd2  let us win in many different ways. For example,  11.Nxf7!  just kills the game  11...Kxf7  12.dxe6  and black is losing too much material and still the king is exposed. }
11. Qa4+ Nd7 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bh3 Bc8 14. Qc6
{ Black's final position is quite miserable. His central pawns are of no use to him. The threats on the rook on a8 and Nxf7 are decisive. }
