1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb4+
{ This pseudo Bogo-Indian has very different nuances from those exposed in the 3.... Bb4+ variation, so it should be analyzed carefully. }
5. Bd2
{ 5.Nbd2  would not make much sense as Black usually spends the Ba6-tempo to force the move Nbd2 and then he will play Bb7. }
5... Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7
{ A priori this seems ideal for Black. We have a Queen's Indian with a couple of exchanged pieces and on top of that he keeps the idea of answering our Nc3 with Ne4. However, this move order gives a very relevant extra option to White. }
7. Bg2 O-O 8. Nc3 Ne4 { A thematic reply that contains special venom. } 9. Qc2
Nxc3 10. Ng5
{ This is one of the moves that every chess player dreams of playing. We have just captured a piece and instead of recapturing, we leave two other pieces undefended! We threaten mate in one move and at the same time the b7 bishop is undefended. }
10... Ne4
{ Again, Black offers the knight and blocks the square that all the threats were created.   10...Qxg5  11.Bxb7  Both the rook on a8 and the knight on c3 are trapped so we have enough time to capture both and keep the extra exchange. }
11. Bxe4 Bxe4 12. Qxe4
{ Black cannot defend the mate and the rook on a8 at the same time. } 12...
Qxg5 13. Qxa8 Nc6 14. Qb7 Nxd4 15. Rd1
{ White scores greatly from this position either in correspondence chess and in human-to-human games. The extra exchange and the queenside invasion with our queen on b7 are two factors that give us more than enough advantage. }
