[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open Catalan, 5...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6
{ Black wants to defend the pawn which he just captured and supports an eventual b5-push. }
6. Ne5
{ We prevent the b-pawn from being pushed directly and, at the same time, we are threatening to recapture the pawn. I prefer playing this variation, as it cuts off the complexity, and we do not let Black carry out his typical plans with b5 comfortably.   On the other hand, I think there is more play here and also the forced lines are more challenging for Black. }
6... Bb4+
{ A thematic development against a quick Ne5, taking advantage of the fact that we have not castled yet. }
7. Nc3 { Renewing the threat on c4. } 7... Nd5
{ Black's plan is to reinforce the threat on c3 and to close the h1-a8 diagonal in order to be able to defend c4, either with b5 or with Nb6.   Now  7...c5?  does not work as after  8.Nxc4  it is not possible to take on d4 due to Qa4+. }
8. O-O
{ This move can surprise many opponents since it prioritizes the development to defend c3 and raises a gambit that is always is subject to doubt for Black if he accepts it. }
8... Nxc3
{ This move starts a very long sequence where Black should play very precise. Here we can find a lot of correspondence games.   For example,  8...Nb6  seems to defend the pawn, but after  9.Nxc4  there is the decisive resource Qa4+. }
9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Rb1 Bxd4
{ A reasonable alternative, but condemns Black to a passive defense.   10...O-O  In this case, an escape in time is not feasible,  11.e3  the bishop is in no man's land, Black cannot develop his queenside pieces, and the pawns on c4 and b7 will fall. }
11. Nxc4 O-O 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Na5
{ We continue suffocating Black's queenside. Only the bishop on d4 is out of the back rank. }
13... Bb6 14. Nxb7 Bxb7 15. Bxb7 Ra7 16. Bf3 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1
{ Black is comically awkward. If he tries a5-Na6 intending Nb4, we take advantage of the moment when Na6 comes to play Bc6 followed by doubling the rooks, penetrating decisively in Black's back rank, while the rook on a7 and the bishop on b6 ask themselves why are they being where they are. }
