[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open Catalan, 5...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5
{ Black's idea is to put pressure quickly in the center and hope for a quick development, taking advantage of the fact that that White should spend 2 tempi to capture on c4. }
6. O-O Nc6
{ This move increases the pressure in the center and here the main ideas of White diverge. }
7. Ne5
{ Once again, as it happens in the 5... a6 and 5... c6 variations, we make this move once again which quickly frees our bishop on g2 and allows us to fight for central dominance. For the moment we attack the c6 point and also enable to take on c4.   7.dxc5  followed by 8. Nbd2 is the most popular alternative and the one recommended by Narayanan. The problem I see is that the position is always close to equal after the queen trade and recently I faced a very well-prepared player that I could hardly pose any problems.   dxc5 is the most popular variation, so it is to be expected that it is also the one against which they are better prepared against. That's why I recommend 7.Ne5, which leads to positions with more pieces and possible ways to create an unbalance. }
7... Nxe5
{ In the database I find a 75% winning percentage for White out of more than 500 games. This data serves as an introduction to the problems that Black faces after 7... Nxe5. }
8. dxe5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Nd7 10. Na3
{ The bishop on g2 is very strong, the d6-square is fantastic and Black's pieces are in each other's way. }
10... Nxe5 11. Bf4 f6 12. Bxe5 fxe5 13. Nxc4
{ Too many weaknessess and too many passivity. Black cannot move, so we could even make moves as h4-a4-b3 to improve our position and see how powerless Black feels. }
