[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7
{ In my opinion, this variation is the most solid one that Black can choose from. The bishop on d2 disturbs the normal development of White. In this case, Nbd2 is not as playable as with the order 3. g3, since Black has dxc4 before castling. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Bc3
{ After spending a lot of time researching this position, I have opted for this option. It is relatively simple, and we keep practically all the pieces on the board and avoid symmetrical structures.    White has many alternatives to play, but I consider that Black has too many good options to choose from and that his game is very simple and intuitive. With Bc3 we improve the position of our bishop and free the d2-square for the knight. }
8... b6
{ This is the recommendation of the Norwegian IM Tor Fredrik Kaasen in his course Neutralize the Catalan. }
9. cxd5
{ Similarly to what we do against the Queen's Indian, we take on d5, and we look for some play with a fixed structure. In this case, the bishop on c3 is a bit misplaced for that, but I think we are on time to build our favorite setup. }
9... exd5 10. Bd2
{ I do not think it is a surprise for anybody that this move is a novelty. We aim to play Bf4 and Nc3. }
10... Bb7 11. Nc3 Re8 12. Bf4
{ While our position is based on very simple principles established in the variations against the Queen's Indian, Black has a wide range of replies since he has a couple of extra tempi. }
12... Ne4 13. Qb3 Nxc3 14. bxc3
{ Black's queenside structure is very inflexible. We can continue with a4-a5 and maintain the tension.   We enjoy a reinforced center and the typical moves like Bh3-Ne5 as needed. In general, I find it an unpleasant position to play with Black, although I must remember that it is also very solid. }
