[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Dutch Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch is a defense that I hold in high esteem. Black apparently plays a 'symmetrical' Sicilian and should not be so special.   The big difference is that it immediately weakens the black king. Having played this variation dozens of times with Black, I have to admit that it has a certain venom and there are usually very specific positions of the variation where most pieces and pawns still remain on the board, which implies a lot of play. }
2. Nf3
{ I will focus on explaining these positions with 2. Nf3 so we will have no move order nuances and Black will be free to play as they please, but nothing is really particularly effective. I prefer that you can go into these positions with 1. c4 or 1. Nf3 without fearing that certain plans are not covered. }
2... Nf6 3. c4 g6
{ The Leningrad Variation is the most common played of all Dutch possible variations. Black plays a pseudo King's-Indian with the pawn on f5. If they manage to play ...e5 favorably, they will be fine, but the move ...f5 also has a strategical drawback that will be seen later.   The greatest high-level player who goes for the Leningrad is the Spanish Grandmaster David Antón, who practices it assiduously, as well as the French champion Maxime Lagarde. }
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ Both  6...b6  and  6...Ne4  gave nothing to Black in the past.  After  7.Ne5  and  7.Nc3  respectively, Black has obtained nothing. }
7. Nc3 { We have reached the first very big tree of options for Black. } 7...
Nc6
{ This variation is famous for reaching quite unique positions in the whole game of chess. }
8. d5 Ne5
{ If  8...Na5  9.b3  c5  10.Bb2  Black will pay a high price for having played f5. We will simply play Rb1-a4-Ba1 and we can continue with our central expansion.   Black usually pays the price of putting the knight on a5 in order to have control of the pawn breaks they can execute and when to go for them @@StartBracket@@either ...e6 or ...b5@@EndBracket@@. In this position, we have free hands. }
9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qb3
{ This position is tremendously abstract. Black seeks to make progress on the queenside depending on what we play. For example, playing e4 would leave the f4-square vulnerable. The general idea is to look for ...h6-...g5-...Kh8 and perhaps continue with ...Qe8-...Qh5.   Therefore, prophylactic moves such as ...a6 will be common to avoid trouble on c7 after Nb5 ideas. Usually White aims for Rd1 and c5 and gain space. But I really did not understand what that would achieve, so I looked for a more consistent plan. }
10... h6 11. Rd1 g5 12. Bd2
{ We simply aim for developing normally with Rac1 and later bring our bishop to c3 in order for Black to mobilize their center, so that we can go for good pawn breaks for our interests. }
12... Kh8 13. Rac1 a6
{ After  13...f4  14.Ne4  we have control of all the light-squares. It is very typical for us to go Ba5! to force Black to create weaknesses with ...b7-b6. Once done that, we can safely break with c5.  13...e4  14.f3  we will bring the bishop to d4 and then our expansion with c5 will make a lot of sense. }
14. Nb1 Qe8 15. Bc3 e4
{ 15...Nd7  Black can try to keep flexibility in the center.  16.a3  now that there are fewer pieces surrounding our king, it is a good time to continue with the c4-c5 expansion. }
16. Be5
{ With Nc3 we can consider our plan being carried out succesfully.We would only have to worry about Black's more aggressive variation. }
16... Qh5 17. Nd2
{ 17.f3  f4!?  would lead us to a very abstract position. With the text move being played, we are ready to take on c7. }
17... Ng4
{ If  17...Qxe2  18.Re1!  we take advantage of the fact that the knight is taboo -due to Bc3 and Rcd1, after which Black's queen would be trapped- to calmly take on c7 and Black has lost their initiative.  18.Bxc7  is also good, but this will force you to remember that after  18...b5  you have to play  19.f3!! }
18. Bxg7+ Kxg7 19. h3 Nf6 20. f3
{ Black's attack comes to an end and Black will have to deal with their pitiful pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted is an alternative that has always been considered as 'solid', but until the recent years is was not played as frequently by top level players.   The accuracy of today's modern engines have turned around many annoying variations in practice and especially has provided answers against the most critical variation 3.e4. }
3. Nf3
{ We have chosen this variations for various reasons:   1. It fits well in our repertoire: playing 3. e4 would eliminate the possibility of going 1.Nf3 or 2.Nf3   2. I consider this move to be the most sustainable variation in the long run and fits with the 'Lifetime Repertoire' kind of courses. The alternative 3. e4 could be obsolete for sure in a short period of time and the massive memorization it requires would be useless.   3. This is the variation I have always played myself and has given me a lot of success. With little knowledge you can play at a high level and it is also very comfortable to play.   Our idea is to continue with e3 and Bxc4. We play first 3.Nf3 instead of 3.e3 because this way we can avoid Black's extra option 3...e5! }
3... Nf6 4. e3
{ Delaying the capture would only get us into trouble.   The alternative  4.Qa4+  is quite weak as Black is flexible enough to meet the capture with  4...c6  followed by Nd7, with a nice position for the second player. For example, via the move order 1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 dxc4 this would make more sense, as Black has commited to the move ...e6. Even so, we will go for 4. e3 as the alternative does not completely convince me. }
4... e6
{ Black's main continuation, clearing the way of the dark-squared bishop to be able to play ...c5 with the idea of challenging our center. }
5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5
{ When thinking about what to recommend against the QGA, this queenless middlegame came to my mind. I have played it since I was a kid and I have always got nice and almost risk-free positions which, in addition, are hard to play for Black.   Black has quite some options here, which increases the possibility for them to make mistakes, while we have only 2-3 ideas that repeat themselves and are easy to understand. 7.b3 A very practical alternative way of playing these positions.   Our light-squared bishop will go to e2 so that the c4-square @@StartBracket@@probably after a previous a4 to liberate it in case Black plays ...b5@@EndBracket@@ and the d4-square will be booked for our knights. Once we reach such a position, we will usually play Bf3 to challenge the important c6-square, which is usually a big issue for Black if they move the b-pawn and trade the c and d-pawns.   I recommend to practice these positions as they can fit your style. THis way, you can analyze the entire variation with minimum effort. Top players use to choose this variation in rapid time controls, which menas that for the rest of us mortals we can play it in classical time controls. }
7... Bxc5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Be2
{ This retreat keeps the maximum flexibility possible and also removes the bishop from an almost useless square. On the one hand, it was vulnerable to the ...b7-b5-push and, on the other hand, there was little he could do on the a2-g8 diagonal.   This move frees the c4-square for one of our knights, the c-file for one of our rooks, and is one move away from getting to f3, from where it will make a higher impact. }
9... Ke7
{ The king looks for shelter here and Black also keeps the flexibility. } 10.
Nc3
{ So, Ding and Giri tried this move in the past The idea is replacing the f3-knight to c4 via d2 or e5 to make an impact on the queenside. The difference between this move and Nfd2 or Ne5 is that the former keeps certain flexibility.   There are some moves that I consider 'unplayable' in practice for Black such as  10...b6  . After  11.Na4  a5!  , both getting an isolated pawn and giving the bishop pair is justified by dynamic means with ...Ba6 ideas.  Against  10...b6  we play  11.Ne5  forcing Black to go  11...b5!  , as after the 'normal'  11...Bb7  12.Na4  Black will indeed suffer. With this example I want to get out of your head the “engine addiction” that positions like this can encourage; Black is walking on glass floor. }
10... b5
{ This move is Gledura's recommendation. One of the reasons I find this ending interesting is that each of Black's moves magically has a different motive.   In some lines Black prefers the b-pawn to be on b6; in some lines, to keep it on b7; in some lines, the knight gets to c6; in others, it goes to d7... The point is that Black always has a range of reasonable moves and there is a good breeding ground for mistakes. }
11. Nd2
{ 11.Ne5  has no sense in case Black challenges the diagonal with  11...Bb7  and if we try  12.Nd3  Black can meet it with  12...Bd6  and will have no coordination issues. }
11... Bb7 12. Nb3
{ Putting pressure on the c5-bishop and we have in mind the square a5. } 12...
Bd6 13. Na5
{ f3 and e4 was another interesting way of approaching the position. } 13...
Ra7 14. Bd2
{ We proceed with the development and give Black opportunities to make mistakes. }
14... Nc6
{ If  14...Ba8  we assume the fact that Black wants to keep the bishop pair and considers that the a5-knight is left isolated  15.a4!  the c4-square is an unexpected square to get into, and this is annoying for Black  15...bxa4  pushing the pawn forward leads nowhere after we play Na2.   Even after b4-b3 we can ignore the pawn and continue with Nb4 to keep squeezing Black's position.  16.c4  and Black's dark-squared bishop has no reasonable destiny. We will continue with Nxa4 and Black can only sadly see their inability to maintain control of the a3-f8 diagonal, leaving their king very exposed. }
15. Nxb7 Rxb7 16. Rfd1
{ This is the typical position in which we can play whatever we want for free. We can go for moves such as Kf1, Be1, or even f4 followed by Bf3 to restrict Black's control of the dark squares and dominate the light squares ourselves.   Doubling rooks on the c-file is an interesting option as well according to what Black plays. Another idea is to push a4 to force Black to push ...b4 and, after that, maneuver the knight via Na2-Nc1-Nb3, so we exert pressure on the light and dark squares on Black's queenside. We really have quite a wide variety of plans and Black has the long-term problem of having given up the bishop pair. }
