[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Albin Counter Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 e5
{ The Albin Counter Gambithad its golden age in the early 2000s thanks to Morozevich, but has fallen out of favor as the engines have improved. Black gives up a central pawn to gain space in that area of the board and to hinder the development of our pieces. }
3. dxe5 { Why not? } 3... d4
{ This is Black's main idea: to gain some space in the center and benefit from simple piece development. }
4. Nf3 Nc6
{ White has several alternatives to refute the Albin, but 5.a3 seems to me to be the most appropriate, since it is based on the principle that we would like to play 5. e3 to exchange Black's active pawn on d4. }
5. a3
{ Inserting a3-a5 benefits us enormously by avoiding Black's O-O-O plans. And if they let us, we can expand with b4. The other important consideration is that the move 5. e3 fails because of ...Bb4+ followed by dxe3, leaving a very weakened pawn structure. }
5... a5 6. e3 { This was the idea behind 5.a3. } 6... Bc5 7. exd4 Bxd4
{ 7...Nxd4  doesn't retrieve the pawn. } 8. Be2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Bxe5
11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bf4
{ Our bishop pair and better piece coordination make life impossible for Black. I do not see a satisfactory defense against bringing our rooks to the e and d files. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Slav Defense - the Exchange Alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time. It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@1.e4 c6 and 2...d5@@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light-squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop.   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!   Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—.   It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.   Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black.   This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Slav I think it is a very good alternative to be able to play every now and then. Some GMs play it all the time, as it avoids a lot of lines with one move and has some venom.   Many times it will provoke our opponents to prefer to play other openings and it complements very well with the more aggressive main variations that I recommend.   I have played the Exchange Slav a couple of times, and it has more danger than it seems. The main difficulty of these positions for Black is that all the moves look good and acceptable and it is in that situation that mistakes can happen quickly.   Interestingly, I have a couple of wins against Grandmasters with the Black pieces, so this variation does not come without danger and it is easy for one side to overplay or underestimate the risks of symmetrical positions. }
4... cxd5 5. Nc3
{ There are other options with 3.cxd5 followed by 4.Nc3 and 5.Bf4 next. But the main idea is to play an easier and closed alternative in which Black has less options available.   In addition, from experience, the 4 knight is psychologically difficult for Black to deal with if he wants to play for the win. The reason is that, if White wants to, all the pieces can be exchanged, but this is not our goal. }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4 a6
{ The most usual prophylactic move. Black aims to play ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 and have the reaction ...Na5-...Bd7-...b5 against White's typical maneuver Qb3-Qa4+. }
7. Rc1
{ With this move we do not give an 'easy' solution to Black.   After  7.e3  Bg4  can complete the development without any problems and will get rid of the c8-bishop. }
7... Bg4 8. Ne5 { We want the g4-bishop to have no easy way to trade-off. }
8... Nxe5
{ 8...Nd7  This move provides us with a precious set of possibilities.  9.Nxd7  Qxd7  10.e3  and we will play Bd3 and a3 and there we have classical ideas like Na4 or the more 'spicy' g2-g4, launching an attack on the kingside. }
9. Bxe5 e6 { Now it is our time to hassle Black's light-squared bishop. } 10.
h4
{ This beautiful move capitalizes on the exposed light-squared bishop. We look for f3-g4-h5. }
10... h6 { Here we continue with a long but plenty of only moves for Black. }
11. f3 Bf5 12. e4
{ Taking advantage of the possibilities that the move Qa4+ brings us. } 12...
dxe4 13. fxe4 Bh7
{ If Black's f6-knight moves, Black will have no defenders to cover the check on a4. }
14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qa4+ b5 16. Nxb5 axb5 17. Qxb5+ Qd7 18. Qb6
{ Threatening Bb5. } 18... Rc8 19. Rxc8+ Qxc8 20. Bb5+ Ke7 21. Kf2
{ Here comes the rook! Black's king is in a mating net.   The variation  21...Qc2+  22.Kg1  Qc1+  23.Kh2  Qf4+  24.g3  Qf2+  25.Kh3  Bf5+  26.exf5  Qxf5+  27.Kg2  Qe4+  28.Kf2  seems never ending, but Black has to keep delivering checks or we will give checkmate.   Now we will continue with Re1 and we enjoy two great passed pawns and our king will be able to rest at last. After ...Qf5+ Ke3! the checks —and Black's hopes to save the game— would be over. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Slav Defense - the Chebanenko"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time. It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@1.e4 c6 and 2...d5@@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light-squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop.   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!   Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—.   It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.   Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black.   This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.   After  4.e3  Bf5  Black manages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.  In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.bd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently is has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... a6
{ The Chebanenko Variation usually leads to unique positions that require some caution. Black makes a usual waiting move to develop the c8-bishop without so many problems.   The main issue of the text move is that it weakens the b6-square considerably. Incidentally, Black also has the option of taking on c4 and further reinforcing that capture with ...b7-b5. Kamsky and Malakhov are among its greatest exponents. }
5. c5
{ Friendly reminder that here we can play5.cxd5 transposing to what we saw in the Exchange Slav section. For example, I would recommend you to learn the Exchange Slav first 'just in case' as in the Chebanenko we cannot play 'random' moves.   I have suffered two or three defeats because of this, which I think it justifies what I just wrote. I would even see no harm if you chose to say something along the lines of 'then against the Chebanenko I take on d5 to simplify my opening repertoire'.   After 5.c5 White gains some space on the queenside and exploits Black's lack of development. This reminds me of what I analyze after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  a6!?  4.Nc3  d5  5.c5!?  in another section of the course.   The big difference now is that Black holds out hope of developing the bishop on c8 and that has even less flexibility on the queenside. I recently beat a Grandmaster with this variation and then saw that I already won another game 4-5 years ago.   Our plan is to move the bishop from c1 to f4 and look for a fairly natural development with h3-e3-Bd3. Black on the other hand seeks to hinder this development and also go for the e5-break, which can annoy us a lot sincethe c5-pawn is somewhat exposed in case he loses its mate on d4. }
5... Nbd7
{ The main line. It is somewhat strange to block the development of the c8-bishop, but in return it will be seen that it is useful against Bf4. Also, Black is threatening ...e7-e5. In general our response to ...e7-e5 is to take on e5 and then defend the c5-pawn with Na4, keeping the squares on d4 and b6 under our control. }
6. Bf4 Nh5 7. Bd2
{ Now we are threatening e2-e4, gaining space and highlighting Black's lack of reaction on the queenside, so they should react adequately. }
7... g6 8. e4 { Black was threatening ...e5, as the h5-knight was defended. }
8... dxe4 9. Nxe4
{ Aiming to comfortably develop our light-squared bishop to c4. } 9... Ndf6
{ This peculiar move is quite accurate. Black aims to take with the e-pawn and relocate the knight via g7. The doubled f6-pawn controls our f3-knight and makes it difficult for our dark-squared bishop to get into play. }
10. Nc3
{ After the most common  10.Nxf6+  exf6!  I think our play will have to be very precise. We start from the logical deduction that if Black executes this peculiar knightly maneuver he knows what he is doing, one cannot go for this position by accident.   Cheparinov recommends some playable lines here, but one mistake on our end could be decisive due to the hole on d5 and our worse pawn structure, especially our exposed d4-pawn.  I am not convinced by the practical problems we have to face after  11.Bc4  Qe7+!  . After 10.Nc3 my aim is to look for more dynamic positions and to exploit the awkward position of Black's knight on h5. }
10... Bg4 { Black aims to play concretely in the center. } 11. h3
{ This pawn sacrifice aims to exploit the h5-knight's position. By kicking it away with g2-g4, it will be in the way of the f8-bishop's development square. }
11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qb4 14. O-O-O Ng7 15. a3 Qa5 16. Kb1
{ This precise move is aimed at avoiding some annoying checks and now  16...f5  is not possible due to  17.Bg5!  after which White is winning. We will continue with Bc4 and I still think that Black's position is enormously difficult in exchange for a mere pawn. }
