{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time. It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@1.e4 c6 and 2...d5@@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light-squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop.   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!   Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—.   It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.   Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black.   This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.   After  4.e3  Bf5  Black manages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.  In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.bd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently is has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course.   I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  but are very hackneyed variations and also require extensive memorization.   With  5.Qd3  I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.  5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6.  After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss more presence on the dark squares while we enyoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 Bb7
{ This is a good alternative for Black. Now g2-g4 does not work so well, so it is preferable to gain space in the center. }
8. e4 b4 9. Na4 Qa5
{ If Black does not fight for the center, we will have a very healthy position.   9...Ba6  10.Qc2  Bxf1  11.Kxf1  Preventing us from castling may look nice, but now there is no way for Black to play the necessary pawn break ...c6-c5, so after g3-Rg2 we will have a clear advantage. }
10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bf4
{ Nd2-Nc4 and reinforce the center with f3, nullifying the b7-bishop, is the key of this variation. }
11... c5 12. Ne5 Bxe4
{ Taking the pawn now means bad news for Black.   12...Nxe5  13.dxe5  and the key strategic concept is that after  13...Nd7  we will play Nb2-Nc4 and all Black pieces would like to be able to use the c5-square or the c-file.   The doubled pawns also prevent Black from enjoying the d5 square. Our queen can also do a lot of damage from g3 and I find it very difficult for Black to defend. }
13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. Bxb5 cxd4 15. Rc1
{ It's not easy to get rid of the pin. We were threatening to take on c5, but now we can use the file too. }
*

