[White "Transpositions"]
[Black "Transpositions"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this chapter I will talk about the possible transpositions and common move orders. I have also included a brief Content Guide. }
1. d4
{ 1.Nf3  Nf6  2.c4   2.g3!?  This is the King's Indian Attack. Many black players who are queen pawn players--especially those who also know the French--will play Nf6-e6-d5 and allow transpositions to the Catalan.  2...e6  3.Bg2  d5  4.O-O  Be7  5.c4!?  If the moves 3...b5 or 4....b5 annoy you when you play the Catalan without playing an early c4, this is a useful move order for you. At the price of analyzing 5...d4, we avoid many black options against the Catalan.  2...e6  3.g3  d5  4.d4  This is the most common move order starting from the Reti @@StartBracket@@1.Nf3 and 2.c4@@EndBracket@@ and allows you to go for the Catalan and avoid variations in which Black plays d4. The best thing about this transposition is that you will not have to learn anything beyond the scope of this course! }
1... Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ 3...d5  4.g3  Be7   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend to be especially aware of 5.... a6 and 5. ... c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6. Ne5 as they are both quite critical. By having many shared ideas, you will also find it more enjoyable to learn them at the same time. 5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing against them without being fully prepared.  Finally, 5 ...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last.   The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after 5...a5 6. Bg2 to keep in mind the option 6....dxc4 which transposes to chapter 15..   4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.  5.Bg2  From this point on, the festival of transpositions and possible move orders multiplies.   To keep some important ideas:   - In case Black plays a quick Nbd7, Qd3 is a quite frequent idea  (both with or without castling)  .   - The alternatives to 6. O-O I consider very important to make a smooth transition to the main lines.   The huge number of popular and complex lines starting with 6. O-O dxc4, especially with 7. ... b5, incline me to recommend that you have a look at the alternatives first so that you can practice the Catalan without fear of not remembering everything. Another important detail is the different move orders in which the closed Catalan is reached @@StartBracket@@with 6. Qc2 and 6. Nc3 we differ slightly from the main variations I recommend@@EndBracket@@. In practice it will give you more options after 6. O-O c6/Nbd7.   Another reason why I decided to add alternatives is so that you can also understand White's different plans and, who knows, also use that vast knowledge to be able to play some games with Black.  5...O-O  6.O-O  dxc4  As I make special mention in the chapter dedicated to it, I think it is important that here we know about  7.Ne5  or some other alternative. If you like the alternative 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4, then starting with 7.Qa4 is also a good move order as you avoid 7. ... b5. Many Grandmasters have been recently choosing this option. The main line with  7.Qc2  a6  8.a4  seems very comfortable for White to me and also quite easy to remember.   3...c5  4.d5  From my own experience playing with Black, if you have never played this type of positions with White, you should be quite familiar with the chapters in which the Benoni and the Bluemenfeld are explained; they are quite complex and unique positions.   If you play against a better opponent and surprise him by playing the Catalan, he could very well choose c5 to complicate the game and take advantage of the fact you have no experience in these positions. For example, a month before I wrote these lines, I played precisely this setup with black in a tournament game.   3...b6  4.g3  One of the most important variations that occurs when playing 3. Nf3 is the Queen's Indian. In the chapters about the Queen's Indian you should be alert mainly to the c5-break, the Nc3-Ne4 reaction and the numerous move orders available for Black.   In general, I consider there is fairly low risk here and that the positions you reach are quite intuitive and simple after a few moves, just be careful not to get confused by move order tricks by the black bishops!   3...a6  I recently found this 'Anti-Catalan' move order and it is quite important for you to have a quick look at this chapter. In this case general knowledge about the Catalan is useless and you could end up playing a difficult game very quickly. This is a very short and specific chapter in which we play some positions more typical of the Queen's Gambit Declined than the Catalan. }
4. Nbd2
{ This is the only time in the course that we cover the check with the knight. It is easy to remember because in this move order we do not want to play g3. In this variation I would recommend to be specially aware of the different possible captures on d2 and plans depending on how Black plays. Sometimes the dark-squared bishop stays inside the pawn structure and sometimes it develops out of the pawn structure. }
