{ Capturing on c6 would help Black to develop his queenside pieces. } 10. b3
{ As we will see in many variations in the Catalan, we prefer to sacrifice the pawn and take advantage of the fact that Black's queenside is very cramped. }
10... cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Nc3
{ We want to take on f6 and prevent the freeing c5-push. } 12... Nbd7 13. Bg5
{ 13.Bxc6  Qc8  Without control of the long diagonal and with Black fully developed, we would suffer quite a bit in this position.   13.Nxc6  Bxc6  14.Bxc6  Rc8  Once again, we will have to give up our beloved Catalan bishop in exchange for nothing. }
13... Rc8 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Bxe4 h6 18. b4
{ While Black's position is very solid, it is quite unpleasant not to be able to get the bishop out. Many endgames of this style can be won, since the b7-bishop is excessively clumsy.   Unlike other passive positions, Black cannot wait doing nothing. After f4 and Qc3, a plan consisting of Rd2-g4-h4-g5 would be reasonable, as we will strengthen our dark squares. }
