8... b5 9. Ne5 Nd5 10. b3
{ This typical method is not only good to pressure a pawn on c6, but the square itself too! }
10... cxb3 11. axb3 Bb7 12. Ba3 { Exchanging the main defender of c5. } 12...
Bxa3 13. Nxa3
{ Ok, our a3-knight is far away from c5 now, but the weakness is not going away and our Queen can do damage from there too. }
13... Nd7 14. Nc6 Bxc6 15. Qxc6
{ Black is objectively fine, but White's pieces are very annoying, and it seems to be an interesting try, in my opinion. In fact, Dubov beat Vidit from this position. }
