5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2
{ I go for Qc2 before  7.Ne5  because, in general, there is much more play. Although I think it is playable from time to time, Ne5 tends to lead to positions with a lot of initiative by Black and advantages that are very difficult to materialize with White.   On the one hand, White aims to capture on c4 and strengthen his strong center and the bishop on g2. Black aims to challenge the h1-a8 diagonal and tries to prevent white from expanding comfortably with e4. }
7... a6 8. a4
{ We want to avoid b5 and Bb7. The main advantage for Black is that this weakens the b4-square and makes it very difficult to generate counterplay on the queenside after an a5 by Black. It also guarantees a square such as b4 for the knight on b8. These are the reasons why Black plays a6 first and not 7... Bd7 directly. }
8... c5
{ Once the a6 and a4 moves are included, this option is more attractive for Black. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qxc4
{ 10.Nbd2  is not as accurate due to the variation  10...b5  11.axb5  Bb7  12.Nxc4  Be4  this is a very common theme in the Catalan; black forces the queen from the ideal square on c2 to capture on b5. }
10... b6
{ Here we see the great usefulness of inserting a6-a4: Black gets the extra square on a7 for the rook and can quickly challenge the diagonal. }
11. Ne5 Ra7 12. Nd3
{ In the Catalan White can often win simply by putting the pieces on their ideal squares. Having the knight on d3 defended by a pawn on e2 and the bishop on g2 being totally free is quite a deadly duo as it dominates practically all the central squares. }
12... Be7 13. Bf4 Bb7 14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. Na3
{ I prefer White's position. We will put the rooks on d1 and c1 and the constant threat on a6 in addition to the control of the files will force Black to be very precise in order to stay in the game. }
