7... a6 8. a4
{ We want to avoid b5 and Bb7. The main advantage for Black is that this weakens the b4-square and makes it very difficult to generate counterplay on the queenside after an a5 by Black. It also guarantees a square such as b4 for the knight on b8. These are the reasons why Black plays a6 first and not 7... Bd7 directly. }
8... Nbd7 9. Nbd2 b6
{ Again, Black tries to fight for the diagonal and we continue with the usual reply. }
10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5
{ If White plays  11.Bxa8  Black gains sufficient counterplay by capturing the pawn on d4. }
11... Nd5 12. Qxc4
{ This attack pattern with White's e5-pawn against Black's e6 pawn and the queen on g4 is a classic of many positions and variations. Once the knight moves from d2, we threaten Bh6 and can continue with moves like h4, winning the option to play Bg5. }
