5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 a6 8. a4 Bd7 9. Rd1
{ We delay the capture on c4 in order to generate future threats with d5. }
9... Bc6 10. Nc3
{ Black has to react, otherwise after e4 he will have no space to develop his pieces. }
10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Nc6
{ After  11...c6  12.Ne4  White achieves the classic Catalan advantage of the bishop pair. }
12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. a5
{ We want to take advantage of the triple pawn structure and put the rook on c4. I think it is an interesting attempt, since many black players could feel uncomfortable navigating this structure. }
13... Rb8 14. Ra4 Rb4 15. Na2 Rxa4 16. Qxa4 Qb8 17. Qxc4
{ Objectively, this is dynamically equal. Although the c6 pawn is weak, generating a sufficient attack and at the same time defending the b4 pawn is very difficult. However, White has managed to win in two games, so it can be an interesting try. }
