8. a4 b4
{ This move forces us to enter a tremendously complex variation, whether we want to or not. }
9. Ne5
{ This move used to have a bad reputation and is disliked by the computer at low depths, but at higher depths modern engines show a way to maintain an advantage. We do have to memorize some forcing lines here, but the resulting positions all lead to an advantage for White. }
9... Nd5 { 9...c6  10.Nd2  Qxd4  11.Ndxc4  Black's position collapses. } 10.
Nd2
{ A very important move that will allow our b1-knight to quickly come into play. }
10... c5 11. dxc5 Bxc5
{ 11...c3  12.bxc3  bxc3  13.Ne4  Qc7  14.Nd3  Bb7  15.Nd6  with a winning position because taking on d6 leads to a loss of material for Black after:  15...Bxd6  16.cxd6  Qxd6?  17.Ba3  . }
12. Ndxc4 Ba6 13. Be3
{ If we had taken the pawn with our e5 knight on move 10, we would have a similar position, but with the knights on c4 and b1. Here White is practically winning. }
