1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7
{ 4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after  5...a5  6.Bg2  keep in mind the option of  6...dxc4  , which transposes to chapter 15.   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend being especially aware of 5...a6 and 5...c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6.Ne5 as they are both quite critical.   By having many shared ideas, you will also find that it is more pleasant to learn them at the same time.   5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid, and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing them without being fully prepared.   Finally, 5...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last. The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 Bd7
{ Without the inclusion of the moves a6-a4 this maneuver to challenge the Catalan bishop diagonal loses strength. Black will not be able to enjoy the square b4 and we will have more flexibility on the queenside. }
8. Qxc4 Bc6 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Qd3
{ Black was threatening Nb6 followed by Nbd5, challenging our control over the center and the e4 square. With this move, we prevent that, and Black will have trouble finding a good move.   The only thing we should keep in mind is that if we play  10...--  11.e4  , Black will immediately reply with  11...Nc5  and we lose the e4 pawn. }
10... Bb4
{ Black insists on fighting for the central squares.   After  10...Nd5  11.Nxd5  exd5  12.Bf4  followed by Rfc1, the bishop on c6 will be unable to move. We will play for Ne5 and increase the pressure along the c-file. }
11. Bf4
{ I like this approach to the position. We just want to finish our development and enjoy our space advantage in the center. Unlike the main line with a6-a4, the queenside is more open, which is actually an improvement for us. }
11... Bxc3 12. Qxc3
{ It is often good to capture towards the center, in order to have more central control, but after  12.bxc3  Be4  followed by Rc8-c5, Black is controlling the light squares and has a very easy game. With Qxc3, we want to make use of the half-open c-file. }
12... Nd5 { When we have limited space, it is advisable to swap pieces off. }
13. Qd2 Nxf4 14. Qxf4
{ We can use our next moves to develop the rooks to the c and d-files, and the resulting positions should be very comfortable for White.   If  14...Nf6  we can slowly improve our position here with moves like Ne5, e3, h4 and g4. We can also start some kind of minority attack with a3 and b4 in some cases. Our total control over the center makes it easy for us to expand on the queenside or on the kingside. As we have seen in other variations, Black will have to defend passively, which is very uncomfortable. }
