2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7
{ 4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after  5...a5  6.Bg2  keep in mind the option of  6...dxc4  , which transposes to chapter 15.   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend being especially aware of 5...a6 and 5...c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6.Ne5 as they are both quite critical.   By having many shared ideas, you will also find that it is more pleasant to learn them at the same time.   5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid, and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing them without being fully prepared.   Finally, 5...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last. The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4 7. Qc2 c6
{ This variation has became popular in 2019 and is similar to  7...a6  . Black wants to develop the queenside with b5 and Bb7 once White captures on c4. }
8. Qxc4
{ White should capture on c4 directly to take advantage of the fact that Black cannot challenge the h1-a8 diagonal yet.   Starting with  8.a4  to avoid the advance of the pawn to b5 doesn't quite work because of  8...b6  9.Nbd2  Bb7  10.Nxc4  c5  and Black will have gained control over the diagonal without weakening his queenside too much. }
8... b5 9. Qd3
{ By defending d4, we threaten Ne5, but the main benefit of this move is that the usual reply by Black, the move Bb7, is inaccurate. Nevertheless, it has been played 5 more times than the correct Nbd7. Even at the highest level, by players like Duda and Andreikin.   Narayanan in his course recommends 9.Qb3, but for the above reasons I prefer the alternative. }
9... Bb7 10. Ne5 Qb6
{ The usual reply. Black is defending his queenside and trying to play his freeing c5-push.  Black has two major alternatives here:   10...Qc8  11.Be3  Black will not be able to free himself with c5, and we will reach a typical position which is very similar to positions we would normally get with a pawn down and strong compensation in our favor. In this case we're not even a pawn down though. We can continue with Nd2-Nb3 or Nd2-Ne4, increasing the pressure.   10...Nd5  11.Nc3  We want to take on d5 and take advantage of the fact that Black's queenside is exposed. If Black plays  11...Nd7  we will continue with  12.Nxd5  and he will have to recapture on d5 with  12...exd5  , because b5 is hanging, and we can start targeting the c6-pawn.   Black can instead play  11...a5  when after  12.Nxd5  Black can capture with the c-pawn  12...cxd5  , because he can answer  13.Bf4  and Rfc1, and Black has many problems to develop his queenside and defend his b5 pawn at the same time. Against moves like b4 or Qb6, defending b5, we can continue with e4 with great advantage. }
11. Be3 { We continue with our development and prevent Black's c5-push. } 11...
Rd8 { c5 is not an actual threat yet, so we can continue developing. } 12. Nc3
{ We continue improving our pieces to increase our control over the c5-square and at the same time press the kingside. Our total control over the center gives us a big advantage. }
12... c5
{ We should always check if the pawn break works!   12...Nbd7  loses on the spot due to  13.d5!+-  the knight will make it's way to c6 and the open diagonals will give us a big advantage. }
13. dxc5 Qc7
{ Taking on  c5  was impossible because  13...Bxc5  14.Bxc5  14...Qxc5  would abandon the defense of the rook on d8. }
14. c6
{ A brilliant in-between move! The queen cannot be captured because of cxb7. }
14... Nxc6 15. Qxb5
{ Thanks to the strong Catalan bishop pinning the knight on c6 we will obtain a very favorable position. }
15... Nxe5 16. Qxb7 Qxb7 17. Bxb7 Rab8 18. Ba6 Rxb2 19. Rfb1
{ We will first try to trade a pair of rooks and after that we will have an important strategic resource at our disposal: the bishop pair, in an open position and with pawns on both sides of the board. }
