{ This variation has became popular in 2019 and is similar to  7...a6  . Black wants to develop the queenside with b5 and Bb7 once White captures on c4. }
8. Qxc4
{ White should capture on c4 directly to take advantage of the fact that Black cannot challenge the h1-a8 diagonal yet.   Starting with  8.a4  to avoid the advance of the pawn to b5 doesn't quite work because of  8...b6  9.Nbd2  Bb7  10.Nxc4  c5  and Black will have gained control over the diagonal without weakening his queenside too much. }
8... b5 9. Qd3
{ By defending d4, we threaten Ne5, but the main benefit of this move is that the usual reply by Black, the move Bb7, is inaccurate. Nevertheless, it has been played 5 more times than the correct Nbd7. Even at the highest level, by players like Duda and Andreikin.   Narayanan in his course recommends 9.Qb3, but for the above reasons I prefer the alternative. }
9... Nbd7
{ Preventing Ne5 before developing the light-squared bishop is probably the most precise way to continue for Black. }
10. Bg5 { We now threaten to play Ne5. } 10... Bb7 11. Ne5
{ This move is a novelty. In general, we do not want to trade queens and recapture on d3 with the e-pawn, but in this case, White is in time to keep an eye on Black's long-announced c5-push. }
11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5
{ The best continuation. Black is still aiming to play c5, but has to defend b5 first. }
13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nd2
{ The knight is heading for e4, where it will eye the important c5 and d6 squares. }
14... Qc7
{ Black's idea is to gain a tempo by threatening the e5 pawn. If we spend a move to defend it, Black will be able to play c5. }
15. Nb3
{ We give up the pawn, but we do secure the c5-square for our knight. This will restrict Black's light-squared bishop and the activity of Black's rooks.  Our next moves are aimed at increasing our control over the c and d files and to prevent any attempt by Black to activate his pieces. }
15... Qxe5 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. Qd2
{ In exchange for a pawn, we have a huge positional advantage and the position is easier to play for us. Our rooks will go to the center and, if there are no direct threats, we will make improving moves like h4 and Bf3 that will create problems -what kind of problems will these two moves create?- for Black, because his position is extremely passive.  The knight on d5 has nowhere to go, and White will always be able to attack it with e4. Besides, the bishop on c8 has no more promising squares, the rooks can't challenge any file because they're not connected. Once Black has exhausted joker moves such as h6, he will have to come up with a plan to improve his pieces, which isn't easy at all. }
