[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Catalan Opening, Main Line - Alternatives to 7.Qc2 "]
[Black "7.Qa4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3
{ The first big question this course raises is: What is the benefit of playing 3. Nf3 and not 3. g3?. I will go step by step.   1. The main reason for this move order is that I consider 3. g3 c5 to be very playable for Black. The Benoni Variation has been my main weapon against d4 from the age of 12 to 16-17, and I got especially good results against the 3. g3 variation. In fact, I must admit that after Avrukh's book on the Catalan for the white pieces made 3. g3 fashionable again, I returned to the Benoni as Black against that setup and had very good results.   The bishop on g2 does not coordinate very well with the rest of the pieces and plays a secondary role. In contrast to the main lines of the Catalan, the positions are extremely unbalanced, and it is very difficult to keep 'control'. Benoni's variations work for very specific reasons, have no 'rules of thumb' and are chaotic. A player can easily get lost.   The Catalan is characterized by positions with initiative and by play with general concepts  (strong bishop on g2, fighting for the center, control of weak squares)  that are repeated throughout the course. If you wish to explore the black possibilities further, the Re8 and Bf5 variation of the Benoni discussed in Narayanan's course would seem to me a very good answer.   Reti players 1. Nf3 with 2. c4 have more pleasant transpositions to our 1. d4 lines. In an era characterized by the constant change of repertoires and openings, playing 3. Nf3 allows us to began with a Reti move order or even with 1. d4 and 2. Nf3 if we want to avoid aggressive lines like the Benko   1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  b5  and have a more flexible reply to critical lines such as the King's Indian and the Grunfeld. @@StartBracket@@1.d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6@@EndBracket@@.   For the small price of avoiding the Queen's Indian, we are also forced to enter fully into most of the critical variations against 1.d4, and we totally lose the flexibility with the move order. The initial idea of the course was to discuss the subtleties of each move order, but its scope and nuances that had to be kept in mind would have made it too long. }
3... d5 4. g3 Be7
{ 4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after  5...a5  6.Bg2  keep in mind the option of  6...dxc4  , which transposes to chapter 15.   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend being especially aware of 5...a6 and 5...c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6.Ne5 as they are both quite critical.   By having many shared ideas, you will also find that it is more pleasant to learn them at the same time.   5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid, and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing them without being fully prepared.   Finally, 5...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last. The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4
{ In this chapter we will take a walk through the alternatives to  7.Qc2  . It is very important to know the main alternatives in order to elaborate an adequate repertoire. Many times it can save us in a game when we are surprised or against a player who we think that his style does not work well in that variation. }
7. Qa4
{ This variation allows us to dodge main lines such as a6-a4 or more forced lines such as 7... b5. The main virtue for Black is to counter the a8-g2 diagonal. Ne5 can be a good alternative against more ambitious players with Black. }
7... a6
{ Grigorov proposes  7...b6  and there it would serve us by transposition, after  8.Ne5  , the exposed as an alternative in the variation 6...dxc4 7...a6. The only difference would be that after 10.Bf4 Black has the extra option Ba6 and after 11.Nc3 the computer proposes g5 to avoid Bf4 to the next move.  There I simply propose 12.Qc2 and after 12...Nd5 13.Bd2 and in exchange for not winning back one of the pawns, Black will have to deal with the weakness of g5. It seems to me an inhuman position to play with black. }
8. Qxc4 b5 9. Qc2 Bb7
{ The battle revolves around whether Black can control e4 properly and whether he can play c5 in an advantageous way. }
10. Bd2
{ This move prevents Black's usual development with  10...Nbd7  due to  11.Ba5!  Rc8  12.b4  , blocking black's progress on the queenside. }
10... Be4
{ Black seizes the opportunity to push our Queen away to a sub-optimal square. }
11. Qc1 Nc6
{ 11...Bb7  This curious retreat is the main move and has been played more than 1800 times! Black pre-empts the Nc3 threat and leaves the queen on a less than ideal square interfering with the connection between his rooks.  12.Bf4  In view of this repetition, I propose the move 12. Bf4, with similar ideas to 10. Bf4. }
12. Be3 Rc8 13. Rd1 Na5 14. Nbd2
{ If you now undo the moves you will see that we have been 'forced' to play the main ones. The knight on a5 is a bit out of position and it won't be easy to play c5 properly because of the exposure of the queen on the d-file and the control of the square itself... Starting with Ne5, we can then relocate the rest of the pieces. }
