urse was to discuss the subtleties of each move order, but its scope and nuances that had to be kept in mind would have made it too long. }
3... d5 4. g3 Be7
{ 4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after  5...a5  6.Bg2  keep in mind the option of  6...dxc4  , which transposes to chapter 15.   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend being especially aware of 5...a6 and 5...c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6.Ne5 as they are both quite critical.   By having many shared ideas, you will also find that it is more pleasant to learn them at the same time.   5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid, and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing them without being fully prepared.   Finally, 5...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last. The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O dxc4
{ In this chapter we will take a walk through the alternatives to  7.Qc2  . It is very important to know the main alternatives in order to elaborate an adequate repertoire. Many times it can save us in a game when we are surprised or against a player who we think that his style does not work well in that variation. }
7. Ne5
{ As we will see throughout the course, this move appears on countless occasions, and here it became the main line for a long time at the elite level. It is currently considered very solid for White, and I think it is a good alternative to play from time to time.   Another positive effect of preparing alternative lines is discouraging opponents by playing certain variations. In this case, if your future opponent sees that you have played Ne5 and know it well, he may vary his normal repertoire. In fact, it happened to me with Peter Leko.   He had been playing the Catalan with Black for 15 years in a row, and against me, he changed and went for a Grünfeld precisely because I played this variation.  As a special mention in the chapter dedicated to it, I think it is important that we know here 7.Ne5 or one of the other alternatives.   If you like the alternative variation with  7.Qc2  a6  8.Qxc4  , It's also a good move order to start with  7.Qa4  , so you avoid each other 7... b5. Many Grandmasters have opted for this option recently.  The main line with  7.Qc2  a6  8.a4  I find it very comfortable for white and quite easy to remember. }
7... c5
{ Black tries to simplify everything in the center and hopes to be in time to develop his exposed queenside. It's quite a recurring theme, but as always I think that Black is required to play very precisely while we develop our pieces very comfortably and generate a great number of threats. }
8. dxc5 Qc7 9. Nxc4 Qxc5 10. b3 Rd8 11. Nbd2 Qc7 12. Bb2
{ White's play is very comfortable and we only have to worry about placing the pieces in their best squares possible. We start first with a3-b4-Rc1, winning space on the queenside. Then, the second part of the plan, the move Qe1 followed by Nb3 will give us a complete control on every queenside break and will highlight Black's lack of space and the precarious situation of the queen on c7. }
