5. Bg2 O-O
{ The evolution of chess theory does not follow the same guidelines as it did 20 years ago. The playing strength of today's engines gives us answers understandable to a human  (not based exclusively on brute force and calculation)  and with a high degree of reliability in a matter of minutes.   Therefore, I consider it necessary to give a few alternatives to the main line  6.O-O  . They have a very low cost of time and allow us to avoid many variants that at a particular level can bother us, since it is feasible not to remember everything or prefer to dodge a little the main options.   A personal recommendation for the management of this course would be to start with some of these less ambitious but playable variations than 6.O-O, and as we progressively absorb the knowledge of the main lines, we can dare with 6.O-O.    Realistically, at this point in the opening we should already know very well Black's alternatives with 4.... dxc4. }
6. Nc3
{ With this move, we intend to pre-empt 6... dxc4 and avoid most of the critical lines. }
6... Nbd7 { Black tries to take on c4 and play Nb6. } 7. Qd3 b6
{ 7...c6  8.O-O  b6  9.b3  Transposes to chapter 7.. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Black wants to trade a pair of pieces before going for a fixed pawn structure. In this case, I prefer to not trade on d5 and play for the expansion with e4.   I think Black has enough counterplay in case of  9.Nxd5  .  As proof of this, I will say that I started this position with Black against a 2600 player.   If  8...exd5  9.O-O  Again we enjoy the advantageous structure typical of the Queen's Indian. }
9. O-O Bb7 10. Rd1
{ The direct  10.e4  loses a pawn after  10...Nxc3  followed by Nc5. } 10...
N7f6 { Black pre-empts the e4-push. } 11. Nxd5 exd5
{ 11...Bxd5  12.Bf4  Black will be able to play c5, but we will play for Rac1-Ne5 and our queen will go to f3 in the future. The c6-square will always be weak and could help us to gain a nice advantage.   In addition, Nd3 will also allow us to fight for the c-file if necessary. Finally, I like this type of positions because they are almost risk-free. }
12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Rac1
{ We intend to play Ne1 followed by Qc2-e3-Nd3. This is aimed at neutralizing Black's counterplay with c5, and we can aim to expand ourselves on the queenside with b4.   If Black tries to answer with a quick c5, it will be difficult for him to do as our g2-bishop will be already putting pressure on d5. }
