5. Bg2 O-O
{ The evolution of chess theory does not follow the same guidelines as it did 20 years ago. The playing strength of today's engines gives us answers understandable to a human  (not based exclusively on brute force and calculation)  and with a high degree of reliability in a matter of minutes.   Therefore, I consider it necessary to give a few alternatives to the main line  6.O-O  . They have a very low cost of time and allow us to avoid many variants that at a particular level can bother us, since it is feasible not to remember everything or prefer to dodge a little the main options.   A personal recommendation for the management of this course would be to start with some of these less ambitious but playable variations than 6.O-O, and as we progressively absorb the knowledge of the main lines, we can dare with 6.O-O.    Realistically, at this point in the opening we should already know very well Black's alternatives with 4.... dxc4. }
6. Qc2
{ We pre-empt the defense of the c4-pawn.   This is the second most common move after  6.O-O  . }
6... c5
{ The main reply. Black takes advantage of the fact that we have moved the queen  too early to try to challenge our pawn center. }
7. O-O
{ Black has to justify this central tension, otherwise we will simply continue with Rd1 and put the second player in trouble. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 e5
{ 8...Nc6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  This pawn structure is very similar to that in the Grünfeld. However, in this case, Black cannot easily take advantage of his central majority and our game is much more comfortable. After Rd1-Nd2-b3-Bb2-e3 we can try to activate our knight via f3-e5 or simply play on the c-file. }
9. Nf5 d4 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. b4
{ Black has built a strong center, but, in return, he has given up the bishop pair and the possibility for us to expand on the queenside. }
11... Be6 12. Nd2
{ We take advantage of the fact that Black cannot already take on b4, in this case due to Rb1. }
12... Rc8 13. Qd3 Nc6 14. b5 Na5 15. Ba3 Qd7 16. Rfc1
{ White's position seems to be more playable to my eyes. After Bb4 and e3, we will open lines for our bishops. Black should be very precise, and it must be taken into account that the second player has already made quite precise moves so far to get to this position. }
