{ I discovered this move order in a game against the strong Spanish Grandmaster and great theoretician Ivan Salgado. Black tries to carry out his business on the queenside quickly before castling, and this allows him to dodge some variations.   5...Nbd7  6.O-O  c6  7.Qd3  transposes to 5... c6. }
6. O-O b6 7. Nfd2
{ This move order allows us to play this peculiar move. Black cannot prevent our e4 in good conditions without requiring our queen's help which is always a good sign. }
7... Ba6 8. b3 O-O 9. e4
{ We gain space in the center, but there is still the unfinished business of the pinned c4 pawn. }
9... Nbd7 10. Nc3 Rc8 { Black insists on pinning the c4-pawn. } 11. e5
{ White has several alternatives to gain an advantage, but this seems to be very simple, in my opinion. }
11... Ne8 12. Re1
{ We have gained a lot of space in the center and Black has not achieved much. The bishop on a6 is very badly placed, we are very well-prepared against any break in the center, and we have several plans to improve the position depending on how Black plays.   Apart from the typical h4-h5, if they let us fix the structure with cxd5 cxd5 once our development is finished, we can freely attack the kingside. }
