5. Bg2 c6
{ I discovered this move order in a game against the strong Spanish Grandmaster and great theoretician Ivan Salgado. Black tries to carry out his business on the queenside quickly before castling, and this allows him to dodge some variations.   5...Nbd7  6.O-O  c6  7.Qd3  transposes to 5... c6. }
6. O-O Nbd7 7. Qd3
{ I really like the flexibility that this move gives us, even though it has been played in one out of a hundred games in this position. The knight can go to c3 or d2, we defend c4 and support a future e4. We also keep b3 in reserve if necessary. }
7... b6 8. b3 Ba6 9. Nc3
{ The great drawback of not inserting a5 is that b5 is much less effective. The bishop on a6 is not defended, so Black cannot play b4. }
9... Rc8 10. e4 O-O 11. e5 dxc4
{ 11...Ne8  12.a4  Not inserting a5 also makes Black's position more desperate. An attacking plan that I find beautiful after Rd1 and Qe2 is h4-Nh2-Ng4 going for h5-h6 or sacrifices on h6 in any case.   Black has no easy reaction in the center: c5 is always answered with an annoying Nb5, threatening the a7-pawn, that is taboo, since the a7-pawn would be exposed to the a1-rook and would be a fixed weakness. }
12. bxc4 Nd5
{ Black takes advantage that the c-pawn is pinned and threatens to break with c5 with dangerous consequences for our center if we do not play correctly. }
13. a4
{ A key move. We prepare to play Nb5 as a reply to c5 in a way that we are able to recapture with the a-pawn. }
13... Nb4 14. Qe2 c5 15. Nb5 Bxb5 16. axb5 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Qc7 18. Bb2
{ The knight on b4 is dangerously exposed and after Ra4 and Rfa1 the a7-pawn will fall. In addition, our bishop on g2 is very strong, and we have access to the c6 square. }
