{ 10...dxe4  11.Nxe4  Now that the pressure on c4 is gone, the bishop isn't doing anything on a6 anymore  (etc.)  . And we also gained a lot of space in the center. We have a clear advantage. We have a clear advantage. }
11. bxc4 e5 12. Ne2
{ We want to recapture on d4 with the e2-knight, because capturing with the f3-knight would allow Black to play Ne5. By playing Ne2, we will be able to maintain our control over the e5 square.   With  12.dxe5  We go for an extremely complex sequence for my taste, but it is important to know this e5-motif followed by Ng4 as, for example, it appears quite often in certain Semi-Slav variations with g3,  12...Ng4  13.Bf4  g5  we would go for an extremely complex sequence which is too complicated for my taste, but it's important to know the e5-motif followed by Ng4, because it appears quite often in certain Semi-Slav variations with g3. I would not recommend playing this position with either side, as it is very unbalanced. }
12... Qc7 13. Qc2 Rfe8 14. Bb2 exd4 15. Nexd4 Ng4 16. Nd2
{ This position has been played in 3 correspondence games, and I think it will be very difficult for Black to defend: there is no counterplay for Black on the queenside, we have more central control and our bishop on b2 is very dangerous. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Closed Catalan"]
[Black "Closed Catalan after 0-0 - 6...c6 7.Nc3 a5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7
{ 4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after  5...a5  6.Bg2  keep in mind the option of  6...dxc4  , which transposes to chapter 15.   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend being especially aware of 5...a6 and 5...c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6.Ne5 as they are both quite critical.   By having many shared ideas, you will also find that it is more pleasant to learn them at the same time.   5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid, and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing them without being fully prepared.   Finally, 5...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last. The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c6
{ In my opinion, this is probably the most flexible move order. Black will play b6 and will follow up with either Ba6, a5 or Bb7 depending on White's moves. }
7. Nc3 a5
{ These structures with a5 have not been played much, but they can be very annoying. Black has the a6 square available for the bishop and reserves the option of playing a4 later, making our queenside uncomfortable.   Black has also played  7...dxc4  here, but even though there are many positions in which this is interesting, here the capture is very bad. After  8.Ne5  we regain the pawn and Black will have gained nothing. This position has been played in almost 400 games and White scores 75%. }
8. b3
{ The alternative  8.Re1  requires a lot of in depth knowledge to play, and I don't think that this is worth the effort. }
8... b6 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. a3
{ If we play  10.Nd2  , here Black can continue with  10...b5  11.cxb5  cxb5  12.Nxb5  Qb6  13.Nc3  , with 10.a3 it doesn't work  13...a4!  would give Black a lot of counterplay. }
10... Bb7 11. Nd2 c5 12. e3
{ The b5-square will be very useful for us if Black attempts to create hanging pawns on the c and d-files. The b6-pawn will always be vulnerable, and Black's minor pieces will have trouble undermining our center. }
*

