{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bd6
{ This most common variant in the elite, I found it on the board against the strong player Aryan Tari in the Blitz World Cup. It was quite symptomatic that he could answer it simply by using the same concepts explained in this course in similar variants. }
5. Bg2 h6
{ Black's idea is to cover the natural development squares of the c1-bishop. }
6. O-O O-O 7. Qc2 b6 8. cxd5
{ We remain consistent in our approach to these pawn structures. Now Black will have to deal with the added cost of playing h7-h6 soon. }
8... exd5 9. Nc3 a6 10. Bf4
{ Since it was a blitz game I went with the standard plan.   Now  10.Ne5!  was very strong followed by Bf4, taking the rook to d1, the queen to b3 to put pressure on d5 and have pressure on f7 and e2-e4 options.  Black has trouble developing his pieces naturally. I will take advantage of the fact that this variant is very simple conceptually to show an example game with relevant strategic themes. }
10... Bb7 11. Rad1 Re8 12. Bxd6
{ Again, I opted for a very practical plan. Ne5-f4-e3-g4-g5.   Objectively it's better  12.Ne5  , but I want you to see the danger of my idea. }
12... Qxd6 13. Ne5 Nbd7 14. f4 b5 15. e3 Nb6 16. g4 b4
{ Black's latest moves have been aimed at making room on the e4 square for the f6 knight. }
17. Ne2 Ne4 18. g5
{ We sacrifice the pawn that is poisoned to open lines against the enemy king. }
18... f6 19. gxf6 gxf6 20. Bxe4
{ Again I embark on a somewhat speculative variant but very difficult to defend in blitz.   20.Ng4  It gave me a decisive advantage. }
20... dxe4 21. Ng3
{ I want to open the f-file and give way for my queen to the kingside. } 21...
fxe5 22. fxe5 Qc6
{ This move loses.   After the precise  22...Qd7!?  the machine gives even better options for black, but it's still very complex. }
23. Qg2 Qg6 24. Rf6 Qg5 25. h4 Qg4 26. Rd2
{ I defend the rook and the queen and prepare the final trick that I had seen in advance. }
26... Nd5 27. Nh5
{ The queen can't be captured by Rxg2+ and mate in a few moves and the f6-rook can't be captured by double either. }
27... Nxe3 28. Rg6+ Kh7 29. Rxg4 Nxg2 30. Nf6+ Kh8 31. Rdxg2 e3 32. Rg7
{ And Black gave up.   1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Alonso Rosell,A @@StartBracket@@2514@@EndBracket@@-Tari,A @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ Almaty 2022 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ "]
[Black "The 5.Nbd2 Alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nbd2 dxc4
{ One of the key differences of this course compared to the 3. g3 move order in the Catalan is that, if we play Nd2 against Bb4+, Black can capture right now on c4 and play b5 quickly before castling. This option seems to me substantially better, and Black's results are very good. The knight on d2 is a piece that is momentarily misplaced and that we will find it hard to justify with this move order.   5...O-O  6.Bg2  b6  This will lead us to a Queen's Indian position with almost no risk, but with a suboptimal knight on d2. We want to play b3-Bb2 and after Qc2 be alert for a good opportunity to play Ne5 and bring our bishops into play. }
6. Bg2 b5 7. O-O O-O 8. a3
{ I would recommend to choose this less common path. If they exchange the knight on d2 we will be happy to gain presence on the dark squares and to have exchanged a piece that slightly hinders our development. }
8... Bxd2
{ 8...Be7  9.b3  We go for the usual pawn sacrifice in return for a somewhat more comfortable development and for some initiative. }
9. Nxd2
{ Black will not be able to keep his b5-c6 stucture without paying a positional price. }
9... Nd5 10. a4 c6 11. e4
{ We start a quick attack on the kingside, e5-Ne4-Qg4-Bh6. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ "]
[Black "The 5.Nc3 Alternative #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3
{ In general, we play the Catalan to prevent the bishop pin on b4, very annoying, by the way, in the Nimzo-Indian. However, this move order leads to very unbalanced positions as it forces Black to take the c4-pawn if they want to have a good position, while we prioritize the development.   I think that 4 ... Bb4+ is the 'best' move, objectively. It is very solid, and White struggles to get playable positions. That is why I recommend you to pay attention to this move. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 c5
{ 6...c6  7.O-O  Playing like in the Closed Catalan with a bishop on b4 is much worse as Black loses flexibility. }
7. dxc5 Nc6 8. O-O Bxc5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. a3
{ Interestingly, this transposes to the Tarrasch Defense. The most comfortable plan for white is 10. a3, trying to expand on the queenside. }
