[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3
{ In general, we play the Catalan to prevent the bishop pin on b4, very annoying, by the way, in the Nimzo-Indian. However, this move order leads to very unbalanced positions as it forces Black to take the c4-pawn if they want to have a good position, while we prioritize the development.   I think that 4 ... Bb4+ is the 'best' move, objectively. It is very solid, and White struggles to get playable positions. That is why I recommend you to pay attention to this move. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6
{ The only relevant move in this position. Black prevents Ne5 and puts pressure on our center. }
8. a3
{ Once Black cannot play the plan that I consider to be 'easy', i.e., c5-Nc6, this move gains followers. }
8... Be7
{ Black has pre-empted the jump Ne5, so, in this case, it is not necessary to take prematurely on c3. }
9. e4 Na5 10. Be3
{ Black has a quite reasonable plan with a6-b5-Bb7, but in return, he has a certain momentary uncoordination of his pieces and White is in control of the center. }
10... a6 11. Qc2 b5 12. d5
{ 12.Ng5!?  This forgotten move by humans has a lot of poison and is a good example of how quickly can the position become difficult for Black if he is not careful. }
12... exd5 13. Rad1
{ Another alternative way of playing this position. Although it seems delicate for Black, as the other variation, I think Black is fine with some of the options he has.   However, the engines claim that the position is even, and they can be positions that one looks for to unbalance the balance or to try to make an opponent nervous who surely expected to give a check on b4, then return quietly to e7 and have a positional type of game. The results are quite good in this type of positions for our interests. Taking on d5 or advancing with e5, some knight jumps from f3, problems on the diagonals, the passivity of Black's pieces, are many ideas to take into account.   My personal recommendation would be to play some games with this type of positions to see how you do, maybe you will be surprised, and you will have a Mihail Tal inside you! I repeat that my goal with this course is to give you a main weapon and then provide you with 'gadgets' so that you can choose depending on the situation or tastes. }
