1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Nc3 Ne4
{ Also add a note on move 7... This curious option was played to me twice in the recent Blitz World Cup. We will see the idea of black quickly, and it has the main virtue that it is relatively simple, and it is white that must be somewhat precise. }
6. Qc2 O-O 7. Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 Na5
{ Herein lies the key to the variant. Black directly seeks to dominate the light squares, especially c4, and if white does not react properly it is possible that the bishop on c8 develops through f5 or a6 making a dent. }
10. Ba3
{ In the game against Nihal I found this creative sequence to prevent Black from settling on the c4 square. I had a very adequate reaction and I would say that this play is quite interesting, but in the subsequent complications I was quite inaccurate and quickly became worse. }
10... Re8 11. Ne5 f6 12. Bb4
{ With this intermediate we try to prevent the knight from going to the c4 square. }
12... c5
{ 12...c6  is somewhat finer, but after  13.Qa4  the position is still very complex and playable. }
13. Bxa5 Qxa5 14. cxd5
{ In this position after  14...exd5  15.Bxe4  could have fought for some advantage. }
