2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5
{ A move that often goes hand in hand with Bb4+. It defends the bishop and makes it difficult to capture. We do not want to activate the rook on a8 and we do not want an annoying Black pawn on b4. }
6. Bg2 O-O { 6...dxc4  7.a3  Transposes to the 4. ... dxc4 and Bb4+ chapter. }
7. Qc2 Be7
{ In modern chess, transpositions are very common. We go back to positions that occur in the 5 ... Be7 variation.   Although it is a bit different from what we have seen in chapter 10, the fact that Blck has played a very quick a5, although thematic, gives us some extra options that justify our queen being on c2. }
8. O-O c6 9. b3 b5 10. c5 Nbd7 11. Bf4
{ We want to avoid Black's only pawn break. } 11... Nh5 12. e3 g5
{ 12...Nxf4  13.exf4  Black is completely neutralized and we play the way we want. }
13. Bd6
{ We take very good advantage of the dark squares and Black will pay for his self-inflicted weakening. After Bd6 and Ne5, moves like e4 that open up the position can be deadly. }
