2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5
{ A move that often goes hand in hand with Bb4+. It defends the bishop and makes it difficult to capture. We do not want to activate the rook on a8 and we do not want an annoying Black pawn on b4. }
6. Bg2 O-O { 6...dxc4  7.a3  Transposes to the 4. ... dxc4 and Bb4+ chapter. }
7. Qc2 Be7
{ In modern chess, transpositions are very common. We go back to positions that occur in the 5 ... Be7 variation.   Although it is a bit different from what we have seen in chapter 10, the fact that Blck has played a very quick a5, although thematic, gives us some extra options that justify our queen being on c2. }
8. O-O c6 9. b3 b6 10. Bc3 Ba6 11. Nbd2 Nbd7 12. e4 Rc8 13. Rfe1
{ After Rad1, we can play the typical h4. If they react with c5, exd5 exd5 followed by Bh3 will put Black in a lot of trouble.   If Black still does nothing, I like the plan Bb2-Nh2-Nf1-Ne3. Catalan always encourages us to look for new ways to place the pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ "]
[Black "Black sidelines - 5...a5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 a5
{ A move that often goes hand in hand with Bb4+. It defends the bishop and makes it difficult to capture. We do not want to activate the rook on a8 and we do not want an annoying Black pawn on b4. }
6. Bg2 O-O { 6...dxc4  7.a3  Transposes to the 4. ... dxc4 and Bb4+ chapter. }
7. Qc2 c5
{ This move has become more and more popular among 2600+ GMs since late 2019. This is one of the few variations of the Catalan in which Black enjoys a lot of activity and takes the initiative. That is why we should play very carefully. }
8. cxd5
{ If  8.dxc5  Black would follow with  8...d4!  and although I think  9.Ne5  , is playable, I also think that Black has a lot of space and a dangerous initiative. It is interesting if you play it once with a surprise effect, but I think that 8. cxd5 is, more consistent. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Qb6
{ This move order is important. If cxd5 and Qb6, we could play O-O and Be3, and we have a huge advantage. After Qb6, we have to make the move e3, trapping our bishop on d2. }
10. e3 exd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6
{ Black has scored very well in this variation. In return for a delicate pawn structure, they have a lot of activity and counterplay along the b-file and especially by doing h5-h4  (a plan that exists practically in all variations of chess since the neural networks appeared)  .   The key lies in the fact that Black has few alternatives, so we have to play with some precision to avoid encountering the Black pawn on h4 and Black's pieces near our castling. }
13. Rc1 Be6
{ This line forces us to go into a very complex line.   13...Qb8  was the novelty used by Magnus Carlsen against Wojtaszek in the FIDE World Cup 2021. He pursues the same idea of pressing on b2 but with a subtle twist and seeking to move the queen to the kingside via e5.  Faced with such a special move, I propose a curious novelty  14.a3!  Bxd2  15.Nxd2  Be6  both h5 and a4 allow Qxc6 in a good version.   15...Bd7  16.Nb3  h5  17.Nc5  Bc8  18.h3  with great advantage, since we achieve both objectives, knight on c5 and avoid h4-h3.   @@StartFEN@@rq3rk1/3b1ppp/2p2n2/p2p4/8/PN2P1P1/1PQ2PBP/R1R3K1 b - - 2 16@@EndFEN@@  16...Rc8  17.Qc3  we prevent the queen from accessing e5  Qb6  18.Nc5  and we will continue to triple in the cfile. For me this is the ideal position profile in which we play quite freely.   Against  13...Rb8  there would now be a Qb6 that would prevent us from playing Nb3, but in this case it doesn't exist. }
14. Qxc6
{ 14.Nc3  We are not in time to play Na4-Nc5  14...c5  15.a3  Bxc3  16.Bxc3  d4  17.Be1  Rac8  We are following a game between two strong Grandmasters. I think Black has enough counterplay to compensate our bishop pair.   15.Na4  Qa7  The c5-pawn is taboo due to the pin on c8. Black is in time to prevent us from going for our desired blockade on c5. }
14... Bxd2
{ The key of the sacrifice! We struggle a bit developing our queenside. In return for the queen, Black has a rook, bishop and a bit of activity. }
15. Qxb6 Bxc1 16. Qd4 Rfb8 17. b3 Rb4 18. Qd3
{ 18.Qc3  worsens the situation, as after Rc8 we cannot prevent Bb2. } *

