13. Rc1 Rb8
{ Black replies to White's attack against c6 by increasing the pressure on b2.   13...Bd7  14.Nc3  h5  15.a3  Once Bd7, Na4 and Nc5 are played, we will gain a vital tempo by threatening Nxd7.   If Black retreats his bishop to c8, we will be able to play Qa4-Nb3, and both c6 and a5 are very vulnerable. This is a very difficult position for Black to handle. The delicate balance between having counterplay and having a lot of weaknesses can be decisive. }
14. Bxb4
{ Both in case of 13.Nc3 and  14.Nc3  , Black could be a little annoying with h5-h4. We want to play in a way that Black has to combine both activity and defensive play, and there is where the mistakes come up. }
14... Qxb4 15. b3 Be6 16. Nc3
{ This position has been played 4 times between GMs. After Ne2-Nf4, Black should go for Rfc8 and c5-c4 to justify his weak center, preventing us to blockade on c5 with Nd3.   Against such a plan, we can take on c4 and play Qd1, as three of the games show. It is very difficult to handle the isolated d5-pawn in practice. Black would definitely feel uncomfortable. }
