Bf4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6 12. c4
{ We want to take advantage of the initiative and activate our bishop on g2. }
12... Bb7 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Qc2
{ Once again, we take advantage of the sacrifice of the c5-pawn to play for the initiative. }
14... bxc5
{ 14...Nf6  15.Rac1  Black has a strong bishop on d5 but the hole on c6 together with how quick we put pressure with moves like Rfd1, Qa5 and Ne5  (or Bf1 depending on what the opponent plays, to avoid the bishop exchange)  , I find it complex to play with Black.   The tension between the pawns on b6 and c5 is weird, as Black does not want to open the d-file nor play b5, which would condemn the c6 square to be permanently weak, and we will have a healthy central pawn majority. }
15. e4 Bb7 16. Rab1 Rb8 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Ne5
{ The knight on c5 is in no-man's land, and the c7-pawn will always be weak. Besides, Black suffers quite a lot with his lack of space and how to manage his pieces.   We will go for Rfd1 or Rfc1 if the option arises, and then Be3 will ask an important question to the knight on c5. To give us an idea, if it moves away to a6, Nc6 would give us an almost decisive advantage on the light squares and the knight would remain in no-man's land. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ "]
[Black "Black sidelines - 5...Bd6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bd6
{ This retreat became fashionable 5–6 years ago, One of the main reasons is the fact that White's intuitive plan Bg5-Bf6-Nbd2-Qc2-e4 gives good play for Black.   5...Bxd2+  6.Nbxd2  It will be difficult for Black to have presence in the center. Usually, our bishop on d2 is annoying, but it is not the case.   A plan that I really like after Black plays b6 would be Rc1-Qc2 and taking on d5. When Black recaptures with the pawn, we can relocate our knight on c3, and then it will be an improved version of the extensively spoken Queen's Indian structure.   The weaknesses on the dark squares will allow White to generate pressure with a3-b4 and Ne5-f4 ideas. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. c5
{ We can punish BLack if he goes for this move order. } 8... Be7 9. Nc3 Ne4 10.
Bf4 Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6 12. c4
{ We want to take advantage of the initiative and activate our bishop on g2. }
12... bxc5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Ne5 Bb7 16. Rb1
{ Black's pieces are very clumsy. Our threat is Be3 and also some Qc2-Rfd1 ideas. Bh3 will always be an option in case of Rc8. Finally, Rb8 has a problem: Black cannot move the bishop away due to Rxb8 followed by Nd7. Besides, the c7-pawn is very weak and the knight on c5 is very exposed. }
*

