[White "7. Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ "]
[Black "Main Line - 7...c6 8.Bc3 Nbd7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7
{ In my opinion, this variation is the most solid one that Black can choose from. The bishop on d2 disturbs the normal development of White. In this case, Nbd2 is not as playable as with the order 3. g3, since Black has dxc4 before castling. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Bc3 Nbd7
{ 8...b5  9.c5  Black's expansion with b5 only makes sense if he manages to play a5-b4 and Ba6. In this case, Black is simply closing the queenside letting us free hands to expand on the center taking advantage of the fact that our pieces have a lot of space. }
9. Nbd2
{ This move order allows us to play b3 or b4 depending on how our opponent plays. }
9... a5 10. b3 b6 11. Qc2
{ Going for the typical Catalan expansion in the center with e4. } 11... Bb7
12. e4 dxe4 { If  12...Rc8  13.Rfe1  we get the ideal Catalan. } 13. Nxe4 c5
{ Black wants to challenge the diagonal. } 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ If  14...Nxf6  15.Rad1  Qc7  16.dxc5  The triad Knight + dark-squared bishop and the pawn structure a2,b3,c4 against a5,b5 is a known advantage in the Catalan.   We will aim to gain control of the d-file and endgames are always very comfortable as the Black pawn structure on the queenside has no flexibility and is very weak on the light squares,  16...bxc5  in this case we will aim to play Ne5 and put a rook on e2. The rook will have a double purpose: to facilitate the control of the d-file and at the same time to defend a2 in case of a4. }
15. Ng5
{ A very common tactical motif. It looks very spectacular, but in practice it is a simple piece exchange. We win the bishop pair.   15.Rad1  This is also possible and will lead to already mentioned  structures after Nxd4. }
15... Bxg5 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. Be4 cxd4 18. Bxd4 Nf6 19. Rad1
{ Comer Taking on f6 and on h7 later will not give us an advantage due to the fact that this is a structure in which our queenside pawns are fixed in the same color complex as our bishop and, in addition, there are opposite-colored bishops on the board. }
19... Rd7 20. Bc3 { Again, we have a more comfortable structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Catalan Opening, 4...Bb4+ "]
[Black "Main Line - 7...c6 8.Bc3 Nbd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Be7
{ In my opinion, this variation is the most solid one that Black can choose from. The bishop on d2 disturbs the normal development of White. In this case, Nbd2 is not as playable as with the order 3. g3, since Black has dxc4 before castling. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O c6 8. Bc3 Nbd7
{ 8...b5  9.c5  Black's expansion with b5 only makes sense if he manages to play a5-b4 and Ba6. In this case, Black is simply closing the queenside letting us free hands to expand on the center taking advantage of the fact that our pieces have a lot of space. }
9. Nbd2
{ This move order allows us to play b3 or b4 depending on how our opponent plays. }
9... b6 { 9...b5  10.c5  . } 10. b4 c5
{ This break has been tried by 3 Grandmasters, and will lead Black to serious trouble. }
11. bxc5 bxc5 12. Ne5
{ Black's center is very vulnerable, and the b-file will allow us to make the ideal development of the bishop on c8 difficult. }
12... Bb7
{ 12...Qc7  13.Rc1  In this case, after Nxd7 and dxc5, Black loses material. All our pieces are playing. }
13. Rb1
{ At least we can take the isolated pawn on d5 after moves like Nxd7 and cxd5, which will give us a very comfortable advantage. }
*

