{ If  10...Bb7  11.Qb3  Our plan is to play e3-Rfc1 and expand later on with a4. In this uncommon variation, we gaina lot of space in the queenside and later we can aim to break with b5, close the position with c5 or wait to the best moment to play Ne5.   The typical c5-break by Black can be answered with dxc5 and b5, creating a couple of strong passed pawns. }
11. Qb3 Ne4 12. Rac1 Nxc3 13. Rxc3
{ We have the base of our structure on dark squares, which is perfect for our Catalan bishop, and the rest of the pieces are ready to prevent any kind of counterplay by Black. We can improve our position with moves such as h4-a3 and, later, we can go for c5-e4 suffocating the Black bishops and taking advantage of the great amount of space we have. }
