9... exd5 10. Bd2
{ I do not think it is a surprise for anybody that this move is a novelty. We aim to play Bf4 and Nc3. }
10... Bb7 11. Nc3 Re8 12. Bf4
{ While our position is based on very simple principles established in the variations against the Queen's Indian, Black has a wide range of replies since he has a couple of extra tempi. }
12... Nf8
{ 12...c5  13.h4  is not a problem as we will take back with the e-pawn, and we aim to play Ne5. After h4, we can play Qc2-Rfd1 or ideas like Bh3.   12...c6  a solid option  13.Rc1  By transposition, we found a couple of games in which white won. An extra plan, apart from those already explained that allows c6, would be to go for Qb3-Rfd1-Ne5 and ideas with e4.   12...a6  13.Rc1  By transposition, I find two games in the reference. One of them was played by Shankland, in which he entered this type of structure with the knight on d2 and played Nb1! And Nc3.   Here we will continue with the plans that we will explain in more detail in the Queen's Indian chapter. We look for h4 to enable Bh3 and take good care of the bishop on f4. Then we will also play e3.   We have no problems if Black takes the bishop on f4  (for example with Nf8-Ne6)  since we will recapture with the e-pawn and have a strong outpost on e5 for our knight.   From that position we will have pressure on d5, the c-file and the e-file. It will be possible to continue with g4-g5 in case Black stays passive. }
