2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c5
{ Black's idea is to put pressure quickly in the center and hope for a quick development, taking advantage of the fact that that White should spend 2 tempi to capture on c4. }
6. O-O Nc6
{ This move increases the pressure in the center and here the main ideas of White diverge. }
7. Ne5
{ Once again, as it happens in the 5 ... a6 and 5 ... c6 variations, we make this move once again which quickly frees our bishop on g2 and allows us to fight for central dominance. For the moment we attack the c6 point and also enable to take on c4.   7.dxc5  followed by 8. Nbd2 is the most popular alternative and the one recommended by Narayanan. The problem I see is that the position is always close to equal after the queen trade, and recently I faced a very well-prepared player that I could hardly pose any problems.   dxc5 is the most popular variation, so it is to be expected that it is also the one against which they are better prepared against. That's why I recommend 7. Ne5, which leads to positions with more pieces and possible ways to create an unbalance. }
7... Bd7
{ This is the main reply. Black defends the c6 point and enables the move Rc8 to reinforce the busy c-file. }
8. Na3
{ The e5-square is very important in these structures, as it restricts the activity of the light-squared bishop and prevents Black's expansion in the center. That is the reason why we play Na3: to take on c4 and defend the outpost.   All this combines amazingly with the Catalan bishop on g2 and a later Bf4 to control the h1-a8 and h2-b8-diagonals. }
8... cxd4
{ If Black allows us to take on c4 without even losing a pawn in the process, it would be a complete success. Other moves would be answered in a similar fashion. }
9. Naxc4 Be7 10. Bf4
{ If we play the usual  10.Qb3  I have found that  10...Qc7!  in this move order gives Black a great position after a deep analysis.   It should also be noted that against an unprepared opponent it is a relatively dangerous move and that it is necessary to know it with Black. As we have already seen, our natural moves Qb3-Bf4-Rac1 require Black to be somewhat precise. }
10... Nd5 11. Nxd7 Nxf4
{ 11...Qxd7  12.Ne5  We get the d4-pawn back, and we enjoy a comfortable advantage as we have the bishop pair. }
12. Bxc6 { An important intermezzo to weaken Black's pawn structure. } 12...
bxc6 13. Nde5 Nh3+ 14. Kg2 Ng5 15. f3 Qd5
{ The queen occupies a very important square. } 16. e4
{ A very interesting concept of correspondence. Since Black was threatening f6, we have to react quickly and take advantage of the fact that the queen is exposed in the center. On the other hand, the knight on g5 has no jump available, so it is a pending issue for Black. }
16... dxe3 17. Qe2 f6 18. Rfd1 Qc5 19. b4 Qxb4 20. Nxc6 Qc5 21. N4a5
{ Black cannot castle as the e7-bishop cannot be defended once we attack the queen with Rac1-Nc4. All of our pieces coordinate, while Black's rooks and the g5-knight are totally useless. The attack will be withering the enemy king. }
*

