10... Rc8
{ This seems to me Black's best defense, as it reinforces the c6-point. } 11.
Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 d3
{ This move has only been played only in one elite game between two 2600+. Black wants to return the pawn in exchange for upsetting White's pawn structure. }
14. Qxd3 Qxd3 15. exd3
{ In general, isolating a pawn by ourselves is a bad deal, so we have to play energetically. }
15... b6 16. Bb7
{ We take advantage of the fact that the rook has a reduced room for maneuvering and, if it goes to the c-file, we will challenge it with Rac1 with a devastating entrance to the 7th rank in our favor. }
16... Rd8 17. Bc6+ Kf8 18. Rfc1 Bc5
{ 18...Rxd3  19.Ba4  The entrance on the 7th rank decides the game because the rook on h8 is passive.   18...Bd6  19.Bd4  Ke7  20.a4  We will have access to the 7th rank, and we will weaken Black's queenside. In general, this seems to me a quite good and risk-free endgame for White, and with a simple plan to follow. }
19. d4 Bd6 { 19...Bxd4  was impossible because of  20.Rd1  . } 20. Bxd6+ Rxd6
21. d5
{ A vital move. We get rid of our isolani and, after that, we will be able to take on d5 due to the fact that Black's back rank is weak. The resulting endgame is very annoying, practically for Black.   Our bishop is better than the knight because there are pawns on both sides of the board. The fact that we can infiltrate in the position via the c-file is also another plus. With perfect play by Black, the game should end in a draw, but reaching this far requires to be very precise. }
21... exd5 22. Bxd5
{ And we reach the superior ending, mentioned above after:  23...g6  24.Rc8+  Kg7  25.Rxh8  Kxh8  26.Bxf7  . }
