{ If we play the usual  10.Qb3  I have found that  10...Qc7!  in this move order gives Black a great position after a deep analysis.   It should also be noted that against an unprepared opponent it is a relatively dangerous move and that it is necessary to know it with Black. As we have already seen, our natural moves Qb3-Bf4-Rac1 require Black to be somewhat precise. }
10... Rc8
{ This seems to me Black's best defense, as it reinforces the c6-point. } 11.
Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Qb5
{ The move recommended by Christof Sielecki in Keep It Simple For Black. Objectively, Black should be fine, but it requires from Black precise play in a complex position in a practical game.   13...O-O  14.Bxd4  Once again we reach a comfortable position for White. We have the bishop pair, there are pawns on both flanks, and the play is easy and risk-free.   After e3-Qe2 we will bring the rooks to the center and depending on how Black plays, we can put pressure on the light squares on the queenside  (for example, Black may have played b6 to defend the queenside pawns from the harassment of our bishops, so the a6 square would be a good access point for our queen)  . }
14. Qxd4 O-O 15. Bf3
{ With this move we defend e2, we control more of the knight's jumps and we give the king an air that always comes in handy. On the other hand, we also depart from what Surya Ganguly contributed in his Lifetime Repertoire for Black, where he only comments 15.  e3 . }
15... Rfd8 16. a4
{ An annoying intermezzo that allows us to have pressure on b7 in view of eventual exchanges. }
16... Qa5 { Maintaining the threat on the e5-bishop. } 17. Qf4
{ This position still seems to me to be very favorable to White's interests. To show what is required of Black we will see that the following moves recommended by the engines are quite precise and difficult to justify in practice. }
17... Nd5 18. Qe4 f5 19. Qd3 Kf7 20. Qb3
{ We will activate our rooks and the play is still very rich. While Black has to continue to actively counter the effect of our bishop pair, we can continue to improve our rooks and be alert for pawn breaks like e4 or g4. }
*

