{ This is the main reply. Black defends the c6 point and enables the move Rc8 to reinforce the busy c-file. }
8. Na3
{ The e5-square is very important in these structures, as it restricts the activity of the light-squared bishop and prevents Black's expansion in the center. That is the reason why we play Na3: to take on c4 and defend the outpost.   All this combines amazingly with the Catalan bishop on g2 and a later Bf4 to control the h1-a8 and h2-b8-diagonals. }
8... cxd4
{ If Black allows us to take on c4 without even losing a pawn in the process, it would be a complete success. Other moves would be answered in a similar fashion. }
9. Naxc4 Rc8 10. Qb3 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bd6
{ Black prioritizes development and, apart from attacking the knight on e5, he wants to enable a possible central advance to consolidate the d4 pawn. }
12. Nxd7
{ 12.Bf4  would not have the same effect. Now Black could play  12...Bc6  comfortably. }
12... Qxd7 13. Rd1 e5 14. Bg5 Ng4
{ Against options that would allow us to take and double the pawns, we would enjoy a nice structural advantage and after e3 or Qd3-Be4 Black would struggle to defend his weak light squares.   The opposite-colored bishops and the major pieces, as we have mentioned in other chapters, are a very dangerous combination if there are weaknesses in the same color complex as the bishop. }
15. Rac1
{ We continue threatening b7 and we aim to control the open c-file before we take. }
15... O-O
{ Necessary. The king was very exposed and the rooks should be connected to keep control of the c-file. }
16. Qxb7 Qf5 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. h3
{ I like the idea of taking advantage of the course to show different tactical and strategic themes. The queen on f5 is overloaded. If he captures on f2, both the knight on g4 and the rook on c8 will be hanging. }
18... Rd8 19. hxg4 Qxg5 20. Qxa7
{ Although there is still a lot of work to be done, the two passed pawns and the opposite-color bishops guarantee suffering for Black. }
