12... Qxd7 13. Rd1 Be5 14. Qxb7 Qxb7 15. Bxb7 Rc7
{ Magnus recently played 16. Bf3, a good option, in my opinion. I also give an alternative plan. }
16. Bf3
{ Our goal would be to exchange at least a pair of rooks and then take advantage of the strength of both bishops. Once the access to the c-file is under control, we can bring the king closer and mobilize the pawns on the kingside. The idea would be to generate pawn tensions on both sides to maximize the effect of the bishop pair.   16.Ba6  In this line we have both bishops in the center, and we will look for a cautious expansion with b4-f4 and future pushes on the sides. Exchanging a pair of rooks would be ideal.   The endgame is quite promising. Black does not have much counterplay, as we block his central pawns on light squares, and he should be alert to prevent us from creating a passed pawn on the queenside. Both bishops allow us to dominate both flanks, and they restrict the access of Black's rooks to the open c-file. }
