Nxc3 15. Qc2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qc6+ 17. f3 h6 18. Bd2 Nd5 19. Rfc1
{ Putting a lot of pressure on the c-file. } 19... Qxc2
{ Here at Modern Repertoire against the Catalan Robert Ris for Modernchess in 2020 gives, instead of 19...Qxc2,  19...Ne7  20.Bb4  Qxc2  21.Rxc2  Nbc6  22.Bxe7  Nxe7  23.Rxc7  Nf5=  . However, following the philosophy of the position, after  20.Qb2  Qb7   o  20...Qd7  21.Nc5  Qc8  22.e4  I still find it very comfortable for white. In exchange for a pawn, we get a very strong knight, a bishop that flows through both f4 and b4 or a5, both ideal rooks, and a center that restricts enemy knights.  In case of Nd7 we would not want to trade knights and would still go for Nd3.  Also  20.e3!  would be very strong, as black will not be able to get rid of the pressure on the c file and will continue with both knights getting in the way. We are not interested in exchanging pieces, since the d3-knight and the d2-bishop make good use of the gaps in Black's position. }
20. Rxc2
{ The c7 pawn will fall. White has  the dominant position of the knight on d3 at his favor and Black has no safe  outpost for his knights. }
