{ After this move which aim is to keep the extra pawn, White  has two alternatives that to my eyes are very reasonable. }
10. Qc2
{ We admit the pawn sacrifice, but we continue developing our pieces and connecting the rooks. }
10... cxb2 11. Bxb2 Nd7
{ 11...Be7  This was played between two 2550+ human players recently,  but after  12.Rfd1  Nd7  13.Nd3  we transpose to 11... Nd7. }
12. Rfd1 Be7 13. Rac1
{ After finishing our development, the compensation is quite apparent. Black still struggles to develop the c8-bishop and the queenside, and we enjoy a great amount of space in the center. }
13... a5 { Black tries to gain some space. } 14. Nc5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qe8
{ Black's queen gets out of the pin in order to be able to  play b6-Bb7. } 16.
Nd3
{ The only game, a correspondence one, that features this position was won by White very strongly by bringing the knight to h5 followed by e4 and Nf6 with an unstoppable mate attack, which gives an idea of White's possibilities.   Apart from such an attack, Black still has a lot of problems defending his queenside and moves like c6 would doom Black's position as it leaves a hole on d6. }
