6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ We continue giving priority to our development and we threaten to recapture on c4. The trick in case of Bd2 would be Be7, attacking d4, and in case of e3 b5 the position becomes very unbalanced. }
7... Nd5
{ c3 is also under attack, but, once again, we prioritize our development. } 8.
O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Nxc4
{ The fact that Black has not castled allows us to do without the services of an entire rook without harmful consequences for our interests. }
10... Bxa1 11. Ba3 Qxd4 12. Nd6+ Kd7 13. Qb1
{ Black's king will not survive.   For example, you could continue with  13...Qa4  14.Rd1  we indirectly defend the bishop on a3 with the discovered check  14...Bd4  15.Qc1  we defend the bishop now from a3 and look for e3  15...f6  16.Be4  fine intermediate that threatens Bc2  16...Bb6  .   If  16...e5  17.e3+-  we will recover material and black will continue without having the safe king or development  17...Bxe3  18.fxe3  Kc7  19.Bc2  and now Black's position is destroyed while the entire queenside remains undeveloped.   @@StartFEN@@rnb4r/pp1k1ppp/2pNp3/8/q7/B5P1/P3PPBP/bQ1R2K1 b - - 5 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Kc7  15.Rd3!  and the threats of Nxf7-Bd6 together with Qxa1 decide. }
