[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c6
{ Black wants to play b5 and consolidate his extra pawn on c4. This line is mainly known as being an interesting way to unbalance. Both  6.O-O  and  6.a4  would be the main alternatives. However, for this course, we reply in an analogous way to 5. ... a6.   I consider that it is easier to remember a repetition if we more or less play similar plans each time. In the case of this course, Ne5 should be the most popular move. }
6. Ne5
{ We prevent b5, we activate our bishop on g2, and we go for taking quickly on c4. Again it seems to me a very good solution as it limits Black's tree of possibilities quite a lot and I especially like it because we avoid the more usual plan with b5. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3
{ We continue giving priority to our development and we threaten to recapture on c4. The trick in case of Bd2 would be Be7, attacking d4, and in case of e3 b5 the position becomes very unbalanced. }
7... Nd5
{ c3 is also under attack, but, once again, we prioritize our development. } 8.
O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Nxc4
{ The fact that Black has not castled allows us to do without the services of an entire rook without harmful consequences for our interests. }
10... O-O 11. Rb1
{ Black's pieces do not coordinate at all. Ba3 is a very strong threat, followed by the knight jump to d6. }
11... b5 12. Ne5 Qxd4
{ Attempting to simplify the position is not an option either. } 13. Qxd4 Bxd4
14. Nxc6 Nxc6 15. Bxc6 Rb8 16. Ba3 Rd8 17. Be7
{ This is how the Woman World Chess Champion Ju Wenjun won the game. The rook can't escape. }
