7... Nd5
{ c3 is also under attack, but, once again, we prioritize our development. } 8.
O-O Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Nxc4
{ The fact that Black has not castled allows us to do without the services of an entire rook without harmful consequences for our interests. }
10... b5 11. Bb2 Bxb2 12. Nxb2 Bb7 13. e3
{ White protects the d4-pawn and makes Nd3 possible. } 13... O-O 14. Nd3
{ Nd3 is the typical idea on that position, target c5 and e5 square, and followed by Rc1. }
14... Nd7 15. Rc1 Qb6 16. Nc5 Nxc5 17. Rxc5
{ White ended up winning the only game that has been played with this variation. I really like the h4-Qh5 plan and forcing a weakness with Be4 to be able to attack it with g4-g5 or h5. The bishop on b7 is totally out of play and our rook on c5 blocks and can attack on the queenside. }
