{ c3 is also under attack, but, once again, we prioritize our development. } 8.
O-O O-O
{ After  8...Bxc3  9.bxc3  Nxc3  10.Qc2  Black's position is collapsing on the dark squares.   The move  10...Qxd4  is bad because of  11.Nxf7  followed by Bb2. }
9. Qc2
{ At this point I give you two variations to choose from depending on the style you like. Qc2 tends to lead to very unbalanced attacking positions, while 9.Ne4  aims to play the typical b3 and positions with very good compensation for the pawn. }
9... b5
{ 9...Nb6  10.Rd1  Not having played b5 greatly restricts Black's queenside. We can calmly take the pawn on c4 and Black will not be able to react. }
10. a4 f6 11. Ng4
{ With this move we intend to play e4 and bring the knight on e3 to enhance a future d5. }
11... Qd7 12. e4 Nc7 13. e5 f5 14. Ne3 a6
{ After  14...Qxd4?  15.axb5  White is just better. } 15. Ne2
{ We continue with b3. The position seems to me very good for White, Black has a lot of problems to neutralize the bishop on g2 and there is no early development of the knight on b8. }
15... Bb7 16. b3 c3 17. h4
{ Once again, we go for this plan while Black can hardly move. } 17... Nd5 18.
Nxd5
{ Here we have a very curious approach, we will close the center and head into a kingside attack if black tries to keep the pawn on c3 alive. }
18... cxd5 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rxa8 Bxa8 21. Qd3 Rc8 22. Bh3
{ The passed pawn on c3 is very well controlled and all of a sudden all of our pieces aim at the black castling. After Kh2 we go for g4-Rg1-h5-Nf4 and I value our initiative very positively. }
