7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O Qd7 { The pawn on d4 is taboo, due to Bxb7 or Bxc6+. } 9.
e3 h5
{ It is always dangerous that Black can attack with h5-h4, but, as we will see, he will miss his light-squared bishop. }
10. Nd2 h4 11. Nxc4 Nd5
{ Black's dream is to play f5-g5 and bring the queen to h7.   11...hxg3  12.hxg3  Black is not mating us anytime soon - or ever... In this kind of situations is usually better to keep the tension instead of releasing it. }
12. a3
{ With a bit of cold blood, we see that Black's attack does not lead to anything, and we can continue with a3-b4. Re1 would be enough to avoid the mentioned plan with Qh7 and our attack will be faster. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Open Catalan, other options"]
[Black "5...Bd7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7
{ Black wants to immediately challenge the diagonal  and, at the same time, having the move b5 available to defend the pawn on c4. }
6. Ne5
{ Again Ne5 seems to me the most adequate option, as Narayanan also recommends in his course. We open the diagonal for the Bishop and at the same time, we want to recapture on c4 with the Knight. }
6... Bc6 { 6...Nc6  7.Nxc4  What Black has played does not make much sense. }
7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O Qd7 { The pawn on d4 is taboo, due to Bxb7 or Bxc6+. } 9.
e3 Rd8
{ Black wants to play e5, so we should move the queen away from the d-file.   9...O-O-O  10.Nc3  Once we open the b-file, our attack plays itself. We have a huge advantage.  If Black tries something like  10...Nd5  , we could continue with  11.Qe2  intending to take on c4. An important practical fact is that white scores 75% in more than 30 games. }
10. Qe2 e5 11. Qxc4 exd4 12. Qb5
{ An important move that forces Black to a lose another tempo with the rook. }
12... Rb8 13. Rd1
{ We aim to play Bxc6, forcing the exchange of queens and weakening the structure. Our follow-up is Rxd4. }
13... a6 14. Qc4 Bd6 15. exd4
{ Now Bxc6 would be a very weak move, as after bxc6 our kingside would be very vulnerable. Without exchanging queens, it is not so easy to exploit the doubled pawns. }
15... O-O 16. Nc3 h6 17. a3
{ In this variation I quite agree with Narayanan. White has a more comfortable position. We want to activate the rook via a2.   The idea of b4 is eventually to look for the break with a4-b5 and boost both bishops. We want to avoid that Black gets a blockade on the d5 square in order not to be left with the pawns on static dark squares. }
*

