{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 6. Ne5 Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. O-O Qd7 9.
e3 Rb8 { I found this peculiar secondary on the board this year 2022. } 10. Qe2
b5 11. b3
{ We want to develop our bishop from c1 to b2, so this option seems the most reasonable. }
11... cxb3 12. axb3 Rb6
{ The key idea of black. He now seeks to play a6 and thus his entire queenside is compact and defended. }
13. Bb2 a6 14. Rd1 Be7
{ Here I played e4 and got a bit better but didn't fully exploit the advantage. Then I discovered a fantastic plan that white can use here. }
15. e4 O-O 16. Nd2 Nb4
{ Here it would have been great to continue with 17. Nf1! and then Ne3-h4-g4 and we have central control and a very clear and easy plan to execute.  The knight on e3 also guarantees a reinforcement on light squares in case black seeks to break with c5 or e5 always having d5 as an option.   ½-½ @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Alonso Rosell,A @@StartBracket@@2564@@EndBracket@@-Suarez Garcia,C @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@ Linares 2022 }
17. Nf1 { Initiating the aforementioned plan. } *

