[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Open Catalan, other options"]
[Black "5...Nbd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nbd7
{ This move intends Rb8-b5 or c6-b5 and, at the same time, it anticipates our Ne5. }
6. O-O Rb8
{ 6...Nb6  7.Nbd2  We get the pawn back, and Black will notice that he has used several development tempi with Nbd7-Nb6 without succeeding in defending c4. }
7. a4 b6 8. Nfd2
{ With this curious move, we force Black to have a weird placed rook on b7 if he wants to challenge the diagonal. }
8... Bb7
{ 8...Ba6  9.Nc3  After Bc6 y Nb5 we will take on c4 and Black will be suffocated. }
9. Bxb7 Rxb7 10. Nxc4 Bb4
{ An attempt to take advantage of the b4 hole and pre-empt our central expansion.   10...c5  11.Nc3  Black is very late in development, which will allow us to gain a strong presence in the center after d5. The knight on c4 will be an ideal blockader and after Bf4 and Rad1 Black will have a lot of coordination problems. }
11. Nc3 O-O 12. Qb3 c5 13. Rd1 cxd4
{ 13...Bxc3  14.bxc3  a nice pawn center, some accessible squares, a clumsy rook on b7 and our pieces on ideal squares are the ingredients to ensure victory. }
14. Qxb4 dxc3 15. Qxc3
{ The control of the dark squares together with f3-e4 are a very good combination for this middlegame scenario in the Catalan. Black will never have well consolidated knights and the holes on d6 and e5 will be avenues of entry for the white pieces. }
*

