[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Open Catalan, other options"]
[Black "5...Nbd7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nbd7
{ This move intends Rb8-b5 or c6-b5 and, at the same time, it anticipates our Ne5. }
6. O-O c6 7. a4 a5 8. Qc2
{ In this case  8.Nfd2  was inaccurate due to  8...Nb6  and we will have to lose a very valuable tempo defending d4. }
8... b5
{ This variation is becoming popular recently. Black wants to defend the c4-pawn and hopes to neutralize the opening of the h1-a8 diagonal. }
9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd5 11. axb5 cxb5 12. Nc3 Qb6
{ Black leaves the d5-square to keep his pawn chain on the queenside. } 13.
Nxd5 exd5 14. Bxd5 Ra7 15. Qe4
{ 15.b3  seems attractive, as Black cannot capture due to the fact that the bishop on c8 is hanging, but after  15...Bc5!  16.bxc4  b4!  Black would have a decisive advantage due to the nice blockade and the two connected passed pawns that remind to the Noteboom variation. }
15... Bc5 { Black prioritizes development but loses a pawn in a forced way. }
16. Bc6+ Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Rxd7 18. Qa8+
{ 18.Qg4  has been quite a popular and successful attempt recently. Black has to play the important  18...Rf8  a novelty, so it seems like a reasonable attempt for our interests. But beware,  19.Qxg7  f6!  gives Black good play.   19.Bf4  a4!?  puts us in trouble in the medium/long term since we would lose a large part of the endgames if our initiative does not prosper.  Finally after coming back with   19.Qe4  now  19...h6!  and Black has the extra option of Ke7 before the check on  a8  , which it's not so clumsy. }
18... Rd8 19. Qxa5 Qc6
{ Black doesn't want to bring our Rook to a5, of course.   18...O-O  19.Qxb6  Bxb6  20.Kg2  we're ready to defend e5 with f4. }
20. Qa6
{ Black's Queen is their most active piece and the main defender of the queenside pawns, so we insist on trading it. }
20... Qxa6 21. Rxa6 O-O
{ 21...Kd7  22.e6+  we return a doubled pawn in exchange for a lot of activity. Black will have a hard time defending his exposed pawn structure, and our bishop on e5 will be very dominant.  We will intend to play Bf4-e5 and our dark squared Bishop will become a monster on e5 as Black's counterpart cannot easily contest due to our strong Rook on a6. }
22. Kg2
{ We will push our central pawn mass and the extra pawn will become evident. }
