1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 c5
{ This move has always fascinated me. Black voluntarily decides to move pawns away from the center! However, with time I understood that it restricts our queenside and can be a dangerous weapon. }
7. Bxb4 cxb4 8. Ne5 O-O 9. a3
{ We want to increase our power on the dark squares to accelerate our queenside development, and activate the a1-rook.   9.Nxc4  Nc6  10.e3  e5  This is the reason for 9. a3. It is always good advice to wonder what happens when facing the most forced reactions of the opponent. Black is just in time to break our strong center, and our lack of development is evident. }
9... Nd5
{ 9...bxa3  10.Nxa3  If they help us in this way, we will win much more quickly. }
10. Nxc4 b5
{ Again, Delchev in his publication in 2016 proposes another move such as  10...Qc7  after  11.Ne5  Nc6  12.Nxc6  bxc6  I consider that the resulting position is quite painful for Black and quite typical of correspondence for the pawn back on c6, but I also propose the following novelty  13.Nd2  with the simple idea of looking for Nb3.  I find it extremely difficult to play Black with the weak queenside pawns, and I see it as quite possible that we end up playing a 5vs4 pawns. }
11. Ne3 { The knight on e3 cannot take, as the rook on a8will be undefended. }
11... Bb7 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. e4 Bb7 14. O-O bxa3 15. Nxa3 a6 16. Nc2
{ We create a very well defended passed pawn, and we will neutralize the bishop on b7. Black's queenside mobility del is quite restricted, taking into account that the minor pieces get in each other's way. An eventual h4 and the knight on e3 will put the black queenside on alert. The 4 correspondence games that exist were quite tough for Black. }
