1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 a5
{ In this similar variation to the Bogo-Indian, Black defends the bishop and gains space on the queenside. In case the bishop is captured, this would also activate the rook.    A significant difference of the variation is that it facilitates the move b5, defending the recently captured pawn on c4, since the rook will not be so vulnerable to the bishop on g2. }
7. a3
{ This seems the most comfortable line for White. We force the development of the knight on b1. }
7... Bxd2+
{ 7...Be7  this move arises from the usefulness of a5 and a possible plan with b6. We will have the square a7 available for the rook  8.Qa4+  Bd7  9.Qxc4  Bc6  once again, we play like in the main variation, but White has not been compromised with the move a4. Therefore, we have a comfortable advantage with natural development as Black does not have the b4-square and our pawn structure is more flexible. }
8. Nbxd2 b5 9. b3
{ As is typical in the Catalan, we sacrifice a pawn and try to take advantage of the holes on the dark squares and also of our best pieces. }
9... c3 10. Nb1
{ We can see how important is to play a quick b3. Black does not have the resource b4 to consolidate his pawn chain. }
10... Bb7 11. Nxc3 b4 12. Na4 Nbd7 13. O-O O-O 14. Qc2 Be4 15. Qb2 Qb8 16. Rfc1
Qb7 17. axb4 axb4 18. Ne1
{ The c7-pawn will always be a weakness for Black, as well as c5. The pawn on b4 is quite exposed. We have a comfortable long-term advantage by taking advantage of the c-file.   Black's counterplay is rather scarce  (e5 does not solve the exposed problems)  and he must play passively, which is always more complicated to do. }
