9... cxb3 10. Qxb3
{ 10.Nxb3  would allow Black to develop his bishop out of the pawn structure. The move Qxb3 forces c6, a move that closes the bishop on c8. }
10... c6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfc1 Nd5
{ A reasonable alternative to improve the future ahead of the bishop on c8.   12...Bb7  13.Qb2  We defend d4 and prepare to relocate the knight to the ideal square d3, from where we can jump to c5 at the right moment. With such a plan, we will also avoid e5, so both breaks are controlled and Black's counterplay is null. }
13. Ne4 Bd7 14. Qd3 h6 15. Ne5
{ Once the move h6 is forced, the g6-square would be weaker. Similarly to what we achieved in the 7 ... b6 seen in the fifth chapter. Apart from this detail, we will occupy the c5 square and keep the pressure. }
