{ 7...Bxe5  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.dxe5  Black's structure is disastrous and the absolute control of the dark squares gives us a lot of advantage. Remember that we usually play this profile of structures being a pawn down, not with a Lord Pawn on e5 restricting the entire Black position. }
8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Nd2
{ The knight on c4 is always ideal if there are doubled pawns. This position would be good and playable for white without the pawn on d4, so we can get an idea of the advantage we have in this position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Open Catalan, other options"]
[Black "5...Nc6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Nc6
{ Black's main idea is to play Rb8 and b5 to defend the pawn on c4 and get out of the diagonal. }
6. Qa4
{ White anticipates this idea and tries to take quickly on c4. As the knight  on c6 can end up being badly placed. Black must react. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Nd5 8. Qc2
{ We deviate from the main lines. We want to take on c4 and take advantage of the fact that Black has a lot of minor pieces in the center.   8.Qb5  , Narayanan's recommendation in his Catalan course, I find it playable too, so I prefer to give you an alternative. }
8... Nb6 9. Bxb4 Nxb4 10. Qc3 Qe7
{ 10...N4d5  11.Qa5  restricting Black's queenside and getting the c4-pawn back. Later, we will have a very comfortable pressure on the c-file and all the ingredients of a good position in the Catalan with the bishop on g2, control of the center and little counterplay from the opponent. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Na3
{ We get the pawn back, and we can again enjoy a great position with the usual ingredients: a strong bishop on g2, a passive black bishop on c8, more space in the center for us and also the c-file to put pressure on. }
