{ Black's main idea is to play Rb8 and b5 to defend the pawn on c4 and get out of the diagonal. }
6. Qa4
{ White anticipates this idea and tries to take quickly on c4. As the knight  on c6 can end up being badly placed. Black must react. }
6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Bd6
{ A familiar plan that we already know from other variations is to retreat the bishop to d6 to go for e5. }
8. Na3 Bxa3 9. Qxa3 Qd6 10. Qc3 Ne4 11. Qxc4 Nxd2 12. Nxd2 Nxd4 13. Rc1
{ Black has nothing better than to let us capture on c7 if he does not want to surrender in a few moves after Ne4, which will generate strong pressure on the queenside together with our favorite bishop on g2, and we will have a big advantage in the endgame.   After capturing on c7, plans like f4-kf2 to control the center and at the same time free the rook would be ideal. }
