[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. The Hypermodern ...a6, ...c5, and ...h6"]
[Black "3...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 a6
{ A very interesting option for Black that forces us to deviate from the Catalan.   If  4.g3  , after b5 Black will reach a very good version of the Queen's Indian, as with the pawn already on b5 it will be more difficult to fight for the center with for example an eventual b4.  . }
4. Nc3 d5
{ With this move, we transpose to a typical position of the Queen's Gambit. The idea is to take on c4 and be able to hold the pawn with b5, so that forces us to take an important decision.   4...c5  here might feel challenging, but after  5.d5  there isn't much to claim for black. If  5...exd5  6.cxd5  b5  7.d6!  and black doesn't have a suitable answer to e4-e5. In case of  7...Bb7  8.Qd2!  or Qd3 and Qe3+ followed by Ng5 just wins the game.   Black can also try @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p1p1ppp/p3pn2/2p5/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq c6 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...b5  but we can deal with it  6.dxe6  fxe6  7.e4!  A typical sequence to counter b5-b4 threat as f6 and c3 knights cover the same squares in the center  (taking the pawn on b5 would mean decent counterplay for black)  7...b4  8.e5  bxc3  9.exf6  and black is quite exposed b file will open, targetable center and safer king are good values improved by just finishing the development. If something like  9...Qxf6  10.Bg5!  and then take on c3 would be quite good. }
5. c5
{ This seems to me the most practical option. The move  5.cxd5  would require us to understand a lot of nuances of the Queen's Gambit Declined, so I prefer to show sub-variations involving simpler ideas, as in this course we do not analyze all Black's variations against 1. d4.   We want to gain space on the queenside and transpose to symmetrical structures typical of the Exchange Slav but with the pawn already on e6, which means that the c8-bishop will suffer. }
5... b6
{ Black has to prevent White from consolidating the space we gained with c5.   5...Nc6  taking advantage of the fact that we have given up the pressure on d5, Black wants to push e5  6.h3  a very simple idea. We intend to play Bf4 without fearing Nh5. On the other hand, we prevent Black's typical reaction with e5 dxe5 Ng4. }
6. cxb6
{ Usually we do not want to play a quick c5 with White in the Queen's Gambit, as after b6 we are forced to take and Black will take with the a-pawn, losing central pressure in exchange for a side pawn.   The point of this variation is very clear at this moment. Black will have to take with the c-pawn and remain with a slightly worse version of the Exchange Slav because he cannot develop his bishop on c8 outside the pawn structure. }
6... c5
{ Black's main alternative for a more entertaining game.   It is good to be aware that  3...a6  is known as a very solid move, so it is also very rare for people to play a very active line within a very passive variation. In this variation, Black wants to increase the pressure in the center no matter what, and he will take on b6 later on.   6...cxb6  7.Bf4  As we expected, we have a very comfortable version of the Exchange Slav. After e3, Bd3 and O-O we will go for plans like Qb3 and double rooks on the c-file. The lack of flexibility of Black's structure will mean that if he wants to adequately defend the b6-pawn by playing b5, he will further weaken the dark squares and, if he wants to play a5, he will weaken the b5-square.   In both cases, the bishop on c8 will be a problem in the long run, and the results in practice are very good for White. The only detail to be aware of is a possible Nh5 idea after e3.   In general, we have the trick Bxb8 followed by Ne5 threatening a double attack on c6 and the knight on h5 at the same time. So, if Black develops the b8-knight quickly, we will have to play h3 to avoid exchanging our dark-squared bishop for the knight on f6. In case of Bd6, we will be more than happy to trade the best of Black's bishops.   In these type of positions we are playing for two results and black will not enjoy playing them at all. White scores very well in practice. }
7. Bf4 { We develop and force Black to react to our next move Bc7. } 7... Bd6
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Qd4 Qd6 11. e3
{ After Be2-Rfc1 and an eventual Na4, we have a slightly better position. The bishop on c8 will be quite passive. Black will have to spend quite some tempi to take the pawn on b6, and the lack of development is dangerous. The moves a3-b4 will also be on the agenda once the move Rc1 is played. }
*

