7. Bf4 { We develop and force Black to react to our next move Bc7. } 7... Qxb6
8. Na4 Qb5 9. Nxc5 Qxb2
{ Giving up the bishop pair without any justification with  9...Bxc5  did not make much sense. }
10. Rb1 Qc3+ 11. Qd2 Qxd2+ 12. Nxd2 Nc6
{ 12...Nbd7  13.Nb7  Winning the pair of bishops, with a good practical advantage as we have pawns on both sides of the board. }
13. e3
{ Followed by Na4 and Black's queenside is very awkward. We control the b8-square, Nb6 is always a threat and both the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8 have no clear destination. If Black plays Bb4, we get rid of the annoying pin with Rb3 and pawn to a3. }
