1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 c5
{ The Tarrasch Defense is a very interesting alternative for Black if he wants to play a complex game from the beginning. However, the fact that we have not played Nc3 makes this try less efficient.   4...a6  5.Bg2  dxc4  6.Ne5  transposes to chapter 14. }
5. cxd5 exd5
{ 5...Nxd5  6.Bg2  We will simply castle, and we will go for dxc5 after Black develops with Be7.  In case of  6...cxd4  we will recapture with the knight, and we will play Nc3, giving more power to our bishop on g2. The position is very comfortable, and the pressure on the queenside -especially on b7- sets Black into trouble. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O
{ With  7.Nc3  we would allow an extra, and very competitive, variation for Black,  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5  , the famous Dubov Variation. }
7... c4 { This frequent alternative is  somewhat weak for Black. } 8. b3
{ We will quickly break Black's pawn structure. } 8... cxb3 9. Qxb3 Be7 10. Bg5
O-O 11. Rc1
{ We free the d1-square for the queen, pre-empting Na5 ideas. In general, this position is very problematic for Black. We will take on f6, intending to put pressure on d5 with Nc3.   After that, plans like e3-Ne2-Nf4 and e3-Ne2-Ne1-Nd3 recycling both knights, will give us a very comfortable advantage since we will benefit from the c and d-files and the d5 pawn will always be a weakness.   The lack of mobility of Black's queenside, where he has a majority of pawns, is also problematic. }
*

