2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 c5
{ The Tarrasch Defense is a very interesting alternative for Black if he wants to play a complex game from the beginning. However, the fact that we have not played Nc3 makes this try less efficient.   4...a6  5.Bg2  dxc4  6.Ne5  transposes to chapter 14. }
5. cxd5 exd5
{ 5...Nxd5  6.Bg2  We will simply castle, and we will go for dxc5 after Black develops with Be7.  In case of  6...cxd4  we will recapture with the knight, and we will play Nc3, giving more power to our bishop on g2. The position is very comfortable, and the pressure on the queenside -especially on b7- sets Black into trouble. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O
{ With  7.Nc3  we would allow an extra, and very competitive, variation for Black,  7...cxd4  8.Nxd4  Bc5  , the famous Dubov Variation. }
7... Be7 8. dxc5 { The key is that White still delays Nc3. } 8... Bxc5 9. a3
Ne4
{ The only logical alternative for Black that allows this move order.   If  10.b4  , Black will be in time to play Be7-Bf6, with good counterplay. }
10. Nfd2 f5
{ Black's idea is to reinforce e4, but at the price of  exposing the pawn structure. }
11. Nc3 Be6 12. Nb3 Bb6 { It is necessary to prevent Be3. } 13. Na4 d4
{ Again, the only move. Black could not allow us to  play Nxb6 and Be3. } 14.
Nd2 { Freeing again the g2-b7 diagonal. } 14... Nxd2 15. Bxd2
{ We will follow with Rc1 next, and Black's so exposed pawn structure will give us a great advantage. In practice, White has won 2 of the 3 games that has been played, with a draw being played in a correspondence game. }
