[Round "?"]
[White "12. The Hypermodern ...a6, ...c5, and ...h6"]
[Black "3...d5 4.g3 h6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 h6
{ A hypermodern variation against the Catalan. Black wants to develop the bishop to d6 and prevent White from developing comfortably the bishop in c1. }
5. Bg2 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. Qc2
{ As usual in the Qc2 catalan, we defend c4 and increase our control of e4 to be able to expand in the future. }
7... b6 8. Nc3
{ In this case, before taking on d5, it seems better to first force Black to play Bb7. The threat is cxd5 and Nb5. }
8... Bb7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nb5 Re8 11. Re1 Nc6 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. Bd2
{ Although this positions seems to be slightly better for White, the position is quite closed, and we will struggle to take advantage of the pair of bishops. The best plan I have found is Bf1-Rec1-Qd1-Be1-e3. We will have both bishops pointing towards the queenside and our intention is to put pressure along the c-file.   If Black stays rock solid, at some point we will combine our pressure on the queenside with an expansion on the kingside. So, if you like these almost risk-free positions, this is a good choice for you.   13...Rc8  this is the rock solid option for Black  14.Qd3  a5  15.Rec1  and we start our plan combining our pressure on the queenside with an expansion on the kingside. }
*

