[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Bogoindian Defense"]
[Black "4...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ 4.Bd2  seems playable to me as well, but I think this move leads to positions with more play and, above all, that Black's mistakes give us more advantage on average. Having the bishop pair available in most variations is always a not inconsiderable plus. }
4... b6 5. a3 Bxd2+
{ 5...Be7  6.e4  b6 does not combine well at all with the Be7 maneuver. We have won the center again without further counterplay by Black. }
6. Qxd2
{ This capture is quite thematic and known from many Nimzo-Indian variations with Qc2. We will develop the bishop to b2, we gain a lot of space on the queenside, and we have to react correctly in the center against possible plans like Ne4-f5-Rf6 by Black.   Another plans that the second player can choose are not as effective due to the amount of space that we have and also due to our bishop pair. }
6... Bb7 7. e3 O-O
{ 7...a5  It is the move that both Papaioannou  (Modernchess 2021)   and Mihail Marin  (Modern Chess 2020)   recommend  8.b3  O-O  9.Be2  d6  10.O-O  Nbd7  11.Bb2  Qe7  Black keeps the options to play e5 or c5 or Ne4-f5. Here I propose an unusual move  12.Qc3  We free the d2 square for the knight. Although it may not seem intuitive, it has the function of being better prepared against c5-cxd4, by being able to capture with the e-pawn and look for Qe3, we fix the weakness of b6 and have some good hanging pawns, which would be the ideal setup. Also, it allows us to have the Q+B 'battery' mounted in case Black doesn't play The logical answer of  12...Ne4  is also not dealt with, as White has a choice of Qc2 or Qd3.   12...Rfe8  13.Nd2  e5  14.d5  c6  15.dxc6  and we will continue with b4-Rfc1-Bf1. The bishop pair has a lot of potential, and Black will have to remain quiet and attentive to our breaks and the maneuvers we can do with the knight to place it on c3.  The advantage is slight, but my focus is that we have anticipated all of Black's counterplay  (hence Bf1)  and that the d6 and b6 pawns will always be vulnerable.   12...c5  13.Nd2  and we want to continue with Rfd1-Rac1-Bf1. Again, we have a position where Black has little counterplay  (eg e5 would meet d5)  and the bishop pair gives us the long-term advantage.  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bpnqppp/1p1pp3/p7/2PPn3/PPQ1PN2/1B2BPPP/R4RK1 w - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  f5  14.d5  e5  15.Nd2  Nxd2  16.Qxd2  Rf6  it is always convenient to anticipate the consequences of a direct attack before the king.   14.Ne1  it is also preferable, but the way of playing is quite different, and we already know the subject of d5.   @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bpnq1pp/1p1p4/p2Ppp2/2P5/PP2P3/1B1QBPPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...e4  another way of conducting a direct attack against our king, and thus we exemplify that it is difficult for black to attack without the two pieces on the queenside  17.b4  Ne5  18.Rac1  we continue with the intention of breaking on c5  18...Rf6  19.c5  Rh6  20.cxb6  cxb6  To other moves we have Bxe5 or Rxc7  21.Rfd1  Nf3+  22.Bxf3  exf3  23.g3  once the storm has passed, we can continue with b5-Rc4-Rc1 and take advantage of the c file. A move like Qd3 will always help us avoid possible mates and defend castling more than enough.   @@StartFEN@@r5k1/1bpnq1pp/1p1p1r2/p2Ppp2/2P5/PP2P3/1B1QBPPP/R4RK1 w - - 1 17@@EndFEN@@  17.b4  Rh6  18.f4  Qh4  19.h3  Rg6  20.Kh1  Nf6  21.Bf3  we have avoided all the attacking themes for black and now we will see the strength of the bishop pair and all the breaking points  (e5,c5)  that we have. The virtue of d5 is that it also neutralizes the bishop on b7. }
8. Be2 d5 { 8...d6  9.b4  And we will end up transposing to 8... Ne4. } 9. O-O
dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. b4 c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Rd1
{ The bishop pair will be very strong, and after Be2, the e1-square will be perfect for the queen if necessary: We will prevent Black from exchanging the last queenside pawn, and we will set our rooks and bishops free. }
*

