6... Bb7 7. e3 O-O
{ 7...a5  It is the move that both Papaioannou  (Modernchess 2021)   and Mihail Marin  (Modern Chess 2020)   recommend  8.b3  O-O  9.Be2  d6  10.O-O  Nbd7  11.Bb2  Qe7  Black keeps the options to play e5 or c5 or Ne4-f5. Here I propose an unusual move  12.Qc3  We free the d2 square for the knight. Although it may not seem intuitive, it has the function of being better prepared against c5-cxd4, by being able to capture with the e-pawn and look for Qe3, we fix the weakness of b6 and have some good hanging pawns, which would be the ideal setup. Also, it allows us to have the Q+B 'battery' mounted in case Black doesn't play The logical answer of  12...Ne4  is also not dealt with, as White has a choice of Qc2 or Qd3.   12...Rfe8  13.Nd2  e5  14.d5  c6  15.dxc6  and we will continue with b4-Rfc1-Bf1. The bishop pair has a lot of potential, and Black will have to remain quiet and attentive to our breaks and the maneuvers we can do with the knight to place it on c3.  The advantage is slight, but my focus is that we have anticipated all of Black's counterplay  (hence Bf1)  and that the d6 and b6 pawns will always be vulnerable.   12...c5  13.Nd2  and we want to continue with Rfd1-Rac1-Bf1. Again, we have a position where Black has little counterplay  (eg e5 would meet d5)  and the bishop pair gives us the long-term advantage.  @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bpnqppp/1p1pp3/p7/2PPn3/PPQ1PN2/1B2BPPP/R4RK1 w - - 6 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Qc2  f5  14.d5  e5  15.Nd2  Nxd2  16.Qxd2  Rf6  it is always convenient to anticipate the consequences of a direct attack before the king.   14.Ne1  it is also preferable, but the way of playing is quite different, and we already know the subject of d5.   @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1bpnq1pp/1p1p4/p2Ppp2/2P5/PP2P3/1B1QBPPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16...e4  another way of conducting a direct attack against our king, and thus we exemplify that it is difficult for black to attack without the two pieces on the queenside  17.b4  Ne5  18.Rac1  we continue with the intention of