8. Be2 Ne4
{ Black usually goes for a berserker attack with f5-Rf6-Rh6. This will serve as an example to counter it. }
9. Qc2 f5 10. O-O d6 11. b4 Nd7 12. Bb2
{ Followed by the typical d5 sacrifice opening the c and d-files and the diagonals for the bishops.   In case of  12...c5  13.dxc5  bxc5  14.Rad1  and we look for Nd2 and press the black center, the b2 bishop dominates the board.   And if, for example, black answers with  12...Rf6  13.d5  e5  we can continue with  14.Nd2  exchanging his best piece and continuing with f3, dominating the center and taking advantage of the closed bishop on b7. In these positions we have breaks on c5, a5 and also with f4, so Black has to coordinate his forces very well to minimize the impact of the bishop pair.   In case of  13...Rh6  we would open the position wide with dxe6 and c5. }
