{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ 4.Bd2  seems playable to me as well, but I think this move leads to positions with more play and, above all, that Black's mistakes give us more advantage on average. Having the bishop pair available in most variations is always a not inconsiderable plus. }
4... c5
{ This is another of Black's alternatives that doesn't work very well in case of Nbd2. Black tries to press the center quickly, but doesn't have time to have enough presence to compensate our bishop pair. }
5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Bxd2 cxd4 7. Nxd4 d5
{ While  7...O-O  runs into  8.Bb4!  followed by Nb5.   We can deal @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp1p1ppp/4pn2/8/2PN4/P7/1P1BPPPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Nc6  with  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.c5!  seizing the dark squares.  Or  9.Bc3  and keeping both bishops is a great advantage in the middle game. }
8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. e3
{ As in most variations in this line, the pair of bishops gives us a huge advantage in the endgame. Once we trade queens, it is important to play f3-e4. This way we neutralize Black's light-squared bishop and also the knight on f6, and thus we will emphasize the strength of our dark-squared bishop. }
