4... O-O 5. a3 Be7
{ This retreat tries to punish the delicate position of the knight on d2 in exchange for giving up the center. }
6. e4 d6
{ Black's idea is still to take advantage of the fact that our knight on d2 would be perfect on c3. }
7. Be2
{ On d3 the bishop would be a little more vulnerable to moves like e5. It is not easy for Black to fight for the center. }
7... Nbd7 8. Qc2 c5
{ 8...e5  9.Nb1  here we can see one of the advantages of the move 7. Be2.   After Black takes on d4, Nc5 would be annoying for us because our bishop on d3 will be under attack. Once we bring the knight to c3, we will have total control of the center, and we will have a classic advantage. }
9. d5 e5 10. Nb1
{ I love the plan of playing g3 and h3 and then, at our convenience, either g4 or h4. White can temporarily delay the long castling and make progress with Be3-Qd2. I find this much more preferable to the very difficult to materialize attacks on the queenside with b4 while Black attacks on the kingside.   Since Black is looking to play Nh5 regularly, I love the plan to play g3 and h3 and then, as we see fit, either g4 or h4. All this will make it difficult for Black to play f5.  White can temporarily delay long castling and make progress with Be3-Qd2 after Nc3. It seems to me much more preferable to the very difficult attacks to materialize on the queenside with b4 while black attacks on the kingside. }
