1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ 4.Bd2  seems playable to me as well, but I think this move leads to positions with more play and, above all, that Black's mistakes give us more advantage on average. Having the bishop pair available in most variations is always a not inconsiderable plus. }
4... O-O 5. a3 Be7
{ This retreat tries to punish the delicate position of the knight on d2 in exchange for giving up the center. }
6. e4 d6
{ Black's idea is still to take advantage of the fact that our knight on d2 would be perfect on c3. }
7. Be2
{ On d3 the bishop would be a little more vulnerable to moves like e5. It is not easy for Black to fight for the center. }
7... Nfd7
{ This peculiar move allows Black to have the extra option of the f5-break after e5. }
8. b4
{ This move, apart from allowing our obvious queenside expansion, it also allows us to castle long depending on the variation chosen by Black. }
8... e5 9. d5 a5 10. Bb2 c6
{ 10...c5  This move has been played in a dozen games. Black wants to get the c5-square or closing the queenside to push on the kingside  11.b5  After closing the queenside and castle, our kingside attack is practically lead without opposition, and we will see a model game on how to lead the attack. }
11. O-O cxd5 12. cxd5 axb4
{ 12...Nb6  13.bxa5  Again, we have a lot of space to attack on the queenside and it's clear that Black's pieces are in the way of each other. }
13. axb4 Rxa1 14. Qxa1
{ We have a lot of ways to get through the queenside and Black's development is still very scarce. We have a clear advantage.   14...Nb6  15.Qa7  15...N8d7  with the idea of f5 and Nf6 is what Adrien Demuth proposes in his bogoindian series for c24. Here I like to continue with the plan of giving meaning to the d2 knight that is somewhat out of place  16.Rd1  f5  17.exf5  Nf6  18.Nf1  we headed to e3  18...Bxf5  It is important to note that it does not seem like an easy move to me, since after Qxb7 the engine gives equality with Qb8!, and it is not at all obvious how Black handles the position with a pawn down  19.Ne3  Bc8  20.Ng5  We are looking to enter on e6 and when faced with issues with Nxd5 Qa2 is always useful and the d6-pawn is very vulnerable.  The Bogoindia, in general, is a very conceptual and simple opening to play with black, so it seems unlikely to me that we will find someone looking to 'insert theoretical tubes' or tune as much with black. So I want to emphasize the importance of understanding the simplest and most common plans, but I also respond to the most specific variants of black.  This variation serves as a general example of the priority to give meaning to the knight on d2 that is momentarily out of place. }
