1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2
{ 4.Bd2  seems playable to me as well, but I think this move leads to positions with more play and, above all, that Black's mistakes give us more advantage on average. Having the bishop pair available in most variations is always a not inconsiderable plus. }
4... a5
{ A very recent idea which seems a bit stupid since we don't threaten the b4 bishop, but it makes sense.   In the  4...O-O  5.a3  line, Black plays  5...Be7  and after  6.e4  d5  7.e5  we have a very strong attack.   On the other hand, the virtue of a5 is that it allows us to enter the same line without having castled, so that white does not have the strong attack initiated by the move h4! }
5. a3
{ The plan of taking on d2 and go for a4 does not work so well as after e3-Bd3 both Bc2, attacking the pawn, and Qc2-e4 taking the center would not justify Black's tempi spent on weakening b3. }
5... Be7 6. e4 d5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. Bd3 c5 9. O-O
{ We do not lose our calm and try to strengthen the e5-point.   Now  9.h4  would not be so effective due to the fact that there is no castled king to mate! }
9... Nc6 10. Re1
{ This time, our plan is less ambitious: we want to bring our knight to b3 and our bishop to f4. }
10... O-O 11. Bc2
{ Against  11.Bb1  a4  would be very annoying as we would not allow us to play Nb3.   11.Nb3  We play 11. Bc2 to prevent the following forced sequence  11...dxc4  12.Bxc4  a4  13.Nxc5  Nxc5  14.dxc5  Qxd1  15.Rxd1  Bxc5  Black has solved all his problems. }
11... Qb6 12. dxc5 Nxc5
{ 12...Bxc5  13.Bxh7+  winning with a very well-known tactical motif. Black's king feels very vulnerable. }
13. Nb3 Nxb3
{ 13...dxc4  14.Nxc5  Our attack is fast and Black will struggle to activate his queenside. }
14. Qd3
{ We first create weaknesses on the kingside, and then we take the knight back. The bishop on c8 is very passive, and we can continue bringing pieces to the kingside. I love this move as an example of how important it is to pay attention to the in-between moves that can give us a lot of points. }
