[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "4...Bb4+ with 5...c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb4+
{ This pseudo Bogo-Indian has very  different nuances from those exposed in the 3.... Bb4+ variation, so it should  be analyzed carefully.   4...c6  5.Bg2  d5  6.O-O  This move order has been tried on multiple occasions by the Spanish number one Paco Vallejo among other strong players.   The problem is that we will play Nfd2 on the next move followed by e4 and Black has no satisfactory reply and will have to settle for a slightly worse position from the start. Then we continue with our usual development with moves like b3-Bb2. }
5. Bd2
{ 5.Nbd2  would not make much sense as Black usually spends the Ba6-tempo to force the move Nbd2, and then he will play Bb7. }
5... c5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. Bxb4 cxb4 8. O-O O-O 9. Qd3
{ I love this position for White. We will develop with moves like Nbd2 and Rfd1 and after Ne1, followed by the exchange of the light-squared bishop, we will play Nc2, and we will expand with e4.   Black would be in trouble if he plays e5 due to Ne3-Nf5 and, also, f4 will be a reasonable alternative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "4...Bb4+ with 5...a5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb4+
{ This pseudo Bogo-Indian has very  different nuances from those exposed in the 3.... Bb4+ variation, so it should  be analyzed carefully.   4...c6  5.Bg2  d5  6.O-O  This move order has been tried on multiple occasions by the Spanish number one Paco Vallejo among other strong players.   The problem is that we will play Nfd2 on the next move followed by e4 and Black has no satisfactory reply and will have to settle for a slightly worse position from the start. Then we continue with our usual development with moves like b3-Bb2. }
5. Bd2
{ 5.Nbd2  would not make much sense as Black usually spends the Ba6-tempo to force the move Nbd2, and then he will play Bb7. }
5... a5
{ Black defends his bishop and, if we capture it, that would be beneficial for him, as he will open the a-file and would restrict the development of our kingside. }
6. Bg2 Bb7
{ 6...Ba6  7.Bxb4  Bxb4 works very well in this move order  7...axb4  8.Ne5  the one and only Kortschnoj was defeated like this. The pin of the bishop on a6 followed by a3 or the loss of the b4-pawn, depending on which scenario Black chooses, gives us a clear advantage. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Bf4 Be7
{ 8...d5  9.c5  playing the opening carelessly has its consequences. The bishop on b4 is in serious trouble. }
9. Nc3 Ne4
{ 9...Na6  10.Qd3  d5  11.a3  The knight on a6 is very badly placed, and after placing the rooks we will have a great advantage. }
10. Qd3
{ I had a hard time deciding on a move at this point.  10.Rc1  is interesting to play it to have a quiet game, but I consider that Black is very close to equalize.   10.Nb5  c6  This main move did not appear in Shankland's course. Black takes advantage of the fact that the knight on c7 will have problems to get out. I think it is important to emphasize that both ways that White can choose are slightly unfavorable in my opinion.  11.Nc7  Ra7  12.Qb3  g5!  A very evident novelty that forces White to play very accurately if he wants to equalize.   11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  d5  After Nd7 and Ba6 I prefer Black. We will have a lot of problems to justify the backward pawn on c3. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Qc8 12. e4 d6
{ There were two White defeats in this position against two 2700 players. This fact serves to make us aware of the dangers that this structure involves. }
13. Nd2
{ A novelty in this concrete position. I like White more. The space advantage is somewhat clouded by having a worse structure, but with the f4-f5 plan Black will be forced into a rather nasty defense and I think it revitalizes the variation for White. }
*

