[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "4...Bb4+ with 5...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb4+
{ This pseudo Bogo-Indian has very  different nuances from those exposed in the 3.... Bb4+ variation, so it should  be analyzed carefully.   4...c6  5.Bg2  d5  6.O-O  This move order has been tried on multiple occasions by the Spanish number one Paco Vallejo among other strong players.   The problem is that we will play Nfd2 on the next move followed by e4 and Black has no satisfactory reply and will have to settle for a slightly worse position from the start. Then we continue with our usual development with moves like b3-Bb2. }
5. Bd2
{ 5.Nbd2  would not make much sense as Black usually spends the Ba6-tempo to force the move Nbd2, and then he will play Bb7. }
5... Be7
{ If we now play the same way we did in the 4 ... Bb7 chapter, the bishop on d2 will not let any of our ideas work. }
6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Bg2 c6
{ We could say that this is the Eljanov variation. Black lets White play e4 but, in return, he will have a very powerful counterattack by means of d5.   7...O-O  Black cannot play Ne4, his main idea; that is a good sign for us  8.Qc2  d5  9.cxd5  exd5  At this point in the course, we already know how to play these positions. }
8. Qb3
{ It seems to me that in this variation, White will have a very comfortable advantage. }
8... d5 9. O-O O-O 10. Bf4
{ If  10...Nbd7  Black's position would be very uncomfortable after  11.cxd5  cxd5  and  12.Nb5  followed by Rfc1 and penetrating on c7. }
10... Nh5 11. Be5 Nd7 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Nb5 a6
{ 13...Nxe5  14.dxe5  g6  We will bring our pieces to the queenside while Black cannot solve the issue of his knight not having any square to go to. If it goes to f5, the pawn structure will be very compromised. }
14. Bc7 Qc8 15. Bd6 Qd8 16. Qa3
{ We are following a game by Andrey Esipenko. Our knight will get to d6, preventing any rook to have access to the c-file. Later on, we will occupy that file and, with moves like Ne5, I do not see Black surviving this. }
