2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6
{ Black wants to put pressure on c4, and a range of interesting possibilities opens up now for White. }
5. Nbd2
{ Although ideally we would like to develop the knight on c3, we have to keep in mind that the bishop on a6 will most likely relocate to b7 once its function of pressing c4 is over. A very substantial plus of this move is that it requires very little knowledge to have a playable game, while the others may be affected by more incisive variations.   Another very interesting option if our opponent plays this variation exclusively is to try to play the Catalan by delaying 2.c4. I recently encountered a student who did not have an alternative planned for it and had to play Bb7 straight. I always encourage being demanding with the move order, you can win many points this way. }
5... Bb7 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. b3 d5 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Ne5
{ After this natural development of pieces from both sides, we seek to have more presence with the Catalan bishop. In general, these double fianchetto positions are very comfortable and harmonious, and I have often won games without doing anything special. }
10... a5
{ This attempt to break our queenside with a4 has been tried in 3 games.   10...c5  11.cxd5  exd5  12.e3  We have an ideal blockade and a long game full of suffering ahead for Black trying to defend d5. Even in correspondence chess did White win one game. }
11. cxd5 exd5 12. Rc1 c5 13. Nxd7 Nxd7
{ In case of  13...Qxd7  14.dxc5!  and the bishop on e7 will need to ask for a raise in his salary, as 15.Bxf6 will win us a pawn or destroy black's castle. }
14. e4
{ Black is not ready for the center to be opened and, seeing the possible alternatives, it is quite certain that he will have to give up the bishop pair. }
