[Black "4...Ba6 with 5...Bb4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6
{ Black wants to put pressure on c4, and a range of interesting possibilities opens up now for White. }
5. Nbd2
{ Although ideally we would like to develop the knight on c3, we have to keep in mind that the bishop on a6 will most likely relocate to b7 once its function of pressing c4 is over. A very substantial plus of this move is that it requires very little knowledge to have a playable game, while the others may be affected by more incisive variations.   Another very interesting option if our opponent plays this variation exclusively is to try to play the Catalan by delaying 2.c4. I recently encountered a student who did not have an alternative planned for it and had to play Bb7 straight. I always encourage being demanding with the move order, you can win many points this way. }
5... Bb4
{ Black renews the threat against c4, and we cannot avoid it with  6.a3  as this move would force us to take on d2 with the f3-knight. }
6. Qc2 c5
{ We must be careful with the move order. After this move, we can win the bishop pair. }
7. a3 Bxd2+
{ Playing  7...Ba5  would virtually remove any option of taking on d4, since b4 would trap the bishop. Since c5 has been played with the intention of contesting our pawn center, it would be a rather counterproductive move. }
8. Bxd2 cxd4
{ 8...Bb7  9.dxc5  bxc5  10.b4  Black will have control over the diagonal, but our bishop pair benefits enormously from the fact that the position has been opened up on the queenside. The dark squares will be a perennial problem for Black. }
9. Nxd4 Bb7 10. f3
{ The game will end very soon after e4 and long castling. We have the bishop pair and Black has to open the position to prevent being suffocated. This is an example in which hunger is combined with the desire to eat. }
