[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "4...Ba6 with 5...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. Nbd2 d5
{ Now we have the typical pawn structure that we often see in the Queen's Indian with Bb7. Can you think of what plan we can use? }
6. Bg2 Be7
{ Placing the bishop on e7 gives Black an extra option as we will see later. }
7. O-O O-O 8. cxd5 { Again  8.b3  is a practical and healthy alternative. }
8... Nxd5
{ A fairly common attempt by Black to hinder our automatic plan. Now we are faced with some awkward questions: How do we develop the c1-bishop? What do we do with the knight on d2?   8...exd5  9.Nb1!?  and again we would follow the plans fully explained in this course. }
9. Re1
{ We are planning to play a2-a3 @@StartBracket@@ to control the jump of the knight from d5 to b4@@EndBracket@@ and continue with the central expansion e2-e4. }
9... c5
{ If Black lingers too long he will find himself in a very passive position. }
10. dxc5 bxc5
{ This nasty move is the best. Black is dynamically active, but he has isolated a pawn, and we want to take control of the blockade on c4.   10...Bxc5  11.a3  we want to stick with b4-Bb2 and our development advantage is overwhelming. Be careful with the jump Nd5-Nc3, many times we will want to start with e2-e4. }
11. Ne5 Qc7 12. Ndc4 { We threaten Bxd5 so  12...f6  is not a serious threat. }
12... Rd8 13. Bd2
{ Thus followed a correspondence game. With the timing of threatening Ba5, we complete development and can adequately defend the c4-knight in order to free up our other knight on e5 and perhaps redirect it to d3 for action against the c5-pawn.  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Lins,T @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@-Reinhart,K @@StartBracket@@2479@@EndBracket@@ GER email 2019 }
