[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "4...Ba6 with 5...d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Ba6 5. Nbd2 d5
{ Now we have the typical pawn structure that we often see in the Queen's Indian with Bb7. Can you think of what plan we can use? }
6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nb1
{ Congratulations to those who have succeeded! It seems very coherent to look for this maneuver again and enjoy the easier game.   It is also possible to play  9.b3  and develop peacefully with the double fianchetto and thus have a slow but sure game. This is how I recently played in the European blitz against the strong Czech player David Navara. Curiously, I later saw that neither more nor less than Ding Liren had used the same maneuver against Navara. }
9... Re8 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Re1 h6 12. Bf4
{ Again I am looking to strengthen the e5 point and I don't mind weakening my kingside structure a bit. }
12... Bxf4 13. gxf4 c5 14. e3 Bb7
{ So far, it is a very common position in these structures.   Now I continued with  15.Ne5  . I did have a very interesting game, in which I was winning at some point. }
15. a4
{ Perhaps a4!?, was more instructive, to look for a4-a5!, and gain control of the d4 square or weaken the opponent's dark squares.   In case of  15...a5  Black would have lost a lot of flexibility, and we could now continue with  16.Ne5  with a comfortable position. Although another good piece of advice is that after doing a thousand wonders and staying better, don't get hung up on a piece in a final, like I did against Navara :@@EndBracket@@.   0-1 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Alonso Rosell,A @@StartBracket@@2561@@EndBracket@@-Navara, D @@StartBracket@@2684@@EndBracket@@ Katowice 2022 }
