[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "4...Bb7 with 5...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7
{ In the Queen's Indian Defense, as opposed to the variations with 3. ... d5, Black wants to respond to the long diagonal in exchange for not having so much presence in the center. The great flexibility of plans for Black has always been one of the greatest virtues of such a defense.   Although it has lost quite a bit of popularity in favor of 3.... d5 is still a very playable reply. }
5. Bg2 c5 6. d5
{ This move is known to refute 5. .... c5. LC0 amazed us in his appearance with brilliant victories in this variation. }
6... exd5 7. cxd5
{ 7.Nh4  gives also an advantage, but this is more direct. We give up the pawn in exchange to speed our development. }
7... Bxd5 8. Nc3 Bc6 9. e4 Be7 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nd5
{ The knight on e4 is in trouble. } 11... f5 12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Ne5
{ Black cannot move. The rook on a8 is in a lot of danger before any exchange of pieces, and simply O-O Re1 Bf4 will still give us an advantage.   Two wins in correspondence chess show that prove that even with the creativity of the engines, it is not possible to resist the strength of our knights. }
