10... Nc6
{ A difficult move to play, but it has been seen in a human-to-human and in two correspondence games. Black assumes that White's plan is strong and redirects the bishop to the kingside. }
11. Ng5 Bg6 12. e4
{ We have gained the control of the center, but our pieces are momentarily uncoordinated, giving Black an opportunity to create counterplay. }
12... f6 13. Nf3 Bh5 14. Be3
{ White won the correspondence game, but I would claim that our plan is to simply relocate our pieces and enjoy the space advantage in the center.   Looking at eventual Black's continuations, it seems that this position requires too much level to coordinate with so many strange factors on the board: bishops on h5 and e7, the knight in front of the pawn structure, the queen in an unusual square, etc. }
