[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 Ne4
{ This little-known idea has much practical interest. Black wants to play d5-f5 and reinforce his advanced point on e4.   It is relevant to add this variant since after the typical  8.h4  h6!?  and we find that an alternative method must be considered to resolve the situation to those already seen. }
8. Nfd2
{ We take advantage of the pin of the Catalan bishop. It is appreciated to look for solutions that depend on the specific casuistry of the position.   For example, if I now told you to play  8.h4  and only in some specific cases then stick with Nfd2, it would be a bit confusing to remember. Now we associate this 'strange' move @@StartBracket@@since it doesn't solve the typical exchange of pieces because our knight is still on b1@@EndBracket@@ with our peculiar answer. }
8... d5 9. cxd5 exd5
{ Instead  9...Nxd2  would make little sense after  10.Bxd2  followed by Nc3-Bf4, and Black has exchanged his best piece. }
10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Nc3 f5 12. Bf4
{ So far the sequence has been relatively forced. Black has gained space in the center, but has greatly reduced his flexibility.  This relative exchange of strategic concepts favors us in one aspect: Black will have to play more precise, as the pawn structure is more fixed. On the other hand, we cannot relax and let him consolidate his space advantage by finishing the development without any resistance. }
12... Bd6
{ In case of  12...Na6  we would continue with the maneuver  13.Qb3+!  and Red1-Rac1, completing our development beautifully. }
13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. e3
{ Our rough plan is to play Rc1 and then look for opportunities to play Nb5 or take advantage of Black's fixed pawn structure with g3-g4 or f2-f3. }
14... a6
{ Against  14...Nd7  there were some technical problems with  15.Qb3+  followed by Nb5, so Black must first check our foal. }
15. g4
{ I love variations that bring us new dynamic or strategic concepts.   15.f3  and then looking for the exchange of queens on d5 would give us a very comfortable and practical ending, but perhaps very close to equality.  With g4, we want to attack the pawn structure and become strong in the center. It is very important to keep in mind that we want to get ahead of Nd7-Nf6, which would be Black's dream position. }
15... Qg6 16. Rc1
{ By inserting this move, we make a future Ne2 possible because this will threaten c7 and thereby win an essential tempo so as not to lose the g4-pawn. }
16... Nd7 17. Qb3+ Kh8 18. Nd5
{ With this move, we fully enter the black position that is half developed. }
18... Qxg4 { 18...c5  19.Nf4  Qxg4  20.dxc5  and the pin decides. } 19. Rxc7
Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Nf6 21. Qe5
{ The c file, the passed pawn, the advanced pawn structure and having a bishop give us a huge advantage. Black, on the other hand, cannot take advantage of our weak king. }
*

