[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "7.Re1 Main Line  - 7...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7
{ In the Queen's Indian Defense, as opposed to the variations with 3. ... d5, Black wants to respond to the long diagonal in exchange for not having so much presence in the center. The great flexibility of plans for Black has always been one of the greatest virtues of such a defense.   Although it has lost quite a bit of popularity in favor of 3.... d5 is still a very playable reply. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O
{ In this position, Black wants to answer to Nc3 with Ne4. Therefore, we will propose a plan to delay the development of the knight on b1 and force Black to change his mind.     On the other hand, Black also wants to strike with c5 to reduce our control of the center. It is important to keep in mind that it is in our interest to answer this with d5 and, after ed5, to remove the knight from f3 and taking advantage of the pinned pawn on d5 to regain central control. }
7. Re1 { We prepare a future e4 and ask Black to show what he wants to play. }
7... d5 8. cxd5
{ Practically, we are always interested in capturing on d5 in the Queen's Indian. Black cannot recapture with a piece and keep control of the diagonal without allowing us to gain space in the center. Therefore, we close the diagonal for the b7-bishop and continue with Nc3-Bf4.   Our queen can go to b3 or a4 according to our needs. In case Black plays c5, he will always have to watch out for the possibility that the d5 pawn can become isolated, and if he prefers to play solid, White can then gain space in the center with Ne5 followed by e4. For all these reasons, it is considered quite accepted that these structures favor White. }
8... exd5 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Bf4 a6
{ This is a common move that leads to disaster for Black. } 11. Ne5 Re8 12. Qb3
Nf8 13. e4 { All our pieces are perfectly coordinated. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "7.Re1 Main Line  - 7...d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7
{ In the Queen's Indian Defense, as opposed to the variations with 3. ... d5, Black wants to respond to the long diagonal in exchange for not having so much presence in the center. The great flexibility of plans for Black has always been one of the greatest virtues of such a defense.   Although it has lost quite a bit of popularity in favor of 3.... d5 is still a very playable reply. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O
{ In this position, Black wants to answer to Nc3 with Ne4. Therefore, we will propose a plan to delay the development of the knight on b1 and force Black to change his mind.     On the other hand, Black also wants to strike with c5 to reduce our control of the center. It is important to keep in mind that it is in our interest to answer this with d5 and, after ed5, to remove the knight from f3 and taking advantage of the pinned pawn on d5 to regain central control. }
7. Re1 { We prepare a future e4 and ask Black to show what he wants to play. }
7... d5 8. cxd5
{ Practically, we are always interested in capturing on d5 in the Queen's Indian. Black cannot recapture with a piece and keep control of the diagonal without allowing us to gain space in the center. Therefore, we close the diagonal for the b7-bishop and continue with Nc3-Bf4.   Our queen can go to b3 or a4 according to our needs. In case Black plays c5, he will always have to watch out for the possibility that the d5 pawn can become isolated, and if he prefers to play solid, White can then gain space in the center with Ne5 followed by e4. For all these reasons, it is considered quite accepted that these structures favor White. }
8... exd5 9. Nc3 Nbd7 10. Bf4 c5 11. h4
{ This move has several purposes and is very common in this pawn structure in conjunction with the arrangement of pieces:   1. Enable Bh3 in better conditions, for example in the event that Black plays Rc8.   2. Since in the future we will want to play e3, we anticipate that the bishop on f4 may have problems.   3. It gives us an extra option to expand on the kingside with g4. }
11... Ne4 12. e3 Ndf6 13. a4 Nh5
{ A good example of the strength of this piece arrangement can be found in a recent game between two +2650.   13...h6  14.Nd2  if  14...Nxc3  we have a very strong center and black's difficulties on the b-file will increase as he will not be able to expand on the queenside. In general, this type of positions are very uncomfortable for Black, as he cannot build any kind of counterplay and, in a lot of situations, he will end up with an isolated pawn on d5.   If  14...Nxd2  we will focus our attention on d5 and, thanks to a4, Black will again struggle to play actively. }
14. Ne5 { The rook on e1 will be activated by recapturing on f4. } 14... Nxf4
15. exf4 f6
{ 15...Nf6  16.dxc5  bxc5  17.g4  exemplifies very well the harmony of the position. The pawn on d5 will fall. }
16. Bxe4 fxe5 17. Bc2 cxd4
{ 17...e4  18.dxc5  Black cannot deal with the threat of Bb3, because after  18...bxc5  19.Bxe4  would win the game. }
18. Rxe5 dxc3 19. Qh5 h6 20. Rae1
{ After Qg6 and Qh7+, Bd1 will decide the game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Queen's Indian Defense"]
[Black "7.Re1 Main Line  - 7...Na6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7
{ In the Queen's Indian Defense, as opposed to the variations with 3. ... d5, Black wants to respond to the long diagonal in exchange for not having so much presence in the center. The great flexibility of plans for Black has always been one of the greatest virtues of such a defense.   Although it has lost quite a bit of popularity in favor of 3.... d5 is still a very playable reply. }
5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O
{ In this position, Black wants to answer to Nc3 with Ne4. Therefore, we will propose a plan to delay the development of the knight on b1 and force Black to change his mind.     On the other hand, Black also wants to strike with c5 to reduce our control of the center. It is important to keep in mind that it is in our interest to answer this with d5 and, after ed5, to remove the knight from f3 and taking advantage of the pinned pawn on d5 to regain central control. }
7. Re1 { We prepare a future e4 and ask Black to show what he wants to play. }
7... Na6
{ The knight on a6 will make sense in case of playing d5 followed by Black's c5, and also serves as a waiting move to continue reacting to Nc3 with Ne4. The main problem is that in many variations it can get a bit out of play after moves like a3. In general, do not bring your knights to the edge if you do not have a clear reason for doing so. }
8. h4
{ This creative waiting move allows us to gain space on the kingside and keep putting pressure on the e4-square with the Nc3-Ne4 reaction. In practically all the resulting structures it is useful and also increases our options on the g5 square. At the time of writing, I already have two wins in the pocket with this move. }
8... h6
{ We have already talked about how the structures after d5-cxd5-exd5 cause little mobility in the pawn chains, so in this case h6 reduces Black's options.   For example, as we have seen in other positions during the course, we imagine a knight on e5 and no longer having to fear the f6 move because it creates a weak square on g6.   8...Re8  9.a3  This would be very similar to 8 ... h6. }
9. a3 { The knight on a6 will suffer if Black does not go for d5-c5-Nc7. } 9...
d5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nc3
{ Obtaining again the desired structure with the addition of the move h6. } *

