[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Blumenfeld Gambit "]
[Black "6...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 b5
{ The Bluemenfeld Gambit is a quite dangerous sideline if White does not know how to meet it. Black sacrifices a side pawn in exchange for obtaining a strong center. The struggle lies in preventing and/or counteracting in time Black's expansion in the center. }
5. dxe6 { Accepting the gambit is the simpler and most direct option. } 5...
fxe6 6. cxb5 { Here Black has a couple of main options at his disposal. } 6...
a6
{ This Black's alternative is very important since it allows us to illustrate how to play if we cannot react with the e4-break. }
7. e3 d5 8. Nc3
{ In general, we want to take on b5 with the knight, finish the development with Be2 and O-O and then playing Bd2 or b3, depending on the circumstances. We will see some concrete examples. }
8... Bd6
{ 8...Nbd7  9.bxa6  Bd6  10.Nb5  After Be2, O-O-O and b3-Bb2 we will be well-prepared for any central expansion, and we have a healthy extra pawn. We remember the importance of being aware of being able to play e4 with White and gain control of the light squares. }
9. e4
{ Challenging Black's center again.  Black needs to defend and keep the center. Taking on e4 would be awful structure-wise and we always rely on Ng5 to take back the pawn. }
9... Be7 10. exd5 exd5 11. Bg5 d4 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Ne4
{ Black's passed pawn is under control, and we have a total domination of the light squares. There is no compensation whatsoever for the pawn. }
*

