d5
{ This is the most common one, but also allows White to play the strongest reply. }
7. Nc3 { We want to blow up Black's center as quickly as possible. } 7... Nbd7
{ This move order seems to me to be a little more accurate.   The big difference is that the plan with  8.e4  followed by 9.e5 does not work so well in this case, and many GMs have omitted this subtlety. Recently, Mamedyarov realized this and got very good results against the top players. }
8. e4 d4
{ Black wants to keep his three central pawns. Otherwise, the compensation will be gradually reduced with each pawn exchange. }
9. Nb1 { Our goal is building a blockade on light squares. } 9... Bb7 10. Bd3
Bxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. O-O
{ The next moves are very easy to play. We have to put pressure on e6, and Black wants to defend and develop at the same time. }
12... Ndf6 13. Nbd2 Nxd2 14. Bxd2 Qd5 15. Re1 Bd6 16. Qe2 h6
{ Black assumes he will lose the pawn and tries to prevent Ng5 and  prepare for the queenless middlegame.   16...Kd7  17.Rac1  After Qd3 we can continue with moves like Bg5-Nd2, we have absolute control of the light squares. Black's king will always be exposed and, once we have controlled Black's center, he can do little. }
17. Qxe6+ Qxe6 18. Rxe6+ Kd7 19. Rae1 Rae8 20. Rxe8 Rxe8 21. b3
{ We bring the king to the center and with the extra pawn and Black's weak light squares I see it very unlikely that the second player can defend this endgame.   21.Rxe8?  I like to end this variation with this little trap that we could easily fall into if we lower our guard once we have played all the opening preparation on the board,  21...Nxe8  22.b3  Ke6  Black's king gets active too quickly and White's queenside pawns will fall one by one. }
