5. Nc3 g6
{ Playing without taking quickly on d5 has a drawback. We can play e4 and take later on d5 with the e-pawn. The pawn symmetry gives us a comfortable space advantage. For this reason, Black usually goes for Bf5-Ne4 and exchanges a couple of pieces to have more space.     The main virtue is that Black directly avoids most of the critical lines. }
6. e4 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O exd5 9. exd5 Bg4
{ This may seem a success for Black. It is The fact that he wants to play Bg4 is very usual to free himself from the clumsy bishop. The subtle difference in this Benoni with a symmetric pawn structure is that Black has much less counterplay and can miss having more presence on the light squares.   For example, it is not a possible scenario in which Black can break with b5. }
10. h3 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Ne8
{ In these positions, it is very important to go for f5 with Black in order to hinder our plan Qc2-Bd2-Be2-f4-g4. Later we will see a model game on these structures, as I consider that they can be a bit complex to play with White at the beginning. }
12. Qc2 Nd7 13. Be2 f5 14. f4 a6 15. Bd2 Bd4+ 16. Kh2 Ng7 17. Bf3 Re8 18. Rae1
