[Round "?"]
[White "16. Modern Benoni"]
[Black "Modern Benoni 7...a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6
{ This seems to me the best move order, as Black keeps all the alternatives at his disposal. }
5. Nc3 exd5
{ The Benoni has always been special in my bond with chess. It was the first defense that I played since I was 11 years old until I was 15-16 exclusively, and it gave me very good results.   Its main virtue is that, even knowing that it is objectively weak, the answers to the different problems posed by Black are quite specific. White has to be constantly in a balance between controlling Black's counterplay and expanding by taking advantage of his central pawn majority.   While I try to explain each line, my main intention is to equip you with all the 'issues' we have to watch out for and that you can use them to counter the Benoni. }
6. cxd5 g6 7. h3
{ Preventing Bg4 and preparing the development of the bishop on c1. With this move, we open a safe square on h2 for the bishop in case Black plays Nh5.   7.Nd2  covered by Shankland, seems to me a very good alternative. However, there are certain variations which I find them too technical for White, so I preferred this alternative. }
7... a6 8. a4 Qe7
{ A very typical maneuver that I myself have played with success. Bf4 followed by e3 was not very popular before; therefore, it was a discomfort for White to be forced to give up playing e4 in one move. }
9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. e3 { And we end up transposing to 10... Qe7. } 10... Ne4
{ The only extra detail that this move order brings to Black is not very promising. }
11. Nxe4 Qxe4 12. Nd2 Qxd5 13. Nc4
{ We will take the d6-pawn back. Besides, Black will have the additional problem of not being able to move his queenside pawns, making them very vulnerable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16. Modern Benoni"]
[Black "Modern Benoni 8...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 d6 5. Nc3 exd5 6. cxd5 g6 7. h3 Bg7
{ The line  7...b5  8.Nxb5  Bg7  9.Bf4  transposes to 8...b5. } 8. Bf4 b5
{ This curious alternative was used by Paco Vallejo against me in the Blitz World Cup. Black sacrifices a side pawn  (the b-pawn)  to gain development times and recover the pawn in the future. }
9. Nxb5 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Ne4 { Here we see how the g7 bishop is activated. } 11.
Nd2
{ In the game, I continued with the safe  11.Bd2  and it was a game with comings and goings typical of blitz in which I ended up prevailing 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Alonso Rosell,A @@StartBracket@@2514@@EndBracket@@-Vallejo Pons,F @@StartBracket@@2644@@EndBracket@@ Almaty 2022. }
11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Bxc3 13. Rc1
{ And now we just want to continue with e2-e4, Be2 and O-O and Black will suddenly see that he has d6 weak and that our knight from d2 jumps to the c4 square wreaking havoc.  Black has all the pieces at home, he is not castled, and he will also have to lose another tempo for the bishop on c3. }
13... Nd7
{ As an example, I put the best sequence of Black to justify his initiative. Black will try to delay our castle as long as possible. }
14. e4 Rb8 15. Be2 Rb2 16. Rc2 Rxc2 17. Qxc2 Ba6 18. O-O
{ Thanks to some fancy stuff, we put our king into safety! } 18... Bxe2 19. Nb3
{ We recover the sacrificed bishop and the black position still has many problems. }
19... Qb4 20. Qxe2 c4 21. Na1
{ We will have a very good blockade on c2 and our knight in conjunction with the other pieces will jeopardize Black's delicate balance. }
