6. cxd5 g6 7. h3
{ Preventing Bg4 and preparing the development of the bishop on c1. With this move, we open a safe square on h2 for the bishop in case Black plays Nh5.   7.Nd2  covered by Shankland, seems to me a very good alternative. However, there are certain variations which I find them too technical for White, so I preferred this alternative. }
7... Bg7 8. Bf4
{ 8.e4  probably has been tried in 20 games, but the amount of variations you have to learn, and, especially the variation  8...O-O  followed by b5, make me inclined to recommend this alternative. }
8... O-O 9. e3
{ The key of this setup is that the bishop on e4 will eternally harass d6. Also, the bishop on c8 has no comfortable square to develop to due to the lack of space. That is the reason why this will always be an unresolved issue for Black.   The little price we pay is that we are not in time to play e4, as Black can continue with moves like Nxe4 and Re8. For this reason, we will regain the space in the center as soon as we have the chance to do so. }
9... a6
{ In the Benoni there is always the doubt whether the moves a6-a4 should be included or it is better to wait. In general, taking into account my personal experience, the differences are minimal. }
10. a4 Ne8
{ Black has maximum flexibility and  wants to develop the knight on b8, as d6 is defended. However, this also  allows a very interesting, yet little explored move. }
11. e4
{ This move has not been played in any of the 500 games that have reached this position. As Black does not have any presence in the center anymore, We take advantage of this to gain space there before finishing the development.   In general, it is not advisable to move the same pawn twice in the opening, but we will have already surprised the opponent and the position is easier to understand, in my opinion, with this pawn structure. }
11... f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. Be2
{ The hole on e6 is very weak and the bishop on f5 is still very vulnerable to g4. }
13... Nf6 14. O-O Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. g3
{ We want to play Ng5 and Ne6. The b2-pawn is relatively important, and this is because the knight on b8 and the rook on a8 are not playing and Black is in trouble due to the fact that the pawn on d6 is vulnerable. }
16... Bxb2 17. Ra2 Bf6 18. h4
{ Intending Ng5 and again, Black will struggle to find a safe square for the light-squared bishop. }
18... Bxf3 19. Bxf3
{ We will enter on e6 and Black will be very vulnerable to ideas like Bh6-f4-f5 or simply h5. Black's extra pawn is useless against White's attack, that can be combined with some pressure along the b and e-files, depending on the situation. }
