[White "17. Indian Defenses - Anti Benoni transpositions"]
[Black "3...c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 c5
{ We will see the different options that Black has in each move to avoid a hole in the repertoire that plays a dirty trick on us over the board. }
4. dxc5
{ This is one of the only cases in which taking on c5 could be better than pushing or letting Black take on d4. }
4... Qa5+ 5. Bd2 Qxc5 6. Nc3
{ Black is not developed and our c4-pawn is immune to capture. } 6... Qxc4 7.
Rc1 Nc6 8. e4 { Now White wins after a more or less forcing sequence. } 8...
Qe6 9. Nb5 Qxe4+ 10. Be2 Nd5 11. Rc4 Qe6
{ If  11...Qf5  we will play  12.Rc5! } 12. Ng5 Qf6 13. Bf3 Qe5+ 14. Re4 Qb8
15. Bf4
{ And Black's house will fall after 16.Nd6+. This is a great example of the activity of our pieces. I would recommend you try to complete how to finish off the game against each of Black's queen move as a good concrete calculation exercise.   There are several openings and defenses in which Black has these overly ambitious options to take pawns with the queen, and it is often hard to appreciate when do we have so many ways to threaten the exposed queen. }
