{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 c5
{ Here we can see the slight drawback of Black's mover order. WE would wish to play d5, but both the g3-Benoni @@StartBracket@@which I consider impractical for White@@EndBracket@@ and the g3-Benkö @@StartBracket@@which we do not cover in the course@@EndBracket@@ would annoy us a lot.   5.dxc5  is a quite weak move, as after  5...Qa5+  we cannot reply with Nc3-e4 as we have played g3. }
5. Nc3
{ I think I have played this kind of structures as White in 20 games or so. We give up the center a little bit, but we can enjoy our Catalan bishop on g2 at full power.   WATCH OUT here because  5.dxc5  would be enormously clumsy because of  5...Qa5+  and in this case we cannot go for a Maroczy kind of structure with Bd2-Nc3-e4-Bd3 as we have committed to g3.   In case of  5.Bg2  I found the reply  5...d5  quite annoying. We try to deal correctly with possible symmetries. }
5... Qa5
{ Black always tries to take advantage of what our move order allows.   5...d6  6.dxc5  we will exchange the queens and we will keep on putting our pieces closer to our opponent's king. If Black had the pawn on c6 it would still have some interest  (covering key squares such as d5 or b5 and leaving the knight on c3 somewhat useless)  but the symmetry is unfortunate for Black. }
6. Bg2 Ne4
{ The only real alternative that our move order allows.   6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  Qc5  8.b3  I wanted to mention this kind of maneuvers.  8.Qd3  seems to be very logical and healthy, but against  8...Ng4!  followed by Ne5 we would be in trouble. Now black simply does not have enough counterplay and we finish our development without problems. }
7. Qd3 { Defending c4, d4 and c3. } 7... cxd4
{ 7...Nxc3  8.Bd2  therein lies the key. We will not weaken the structure and we will gain a lot of presence in the center and development exploiting the fact that the Black queen is moving so much. }
8. Nxd4 Nc5 9. Qd1 Nc6 10. e3 Ne6
{ Black puts all the pressure on d4 to make us give up control. It is very feasible that before Nxc6, apart from worsening our pawn structure, we can fall into the annoying intermezzo ...Bxc3+!, which destroys our pawn structure and fights against our weak pawn on c4. }
11. O-O
{ The extra development allows us the luxury of giving up the pawn on d4. }
11... Nexd4
{ 11...O-O  12.Nde2  followed by Rb1-Qd2-b3-Bb2 with a clear advantage for White.The knight on e6 has been left with no real goal since it cannot be exchanged and Black has a couple of minor pieces left over considering the space available to them. }
12. exd4 Nxd4
{ The move  12...Bxd4  would not really change the outcome. After  13.Nd5  we will go for the same ideas. Even after  13...e6  14.Bh6!!  , Black would be lost anyway. }
13. Nd5
{ Our knight is threatening many things, and Black's queen is completely hopeless. }
13... Nc6
{ Against  13...e6  there is a very nice tactical theme:  14.Bh6!  and Black collapses.   13...Ne6  14.f4  f5  15.g4  the problem of ...Ne6 is that Black will never be able to castle comfortably and e7 is always a weakness. Another consideration is that the knight is badly placed and our natural development  (Be3)  nullifies it even more. Nor do we see on the horizon how Black will develop their queenside pieces. }
14. Bg5 { Threatening Bxe7! } 14... f6
{ If  14...O-O  we simply take on e7 and then follow up with Bd6! restricting Black's entire position. It doesn't matter that we lose the b2 pawn if Black can't move two of their pieces. }
15. Bf4 Ne5
{ Against  15...d6  both  16.Nxe7!  and  16.c5!  crack Black's fortress. } 16.
b4 { Starting a sequence of moves that will allow us to gain a lot of space. }
16... Qd8 17. c5 O-O 18. Rc1 e6 19. Bxe5 fxe5 20. Ne3
{ It is very common to make a transition from having sacrificed a pawn to suffocating the opponent with the extra tempi in development. Both Black's bishops are crying, while we have a clear plan with Qd3-Nc4-Nd6 that would leave Black totally in our hands. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Indian Defenses - Anti Benoni transpositions"]
[Black "4...c5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 c5
{ Here we can see the slight drawback of Black's mover order. WE would wish to play d5, but both the g3-Benoni @@StartBracket@@which I consider impractical for White@@EndBracket@@ and the g3-Benkö @@StartBracket@@which we do not cover in the course@@EndBracket@@ would annoy us a lot.   5.dxc5  is a quite weak move, as after  5...Qa5+  we cannot reply with Nc3-e4 as we have played g3. }
5. Nc3
{ I think I have played this kind of structures as White in 20 games or so. We give up the center a little bit, but we can enjoy our Catalan bishop on g2 at full power.   WATCH OUT here because  5.dxc5  would be enormously clumsy because of  5...Qa5+  and in this case we cannot go for a Maroczy kind of structure with Bd2-Nc3-e4-Bd3 as we have committed to g3.   In case of  5.Bg2  I found the reply  5...d5  quite annoying. We try to deal correctly with possible symmetries. }
5... cxd4
{ 5...d5  6.dxc5  Qa5  7.cxd5  and Black is simply a pawn down. Black does not arrive in time to generate any counterplay typical of the inverted Catalan. }
6. Nxd4 O-O
{ 6...Qc7  does not work so well in this move order because of  7.Bf4  . } 7.
Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O
{ Reaching one of the most frequently played positions of the entire game of chess. We could have also reached this position from the Symmetrical English. Now Black has three main alternatives. }
8... d6
{ The critical move of this variation. Black wants to develop their pieces by quickly offering a very interesting pawn sacrifice. }
9. Nc2
{ Here I was thinking about whether it was worthwhile to delve extensively into the critical  9.Nxc6  , but I think it doesn't pay off in the long run, as it requires extreme precision from our side and there is no real objective advantage either. So I prefer to give you this more consistent move that I played myself years ago.   White is humbled by his ambitions and prepares to develop with Bd2-b3 and keep control of the center.   Another idea such as  9.e3  would give Black good play after  9...Bg4!  10.Qd2  Qd7  . }
9... Qa5 10. Bd2 Qh5
{ This is Black's idea, exploiting the fact that White's knight is not in the kingside. }
11. e4
{ The queen trade favors us as the space in the center is under our control. }
11... Ng4 12. h4
{ The problem with  12.h3  is that after  12...Nge5  and the queen trade black is threatening both ...Nxc4 and ...Bxh3!, followed by ...Nf3+. The text move defends against the checkmate, and our idea is to play f3. The queen also has certain problems to meet, Nd5-Nf4. }
12... f5
{ Black's only move to capitalize on the move h2-h4; other moves would simply lead us to continue with the usual sequence of moves. }
13. Nd5 { Intending to discomfort the queen. } 13... Nge5
{ 13...fxe4  14.Bxe4  and our idea is to continue with Bg5, after which Black's position is completely clumsy. }
14. exf5
{ Black should take on f5 and we will continue with Nce3 and Bc3, giving meaning to all our pieces.   These positions of 2 vs. 3 pawn islands @@StartBracket@@a-b and g-h against a-b-c f-g-h@@EndBracket@@ are always problematic for the side with 3 islands as they have to simultaneously defend 3 pawn chains, while we can easily vary the pressure and enjoy the space and activity of our pieces. }
*

