Bg2 Nc6 8. O-O
{ Reaching one of the most frequently played positions of the entire game of chess. We could have also reached this position from the Symmetrical English. Now Black has three main alternatives. }
8... Qa5
{ Aiming to hinder our development and also make it difficult to defend c4. }
9. e3
{ The healthiest option, in my opinion, overdefending d4 and increasing our fleibility to be able to neutralize the threats of Black's queen. Now we pose the next question: How do we develop the rest of the pieces? }
9... Ne5 10. Qe2 Qb4
{ It is important for us to be alert to all combinations. Now we see that we cannot defend c4 in any conventional way.   10...d6  11.h3  and, if Black does not force us to go f4 by playing ...Qb4 we will continue with Bd2-b3 with the typical space advantage. }
11. f4 Nxc4
{ This move loses after:   If  11...Nc6  12.Nc2  we continue with Rb1-b4, and again we enjoy all the space in the world. Black has spent a million tempi with the minor pieces and the queen has achieved nothing. }
12. a3 Qc5 13. b4 Qc7 14. Ncb5 { Winning a clear piece for nothing. } *

