{ Aiming to hinder our development and also make it difficult to defend c4. }
9. e3
{ The healthiest option, in my opinion, overdefending d4 and increasing our fleibility to be able to neutralize the threats of Black's queen. Now we pose the next question: How do we develop the rest of the pieces? }
9... d6
{ Black offers the pawn again. Now it would be horrible to accept it, having invested some time in a center holding move like 9.e3, which would contribute nothing after having taken on c6. }
10. Bd2
{ Almost by elimination, we continue with our development. Now, Black has several moves to embarrass our strange development. }
10... Qc5
{ Against  10...Qb6  we could play the same way for practicality's sake.   10...Bd7  11.b3  Rfc8  it is common for Black to aim to connect the rooks and then return with the queen to d8.  12.Rc1  we want to play Qe2-Rfd1 and then continue with Nxc6 and e4. Suddenly, everything makes sense: we control the center and enjoy a lot of space for our pieces. }
11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Rc1
{ After b3-e4-Be3-h3-Kh2 we have again the typical comfortable position. Here I propose a different plan just to give you more options. Our idea is to follow with f4 and generate options to play e4-e5 to crush Black. }
