{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 c5
{ Here we can see the slight drawback of Black's mover order. WE would wish to play d5, but both the g3-Benoni @@StartBracket@@which I consider impractical for White@@EndBracket@@ and the g3-Benkö @@StartBracket@@which we do not cover in the course@@EndBracket@@ would annoy us a lot.   5.dxc5  is a quite weak move, as after  5...Qa5+  we cannot reply with Nc3-e4 as we have played g3. }
5. Nc3
{ I think I have played this kind of structures as White in 20 games or so. We give up the center a little bit, but we can enjoy our Catalan bishop on g2 at full power.   WATCH OUT here because  5.dxc5  would be enormously clumsy because of  5...Qa5+  and in this case we cannot go for a Maroczy kind of structure with Bd2-Nc3-e4-Bd3 as we have committed to g3.   In case of  5.Bg2  I found the reply  5...d5  quite annoying. We try to deal correctly with possible symmetries. }
5... cxd4
{ 5...d5  6.dxc5  Qa5  7.cxd5  and Black is simply a pawn down. Black does not arrive in time to generate any counterplay typical of the inverted Catalan. }
6. Nxd4 d5 { Black's aim is to liquidate the whole pawn center. } 7. Bg2
{ Playing in Catalan style, which means giving priority to the development of the bishop on g2. }
7... e5
{ Both  7...dxc4  and  7...e6  were very weak moves due to  @@StartFEN@@@@EndFEN@@  8.Qa4+  and  (@@StartFEN@@@@EndFEN@@8.Bg5)  respectively. }
8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Ndb5 O-O
{ Only move. Now we have to make sure that the pinned knight on b5 does not create any problems for us.   The point is that Black's a6 does not threaten the knight, but let's note that if we want to unpin with Qa3 @@StartBracket@@and keep Black's a-pawn pinned@@EndBracket@@ the b5-knight will only be able to jump into enemy territory through the d6-square so not acting in anticipation of these threats can be dangerous for White. }
10. Bg5 { Keeping our initiative going. } 10... d4
{ This move requires a certain amount of cold blood.   If  11.Bxb7  a6!  loses both knights. Black has to find a lot of only moves to reach this position. }
11. Nd5 Bc6
{ 11...a6  this tempting move is a blunder  12.Qa3  entering decisively on c7 and d6. After ...Bc6, Nd6 is very oppressive. It is a very curious maneuver to take everything on f6 and continue with ...Nc7....Nd5. This sequence is forced and can benefit us, as Black has to find a compromising Ra7 move at some point. }
12. Qa3 { Threatening Nbc7. } 12... Bxd5 13. cxd5
{ If black does nothing and allows our knight to d6, he would be in trouble. Our priorities would be O-O, Nd6 and Rac1 and black has to play very precisely as our pieces are very active. }
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Rc1
{ Threatening Nc7, forcing Black knight's condemnation. } 15... Na6
{ If  15...Nd7  16.Nc7  Rc8  17.d6!  wins some of Black's queenside pawns. }
16. O-O Qb6
{ If Black tries ...Bg5 we will meet it with f4!, and eventually f5.   In case of  16...Qd7  we could play  17.Nd6  , even if scary @@StartBracket@@if  17...Be7  18.Ne4!  with a nice fork on f6@@EndBracket@@.  The move  17.Qb3!  makes us pay attention to the poor Black coordination. }
17. Qd6 Qxb5
{ Taking on d6 would mean ceding control of the c file and giving us all the initiative. }
18. Qxf6 Rae8 19. Be4 { Intending to go Bxg6. } 19... Qxe2
{ For example.   19...Nb4  another only move from another planet  20.Qd6  renewing the threat of Bxg6  20...Nxa2  Obvious, isn't it? :  21.Rc7  I will end the variation here. Black has a lot of problems, starting with our Bxg6 and Black's position is impossibly difficult due to the activity of our rooks and the passed pawn.   Black evaluates that after @@StartFEN@@4rrk1/pp3p2/5Qpp/1q1Pp3/1n1pB3/6P1/PP2PP1P/2R2RK1 w - - 3 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bxg6  Nxd5  they arrive in time. }
20. Bxg6 fxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Qxh6+ Kg8 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Rce1
{ And the rook lift Re4-Rh4 is irresistible @@StartBracket@@be careful with ...Qxh4 followed by Rg8!@@EndBracket@@. We can also go for the maneuver Qh5+ followed by Rg4. }
