{ A very interesting way of playing against Black's chosen move order.   Against  7.Nxd4  we find that ...d5 is very dry. It is unusual to find these move orders as they are unambitious for Black @@StartBracket@@symmetries with tempi down that give few options to Black are also common@@EndBracket@@.   In fact, I had never paid attention to them until writing this course, but perhaps, erring on the side of thoroughness, I prefer to give you this alternative.  If you prefer  7.Nxd4  in case you expect your opponent to transpose to more normal stuff with  7...Nc6  , it is covered in the course as well.     What does Qxd4 do? WE want to bring the queen to h4 to hassle Black on the kingside. }
7... d5 8. cxd5 Qxd5
{ There are certain symmetries that are very delicate for Black to deal with. }
9. Nc3 Qh5
{ If  9...Qxd4  10.Nxd4  and this symmetry with two extra tempi is a very bad sign.Black's position is already very difficult, and developing the queenside is going to be an odyssey. Rd1 and we can see if Bg5-Bf4 or Be3 is of interest to us. Each of Black's moves can be the last chance to stay in the game. }
10. Qe5
{ We continue with our plans to exchange queens and enjoy a comfortable plus in development. }
10... Nc6 11. Qxh5 Nxh5 12. Rd1 Be6
{ 12...h6  13.Be3  is played here, and the plan Ne1-Nd3-Nc5 would be a headache for Black. }
13. Be3 Rfd8 14. Ng5 { Nge4 and Nc5 would make Black's defense difficult. } *

