2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... c5
{ Finally, Black can opt for this move order.   Now if  6.Nc3  d5  seems annoying to me.  Remember that we used to play  6.dxc5  but only when the knight was on c3 and our bishop on f1. These d5-ideas lead to drawish positions and are not so ambitious, but are quite annoying for our interests.   Another option is to simply play normal moves, ignoring their ideas. In the 99% of the times you will face ...d6, so this strategy is not bad either. }
6. O-O cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ A very interesting way of playing against Black's chosen move order.   Against  7.Nxd4  we find that ...d5 is very dry. It is unusual to find these move orders as they are unambitious for Black @@StartBracket@@symmetries with tempi down that give few options to Black are also common@@EndBracket@@.   In fact, I had never paid attention to them until writing this course, but perhaps, erring on the side of thoroughness, I prefer to give you this alternative.  If you prefer  7.Nxd4  in case you expect your opponent to transpose to more normal stuff with  7...Nc6  , it is covered in the course as well.     What does Qxd4 do? WE want to bring the queen to h4 to hassle Black on the kingside. }
7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Qh4 Nc6
{ The best move. It's a little scary to walk into a pin  (on the d-file)  by yourself and be vulnerable to ideas such as ...Bh6 if you do not know what you're doing. }
10. Rd1 Qa5
{ The most natural way of unpinning the d5-knight.   10...e6  11.Bg5  f6  12.Bd2  and, again, I find this position very difficult to play for Black. }
11. Bd2 Qb5
{ After  11...Qb6  12.Nc3  Nxc3  13.Bxc3  we will continue with Nd4 with a slightly better position thanks to our Catalan bishop. }
12. e4 { Deviating from the game Dubov-Jones played in 2018. } 12... Nf6
{ All this disjointed engine play is hardly to be expected, but I guess I am a bit stubborn that we will not have practical problems. The problem of having played e4 is that many times the bishop on g2 is not active, and we have to justify this setup; otherwise, we will have problems. }
13. Nc3 Qxb2
{ Other moves would leave Black underdeveloped. It is to be expected that it would not be very appetizing to go into this sequence with Black. }
14. h3 { Threatening e5 and preventing Black's knight from jumping to g4. }
14... Rd8
{ If ...Nd7 we could go Rab1 and Nd5, I really like our initiative and the clumsiness of Black's pieces. }
15. e5 Ne8 16. Rdb1 Qc2
{ 16...Qa3  17.Ne4  and the threat of Bb4 hinders ...Nxe5. Therefore, Black is very vulnerable to attacking moves like Nfg5 and Nxf7 tactics, among other things. }
17. Rc1 Qf5 18. g4 Qd3
{ Now it turns out that if we play Be3 things will change, and we will be able to take on e5. Against Rd1, the move ...Qxc3 will be possible as after playing g4 we will no longer be able to hide on h2. This is even more than an opening lesson, I think it is a good tactical exercise, and it is good for you to appreciate the changing nature of small details in a chess position.   18...Qd7  19.e6  . }
19. Rd1
{ Aiming to play Rac1 with a nice compensation. Maybe we can later continue Re1-Ne4 and try to find mating nets. }
19... Qc2 { Another interesting move. } 20. Rac1 Qb2 21. Ne4
{ With a correct defense, Black could stay in the game, but I think that our position is much easier to play in practice. We aim for Re1, with this move we free the d1-rook from the defense of the d2-bishop. }
