12. e4 { Deviating from the game Dubov-Jones played in 2018. } 12... Nb6 13.
Bc3 Be6
{ Black's only move, but I find it an incredible and difficult one to find.   If  13...h6  14.Nbd2  we aim for Nb3-Nd4 unless Black plays ...Bxc3 and ...Kg7, when Black would counter our idea with...e5!. If Black takes the bishop on c3 and plays Kg7, we immediately counter with Nd4. Another latent white threat is a4! since Black cannot capture with the knight since Bf1! wins material for White. Black has had to play quite precise to get here, and I think that in this position Black still has to justify their setup and respond to our simple ideas.   After  13...Bxc3  White plays  14.Nxc3  Qxb2  15.Nd5  with the idea of playing a4 or Rac1. I find it very difficult to enter this variation as Black because their king feels very vulnerable and our pieces are quite annoying for our opponent. In many situations we will continue with Nc7 and e5 to open our bishop's way. }
14. Ng5 h6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Qg4 Kh7 17. e5
{ We sacrifice the pawn and, in return, we get the key e4-square. I believe this position is very hard to play with Black and their pawn structure confirms my point. We will simply aim at finishing our development and Black should take care of their weaknesses. }
