{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... c5
{ Finally, Black can opt for this move order.   Now if  6.Nc3  d5  seems annoying to me.  Remember that we used to play  6.dxc5  but only when the knight was on c3 and our bishop on f1. These d5-ideas lead to drawish positions and are not so ambitious, but are quite annoying for our interests.   Another option is to simply play normal moves, ignoring their ideas. In the 99% of the times you will face ...d6, so this strategy is not bad either. }
6. O-O cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ A very interesting way of playing against Black's chosen move order.   Against  7.Nxd4  we find that ...d5 is very dry. It is unusual to find these move orders as they are unambitious for Black @@StartBracket@@symmetries with tempi down that give few options to Black are also common@@EndBracket@@.   In fact, I had never paid attention to them until writing this course, but perhaps, erring on the side of thoroughness, I prefer to give you this alternative.  If you prefer  7.Nxd4  in case you expect your opponent to transpose to more normal stuff with  7...Nc6  , it is covered in the course as well.     What does Qxd4 do? WE want to bring the queen to h4 to hassle Black on the kingside. }
7... h6
{ What if Black does not want our queen to go to h4? This is a reasonable option that has been played by several GM's. Among them, someone called Ding Liren. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Qd2
{ A very typical retreat. When we fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, we already point to an ideal square to defend the c3-knight.   9.Qd3  would be an inaccuracy because  9...d6  10.b3  Bf5!  is really annoying since we cannot meet it with e4. }
9... d6 10. b3
{ Here it is also noteworthy that Black has played ...h6, as we shall see. }
10... Ne4
{ After  10...Be6  11.Bb2  I like to continue with moves such as Rfd1, Rac1 and later Ne1-Nd3. With this maneuver, we strengthen our light-squared bishop, take advantage of relevant squares such as b4 and our knight can jump to f4 to tame Black's ...d5 break. By not having exchanged minor pieces, Black will feel a bit uncomfortable. }
11. Nxe4 Bxa1 12. Qxh6 Bg7 13. Qh4 f6
{ It seems that Black prevents our plan to invade g5 with the knight followed by Qh7. }
14. Nfg5
{ We will have to see about that!   Starting with  14.Rd1  is even better, so I let you know about it here in case you want to investigate further.   But I feel that 14. Nfg5 is easier to explain and understand. : }
14... fxg5 15. Nxg5 Rf6 { The only good response against both Qh7+ and Bd5+. }
16. Rd1
{ After Bb2 e5 our bishop would be out of play, even though we can invade the d5-square with Bd5+. Now the rook enters the equation and Black continues to watch helplessly as they cannot bring their queenside pieces into play. }
16... Kf8 17. Bb2 e5 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Bxe5
{ We see the usefulness of bringing the rook on d1 first. In the worst case scenario, we are threatening Bxf6 and Nh7+ followed by taking everything on f6. Besides, we can enter with the rook by taking on d6 and we will reach an endgame of rook and 7 pawns against rook, bishop, and two pawns.   For example, after the best move  19...Qe7  we play  20.Nh7+  Kf7  21.Bxf6  Bxf6  22.Qxf6+  Qxf6  23.Nxf6  Kxf6  24.Rxd6+  followed by Rxc6, reaching a version of the aforementioned endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. Indian Defenses - Anti Benoni transpositions"]
[Black "5...c5 6.O-O cxd4 7.Qxd4 with 8.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... c5
{ Finally, Black can opt for this move order.   Now if  6.Nc3  d5  seems annoying to me.  Remember that we used to play  6.dxc5  but only when the knight was on c3 and our bishop on f1. These d5-ideas lead to drawish positions and are not so ambitious, but are quite annoying for our interests.   Another option is to simply play normal moves, ignoring their ideas. In the 99% of the times you will face ...d6, so this strategy is not bad either. }
6. O-O cxd4 7. Qxd4
{ A very interesting way of playing against Black's chosen move order.   Against  7.Nxd4  we find that ...d5 is very dry. It is unusual to find these move orders as they are unambitious for Black @@StartBracket@@symmetries with tempi down that give few options to Black are also common@@EndBracket@@.   In fact, I had never paid attention to them until writing this course, but perhaps, erring on the side of thoroughness, I prefer to give you this alternative.  If you prefer  7.Nxd4  in case you expect your opponent to transpose to more normal stuff with  7...Nc6  , it is covered in the course as well.     What does Qxd4 do? WE want to bring the queen to h4 to hassle Black on the kingside. }
7... h6
{ What if Black does not want our queen to go to h4? This is a reasonable option that has been played by several GM's. Among them, someone called Ding Liren. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Qd2
{ A very typical retreat. When we fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, we already point to an ideal square to defend the c3-knight.   9.Qd3  would be an inaccuracy because  9...d6  10.b3  Bf5!  is really annoying since we cannot meet it with e4. }
9... Qa5
{ Black will not let us play b3 as ...d5!-ideas —or Rd8 followed by ...d5!— could catch us half-developed. }
10. Rb1
{ Exploiting the fact that the queen is exposed to develop our pieces more ambitiously. }
10... d6 11. b4 Qd8 12. Nd5
{ Again, it is key for us that Black's h-pawn on h6. Usually, Black is not intimidated by White's Nd5-ideas as they can ignore it. But in this case the h6-pawn will be hanging after recapture our knight on f6. Both letting Black take our d5-knight or taking the f6-knight ourselves are very unpleasant for Black. }
12... Bf5
{ Our idea is to continue with Bb2, so Black has to be alert and react against it. }
13. Rb3 Ne4
{ Against other moves, we will simply take on f6, ruining Black's pawn structure. }
14. Qd1
{ We will continue with Ne3 and Bb2, exchanging the key dark-squared bishop or, at least, reducing its power. Then we can continue with our queenside expansion with a4-a5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Grünfeld without ...c6"]
[Black "4....d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3
{ I wanted my recommendations to keep the maximum flexibility possible according to what I recommend in the Catalan chapters.   There are quite a few players who opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  and if Black plays  2...d5  , they go  3.Bf4  and if they continue  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  they can already play the King's Indian.   It is very important to be aware of our memory and mastery of the openings and these little shortcuts or tricks in the move orders that allow you to 'close' one way while you are learning another. It is better to have a simpler path than to go into main lines with everything half done.   For all these reasons I continue with this move order which will also benefit Reti players  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  --  2.c4  and you will be able to appreciate Black's numerous reactions.   At the top level it is considered that the most precise move order is  3.g3  delaying as much as possible the move Nf3 to keep the dxc5! option open in case Black wants to transpose to Benoni positions by going ...c7-c5.   The move 3.g3 allows certain move order pluses against the Grünfeld in some concrete variations. The point is that, in exchange for these small details, we lost a lot of move order flexibility and we did not avoid the most relevant variations with ...d6 or ...c6-d5.   So consistently with the rest of this course and the Part 1 we will go for this move order and give an answer to all Black's alternatives. }
3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... d5
{ This move order allows an extra option for Black and, besides, our opponent has some chances of getting worse. Taking that into account, we should not be worried about this sequence of moves. }
5. cxd5
{ The  5.Bg2  variations involving the sacrifice of the c4-pawn are also interesting, but, in general, I think our main reply will be cxd5. }
5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 Nb6
{ Black can avoid ...O-O if they want to, but it is important for our opponent to start with the text move.   The move order  6...Nc6  can be punished easily with  7.e4  Nb6  8.d5  Na5  it is very typical for Black to go for ...c7-c6 to break in the center and increase the g7-bishop's power.  9.Qc2!  If we played  9.O-O  , after  9...c6!  black would have got dangerously far in its ambition to burst our center.   Now we can simply continue with Bd2-Bc3 to neutralize our opponent's counterplay by trading the dark-sqaured bishops. Against  9...f5  the amazing  10.e5!  push seems to be very strong, but it rqeuieres certain knowledge of what we should be aiming for. Therefore, the simple  10.Ng5  aiming at the e6-weakness we would have a nice and comfortable advantage by simply developing our pieces.   6...c5?!  7.e4  followed likely by d5 and then, if Black goes for ...e6, we can go for typical Bg5! ideas, which will be quite annoying for Black. Our opponent has lost quite a few tempi with their knight and, in general, it is not recommendable for Black to allow White to go for e4 without being able to take the c3-knight. That is why Black usually waits for us to play Nc3  (threatening e2-e4, moving to a King's Indian)  to play ...d5. }
7. O-O Nc6 8. e3 e5 9. Nc3
{ Black usually transposes here with  9...O-O  but we will allow him to go for a variation that could give us an advantage. }
9... Bg4
{ This move has been played in quite a few games, but it is very risky to keep the game going without castling. }
10. d5 e4
{ If the c6-knight moves, we would play  11.h3  reinforcing our center. } 11.
dxc6 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxf3
{ After  12...exf3  13.cxb7  Rb8  14.h3  the endgame is very bad for Black, as they are a pawn down and the queenside structure is quite weak. }
13. Bxf3 exf3 14. cxb7
{ We will continue with moves such as Rb1-Ne4-b3-Bd2 and our idea is to wait for the right moment to consolidate our extra pawn by taking on f3 with the knight. Black cannot keep the pawn and, in addition, the queenside pawn structure is quite bad for them. }
*

