{ Taking on d4 is bad for many reasons.   After  10...Nxd4  11.Nxd4  and both our Nb5 ideas and Black being vulnerable to forks on c7 give us an advantage even if the queens are off the board. In addition, Black will have to withstand a future Re1+ and will have to give the key b7 pawn as it is totally hopeless to be left without castling against our overwhelming activity. }
11. Bg5
{ A very common move. Black does not want to give up their dark-squared bishop neither to play the weakening move ...f6. }
11... Qd7 12. Ne4 { Aiming for Nf6. } 12... Nd5
{ After  12...f6  we will play  13.Bf4  followed by developing our rooks. Again we will benefit from the weakness of the black kingside. }
13. Re1
{ Following our natural development. We will have an eye on the c5-square for our knight to eventually get there while BLack, however, suddenly realizes that the c8-bishop cannot be developed by conventional means. }
13... h6 14. Bd2 Qd8 { Black's aim is to develop the c8-bishop. } 15. Qb3
{ Gently hindering the c8-bishop development, as we are putting pressure on b7. Later on, we will continue with something like Rad1, Nc5 and Ne5 reaching a comfortable position, in my opinion. We will move around the central blockade and Black cannot find a pleasant way of developing their pieces.   If Black tries ...b6, then we could play Rac1 and meet ...Nce7 with Qd3 intending to go b4 and consolidate the pressure we exert along the c-file on Black's c7-pawn, as it has lost the support from its partner on b7. }
