4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5
{ It seems sensible to me to simplify the variations and assume that we capture as long as Black does not have the d5 pawn defended by a pawn.   Playing gambit-style is interesting but the resulting positions are more preferable for Black @@StartBracket@@we will have a better center while BLack will enjoy a typical counterplay, much more common in the Grünfeld, after something like dxc4-Na3-c3-bxc3@@EndBracket@@. Instead, after cxd5 we are looking for somewhat different positions than usual in which Black plays with minor pieces rather than pawns. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O c5 8. e4
{ Gaining some space in the center and our development becomes quite dangerous for Black. }
8... Nf6
{ If  8...Nb6  9.d5  followed by Nc3 and Re1. We have a strong center and Black has lost quite some tempi with the knight. Against ...e6 we could simply go Bg5 to uncoordinate Black's pieces. }
9. e5 Nfd7
{ This move was played by Nepomniachtchi in quite some games, but it can be met with a very tipical plan that White has available in the Grünfeld. }
10. e6
{ We often simply sacrifice the pawn to ruin Black's structure and hinder the development of the bishop on c8, but here Black also has more concrete problems. }
10... fxe6 11. Ng5
{ To give you an idea, we will get a great long-term advantage by simply going  11.dxc5  and Nc3 next, following our normal development. }
11... Nf6
{ 11...Qb6  12.Qe2  and we will win the exchange after Qxe6+ or play dxc5 and Black's position would be worse in both cases. }
12. Qe1
{ Now with  12.Qe2  Black would play  12...Nc6  and after  13.Nxe6  Nxd4!  would be extremely annoying for Black. We will take on e6 or on c5, as convenience, and Black will have weaknesses on the light squares. Our Catalan bishop is very strong and, above all, it is very uncomfortable for Black to deal with so many holes and imbalances. }
