3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5
{ It seems sensible to me to simplify the variations and assume that we capture as long as Black does not have the d5 pawn defended by a pawn.   Playing gambit-style is interesting but the resulting positions are more preferable for Black @@StartBracket@@we will have a better center while BLack will enjoy a typical counterplay, much more common in the Grünfeld, after something like dxc4-Na3-c3-bxc3@@EndBracket@@. Instead, after cxd5 we are looking for somewhat different positions than usual in which Black plays with minor pieces rather than pawns. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nc6 8. e4
{ I remember that here we also have the option of playing 8. Nc3 and go back to known territory. }
8... Nb6 9. d5 Na5
{ 9...Ne5  10.Nxe5  Bxe5  11.Nc3  followed by Qb3 and, if Black takes it easy, a4 to greatly annoy the knight on b6. The bishop on c1 has several options for direct development, but the most usual would be h6 or e3 and our rooks will probably end up on d1 and e1. The bishop on c8 will always be uncomfortable because of the X-ray pressure on the b7 pawn and will be hindered in case we need to relocate the knight. }
10. Qe1
{ We want to discomfort the knight on a5 and at the same time defend the c3 square to be able to bring our knight there.   Besides, this move is more concrete than, say  10.Nc3  c6  when Black's play is very automatic. }
10... Nac4 11. Nc3 e6 12. Bg5
{ If Black plays  11...e6  the story is a bit different. Now the line  12.b3  Qf6!  has been quite successful for Black. Instead, we go for a typical idea in these positions: develop the bishop to hassle Black's queen. }
12... f6 { Otherwise, we wuld play b3. } 13. Bc1
{ Again, Black's structure is ruined. } 13... exd5 14. exd5 Nxd5
{ If Black does not take on d5, we would continue with the typical harassment to BLack's knights with a2-a4 and our queen would go to b3, again taking advantage of the weak a2-g8 diagonal. In such a scenario, Black will not be able to clear space for the g7-bishop with ...f5-break without first exchanging our knight on f3, and that will not be possible because of Bg5, putting pressure on e7, and because of our Ng5-Ne6 ideas. }
15. Nd4
{ Exploiting the recently created hole on e6 and the weaknesses on the light squares in Black's camp. }
15... Nxc3
{ Other moves would allow Ne6 and the b7-pawn would be hanging in case Black takes our knight with the bishop. }
16. Qxc3 Nb6 17. Bf4 c6 18. Rad1
{ A very good example of how much venom this varaition has. If we manage to start an attack, our development can be fulminant. I will show an example variation with some difficulty so that we get used to look for interactions with minor pieces. }
18... Qe7 { Black seeks shelter from the siege of our rooks. } 19. Rfe1 Qf7 20.
Bd6 Rd8 { Trading rooks when you have the other one undeveloped is suicidal. }
21. Bc7
{ Now the concrete and precise move. We have to keep in mind that the pawn on c6 nullifies quite well our knight on d4 and our bishop on g2, so we have to be incisive. }
21... Nd5
{ Against  21...Rd7  we would play  22.Bxb6  axb6  23.Nxc6!  and we will take on c6 with the queen. The threats of Bd5, winning the queen, and the attack on the rook on a8 decide the game in our favor.   21...Qxc7  22.Nb5  and Black will lose material. }
22. Nxc6 { It is fantastic to see all our pieces coordinated. } 22... Nxc3
{ After  22...bxc6  23.Qxc6  would you win this position? } 23. Rxd8+ Bf8 24.
Bd6 { Black cannot do anything to save the queen. } 24... bxc6 25. Rxf8+ Qxf8
26. Bxf8 Kxf8 27. Bxc6 Rb8 28. bxc3
{ All in all we will gain a healthy extra pawn. It is a good example for you to look for creativity and intermediate moves. }
*

