{ It is very common for Black to delay the e7-e5 push and try to take advantage of our great freedom of moves to confuse us. }
10. h3
{ After  10.d5  Na5  11.Nd4  Black will continue with  11...Bd7  followed by ...c6 and there will be nothing left of our beautiful center. Our problem in this Grunfeld variation often lies in the clumsiness of the bishop on c1, so by expanding in the center we can overextend and then suffer an unforeseen event by not being able to free the bishop on c1 and the rook on a1.   This is why Bg5 and forcing f6 is common, because it solves both problems at once. With 10. h3 we wait for BLack to define what they are going to do and, in general, this is an useful move to prevent future pins by means of ...Bg4. Thus, options to expand with e4 without weakening the d4 point so much are on the menu. }
10... e5 11. d5 Na5
{ Now this option has more importance as ...Re8 is much more useful than h3. }
12. Qc2
{ If we fail to consolidate the center, it is highly recommended to avoid playing e4 and close the bishop diagonal on g2. We want to continue with Td1 and take advantage of the fact that Black cannot take on d5.   12.e4  The move e4 does not work so well now that the moves ...Re8 and h3 are included.  12...c6  13.Bg5  as always, we take advantage of the opportunity to weaken Black's castling.  13...f6  14.Be3  Nac4  Black has a good game, I think, but White has a score of 90%.   White has some initiative and Black's isolated pawn on c6 could be bothersome. However, Black is fine because of the power of the bishop pair and White's clumsy knight on f3 and bishop on g2. Looking at the games, it is pure coincidence that White has had such a resounding success, so be careful to be guided only by percentages. }
12... Bd7
{ It is a common attempt to look for ...Qc8 to move away from the d-file and help playing for c7-c6.   12...e4  now this thematic sacrifice does not so well. THe knight on a5 is out somehow.  13.Nxe4  Qxd5  14.Nd4  our knights are two beasts and I cannot say how will BLack deal with our a5-knight and their c8-bishop. }
13. Rd1 Qc8 14. Kh2 c6 15. dxc6 Nxc6
{ 15...Bxc6  16.e4  now we see how all of Black's pieces have 'jumps' to light squares and we benefit from playing b3 and then Bg5 or Be3. }
16. Ng5
{ Now we can go for moves such as Ne4 and b3-Ba3 or b3-a4 which will highlight Black's weaknesses on dark squares and also the advantage of having the pawn on e3, as it is covering the d4-square and allowing our g2-bishop to play. Compare these two pieces with Black's pawn on e5, which does not control neither d6 nor d5 and, besides, is in the way of Black's g7-bishop. }
*

