3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5
{ It seems sensible to me to simplify the variations and assume that we capture as long as Black does not have the d5 pawn defended by a pawn.   Playing gambit-style is interesting but the resulting positions are more preferable for Black @@StartBracket@@we will have a better center while BLack will enjoy a typical counterplay, much more common in the Grünfeld, after something like dxc4-Na3-c3-bxc3@@EndBracket@@. Instead, after cxd5 we are looking for somewhat different positions than usual in which Black plays with minor pieces rather than pawns. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6
{ The most accurate move order to avoid our expansion and kick our opponents' knights away with e4 and d5. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ Defending the center and now Black has a wide range of options to prepare the move e7-e5 at the right time. The main risk of our position is that the development is not logical at all and solving the situation of the bishop on c1 is annoying.   If b3, Black would play ...e5 and we would have problems on the long diagonal. If we develop the bishop to d2 it will hinder our major pieces. So we must be patient and make slight moves that improve our position. }
9... Re8
{ It is very common for Black to delay the e7-e5 push and try to take advantage of our great freedom of moves to confuse us. }
10. h3
{ After  10.d5  Na5  11.Nd4  Black will continue with  11...Bd7  followed by ...c6 and there will be nothing left of our beautiful center. Our problem in this Grunfeld variation often lies in the clumsiness of the bishop on c1, so by expanding in the center we can overextend and then suffer an unforeseen event by not being able to free the bishop on c1 and the rook on a1.   This is why Bg5 and forcing f6 is common, because it solves both problems at once. With 10. h3 we wait for BLack to define what they are going to do and, in general, this is an useful move to prevent future pins by means of ...Bg4. Thus, options to expand with e4 without weakening the d4 point so much are on the menu. }
10... a5
{ Black continues delaying their decision making. The idea of ...a5 is to hinder the c1-bishop's development y means of ...a5-a4. Another global idea of ​​the grunfeld is that due to the power of the bishop on g7 and the volatility of the center, everything that goes towards generating a possible imbalance or passed pawn will likely favor Black. }
11. d5
{ The strong GM Oparin is our model player when going for this move. Now lack does not have the thematic reply ...Na5, so he has to make a decision regarding the c6-knight's destination. }
11... Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. e4 e6
{ c6 would lead to a slightly worse version of these variations. The knight b6 feels more vulnerable and Black will still not have opened the e-file on their own benefit. We will continue with the same plan of playing Bh6 and Re1. }
14. Bh6
{ In case you are wondering: Àlvar, is it not possible for Black to bring the bishop to g7 first? That is a good question. The problem for Black would be that we would continue simply with Bf4 and we could transfer the pressure to the c7-point and bring our rooks to c1 and e1. }
14... exd5 15. exd5 Nc4 16. Re1 { This position has been reached in 9 games. }
16... Nxb2
{ Taking the pawn is extremely risky.   16...Nd6  17.Qd2  and we look for bringing the bishop to g5, which will be extremely annoying for Black's queen. Later on we will see how weak the c7-pawn will be in this pawn structure in the long-term  (by means of an eventual Ne4)  .   The problem lies in the fact that the bishop on e5 will be tied to the defense of the castling and, at the same time, of the defense of the c7-pawn. It could also be possible to double the rooks on the e-file, but this is more difficult to achieve than it seems.  17...Qf6  .   After  16...Bd7  Black lost a couple of games following  17.Rxe5!  and, after f4 and DQd4 the second player loses material. }
17. Qe2
{ The e5-pawn is pinned and Black's knight is trapped, so it seems we have won a piece. However Black has an ace in the sleeve. }
17... Na4 18. Nxa4 Bd7 19. Qd2
{ Amazingly,  19.Qc2  loses to  19...Bxa4  20.Qxa4  Bxa1  21.Rxa1  Qf6!  and after ...g5 our bishop is trapped on h6. This is the typical line that Black could find by chance, so we have to be alert to our opponent's forcing sequences of moves. }
19... Bxa4
{ Black cannot take the rook as, at the end of the variation, we will have Qd4!, winning material. }
20. Rab1
{ Our idea is to take on b7 and exploit Black's lack of coordination. We are also threatening Rxe5 and Qd4. If 20...b5  we will win an exchange after   21.d6!  . As Black has no practical solutions, we have a slight advantage and Black has had to do a lot of precise moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Grünfeld without ...c6"]
[Black "Main line with 7...Nb6 - 9...Re8 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
