{ The strong GM Oparin is our model player when going for this move. Now lack does not have the thematic reply ...Na5, so he has to make a decision regarding the c6-knight's destination. }
11... Bxc3
{ Black aims for simplifications, but that will lead them to a quite unpleasant position, in my opinion. Black scores quite well here @@StartBracket@@50%@@EndBracket@@, but playing with some precision O think we can quickly put our opponent in trouble. }
12. dxc6 Bf6 13. Qc2 bxc6 14. Nd4
{ Esta novedad me parece muy fuerte conceptualmente. Si no captura conseguiremos un punto fuerte en c6 para nuestro caballo @@StartBracket@@o en caso de Ab7 incluso podemos plantear Cb3-Cc5@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Bxd4 15. exd4
{ Our bishop will go to h6 and we will eventually bring our rooks to e1 and c1 @@StartBracket@@maybe first to d1 to defend d4 if necessary@@EndBracket@@. The rook on C1 will put pressure on c6 and will also enable ideas like Rc5 or Rc4-Ra4 if the b6-knight moves.   Black's pawn structure and weaknesses on dark squares mean that this position will be very uncomfortable for them to play in practice. We can eventually consider attacking with h4 to decrease Black's king safety. }
