9... Bg4
{ Esta jugada funciona de maravilla para nuestros intereses con la estructura de peones en negro, pero tiene un detalle importante. }
10. h3 Bxf3
{ 10...Be6  is a very common move either here or after ...Bg4. Black wants to exploit the fact that we cannot go for our common plan with Qe2. However, I think that our reply is very logical  11.b3  Now that ...e7-e5 is no longer a theat, we can develop our c1-bishop properly.   I like best to develop it to a3 in case Black decides to go for ...a5-a4 and, later, we can go for an important maneuver: Ng5-Ne4-Nc5 squeezing Black on the kingside and increasing the power of our Catalan bishop. }
11. Qxf3 e5 12. d5 Ne7
{ Here the plan is to play a4 to disrupt the knight on b6 and have the idea of a5-a6 if Black tries to play c7-c6. Then h4 to gain space on the kingside and enable the g5 square for the thematic annoying development of our dark-squared bishop.   Also Rd1 to defend our wedge on d5 and finally e4 in the moment that his knight is out of f5 @@StartBracket@@for example, h4 enables to go Bh3 to throw it out if needed also@@EndBracket@@because the knight on d4 would be very annoying. If we follow these 4 simple steps, success is guaranteed :@@EndBracket@@. }
