10. d5
{ Trying the adventure of taking on e5 and then looking for f4-e4 would be much less effective as Black would be able to trade queens.   Capturing on c3 would be more relevant since our pawn structure will be very weak and both their minor pieces' task @@StartBracket@@I mean the b6-knight and the e6-bishop@@EndBracket@@ will be to hassle our queenside, as they are well-coordinated. The pawn structures in this variation have some very special nuances that must be kept in mind. }
10... Ne7 11. e4 Bg4
{ 3 players went ...c7-c6 by habit. Do you see the problem of this move? } 12.
h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3
{ Now we have a very similar position that we had seen before. The big difference is that we had the pawn on e3 and the rook on d1, so Black has an extra idea. }
13... c6 14. Rd1 cxd5 15. exd5 Nf5
{ If we let our opponet bring the knight on d4, the rooks to the c and d files, and, perhaps, go ...f5 to take away the e4 square from our pieces, we can sign the scoresheet after our opponent writes 0-1. It is necessary to act quickly since the simple blockade on d6 would interrupt the position. }
16. d6 { Giving ack our passed pawn in order to activate our bishops. } 16...
Nd4 17. Qxb7 Qxd6 18. Bg5
{ The bishop pair, an open position and 2vs1 on the queenside are guarantees of success. 4 wins, including one in correspondence, certify that Black is in trouble. The queen is a nuisance on b7 or a6 and our bishop on g2 is spectacular. We are not in a hurry and moves like Kh2 and b3 can make Black nervous and could encourage Black to make the final mistake. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Grünfeld without ...c6"]
[Black "Main line - the 11.dxc6 alternative #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3
{ I wanted my recommendations to keep the maximum flexibility possible according to what I recommend in the Catalan chapters.   There are quite a few players who opt for @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.Nf3  and if Black plays  2...d5  , they go  3.Bf4  and if they continue  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pppppppp/5n2/8/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 2 2@@EndFEN@@  2...g6  they can already play the King's Indian.   It is very important to be aware of our memory and mastery of the openings and these little shortcuts or tricks in the move orders that allow you to 'close' one way while you are learning another. It is better to have a simpler path than to go into main lines with everything half done.   For all these reasons I continue with this move order which will also benefit Reti players  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  --  2.c4  and you will be able to appreciate Black's numerous reactions.   At the top level it is considered that the most precise move order is  3.g3  delaying as much as possible the move Nf3 to keep the dxc5! option open in case Black wants to transpose to Benoni positions by going ...c7-c5.   The move 3.g3 allows certain move order pluses against the Grünfeld in some concrete variations. The point is that, in exchange for these small details, we lost a lot of move order flexibility and we did not avoid the most relevant variations with ...d6 or ...c6-d5.   So consistently with the rest of this course and the Part 1 we will go for this move order and give an answer to all Black's alternatives. }
3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. cxd5
{ It seems sensible to me to simplify the variations and assume that we capture as long as Black does not have the d5 pawn defended by a pawn.   Playing gambit-style is interesting but the resulting positions are more preferable for Black @@StartBracket@@we will have a better center while BLack will enjoy a typical counterplay, much more common in the Grünfeld, after something like dxc4-Na3-c3-bxc3@@EndBracket@@. Instead, after cxd5 we are looking for somewhat different positions than usual in which Black plays with minor pieces rather than pawns. }
6... Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6
{ The most accurate move order to avoid our expansion and kick our opponents' knights away with e4 and d5. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3
{ Defending the center and now Black has a wide range of options to prepare the move e7-e5 at the right time. The main risk of our position is that the development is not logical at all and solving the situation of the bishop on c1 is annoying.   If b3, Black would play ...e5 and we would have problems on the long diagonal. If we develop the bishop to d2 it will hinder our major pieces. So we must be patient and make slight moves that improve our position. }
9... e5
{ 9...Be6  10.b3  again we have b3 if black commits to play ...e5. I know I have mentioned this idea in another move order, but I think it is convenient to emphasize it and the fight that is taking place on the board. If Black is looking for a5-a4, what exactly would we do? }
10. d5
{ Trying the adventure of taking on e5 and then looking for f4-e4 would be much less effective as Black would be able to trade queens.   Capturing on c3 would be more relevant since our pawn structure will be very weak and both their minor pieces' task @@StartBracket@@I mean the b6-knight and the e6-bishop@@EndBracket@@ will be to hassle our queenside, as they are well-coordinated. The pawn structures in this variation have some very special nuances that must be kept in mind. }
10... e4
{ Very much in the style of the Grünfeld, Black surprises us with an in-between move.   Under basic strategic and positional canons, this move is rather weak, as Black greatly weakens their pawn structure. But, under the current dynamic canons, it has the h8-a1 diagonal, the b-file, knight jumps that coordinate with the previous premises, and, to top it off, the bishop on c8 can annoy us by developing to f5, g4 or a6, as convenient.   This variation has quite a reputation for being sought for a draw, but in practice I find it very impractical; almost 60% score for White in 80 games is bad news for the driest variation. }
11. dxc6 Qxd1 { Letting us capture on f3 with the queen would be horrible. }
12. Nxd1
{ This alternative is a somewhat more passive and worse version, but has similar venom. }
12... exf3 13. Bxf3 bxc6 14. Bd2
{ Once again we see that this simple idea is very effective in practice and the Chinese Woman World Champion ended up beating a familiar Chessable author. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Ju,W @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ -Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2720@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2022 }
*

