10. d5
{ Trying the adventure of taking on e5 and then looking for f4-e4 would be much less effective as Black would be able to trade queens.   Capturing on c3 would be more relevant since our pawn structure will be very weak and both their minor pieces' task @@StartBracket@@I mean the b6-knight and the e6-bishop@@EndBracket@@ will be to hassle our queenside, as they are well-coordinated. The pawn structures in this variation have some very special nuances that must be kept in mind. }
10... e4
{ Very much in the style of the Grünfeld, Black surprises us with an in-between move.   Under basic strategic and positional canons, this move is rather weak, as Black greatly weakens their pawn structure. But, under the current dynamic canons, it has the h8-a1 diagonal, the b-file, knight jumps that coordinate with the previous premises, and, to top it off, the bishop on c8 can annoy us by developing to f5, g4 or a6, as convenient.   This variation has quite a reputation for being sought for a draw, but in practice I find it very impractical; almost 60% score for White in 80 games is bad news for the driest variation. }
11. dxc6 Qxd1 { Letting us capture on f3 with the queen would be horrible. }
12. Rxd1 exf3 13. Bxf3 bxc6 14. Bd2
{ We are not in a hurry to capture on c6 but we are in a hurry to finish the development. }
14... Nc4
{ Only acceptable move. if Black let us play b3, the knight on b6 would be out of play. }
15. Na4
{ Again we aim to exchange our pitiful bishop on d2. This position is wonderful in practice, with up to 7 wins for white at all levels! @@StartBracket@@hasta +2650@@EndBracket@@ . }
15... Rb8
{ Taking on b2 would be catastrophic because after we conquer the b-file and take on c6 Black has a very bad structure and their pieces are clumsy. }
16. Bc3 Bxc3
{ If Black lets us to trade the dark-squared bishops without ruining our pawn structure, we would be close to winning }
17. bxc3 Ne5 18. Be2
{ A common example of what the Grünfeld is all about. Positionally, it is close to calmness opening, but the play of the pieces is far superior. This implies that Black must keep finding active ideas that compensate, in this case, the double pawns on the c-file.   Objectively Black should hold, but we will see as an example how a 2600+ player quickly made his life difficult. }
18... Be6 19. Rd4
{ Covering the c4-square and our knight on a4 at the moment is excellent to cover the entrance on b2. Playing f4-e4-Kf2 would be nice. }
19... Nd7
{ Another important detail about Grunfeld players is that they have little patience and are used to prioritizing solutions that are forced to wait. }
20. Rad1 Nb6 21. Nc5 Nd5 22. Nxe6 fxe6 23. R1d2
{ We avoided the entry on the seventh and Black's structure is horrible. Now Rc4 and Bg4 would be good moves to start the suffocation. White prevailed showing great technique.   1-0 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Tkachiev,V @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@-Sutovsky,E  @@StartBracket@@2637@@EndBracket@@ Dresden 2007 }
