{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... c6
{ An extremely solid line and very reliable for Black.   For example, if you play the King's Indian Attack @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  --  2.g3  --  3.Bg2  , maye you will have faced 1...d5 and after 2...g6! most times will end up transposing to the g3-Grünfeld.   This order is very fashionable for Black and it is very practical, so I think it is convenient to give you a couple of alternatives depending on how you get to the order, since it changes depending on whether Black has castled and we have made Nc3 or not. I think our main line @@StartBracket@@in which we allow Black to tale on c4@@EndBracket@@ is very explosive and it is convenient to have some extra ideas to approach the variation in a calmer way. }
