3... Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3
{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c6 6. Nc3
{ Here we can continue with  6.O-O  and 7. Qb3, as I recommend as an alternative, or 6.O-O and 7. Nc3, which will lead to the same variation to the one which will be analyzed next —which will be our weapon. }
6... d5 7. cxd5
{ In this move order Black delays the c6-d5 plan and is already castled, and we can go for this interesting alternative if you prefer a more quiet and positional game. }
7... cxd5 8. Ne5
{ Taking advantage of the fact that we have more pieces in the center to generate discomfort. }
8... Bf5
{ This move, although difficult to see, is the best, in my opinion.   8...Nc6  against the most common move, we simply play  9.O-O  and we will go Nxc6-Bf4-Rc1 next, with a very comfortable position. Our idea is to aim for Na4, putting presure on the c6-pawn and use the c5-square. I like this variation because I do not think that either the most normal move @@StartBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/pp2ppbp/5np1/3pN3/3P4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Nc6  @@EndBracket@@ and the most common one @@StartBracket@@  8...e6  @@EndBracket@@ are good because they lead to uncomfortable positions for Grünfeld players, who tend to prefer dynamic play.   8...b6  9.O-O  I like Bf4-Qa4 in this position to exploit the fact that the move weakens the light squares a6 and c6 and after Rfc1 we have a very comfortable position. }
9. Be3
{ This move has been played by 2700 average players, so we can have an idea of what kind of players opt for this kind of moves as Black. For the moment, this move overprotects d4, so the queen is now free to go Qb3 against BLack's ...Ne4 move.   The thematic  9.Qb3  is weak due to  9...Nc6!  . }
9... Qb6
{ Black's best try. In case of ...Nc6 we will simply castle and we could continue with moves such as Nxc6 and Rc1, a plan that I mentioned before. }
10. Rc1
{ A useful move, setting a little trap. We defend c3 and now taking on b2 would be a mistake. }
10... Rd8
{ If ...Qxb2 we would play Bxd5! and Black has no satisfactory reply. } 11. Qd2
{ The previous moves have been extremely precise by Black. We will probably end up needing to play f3 followed by Bf2 or g4 in some cases. I still find White's play more logical, as our development is superior and Black could still be in trouble. }
