{ As we want to play the g3 variation of the Grünfeld, in case of  4.Nc3  d5  we cannot play  5.g3  nor  5.cxd5  Nxd5  6.g3  , as they are slightly imprecise due to  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/5np1/3p4/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...dxc4!  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1ppbp/6p1/3n4/3P4/2N2NP1/PP2PP1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5!  respectively. We should be very careful with the move orders. }
4... O-O 5. Bg2 c6 6. Nc3
{ Here we can continue with  6.O-O  and 7. Qb3, as I recommend as an alternative, or 6.O-O and 7. Nc3, which will lead to the same variation to the one which will be analyzed next —which will be our weapon. }
6... d5 7. O-O
{ Carlsen has once again popularized this typical 'Catalan' sacrifice and it will be our main option being very similar to the positions seen in the Catalan. As a first big difference we have to talk about the bishop on g7.   In the Catalan, Black has less activity with the bishop on the f8-a3 diagonal and that is why this variation against the Grunfeld is considered somewhat risky. }
7... Bf5
{ Against this developing move we will remember a typical Slav: we put pressure on  b7  . We can also simply play  8.h3  or some waiting move, and ...Bf5 does not fit well with the approach of taking on c4. Black's position is already suspicious.   7...Nbd7  8.cxd5  cxd5  9.Bf4  In general, Black wants to develop the knight to c6, not to d7. Now the knight is annoying for Black. We will continue with moves such as Qb3 and a4. In the symmetrical Grünfeld with Nd2, Black always wants to go ...a5-a4 to hasle our knight and exploit the fact that it has no good jumps and is on defensive mode. Here we punish Black in the same fashion.   7...e6  8.Ne5  against bad variations and/or sidelines, I always like to recommend original ideas. Once closed the c8-h3 diagonal, the Ne5-f4 plan is very strong, and it is similar to the 4. e3 Slav: when BLack goes ...g6, we want to go Ne5-f4 as soon as Black goes ...e6. Be3 is an interesting continuation to develop both bishops and then continue Bf2-e4. Another interesting plan is bringing the knight back to f3 cand go for the e4-push if allowed. }
8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qxb6 axb6 11. h3
{ We continue with g4-Bf4 to leave room for our bishop on g3 and to enable Rfc1. It is the typical symmetrical position in which Black will suffer due to the fact that he has two doubled pawns in exchange for nothing. Later we can consider e3-Bf1 if more troops are needed or Ne5, depending on how Black plays. }
