{ Black was also threatening ...Qc8!, preventing us to kick the g4-bishop away. }
9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 e5
{ As we have said, Black wants to gain some space in the center. } 11. dxe5
Nfd7 12. e6
{ This move is much better than simply let Black take on e5. Now Black's pawn structure will be slightly worse. }
12... fxe6 13. Be3
{ Once we sacrificed the pawn, we prevent BLack's knight to jump to c5 and we aim to hassle Black's development, whatever will be. }
13... Ne5
{ So spoke Miguel Santos. When it comes to openings, believe me he has nothing to envy Zarathustra. }
14. Be2 { We want to go f4, kicking away the invader. } 14... Nd3
{ 14...Na6  15.Qa4  hindering Black's ...b5 break and, at the same time, planning to go Rad1-Qc2 and f4-e5 later on. It seems that BLack has access to the d3-square  (for example, by means of ...Qc8, ...b5 and go there with the a6-knight)  . However, the thing is that both the b4 and e5 squares  (the squares from where the other knight can support its partner on d3)  are vulnerable to both a3 or f4 pushes, so Black's position is incredibly unstable.   The move  14...Na6  relies on the difference that if we play now  15.f4  Nd3  16.Bxd3  Qxd3!  we cannot play Qg4, and that will be dramatic for our interests. }
15. Bxd3 cxd3
{ If  15...Qxd3  Qg4!  and Black is in trouble due to moves like Rad1 and the thematic sacrifice e5. }
16. Qb3
{ With this novelty we deviate from ½-½ @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@-Santos Ruiz,M @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@ Los Cancajos 2020.   The idea is to clear the d1-square for our rook and, when it gets there, the d3-pawn can be taken next. The e5pawn will be a permanent issue for Black and, besides, the plan f4-e5 is always on the air, so Black must react to it if they do not want to be in so much trouble. }
