[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. King's Indian Defense - Minor systems"]
[Black "Korobov's line #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... Nc6
{ A variation that Korobov has played in numerous occasions and which has a certain specific interest. }
6. Nc3
{ In case of  6.d5  Na5  7.Na3  Black has the energetic  7...b5!  and I almost prefer their position.   If we played  6.O-O  we would enter on ...d6 territory and and we could not transpose to what I recommend in this course. }
6... a6
{ Black keeps of avoiding ...d6, preventing in this way our thematic d5-push. ...a6 has the aim of going Rb8 and ...b5 next. }
7. O-O
{ These move orders are very confusing. I will try to explain why.   After  7.b3  or  7.e4  it is annoying that after  7...d6  we have not castled yet, so Black can exploit our inflexible position.   For example, if  7.e4  d6  8.h3  @@StartBracket@@to prevent ...Bg4@@EndBracket@@  8...Nd7!?  and suddenly Black is aiming to play ...e5-...Nd4.   If White plays  7.b3  , after  7...d6  we cannot play  8.d5  due to  8...Nxd5!  and cannot transpose to my recommendation. Therefore, I concluded it is best to play 7. O-O here and if Black tries to transpose with 7...d6, they have committed to the move ...a6.   We actually did play the move order with  7.d5  against Black's ...d6-...Nc6 because after 7. O-O I was not interested to allow Black to go ...e5 in one move. I hope everything is clearer now. }
7... Rb8 8. d5 Na5 9. c5
{ This extra option punishes Black's move order. We defend the pawn and shatter Black's idea. }
9... b5
{ 9...d6  10.e4  transposes to other variation covered in this Lifetime Repertoire. }
10. cxb6 cxb6 11. Bf4 d6 12. Nd4
{ We will invade the c6-square after playing b4, and Black's position will be strategically lost. }
