1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... Nc6 7. d5
{ After  7.O-O  e5  I was not convinced by  8.dxe5  as it has been the usual White reply for too long and Black already has satisfactory reactions.  In addition, we also avoid other main variations, such as 7...a6. We force the knight to move to the side and this becomes the key aspect of the position. If Black gets enough dynamism they will be able to justify his situation; if we manage to neutralize the counterplay, the knight will be in evidence.   For example, with this move we are already out of Bologan's book on the King's Indian Defense. }
7... Na5
{ Against other retreats we will `play Nd4, as we always do when we manage to push d4-d5 without Black having any central expansion other than the pawn on d6. }
8. b3
{ The point of this move order. We have no problems on the he weak a1-h8 diagonal. }
8... c5
{ 8...Ne4  fails miserably after  9.Nxe4  Bxa1  10.Bd2  and BLack will lose a piece and the game.   If  8...c6  9.Bb2  the a5-knight will suffer if the position opens up, as the only square it has available is  b7  . Therefore, the usual plan is  ...c5-...a6-...b5  . }
9. Bb2 a6
{ Against any ...e7-e6 or ...e7-e5 ideas we can take on e6 and both bishops on the long diagonals guarantee us a comfortable advantage. Black looks for the typical ...b5-break. }
10. O-O Rb8 11. Nd2 b5 12. Qc1
{ The advantage of this move order is that it allows us to go for this extra move. Usually, the queen is already placed on c2 and this gives Black some extra options. Another important concept is that we are planning to play Nd1-Bc3 later to put pressure on the dislodged knight on a5. As Black tends to take on c4 to have a presence on the b-file, the threat of ...Qa3 is real.    The factor that I would say is more relevant is the variation where Black plays either ...e6 or ...e5, which is the most popular break. Faced with it, we want to take on e6 and look for Nce4, so we can exchange the strong bishop on g7 and also expose the dislodged knight on a5. We see that it is especially important that the queen is on c1 since there is no ...Bf5 against Nce4, which would pin the knight on e4. }
12... e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nce4
{ Here it is clear the difference with the moves Qc1 or Qc2 mentioned before. }
15... Nd5
{ Black dreams of being able to play the ...f7-f5 push to kick our knight away from e4. However, there is no time for that. }
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qb2+ Kg8 18. Nf3
{ We are following a game between two titled players in which White emerged with a completely winning position. Black has a very fragile balance of the position, we have control of the long diagonal, and now we will go for Rfd1 and moves like Nfg5. Black cannot stop all the threats.   ½-½ @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Erdos,V @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@-Tutisani,N @@StartBracket@@2442@@EndBracket@@ Terme Catez 2022 }
