{ This seems to be the most precise move in the position. Black gains some space on the queenside and would eventually like to play ...c5-c4 now that we cannot play b3-b4 in response, which would leave the a5-knight even more out of play. }
16. Rd1 { The d6-pawns are generally very tasty if you are playing White. }
16... Ne8 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Qb2+ Kg8 19. Nf3
{ Here I love the plan of going Qd2-Qf4, increasing the pressure against the d6-pawn and facilitating the option of going for a kingside attack with h4-h5. In addition, Black should always keep an eye on moves such as Nfg5 and also a3 or Rac1, hitting critical squares, in the right moment.   I find it very difficult for Black to coordinate, while we have a very healthy position with no weaknesses. }
