{ Against any ...e7-e6 or ...e7-e5 ideas we can take on e6 and both bishops on the long diagonals guarantee us a comfortable advantage. Black looks for the typical ...b5-break. }
10. O-O Rb8 11. Nd2 b5 12. Qc1
{ The advantage of this move order is that it allows us to go for this extra move. Usually, the queen is already placed on c2 and this gives Black some extra options. Another important concept is that we are planning to play Nd1-Bc3 later to put pressure on the dislodged knight on a5. As Black tends to take on c4 to have a presence on the b-file, the threat of ...Qa3 is real.    The factor that I would say is more relevant is the variation where Black plays either ...e6 or ...e5, which is the most popular break. Faced with it, we want to take on e6 and look for Nce4, so we can exchange the strong bishop on g7 and also expose the dislodged knight on a5. We see that it is especially important that the queen is on c1 since there is no ...Bf5 against Nce4, which would pin the knight on e4. }
12... Bf5
{ In this kinds of structures, Black usually forces White to push e2-e4 to reduce the flexibility of our pawn structure and then goes ...Bd7 and ...e6. In addition, it would take away the ideal square for the c3-knight as we see in the other variations. }
13. Nd1
{ With this move we achieve several goals:   1. We defend the b2-bishop properly.   2. We threaten e4-Ne3, which we can follow up with Bc3 and f4.   3. We pre-empt moves such as ...Bh6 by being able to push f4 and defend preemptively the e3 square. }
13... Bd7
{ Black's most flexible move.   If  13...e5  , we would play  14.e4  followed by Ne3.   If  13...Bh6  we could also play  14.Ne3!  . Remember that Black has to keep in mind that if they try too many adventures on the kingside/center, they may find themselves outnumbered if they do not count on the fact that the knight on a5 has little future. }
14. Rb1
{ The logical consequence. We can now develop the rook and overprotecting the b2-bishop is always a plus. }
14... e5 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. e3
{ Intending to push f2-f4. The pawn 'horns' on c4 and f4 restrict very well Black's e6-f6 center and also enhance the influence of our bishop pair on the two long diagonals.   Our move order is intended to pre-empt  16...Bc6  and we also have the option of playing  17.f3!  delaying the bishop trade and keeping Black's a5-knight problematic while we will bring our knight to f2.   Regarding the pawn structure, it is important to take into account that if BLack plays ...d6-d5, the c5-pawn would be vulnerable @@StartBracket@@since we have a blockade of the pawn structure with c4 and e3-f4 that restricts its mobility@@EndBracket@@. If Black tries ...e6-e5, we will often have the option of fxe5 and gain the e4 and d5 squares for our minor pieces, while Black will not be able to use d4. }
