[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. King's Indian Defense - Minor systems"]
[Black "6...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... c6
{ Apart from the nuisances related to 5...c6 and going ...Bf5, Black also has the option of bringing the queen out quickly. }
7. e4
{ This is the option I chose a few months ago against an Azeri GM who always plays with ...Bf5 and the game went on, as I show below.   Although we avoid the ...Bf5 variation, the problem is that Black can play other annoying moves like  7...e5  followed by ...Bg4 and also  7...Be6  and meet  8.Qe2  with  9...Bg4!  exploiting the fact that d4 is undefended now.   Therefore, we will continue with  7.O-O  , transposing to other known variations. Nevertheless, I will show the continuation of the game. Another relevant detail is that, if Black wants to, can play ...c6 and ...d6 before castling and get ...Bf5 in without us then being able to play e4, so we do not really avoid anything. }
7... Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 Nfd7
{ Black seeks to annoy us on the dark squares, but a precise move order completely neutralizes the second player's ideas. }
10. Be3 Qb6 11. Rb1 c5 12. d5 Qb4 13. Be2 Nb6 14. Bd2
{ And Black is completely lost because they have to give up the g7-bishop. I ended up winning the game; see 1-0 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Alonso Rosell,A @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ -Sadikhov,U @@StartBracket@@2509@@EndBracket@@ Struga 2021 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. King's Indian Defense - Minor systems"]
[Black "6...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... c6
{ Apart from the nuisances related to 5...c6 and going ...Bf5, Black also has the option of bringing the queen out quickly. }
7. O-O Bf5 { Against ...Bf5 right here we will change our plans. } 8. Ne1
{ I think this is the most logical option. Our idea is to play e2-e4 and prevent Black's knight jump to e4 once and for all. }
8... e5
{ Black takes advantage of the fact that we abandon our central control to expand in the center themselves. }
9. d5
{ Again, d4-d5 is an interesting idea. Black is still far away from achieving their ...f5-f4 idea and our knight on e1 will go to d3, a very useful theme in these structures, as it allows us to go for f3 or f4 as convenient. }
9... cxd5
{ Black prefers to liquidate the tension to be able to develop the knight on b8. }
10. cxd5 a5
{ It makes much more sense to go for ...Na6 after playing ...a5 in order to gain even more space. }
11. e4 Bd7 12. Nd3 Na6 13. a3 b6
{ Black prepares the c5-square for the knight and, if White takes, they will take with the b-pawn.   13...b5  14.b4  and we will continue with moves like Qe2-Bd2-Rfc1 and Black will struggle quite a lot to hold their exposed queenside. Against plans such as ...f5-f4 we can simply ignore them because they will have to be alert to queenside pawn breaks like a3-a4 followed by occupying c6 with one of our pieces. }
14. Bg5
{ Again, we are interested in forcing h7-h6 to put pressure on h6 in the future and to weaken any attempt by Black to push ...f7-f5.   14.b4  directly conflicts with  14...axb4  15.axb4  Nc7!  and after Nb5 Black has a great position. }
14... h6 15. Bd2 Ne8
{ Black wants to push ...f7-f5.   15...Nc5  16.Nxc5  bxc5  17.a4  and here White has a fantastic plan. The idea is to play Ra2 and aim for Nb5!. Although we could sacrifice the b5-pawn, we will get it back with Qc2-Rfa1 and Black will miss their light-squared bishop.   If Black does not take on b5, we will continue with Na3-Nc4 and Black will have to deal with the annoying and permanent pressure we will exert on a5. Once done that, we can focus our efforts on moves such as Rf1, Re1 and f2-f4. The c4-knight is a monster. }
16. b4
{ The move  16.a4!?  is also a good option. We want to continue with Qe2 and, as soon as a Black piece gets into c5, take it and go for Nb1-Na3-Nc4 or Nd1-Ne3-Nc4. The main virtue of this move is that we can meet the obvious f7-f5 break with f4! }
16... axb4 17. axb4 Nac7 18. Qb3 Nb5 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 20. Nxb5 Bxb5 21. Rc1
{ Now Black will have to react, and we have a very simple plan. Nb2-Nc4 will help us to put pressure on Black's weaknesses, and the disconnection between their minor pieces will be appreciated. We will also be interested in plans like Ne1-Nc2-Ne3, it is really a very rich position, and we have all the pieces well-placed except the knight on d3 which is now completely out of place in the situation that has arisen on the board. }
