{ I think this is the most logical option. Our idea is to play e2-e4 and prevent Black's knight jump to e4 once and for all. }
8... d5
{ This idea has been tried by some adventurous players who like weird move orders. Black pseudo-transposes to a Grünfeld and aims to take advantage of our knight being on e1.   8...Qc8  9.e4  Bh3  10.f3  after Be3-Qd2 and Nd3 we dominate the whole center and the light-squared f3-e4-c4 pawn structure is perfectly placed in order not to hinder our dark-squared bishop's movement. }
9. Qb3
{ As almost always when the bishop on c8 comes out in these structures, we play Qb3 to threaten d5 and b7 at the same time. }
9... Qb6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bxd5
{ With this novelty, White will enjoy being a pawn up. After Nxd5 Black recaptures, and after Nc6 we have counterplay enough and an advantage in development to compensate it. }
11... Nc6 12. Bxc6 Qxc6 13. d5
{ Our aim is to build a solid pawn structure with f3-e4. } 13... Qa6 14. Bg5
{ Against ...Qa6 we will continue with Ng2, and we are slightly better, as we are a healthy pawn up. }
