Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bc8
{ We have allowed Black to weaken our structure in return for a couple of tempi, so now we have to play energetically. }
10. f4 Nc6 { This move has been played by a strong Russian GM. } 11. f5 e5 12.
d5 Nb8 13. e4 Nd7 14. Nf3
{ This novelty is aimed at relocating the knight on d3 via e1 and to play g4. White has a huge space advantage and although Black is relatively solid, we can play freely on the kingside with zero risk. I like a lot of plans such as Rf3-Rh3 to exploit Black's lack of space. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20. King's Indian Defense - Minor systems"]
[Black "6...Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... Bf5 { Black again aims for Ne4, this time without including ...c6. } 7.
O-O
{ It would be ideal to play  7.Nh4  at first glance, forcing Black to go ...Bc8. We will castle and calmly go back with the knight to f3 after nullifying the effect of ...Bf5.   The problem lies in the fact that after @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppp1ppbp/3p1np1/8/2PP4/2N2NP1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK2R b KQ - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nc6  we play  7.d5  without castling, so it would be an inconsistency hole in our repertoire. }
7... Ne4 8. Nh4 { A common move that regains control of the e4-square. } 8...
Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bc8
{ We have allowed Black to weaken our structure in return for a couple of tempi, so now we have to play energetically. }
10. f4 c5
{ Against an attack on the flank it is best to counter in the center!   Avoiding f5 with  10...e6  would not be very effective since after  11.e4  we renew the idea.   After  10...f5  11.e4  I do not think the ...f5-break has improved Black's position at all. After e5 and Ba3 our position would be crushing. }
11. f5
{ The key idea. The strong point of this curious setup is that Black loses any flexibility of pawns on the kingside.   As we can see, they cannot move any pawn without losing material or being excessively weakened. In addition, Black will always have to deal with future sacrifices on g6 and have a weaker castled position having exchanged the knight on f6. }
11... Nc6
{ Black continues with the counterplay in the center. It is preferable for Black's interests to keep White's doubled pawns on the c-file. }
12. Be3
{ Continuing our development and defending the center. Since we are interested in keeping our light-squared bishop free to play Be4 or Bd5 to put pressure on Black's castling in the future, we do not mind having put the bishop on e3 hindering the advance of the e2 pawn. }
12... Na5
{ This seemingly normal move practically loses. In a game against Russian-American GM Grigoriy Oparin, Caruana did not assess well how weak his castling was and the amount of white pieces that could come into play. }
13. Qd3 Bd7
{ After something like  13...Qe8  to defend g6, we would play  14.Be4!  and the sacrifice cannot be stopped. }
14. fxg6
{ Oparin wasted the opportunity to burst Black's castling with this strong move.   In the game, White went for  14.Rf2  cxd4  15.cxd4  e6  16.fxg6  hxg6  17.Raf1  Qe7  and Caruana managed not only to hold the balance, but to win the game after 86 moves. See  0-1 @@StartBracket@@86@@EndBracket@@ Oparin,G @@StartBracket@@2681@@EndBracket@@ - Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2792@@EndBracket@@ Wch Blitz Warsaw 2021. }
14... hxg6 15. Nxg6 fxg6 16. Qxg6
{ Aiming for Be4 with unstoppable mate on h7. } 16... Rxf1+ 17. Rxf1 Qe8 18.
Qg5
{ Black experiences difficulties transferring his pieces to the kingside. The threat Be4-Bg6 followed by Qh5 is unstoppable. }
