{ Black continues with the counterplay in the center. It is preferable for Black's interests to keep White's doubled pawns on the c-file. }
12. Be3
{ Continuing our development and defending the center. Since we are interested in keeping our light-squared bishop free to play Be4 or Bd5 to put pressure on Black's castling in the future, we do not mind having put the bishop on e3 hindering the advance of the e2 pawn. }
12... Bd7
{ Black aims to complete their development by playing ...b6. We are not interested in going for dxc5, after which we will be left with the doubled pawns on the c-file. Here we have to be careful; since we have a worse pawn structure, we have to keep playing energetically. }
13. Rb1
{ Improving our last piece and prudently removing our rook from the h8-a1 diagonal. }
13... b6 14. Qd3 Rc8
{ If Black does not take on d4 now, we can take the opportunity to close the position and leave Black with a not very active bishop pair. }
15. Bxc6
{ Fantastic concept. We exchange the jumpy knight, and then we close the position and all our attention can be focused into the kingside. }
15... Bxc6 16. d5 Bd7 17. Rf3
{ Doubling rooks and looking for ideas with g4 will give us total control of the position. Our ideas include sacrifices on g6, bringing our rook to h3, and aim for Bg5. Black will really have a difficult task to defend, and both the bishop on d7 and the rook on c8 are totally useless. }
