[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. King's Indian Defense - ...Nbd7 systems"]
[Black "6...Nbd7 - the 8.Qc2 alternative"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... Nbd7 7. O-O e5
{ c7-c5 does not work well at all when the knight is on d7. We could play d5 and Black would not be able to transpose to the Benoni since after ...e6 we would play dxe6 and the pawn on d6 would fall. Without this thematic break, Black would quickly run out of space. }
8. Qc2
{ A classical alternative that I and my students have played many times. The idea is very simple. We want to play Rd1, e4, h3, Be3. Usually Black will have played exd4 and we will then look for Re1-f4-Bf2-Rad1, thus achieving the ideal structure against the Fianchetto Variation of the King's Indian.   Sometimes Black tries to put quick pressure on e4 to upset our plan. In this case we can also play Bf4, putting pressure on d6 and forcing ...Nh5 which would enable Be3. Another alternative that works in many positions is simply to start with f2-f3 and thus enable Be3-Re1-Rad1 and then look for the expansion with h3-f4-Bf2.     The drawback of this move is that Black can play a specific variation, after which they will be fine. However, at medium-lower levels @@StartBracket@@less than 2300 FIDE rating@@EndBracket@@ that variation is already less-known and the text move is a reasonable way of playing. }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 Nb6
{ Of the almost 2000 games that I have in my database with 8. Qc2, only a little more than 200 have reached this position. }
10. Rd1
{ The key lies on the fact that 10. b3 is not possible due to ...c5!, and after ...Bf5  (or inserting ...a6 against Ndb5)  black's dark squared bishop will be too strong on the a1 h8 diagonal. }
10... Nxc4 11. Ncb5 { We will soon get the pawn back. } 11... a6 12. Qxc4 axb5
13. Nxb5 Ne8
{ Against  13...Bd7  we could continue with Bg5 and, later on, we could aim for a4 to increase our control of the light squares. It seems unlikely that Black can play with weak c7 and b7 pawns that have to be constantly checked for tactical measures to justify that they cannot be captured. }
14. Qb4
{ Trying to make Black's life more difficult. Their pieces can barely move, as we can see, while we can go for Bf4 followed by a4-a5 to increase our domination. }
14... c6
{ The key move of the whole variation. Black sacrifices the pawn to hinder our g2-bishop movement. }
15. Nc3 Qa5
{ 15...d5  is not possible due to  16.e4  d4  17.Be3!!  winning Black's central pawn. }
16. Qxa5 Rxa5 17. Be3 Be6 18. a4
{ Intending to continue with b4 and Bd4 or by simply expanding our queenside with a4-a5, playing Bb6 and then Na4 to meet Black's ...d6-d5 push. Objectively, the position is equal but, as you can see, Black has to pass quite a few tests in the form of unnatural moves, and that makes 8. Qc2, a very reasonable alternative. }
