{ Now we will play h3 practically against every Black move. } 10... a6
{ Black is aiming for ...Rb8-Ne5 @@StartBracket@@winning a tempo on b2@@EndBracket@@ and ...c5 @@StartBracket@@winning a tempo on the d4-knight@@EndBracket@@ and ...b5 with good counterplay. As we can see, if we don't know the plan and play as we always do, we can quickly find ourselves in serious trouble. }
11. h3 Rb8 12. a4
{ Magnus has played this move in a couple of games. The idea is to prevent Black's counterplay with ...Ne5-...c5-...b4. In return, we pay the price of having a hole on b4. }
12... a5 13. Be3 c6 14. Qc2 Nc5 15. b3 Nfd7 16. Rab1 Na6 17. f4
{ Going for the supposedly ideal plan, Magnus won the game in the end, but Black has ideal squares for the knights @@StartBracket@@c5 and b4@@EndBracket@@ and this is the typical complex position which Black enjoys, as it is not easy for White to make progress.   We have the everlasting problem of having a weak pawn on b3 and the structure of the queenside is not quite good. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2865@@EndBracket@@-Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2022 }
