{ Now we will play h3 practically against every Black move. } 10... a6
{ Black is aiming for ...Rb8-Ne5 @@StartBracket@@winning a tempo on b2@@EndBracket@@ and ...c5 @@StartBracket@@winning a tempo on the d4-knight@@EndBracket@@ and ...b5 with good counterplay. As we can see, if we don't know the plan and play as we always do, we can quickly find ourselves in serious trouble. }
11. b3 { Pre-empting and completely nullifying Black's plan. } 11... Rb8 12.
Bb2
{ Black would dream to play ...c5-...Ne5, but it does not work. We will simply play Qd2-Rad1. Black has lost so many tempi that we have a good advantage with the bishop on b2, and we can even consider relocating it later on via c1. Taking advantage of what we have, there are also ideas with Nd5 to boost the development and the bishop on b2. }
12... c5 13. Nc2 Ne5 14. a4
{ The move  14.h3  would also be effective, but preventing Black's plan exposes the problems of their position. We will continue with Rb1 next @@StartBracket@@with the idea of overdefending b2 and b3@@EndBracket@@, h3, f4 and we have no such weakness as Black's d6-pawn, so Black will suffer in the long run. }
