Nc5 12. Bf4
{ In general, if Black plays ...c6, our idea is to go Bf4 and meet ...Nh5 with Be3. One of the issues we should solve in these positions is where to develop the c1-bishop; in this case, we can exploit that the d6-pawn is weak. }
12... a5 { With this move order, Black prevents our Ndb5 idea. } 13. Qc2 a4 14.
Rad1 Nh5 { Necessary move to be able to play ...Qa5. } 15. Be3 Qa5
{ This is Black's ideal position. Our queenside is not very elegant and Black seeks to make a dent with ...a3 or ...Qb4 ideas. }
16. g4 Nf6 17. f3
{ Again, I like White's setup. We will continue with Bf1@@StartBracket@@to overdefend the c4-square and pre-empting ...b7-b5 ideas@@EndBracket@@, Bf2, likely Kh1 and we will wait for the perfect moment to aim for f4. With this setup, we limit Black's counterplay and wait for it to backfire. }
