9... exd4 10. Nxd4
{ Now we will play h3 practically against every Black move. } 10... Nc5 11. h3
Bd7
{ A very popular variation, played by non others than Grischuk and Demchenko, among other experts. There are some very interesting plans with Qc8-Re5-Rh5 and other nuances. But the following reply eliminates these options outright and I find it very practical. }
12. f3
{ Reinforcing the center. We simply want to play Be3 and get the classic positional advantage. }
12... Nh5
{ The move chosen by Demchenko, who tries to exploit the fact that we have weakned our dark squares.   12...a5  13.Be3  and now we will play Qd2-Rad1 likely followed by Bf2 and, in case Black attacks out light-squared bishop with ...c4, we will go Bf1. Later on, we will aim for Qc2 and f4 to get the classical advantage White gets in this variation. Once we have Black's counterplay under control, we will likely get to positions where we dominate the center. }
13. g4 Nf6 14. Be3 h5 15. g5 Nh7 16. f4
{ We will continue with Qd2 or Qc2 followed by Rad1. Black is simply cramped and our kingside feels very solid. Eventually, moving our king out of g1 will be necessary. }
