[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... Nbd7 7. O-O e5
{ c7-c5 does not work well at all when the knight is on d7. We could play d5 and Black would not be able to transpose to the Benoni since after ...e6 we would play dxe6 and the pawn on d6 would fall. Without this thematic break, Black would quickly run out of space. }
8. e4 Re8
{ Against  8...a6  we could continue with  9.Qc2  and Rd1, transposing to the alternative plan and hindering Black's, which is to take on d4 and go for ...Ne5-...c5-...b5 in a row, as we do not have a rook on the d-file.   8...exd4  9.Nxd4  a6  10.b3  and we end up transposing. Against the specific  10...Nc5  we could play  11.f3!?  followed by Bb2, completely dominating the position. The pawn on a6 does not contribute much when there is a Black knight is on c5. }
9. Re1
{ This move order seems more precise to my eyes.   If  9.h3  , Black can play the annoying  9...b6!  which has been played recently by quite some young, talented GMs.   As Black has developed the light-squared bishop to b7, our move h3 loses its function, which is preventing ...Bg4, so the move order with Re1 is somewhat finer and more useful. These nuances are actually irrelevant for the 99% of the students of this course, but I think that it is useful to understand and differentiate the move orders. }
9... exd4 10. Nxd4
{ Now we will play h3 practically against every Black move. } 10... Nc5 11. h3
h6
{ After  11...Nfd7  , we will simply play  12.Be3  and after  12...Ne5  13.b3  again, the knight jump to d3 would not give Black anything special. The idea of ...h6 is to hinder the development of our bishop on c1.   Note that after Be3 we lose the e4-pawn and against Bf4 Black will always have annoying ...g5 ideas for us to deal with. }
12. Rb1
{ 12.f3 seems to me to be very precise. Against something along the lines of ...Bd7 or ...a5 we could continue with f3 @@StartBracket@@in this last case the move Ndb5 is also possible@@EndBracket@@ and Black's ...c6 ideas would be harmless. Alternatively, it is a useful move in the position to get away from the g7-bishop's diagonal.   12.f3  the great difference is that now we can meet Black's eventual ...Nfd7-Ne5 plans with f4!  12...c6  this would be the only drawback of our move order —Black will play the ...d5 break and exploit our lack of development, that is—  13.Be3  d5  14.Nc2  attacking on c5 and threatening on d5  14...b6  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.exd5  Bb7  Black has a very reasonable compensation and would be comfortable with this unbalanced position. }
12... c6 13. Bf4
{ Black is not interested in playing ...g5. Our opponent wants to keep that 'threat' to unleash it in the right moment. Once ...c6 is on the board, Black has run out of useful moves such as ...Bd7.   So now we can continue with Qc2-Rad1 completing our development. Another detail is that if they allow us to play Qc2, the ...g5-push will be harmless because we will be able to retreat the bishop back to e3, which is its ideal square. }
13... g5 14. Bc1 a5 15. b3
{ Now that Black has weakened their castled position, we can continue with Bb2 and Re3 against ...Nfd7-...Ne5. Delving a little deeper into a reasonable sequence, Black would want to play ...g4 after bringing the knight to e5. In that case, we would follow with Nce2-Nf4, taking advantage of the squares our opponent has given to us.   Black is overexposed all over the board, and we have several improving moves like Rad1 and no apparent weaknesses in our position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22. King's Indian Defense - 6...c5"]
[Black "9...a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7
{ Trying the double fianchetto with  3...b6  fails because of a theme that we have seen on several occasions.  After  4.Nc3  Bb7  5.d5  the b7-bishop becomes useless and after e4-Nd4 we will control the whole center.   In general, in the Grünfeld it is premature to play ...d5 if White has not committed to Nc3 or g3,  3...d5?!  4.cxd5  Nxd5  5.e4!  comfortably controls the whole center, and we will follow up with h3 to prevent ...Bg4 and then play Nc3-Be2-O-O. }
4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 { Let's go for this move order. } 5... d6 6. Nc3
{ This move order is key against Black's two main alternatives in this position. }
6... c5
{ This is the move that Gawain Jones recommends in his King's Indian course and that has taken me more headaches to deal with. Black aims to fight for the center and play ...Nc6-...Na5.   The great difference between this and  6...Nc6  is that here we have no useful moves rather than  7.O-O  , so we cannot go for the same quick setup with b3-Bb2. }
7. O-O Nc6
{ This is the best move order, which is recommended by Gawain Jones. Other moves aren't as good..   If  7...a6  we play  8.dxc5!  and 9.Be3 would be a terrible version for Black.   Against a move such as  7...Na6  we could continue our development with b3-Bb2 and the knight would be out of play if the center is not closed. }
8. d5 Na5
{ Black's key point. He wants to take advantage of the threat on c4 to look for a6-b5 and crack open the queenside. The usual price for Black is to have a knight that is a bit out of play and that can become a real problem if he does not get enough counterplay. }
9. Nd2 a6
{ Black transposes to the classical plan. I have played this position as White dozens of times and, from experience, I have come to the conclusion that if we simply make the a5-knight's life miserable, we will usually succeed. Plans like Bb2-Nd1-Bc3 will be very common in these positions. }
10. Rb1 { Now  10.b3  is not possible due to  10...Nxd5! } 10... Rb8 11. b3 b5
12. Qc2
{ In the variation where White meets Black's ...Nc6 move with the d5-push straight away, Bb2 can be played directly without including Rb1. Here we can go for the b3-Rb1-Qc2 plan and Bb2 is not needed. }
12... e5
{ In general, King's Indian players are not attracted by the idea of closing the position in this fashion, but we have to take into account that it is usually White who expands on the queenside when the center is closed. However, this is an exception.  Besides, in this move order, we cannot take on e6. The reason is that we have the bishop on c1 and not on b2, so White cannot challenge the long diagonal to the g7-bishop with the typical Nce4 @@StartBracket@@which would also be especially vulnerable to ...Bf5 ideas, as we have the queen on c2 and the rook on b1@@EndBracket@@. Again, the key point is that the poor black knight will have no purpose whatsoever on a5. }
13. e4
{ The thematic capture on b5 followed by b4 does not work so well after   13.cxb5  axb5  14.b4  cxb4  15.Rxb4  Qc7!  and the pin prevents us from going for the ideal setup, that would be Qb1-Ba3 to put pressure on b5 freely.   Black is too close to play ...Bd7-...Rfc8, ...e5-e4 issues and they can also hassle us with ...Bh6 in case we want to play e4. The position is more delicate than it seems. }
13... Bd7
{ Against other careless moves we could consider taking on b5 followed by aiming for the b4-push. }
14. Nd1
{ We would like to play Ne3. I really like the following correspondence game as a strategic example on many things. }
14... Ng4 { Black removes the knight from f6 aiming for the ...f7-f5 push. }
15. f3 Nh6 16. Nf2 f5 17. Bh3
{ Increasing our control of the light squares. Now our plan could be, for example, Bb2-Bc3. }
17... f4 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Bb2 Kh8 20. Kg2 g5 21. Nd3
{ Our knights are doing their job excellently on both flanks. } 21... Ng8 22.
Bc3 { Forcing b4 and then burst Black's queenside. } 22... b4 23. Bb2 Ne7 24.
a3 bxa3 25. Bxa3 Ng6 26. b4
{ We can see how much Black misses the presence of the light-squared bishop to attack on our kingside. We will step by step break Black's wall. }
26... cxb4 27. Rxb4 Rxb4 28. Bxb4 Nb7 29. g4
{ Black was ready to go ...g5-g4. We prevent it and our opponent's position crumbles as the queenside is defenseless. ¡A beautiful game!   1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Mercadal Benejam,J @@StartBracket@@2401@@EndBracket@@-Price,B @@StartBracket@@2064@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2019 }
*

