{ Black closes the center and wants to take advantage of the fact that our g2-bishop would ideally be placed on d3 to find against this kind of structures. }
10. e4 Ng4 { This is another way of preparing the f7-f5 break. } 11. b3 f5 12.
exf5 gxf5 13. h3
{ It is better to include h3 to avoid allowing Black's e4-e3 ideas now that there is a knight on g4. }
13... Nf6
{ 13...Nh6  14.Qc2  now that Black's knight prevents ...h5-h4 ideas. We can continue going for the typical plan Bb2-Ne2-f4-Bc3, strengthening the diagonal and harassing the knight on a5, which will probably end up on b7. }
14. Nf3
{ Now that we have played h2-h3, the pawn structure surrounding our castling is not as flexible as it would ideally be to go for the Qc2-Rae1-Nd1 plan. In this position I recommend going for Nh4-Bg5 @@StartBracket@@although our purpose is not to trade, but only to force ...h6 to weaken the g6-square@@EndBracket@@ and Rb1.   The idea is to be well prepared against each of Black's central pawns advance. We can later look for quieter plans like Qc2-Bf3-Be2 @@StartBracket@@to clear the g-file@@EndBracket@@ and then even Rbe1-Bd1 to point with every piece to the center.   This central blockade by Black is really no mean feat and we will have to know how to take advantage of our f4 or g4 breaks at the right moment. I see it very difficult for Black to stay in such a strategic game without feeling like attacking. }
