14. Qe3 { This strange move allows us to go for a plan with Bd2-Rfc1-Nd1-Bc3. }
14... b5 15. b4 { Of course! } 15... cxb3 16. axb3 Nb7
{ It is vital for Black to play ...a5 and secure the c5-square. I played something similar against GM Inarkiev in a Ruy Lopez variation, that was similar to this one regarding the pawn structure and piece placement.   16...Rc8  17.Nd1  attacking a7, and our next move will likely be Bb2. After Nxb2 we could squeeze Black with something like Nd3-Nb4 —however, be careful with ...f5 in this particular case. b4 is the option here to hassle Black's a-pawn. }
17. b4
{ We want to continue with Bb2 increasing our control of the dark squares. Black has to do something with their sorrowful knight on b7. }
17... a5 18. bxa5 Qxa5 { We can meet  18...Rxa5  in a similar fashion. } 19.
Bb2
{ Intending to offer a dark-squared bishop trade with Nd1 and ask Black how will they coordinate the pieces. The b5-pawn will always be isolated and will be a target we can put strong pressure on. If the b5 pawn is ever supported by dxc5, we will have a passed center pawn.   In addition, we have in mind to insert Ra1, to exchange rooks and bring the other one to a1 before Nd1 in order to take advantage of the fact that the poor rook on f8 is momentarily out of play. }
19... Rc8 20. Nd1 Bxb2 21. Nxb2 Nc5
{ Presumably, the most reasonable continuation. Our plan was Nd3-Nb4. } 22. Ra1
{ Exploiting the fact that Black's queen has no good squares to go to. } 22...
Qd8 23. Nxc5 dxc5 24. Nd3
{ Do not be afraid of the creation of passed pawns, because there are dynamics at work in this position. If c4, we have the good blockade on b4 or Ne5, which is especially strong. The c6 square is an outpost, and Black does not have enough pieces to support the progress of the c and b-pawns.   I find Black's position very uncomfortable to defend, and our play has been based on playing against the knight on a5 and minimizing the impact of the rest of Black's pieces. }
