{ WATCH OUT against this move!! Now b4 would be a terrible blunder.   After  14.b4  cxb4  15.Rxb4  Rc8!  we cannot go for the typical jump Nb5 and the knight saturation is working against us.   13...f5  In King's Indian positions, this move usually does not work if Black has not prevented Ng5 first. The e6-square is very weak, and our knight coordinates very well with the bishop on the long h1-a8 diagonal, which is waiting for its turn.  14.Ng5  Nc7  15.Bf4  now our whole position makes sense, and we will simply accumulate troops in the center with Re1-e4 and Rad1. Against h6, we would jump to e6 and continue with Rad1. When in a position, where natural moves are very powerful, it becomes difficult for our opponent to defend. }
