{ Against the common  14.Bg5  aiming to force ...f6, Black can play  14...Qc7!  and  15.Be7  is impossible due to  15...Bb5!  . Besides, f6 is not a drama or substantially changes the game for Black, so it is not worth the risk. }
14... Bf5
{ Now we had freed up space to be able to threaten b4 properly and have Rc1 in case of what was mentioned a couple of moves ago. }
15. h3
{ Pushing the bishop away and bringing the queen on g3 is extremely pleasant in terms of coordination. }
15... b5
{ Black secures the c4 square for the knight, and makes us pay attention to b4 and c4 in all possible combinations. }
16. g4 Bc8
{ This surprising move is the best. One of the reasons for going for this difficult variation was that Black had no 'obvious' way to answer our questions. Now Nc4 and f5 are threats that should be taken into account. }
17. Qg3 Nc4
{ Black goes for a typical maneuver.   After  17...Nb7  we will simply continue  18.a3  followed by the typical b4.  Black cannot play  18...b4  as after  19.Nd1!  we will bring the knight to c4 without letting the b7-knight getting active. }
18. b3 Ne5 19. Nxd6
{ We punish Black's optimistic play. All of our pieces coordinate to take advantage of the circumstance.   One factor in our favor is that Black will be confident that this maneuver is interesting since  19.Nxc5  , which seems winning, it loses indeed after  19...g5! }
19... Qxd6 20. Ne4 Qb8 21. d6
{ The pawn is taboo because of the influence of our bishop in the h1-a8 diagonal. }
21... f6
{ After  21...Nd7  22.Nxc5  we will continue with Rfd1 and Rbc1 and the compensation for the sacrificed piece is huge. The rook on a8 will be in trouble and Black has little space to cope with. The pawn on d6 is a nuisance and it will be easy to find ideas related to Nxd7 and the entrance of our rook or bishops. The knight on c5 cannot be captured because of d7!. }
22. Rbc1 Ra7 23. g5
{ We will continue with Nxc5 and Black's position crumbles. Having opened the black king with ...f6 only generates more attacking resources in our favor. }
