{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... c5 3. d5 b5
{ The Benkö  (or Volga)  Gambit is a very frequent weapon at club level which guarantees an easy practical game for Black in exchange for a pawn. I have always had issues facing this variation, because it is extremely easy to make a small positional innacuracy, which will be very punishing because of our opponent's solid pawn structure.  In general, White is considered to be better, but I would be very careful with this variation if you haven't faced it in the past. I believe that this is a dangerous weapon in rapid time controls. Besides, even Magnus Carlsen has often played it. Black wants to sacrifice a pawn to open the a and b-files and put pressure on our queenside with a strong bishop on g7. }
4. cxb5
{ I have played the alternative move  4.Qc2  is several games, but I consider the text move easier to play. I prefer to recommend an approach in which we enjoy having an extra pawn. }
4... a6 5. e3
{ This move invites Black to take on b5 so we can develop our light-squared bishop on the f1-a6-diagonal. I don't like the main line with bxa6, g3 and Bg2, because our bishop on g2 is not very effective with a pawn on d5. The resulting position would be similar to a Benoni with g3 and requires a lot of preparation  (or very precise play)  by White to be able to answer the different plans that Black can go for.   The other alternative  5.bxa6  g6  6.Nc3  Bxa6  7.e4  allows Black to take our f1-bishop. Even though I have also played this line, this too requires very precise play. }
5... g6
{ Black usually gives priority to their piece development. One of Black's ideas will be to delay taking on b5 until we move the f1-bishop to force us to lose a tempo. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. a4 { Supporting our b5-pawn. } 7... O-O 8. e4
{ Once b5 is defended, we can start our central expansion. } 8... d6 9. Nf3
Nbd7
{ 9...axb5  10.Bxb5  Ba6  11.Bxa6  Nxa6  12.O-O  transposes to this line. } 10.
Ra3
{ A very useful waiting move, making it possible to take on b5 with the a-pawn. }
10... Ne8
{ When playing against the Benkö Gambit we should always be alert to Black's different ways to carry out their numerous plans.  In this case, Black opens de diagonal and tries to go to c7 with the knight to help untangle our blockade. It also enables ...f7-f5 as an option in the future to play against the d5-pawn. }
11. Bd3 axb5 12. Nxb5
{ Black's idea was to capture the pawn after we develop the bishop to gain a tempo if we take back on b5 with our bishop. By delaying the development of our bishop for some moves we now have this extra option available and we no longer lose a tempo. }
12... Ba6
{ 12...Nc7  13.O-O  Nxb5  14.axb5  The point of Ra3! Now the bishop on c8 is completely passive and we can challenge the a-file. Our knight will have a great outpost on c4 and our idea to push the h pawn is always on the agenda as well. }
13. O-O Nc7 14. h4
{ Whenever Black relocates the f6-knight to the queenside, h4 is a useful move. }
14... Nf6 15. Bd2
{ After Qe2 and Bc3, all our pieces are on ideal squares and we will be able to expand on the queenside with Rb1 and b4. We can also aim for Nd2-Nc4 in the future. }
