[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Budapest Gambit"]
[Black "3...Ng4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e5
{ I have used the Budapest Gambit as a weapon on several occasions, but lately it seems as if it's not so safe and sound anymore. This defense requires very little preparation from Black's point of view, so it is important to have an adequate reply against it.   Black temporarily sacrifices a pawn to break our center and activate his minor pieces. As I said, I played it on several occasions, but ever since I got beaten by a 2500-player without getting a chance, I prefer to play more solid variations. }
3. dxe5 Ng4
{ There are 3 usual replies to this move, divided into 2 concepts.   1@@EndBracket@@ The move Bf4 belongs to the first concept, which consists of defending the e5 pawn. Black usually ends up playing f6 and we will get positions where Black has some compensation. The resulting positions are hard to win.   2@@EndBracket@@ Nf3 and e4 belong to the second concept, which is to prioritize activity. Black is losing time with the knight maneuver and we can make use of this to gain a lead in development and, besides, Black gives up the center trying to take our pawn on e5.   The move I propose is along the lines of the second group, but is somewhat more aggressive. }
4. e3
{ When creating this course, my aim is also to update my way of approaching the game of chess and also my point of view on how the openings are played nowadays.   I would usually recommend the classical  4.Bf4  or  4.Nf3  , but I would like you to see the more modern variations and the style of play that predominates in the era of neural networks. }
4... Nxe5 5. f4
{ Asking Black's knight whether it prefers to hinder the development of the queenside or to retreat to a less than ideal square on the kingside. }
5... Nec6 6. Ne2
{ The knight is heading to g3, where it will be able to jump to f5 and help our expansion with a future e4, while also allowing our queen easy access to the kingside. }
6... d6
{ Black wants to develop the bishop to g7.   6...h5!?  would ask White a very logical question: what are we going to do with the knight on e2? White can play  7.Nec3  here we will continue with moves such as Be2-Nd5 and Bd2-Bc3. We have control over the center and it is not clear why the move ...h5 was played. There are some nice tricks in the position. For example, against  7...g6  we play  8.Nd5  Bg7  9.Bd2!  and the dark squares will be very weak in case Black takes on b2. Black can't play  9...Bxb2  because after  10.Nbc3  Bxa1  11.Qxa1  White is winning because of the weaknesses on dark squares in Black's camp. }
7. b3
{ Adapting our plan immediately to the situation on the board. There's nothing wrong with the intended  7.Ng3  but I prefer giving ideas that make you notice what your opponent played. Here we just counter black-s idea to develop the bishop through the a1-h8 diagonal. }
7... Be7 8. Bb2 Bf6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nbc3 O-O 11. Nd5
{ The knight is extremely strong on the central square d5 and the attack on the queen allows us to gain a tempo and play Ng3 next. We can complete our kingside development with Be2 and continue with e4 later on. Keep in mind that we are not interested in exchanging this knight and it's often better to play Nc3 in the next few moves if that means we can keep the knight on the board. Compared to the line with Bc5, we have exchanged Black's most active piece and we comfortably dominate the center. }
