3. dxe5 Ng4
{ There are 3 usual replies to this move, divided into 2 concepts.   1@@EndBracket@@ The move Bf4 belongs to the first concept, which consists of defending the e5 pawn. Black usually ends up playing f6 and we will get positions where Black has some compensation. The resulting positions are hard to win.   2@@EndBracket@@ Nf3 and e4 belong to the second concept, which is to prioritize activity. Black is losing time with the knight maneuver and we can make use of this to gain a lead in development and, besides, Black gives up the center trying to take our pawn on e5.   The move I propose is along the lines of the second group, but is somewhat more aggressive. }
4. e3
{ When creating this course, my aim is also to update my way of approaching the game of chess and also my point of view on how the openings are played nowadays.   I would usually recommend the classical  4.Bf4  or  4.Nf3  , but I would like you to see the more modern variations and the style of play that predominates in the era of neural networks. }
4... Nxe5 5. f4
{ Asking Black's knight whether it prefers to hinder the development of the queenside or to retreat to a less than ideal square on the kingside. }
5... Ng6 6. h4
{ This move is part of a concept that is repeated in many, many positions. The knights on g6 or b6 are vulnerable to either h4 or a4 pushes, respectively. By extension, it is often strong to play h4 or a4 when the knights are on e7 or d7. It's also a very common idea in hypermodern chess to simply sacrifice the h-pawn  (or a-pawn)  to open the h file  (or the a file)  which adds even more positions for us to consider h4-h5. Finally, I would also like to add that playing 6 pawn moves in a row is very cool :  . }
6... Nxh4 7. Nc3
{ After the standard plan to go Qc2, Bd2 and O-O-O, the rook on h1 makes Black's position uncomfortable. It will be difficult for Black to coordinate his pieces in time. The rest of this variation will show an instructive continuation. }
7... Bb4 8. Bd2 d6 9. Qc2 Nc6 10. O-O-O Bg4
{ Black wants to develop as quickly as possible to be able to castle. However, they still are 2 moves away to do so: The queen will obviously need to move, but Black will first need to move Ng6 because the queen is it's only defender, and a move like Nd5 would force the queen away from the defence. }
11. Be2 Bxe2 12. Ngxe2 Ng6 13. Ng3 Qd7 14. Nh5 Rg8 15. a3
{ Exploiting the fact that we win a tempo with this move. If Black takes on c3, the g7-pawn will be lost. }
15... Bc5 16. b4 Bb6 17. c5 dxc5 18. Be1
{ Black will not be able to castle which is of course good news for us. The moves f5, b5 and Nd5 counter any inventiveness by Black and we can expect our opponent to resign soon. }
