{ This move is part of a concept that is repeated in many, many positions. The knights on g6 or b6 are vulnerable to either h4 or a4 pushes, respectively. By extension, it is often strong to play h4 or a4 when the knights are on e7 or d7. It's also a very common idea in hypermodern chess to simply sacrifice the h-pawn  (or a-pawn)  to open the h file  (or the a file)  which adds even more positions for us to consider h4-h5. Finally, I would also like to add that playing 6 pawn moves in a row is very cool :  . }
6... h5
{ Black prevents us from advancing our h-pawn to make it a lot harder for us to attack the knight, but this move also creates new weaknesses that we can exploit. }
7. Nf3 Be7
{ 7...Bc5  8.Be2  followed by Ng5 and we will be able to eventually pick up the pawn on h5. We will not be in a hurry to take it though. We can prepare with moves like Nc3 and g3 first and after that the weak pawn on h5 and the horrible knight on g6 will still decide the game. }
8. Ng5
{ Continuing with the same plan is met with a curious reaction.   8.g3  defending h4  8...d6  9.Nc3  against this way of playing it is preferable to play e4-Be2-Be3-Qc2 and go for long castling. We have completely dominated both flanks and again Black's castling on the kingside will come with a high price: the weakness of the h5-pawn. }
8... d6 9. Be2 Bg4 10. Bxg4 hxg4 11. Qxg4 Qd7
{ And, suddenly, Black gets the initiative. } *

