{ I have used the Budapest Gambit as a weapon on several occasions, but lately it seems as if it's not so safe and sound anymore. This defense requires very little preparation from Black's point of view, so it is important to have an adequate reply against it.   Black temporarily sacrifices a pawn to break our center and activate his minor pieces. As I said, I played it on several occasions, but ever since I got beaten by a 2500-player without getting a chance, I prefer to play more solid variations. }
