4... Nc6 { 4...b6  5.Nf3  Bb7  6.g3  . } 5. Nf3 d6
{ Now Bc5 makes less sense than in the main line with 4. Nf3, since we don't have to play Bf4 to defend e5. Black seeks to sacrifice the pawn and coordinate their pieces.   If we capture on  6.exd6  we have to be careful with  6...Bxd6  threatening ...Nxf2 followed by ...Bg3+ winning our queen on d1. }
6. Qc2
{ The great problem of the Fajarowicz Variation is that Black has no time to execute their plan and the e4-knight proves to be too vulnerable. }
6... Bf5 7. Nc3
{ Exploiting the 'self-pin' that Black has created with their last move. } 7...
Nxf2 { 7...Ng3  8.e4  is pretty much the same story. } 8. Qxf5 Nxh1 9. e6
{ We will quietly capture the knight on h1 with g3 and Bg2, after which we will have two pieces for the rook and and excellent minor piece coordination. }
