{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... Nc6
{ The Two Knights Tango. I have faced this defence a few times, but I don't consider that it leads to such different positions that we should be overly concerned. Black's plan is to go for ...e5 without having to close the f8-a3 diagonal of the dark-squared bishop. }
3. Nf3
{ Preventing ...e5.   3.Nc3  can be justified as good by other means, but Nf3 seems to me more understandable and simpler to play. }
3... e6
{ Now BLack changes plans and aims to go ...Bb4+ followed by ...d6-...e5, in Bogo-Indian style. }
4. a3
{ The fact that Black's c6-knight is misplaced allows us to spend a tempo on preventing ...Bb4+. Moreover, 4.a3 is a reasonable alternative against Queen's Indian, as it has already been seen in other positions. }
4... d6
{ 4...d5  5.Nc3  the knight is not so well placed overall on c6 in Queen's Gambit structures. With moves such as e3-b4-Bb2 we will especially remark that the knight would prefer another square to be on. }
5. g3 g6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. Nc3
{ Reaching a favorable version of a g3-King's Indian but with the moves ...e6 and a3 included. In general, BLack wants to play ...e5, so they cannot take advantage of the move ...e6. Moreover, we have an extra option of playing e4 directly without being afraid of ...Bg4 ideas. }
