1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... c6
{ In general, this move order will lead to a Slav, but BLack has an interesting option that fascinated me the day I saw it.   2...d6  has no independent value. }
3. Nf3 b5 { Is this a legit move? } 4. cxb5 cxb5 5. e3 a6 6. Bd3 Bb7 7. O-O e6
8. Nbd2
{ A pattern that applies to a huge compendium of positions is as follows: - If Black manages to play ...a6-...b5, our queenside knight will be better placed on d2.    Some examples of this are:   1. Against the Meran Variation, the knight is better on d2 than on c3.   2. A concrete line of the Vienna Variation:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.e3  a6  , here the knight will be in trouble on c3due to the fact that is always vulnerable to BLack's ...b4-pushes.    It is key to have the ...b5-b4-blow available and also to be able to challenge the dark squares. By this I do not mean that it is ALWAYS better, but that the key to the position usually lies in both White's c3-knight and Black's b5-pawn. }
8... d5 9. Qe2
{ If Black wants to prevent our e4-push and our typical plan Re1-Nf1-Ng3, they will suffer due to the holes on the dark squares on the queenside. }
