[Black "2...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... b6
{ The Accelerated Queen's Indian gives Black a lot of interesting practical options. }
3. Nf3
{ The move 2...b6 gives us a few extra options compared to the normal Queen's Indian, but I prefer to lead the game to known territory. I often choose ways of transposing to known lines instead of going for specific variations that may give me a little bit more of an advantage, because it's easier to remember. I have never encountered this move order in a game, but it's relatively popular. }
3... Bb7 4. g3 c5
{ After  4...g6  5.Nc3  is an important move and we will continue with the thematic d5-push, completely closing down the diagonal of the b7-bishop. We are already dominating the center, and after the logical Bg2 and O-O, we can consider moves like Nd4. }
5. d5 b5
{ 5...g6  here is answered by  6.Nc3  again. The resulting position resembles the g3-Benoni, but here Black has played ...b6 and ...Bb7, which are completely useless moves in this variation. Our plan will be to go Bg2, e4 and O-O followed by an eventual e5-push. }
6. b3
{ An important move that pre-empts ...g6 by fighting for the dark-squared long diagonal.   It is important to start with this move, because if we play  6.Bg2  first and then continue with  6...g6  7.b3?  Black would punish us by playing  7...Bg7  8.O-O  Nxd5!  . }
6... e6 7. dxe6 fxe6 8. cxb5
{ This position resembles the Blumenfeld Gambit. Our development is very straightforward: Bg2, Nbd2, Bb2 and after that we should try to push e4. }
8... Qa5+
{ The only move that changes the character of the position and gets the pawn back. }
9. Nbd2 Qxb5 10. Bb2 Be7 11. e4
{ Black has lost some tempi with the queen, which allows us to challenge the center. }
11... Qa5
{ We have two very strong bishops, and if Black tried to gain space in the center, they would miss the f7-pawn and they would have issues with the hole on e6.  -This sentence should be improved, but I'm not sure what the author is trying to say here, because there is no hole on e6. Is the author talking about ...d5 and a weak pawn on e6, or ...d6 and ...e5 with a hole on e6?-  If Black plays standard moves, -such as...?- we should go for O-O and the mini-plan e5 and Ne4.  If Black plays the typical 12...Ba6, I really like the move 13.Ne5!, relocating the knight to d3 after 13...Bxd3 14.Nxd3. We will follow up with Rc1 and our knight d3 will help us to put pressure on c5.  -There's a nice way to trap the queen here after ...Qxa2   After for example:  14...O-O  15.Rc1  Qxa2??  . I'm not sure what the average level of the audience is going to be, but I think it would be nice  (especially for lower rated players)  to add this to the comment.- }
12. Bd3
{ We have two very strong bishops, and if Black tried to gain space in the center, they would miss the f7-pawn and they would have issues with the hole on e6. If Black plays standard moves, we would go for O-O and the mini-plan e5-Ne4.   If Black plays the typical  12...Ba6  , I really like the move  13.Ne5!  , relocating the knight to d3 after  13...Bxd3  14.Nxd3  . We will follow up with Rc1 and our knight d3 will help us to put pressure on c5.  There's a nice way to trap the queen here after Qxa2  for example:  14...O-O  15.Rc1  Qxa2?? }
