3... Bb7 4. g3 c5
{ After  4...g6  5.Nc3  is an important move and we will continue with the thematic d5-push, completely closing down the diagonal of the b7-bishop. We are already dominating the center, and after the logical Bg2 and O-O, we can consider moves like Nd4. }
5. d5 b5
{ 5...g6  here is answered by  6.Nc3  again. The resulting position resembles the g3-Benoni, but here Black has played ...b6 and ...Bb7, which are completely useless moves in this variation. Our plan will be to go Bg2, e4 and O-O followed by an eventual e5-push. }
6. b3
{ An important move that pre-empts ...g6 by fighting for the dark-squared long diagonal.   It is important to start with this move, because if we play  6.Bg2  first and then continue with  6...g6  7.b3?  Black would punish us by playing  7...Bg7  8.O-O  Nxd5!  . }
6... g6
{ After  6...bxc4  7.bxc4  e6  8.Nc3  Black's b7-bishop will be very weak and there's hardly anything that our opponent can do to stop us from expanding in the center. }
7. Bb2 Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O
{ This was Giri's choice in a game he played and he got a huge advantage. We will go Qc2, Nbd2 and e4 and we will have complete control over the center. It will be very hard for Black to create counterplay. }
