[White "25. 1...Nf6, Minor lines"]
[Black "2...b6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... b6
{ The Accelerated Queen's Indian gives Black a lot of interesting practical options. }
3. Nf3
{ The move 2...b6 gives us a few extra options compared to the normal Queen's Indian, but I prefer to lead the game to known territory. I often choose ways of transposing to known lines instead of going for specific variations that may give me a little bit more of an advantage, because it's easier to remember. I have never encountered this move order in a game, but it's relatively popular. }
3... Bb7 4. g3 Bxf3
{ This is one way of justifying this move order on our opponent's end. Black usually wants to fight against our pawn on d4, which will have lost the support of the e-pawn. In return, we have the bishop pair and Black has misplaced the pawn on b6, because it creates weaknesses on the light squares in the long run. The c6 square in particular will often become a problem for our opponent.   Our plan in this type of structure is to play d5 and strengthen our control over the light squares and also to fight for the e-file in the future. }
5. exf3 e6
{ If  5...g6  we play the important move  6.d5  . The first step of our plan is to go Be2, Nc3 and O-O. The next step will be to move Bg5, Qd2 and then bring our rooks to c1 and e1. We will still have the bishop pair and a space advantage.  Black can also play the immediate ...d5 here, which has been played in some high level games. }
6. a3
{ Our doubled pawns will be worse if there are fewer pieces on the board. On top of that, Black doesn't have a lot of space which means that exchanging pieces is desirable for our opponent. We should therefore not allow ...Bb4+. }
6... d5
{ Black's dream would be to block the d4-pawn by playing ...d5 themselves and then to threaten our pawn on d4 with their minor pieces. However, this is still far from being a real thing. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5
{ After  7...exd5  8.Nc3  the position we reach is very similar to what I recommend against the QID, but the difference here is that BLack's light-squared bishop has been exchanged for our knight on f3. Here we will aim for Bg2, O-O, Be3 and h4. After that we would like to play Ne2-Nf4 with the idea of Nd3-Ne5 next. This is a long-term plan, but there's no real way for Black to stop it.  We have to be aware that Black's only break in this position is to play ...c5, which benefits us enormously, since it opens the position for our bishop pair. Please also remember that Black has played ...b6 here. If the pawn were on b7, Black would be much happier, but, in the current position, the hole on c6 will always be problematic for Black. }
8. Nc3 Be7 9. Nxd5
{ We don't let Black get comfortable with their blockade of the d4 pawn. } 9...
Qxd5 10. Be3
{ The move Rc1 is very strong and Black will be left with a backward pawn on c7.   In addition, Black is behind in development and  10...O-O  will be met with  11.Bd3!  The Be4-threat is incredibly annoying for Black to deal with. Later, we can play the useful move Qa4, which will control the key square c6 and, by attacking a7, will hinder Black's development. }
