[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. Early Benoni"]
[Black "2...f5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Going for ...c5 straight away has always been labeled as 'inferior' as it allows White to play Nc3 without c4, which enables the c4 square for the g1-knight. But it is also necessary to emphasize that playing with c4 seems to me equally good and so we make the most of what we learned in the chapter on the Benoni.   Black's aim is usually to enter directly into Benoni structures with the pawn on d5 and seek to confuse White with different move orders. }
2. d5 f5
{ I have seen this variation a few times over the board, but it is a much inferior version of the Dutch. A very cool notion is that the c5 pawn cuts off a very important square for the knight on b8 in these Dutch structures and disables the possibility of playing a typical ...c6 to put pressure on our outpost on d5 and brings nothing in particular that Black can take advantage of. }
3. e4
{ Black's usual reply against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.e4  comes hand in hand with Black's ability to play d5, so we understand that this version is worse and allows White to play in this energetic way. }
3... fxe4 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Nge2
{ 5.g4  is Avrukh's recommendation. I played it back in the day, but now I do not think it is necessary to go for this pawn push.   After Ng3-Nxe4 we will take the pawn back and Black will be left with a weaker king and, besides, the e6-hole will be very uncomfortable to defend. We don't need any fireworks: we simply play Be2, O-O and Re1 and the long-term structural advantage is enormous. For example, we also have the option of playing c3, which completely nullifies the bishop on g7. }
