1. d4 c5
{ Going for ...c5 straight away has always been labeled as 'inferior' as it allows White to play Nc3 without c4, which enables the c4 square for the g1-knight. But it is also necessary to emphasize that playing with c4 seems to me equally good and so we make the most of what we learned in the chapter on the Benoni.   Black's aim is usually to enter directly into Benoni structures with the pawn on d5 and seek to confuse White with different move orders. }
2. d5 b5
{ Playing this move before ...Nf6 simply allows us to control the whole center. }
3. e4 a6 4. c4 bxc4
{ If Black does not take, we would reach a better version of the Benkö Gambit, as we have played e4 in one move instead of e3 and later on e4. }
5. Bxc4
{ We could also continue with f4-Nf3 with a good version of the Benkö Gambit Declined. }
