{ Pre-empting Black's ideas of trading the f8-bishop and delaying our e4-push. }
4... Nf6 5. e4 { Now we can play e4 without any risk. } 5... Be7 6. h4
{ While one of the model games will feature the move  6.h3  , I think 6.h4 also gets ready to meet Black's more obscure plans with ...Nbd7-...Nf8 and ...h5-...h4 in which Black can hold very well if we don't react in time. Another option would be to simply play h3 and if we see that Black goes for that setup, we play h4. A tempo in these fixed structures is not very noticeable. Here I especially like to look for g3-Bh3.   In my experience, these positions can turn against us when minor pieces are exchanged and we end up with the light-squared bishop inside our pawn structure. In this way, we minimize that risk and guarantee a chronic weakness of key light squares in Black's camp such as e6. Another plan that we will see in another variation is to look for Nf3-Nh2-g4, but here it seems to me better to take the opportunity to play h4. }
