1. d4 c5
{ Going for ...c5 straight away has always been labeled as 'inferior' as it allows White to play Nc3 without c4, which enables the c4 square for the g1-knight. But it is also necessary to emphasize that playing with c4 seems to me equally good and so we make the most of what we learned in the chapter on the Benoni.   Black's aim is usually to enter directly into Benoni structures with the pawn on d5 and seek to confuse White with different move orders. }
2. d5 e5
{ Black can reach the Czech Benoni via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  c5  3.d5  e5  move order.   The text move order is much worse, as it allows us to play e4-Nd2 and bring the other knight to c3. In this type of structures we can exploit convincingly the c4-square by giving it to our knight, which will fit perfectly with an eventual f4-push. }
3. c4
{ Although the other setup was quite good, our goal is to understand these structures with c4 to avoid untimely move orders and to better understand these pawn structures with the center closed. Sometimes Black goes for this move order to try plans without ...Nf6. }
3... d6
{ 3...f5  will be strongly met with  4.e4!  and Black loses the control of the light squares. }
4. Nc3
{ Pre-empting Black's ideas of trading the f8-bishop and delaying our e4-push. }
4... Be7
{ A very common plan for Black is to try to exchange the 'bad' bishop. } 5. Nf3
Bg4 { Black insists on trading the bad bishop. } 6. g3
{ This move is a demonstration of Black's technical problems in executing their plan. }
6... Bxf3 7. exf3 Bg5 8. Bxg5 Qxg5 9. Bh3
{ Black cannot stop the multiple threats presented separately with Qb3, Nb5 or O-O followed by f4 and taking advantage of the e-file. Black will pay dearly for the tempo investment to exchange their dark-squared bishop. }
