[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26. Early Benoni"]
[Black "2...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Going for ...c5 straight away has always been labeled as 'inferior' as it allows White to play Nc3 without c4, which enables the c4 square for the g1-knight. But it is also necessary to emphasize that playing with c4 seems to me equally good and so we make the most of what we learned in the chapter on the Benoni.   Black's aim is usually to enter directly into Benoni structures with the pawn on d5 and seek to confuse White with different move orders. }
2. d5 e6 3. c4 d6 { 3...exd5  4.cxd5  d6  transpose to a conventional Benoni. }
4. Nc3
{ The only difference from a conventional Benoni is the knight on g8. So we will see what plans Black has involving the move Ne7, which have sometimes been used as a surprise. }
4... exd5 5. cxd5 Ne7
{ I faced this move once in a tournament game against a Grandmaster. Black aims for the ...Ng6, ...Be7-...Bf6 plan to have good control of the critical e5-square. }
6. e4 Ng6 7. h4
{ We react similarly as we do against the Budapest Gambit. Remember that Black's knights on g6 and b6 are always vulnerable to the pawn pushes h4 and a4, respectively. }
7... Nxh4 8. f4 { Aiming for ...f5, when the knight will have no way out. }
8... Ng6 9. Nf3
{ Now, with the move f5 we prevent Black to occupy the e5-square with a piece. We keep total control of the space on both flanks in exchange for a pawn which absence, in fact, favors us because we can attack along the h-file. }
9... Nd7
{ This position is a fantastic example of how to play with the pawn structure d5-e4-f4 for White vs d6-c5 for Black. }
10. e5
{ Forcing our opponent's d-pawn to occupy e5, the square that both Black knights desire so much. This way, both pieces are left without purpose. }
10... dxe5 11. f5 Ne7 12. g4
{ Black knights are in the way and there is no adequate reply against d6 and Nb5. }
12... a6 13. d6 Nc6 14. Ng5
{ Now f7 becomes a target that Black will not be able to defend. To attack this square, we will go for moves such as Bc4, Qd5 or Qb3. }
