1. d4 c5
{ Going for ...c5 straight away has always been labeled as 'inferior' as it allows White to play Nc3 without c4, which enables the c4 square for the g1-knight. But it is also necessary to emphasize that playing with c4 seems to me equally good and so we make the most of what we learned in the chapter on the Benoni.   Black's aim is usually to enter directly into Benoni structures with the pawn on d5 and seek to confuse White with different move orders. }
2. d5 e6 3. c4 d6 { 3...exd5  4.cxd5  d6  transpose to a conventional Benoni. }
4. Nc3
{ The only difference from a conventional Benoni is the knight on g8. So we will see what plans Black has involving the move Ne7, which have sometimes been used as a surprise. }
4... exd5 5. cxd5 Ne7
{ Yo una vez me encontré con esta jugada en partida de campeonato contra un Gran Maestro. El negro busca Cg6, Ae7-Af6 y tener presencia en la casilla crítica e5. }
6. e4 Ng6 7. h4
{ Reaccionamos de manera similar al Budapest. Recordamos que caballos en g6-b6 siempre son vulnerables a h4-a4 respectivamente. }
7... Nxh4 8. f4 { Buscamos f5 y dejar sin escapatoria al caballo. } 8... Ng6 9.
Nf3
{ Now, with the move f5 we prevent Black to occupy the e5-square with a piece. We keep total control of the space on both flanks in exchange for a pawn which absence, in fact, favors us because we can attack along the h-file. }
9... Bg4
{ Black insists on controlling the e5-square. Now comes a colorful sequence in which we can see the harmony among White's pieces. }
10. f5 Ne5 11. Bb5+ Nbd7 12. Nxe5 { Legal's mate feels! } 12... Bxd1 13. Bxd7+
Ke7 14. Nc6+ bxc6 15. dxc6 { Threatening Nd5++. } 15... Qa5 16. Bd2 Kd8 17.
Rxd1
{ After Nd5 or e5 Black is totally lost. Our two pieces and the pawn on c6 coordinate wonderfully and Black's king is very vulnerable. }
