[Result "*"]

1. d4 c5
{ Going for ...c5 straight away has always been labeled as 'inferior' as it allows White to play Nc3 without c4, which enables the c4 square for the g1-knight. But it is also necessary to emphasize that playing with c4 seems to me equally good and so we make the most of what we learned in the chapter on the Benoni.   Black's aim is usually to enter directly into Benoni structures with the pawn on d5 and seek to confuse White with different move orders. }
2. d5 e6 3. c4 d6 { 3...exd5  4.cxd5  d6  transpose to a conventional Benoni. }
4. Nc3
{ The only difference from a conventional Benoni is the knight on g8. So we will see what plans Black has involving the move Ne7, which have sometimes been used as a surprise. }
4... exd5 5. cxd5 g6 6. h3 Bg7 7. Bf4
{ Applying our knowledge against the main Benoni.   This way, in case of  7...Nf6  we will transpose with 8.Nf3. }
7... Ne7
{ This move was played against me by a GM when I was barely 2200 and it was not at all easy over the board to know how to play against this. }
8. Nf3 O-O 9. e4
{ Similar to the variations in which Black either played ...Ne8 or in which they did not occupy the center, we can play e4. }
9... a6 10. a4 h6
{ This is part of Black's typical plan with the idea of ...g5-...Ng6 or ...g5-...f5 and give a new meaning to the kingside knight. }
11. h4
{ Although we lose a tempo, it seems more understandable to me than letting Black play ...g5-...Ng6 or ...g5 and ...f5-...f4. Now the knight on e7 is out of play. }
11... Re8 { Black aims for ...f5 or ...Nf5-...Nd4. } 12. Be2 Bg4 13. Qd2 h5 14.
Ng5
{ With the moves ...h5 and h4 included, the knight on g5 is so close to Black's castle and, besides, it cannot be kicked away because it has the e6-square as a final destination. Black will have to watch out for g4 at many moments, apart from the typical problems such as the weak pawn on d6 and the poor knight on e7. }
