[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Minor Black's first moves"]
[Black "1...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... g6
{ This special and flexible move only has some impact in a precise sequence of events. }
2. c4 Bg7
{ 2...c5  3.d5  b5  This move order doesn't make much sense as we can play e2-e4 in one move in comparison to the original Benko!  4.cxb5 4.a6 5.e4 }
3. Nf3
{ Again we go for this move order to keep the move orders stable. In case of   3.Nc3  Nf6  and we would enter some undesired Grunfeld positions.    3...f5  4.g3  This is another reason why we checked the Leningrad as a mainline.    3...d6  Transposes to some KID ideas we've seen with 1...d6.    3...b6  4.g3  Bb7  5.Nc3  Again, it's important to have  5...Nf6  6.d5!  as we saw in a different move order. }
3... e6
{ This setup was popularised 4-5 years ago. Black wants to play Ne7, 0-0 and then break the center with d5. It has the feel of the Grunfeld, but has some cracks in it. }
4. Nc3 Ne7 5. Bf4
{ The best and easier answer to it would be to transpose to some kind of classical position. }
5... d5 6. e3 O-O 7. Rc1
{ We delay the development of the Rf1 since 7...dxc4 8.Bxc4 would save us a tempo, and get some pressure into the c file. Black doesn't have any special answer and following with Be2-0-0 and then some Qb3-Rfd1 would be great in practice. }
