[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Minor Black's first moves"]
[Black "1...g6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... g6
{ This special and flexible move only has some impact in a precise sequence of events. }
2. c4 Bg7
{ 2...c5  3.d5  b5  This move order doesn't make much sense as we can play e2-e4 in one move in comparison to the original Benko!  4.cxb5 4.a6 5.e4 }
3. Nf3
{ Again we go for this move order to keep the move orders stable. In case of   3.Nc3  Nf6  and we would enter some undesired Grunfeld positions.    3...f5  4.g3  This is another reason why we checked the Leningrad as a mainline.    3...d6  Transposes to some KID ideas we've seen with 1...d6.    3...b6  4.g3  Bb7  5.Nc3  Again, it's important to have  5...Nf6  6.d5!  as we saw in a different move order. }
3... c5 4. d5
{ Now 4.dxc5 would be not as good, as black has Bg7 instead of Nf6. } 4... b5
{ This is the only annoying move order to claim . I mean, it's incredibly specific, but sneaks past our strong e3 answer against the Benko/Volga. }
5. cxb5 a6
{ Now we got to a weird Volga/Benko and 6. e3 is not an option as black can play axb5 7. Bxb5 Qa5+! winning a piece. }
6. Qa4
{ I love this move because it is only possible if black did not play Nf6 yet so it is easy to remember. Black pins the a6 pawn and most importantly helps the push e2-e4! }
6... f5
{ This funky move now makes quite a lot of sense right here. In Benko/Volga black usually draws upon f7-f5 in the middle game to weaken the d5 pawn, this way black has it far sooner and we could struggle to defend d5 if we don't react. }
7. e4
{ Most practical approach. Playing with e3 could be fine aswell with some investigation. }
7... fxe4 8. Ng5 Nf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be2
{ Considering black doesn't want to play d6 yet @@StartBracket@@weakens e6 enormously and the c8 bishop is required to untangle the queenside@@EndBracket@@ nor h6 as it makes its kingside too frail, delaying the capture makes sense. }
10... Bb7 { Only sensible plan. } 11. Qb3 axb5 12. Bxb5 Qb6
{ ¿What else can black do? } 13. O-O
{ We want to play a2-a4 securing the bishop and maybe threatening some a4-a5. Later we rather take the pawn on e4 finally. }
13... Ba6 14. Be2 { I love this smart move. We make use of the pin. } 14...
Qxb3 15. axb3 Bb7 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17. Bc4
{ We want to quickly invade the queenside and black is incredibly poorly coordinate. Remember, d6 still runs into problems after Ne6!. }
