1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... a6
{ There is a famous game by Tony Miles, who beat Karpov with this move, but unfortunately it is the exception to the rule. Black cannot justify the fact of giving up the center to White. }
2. c4
{ Bauer has frequently played 1...a6 followed by ...e6 and ...d5 against 2.e4. I think it is a very interesting idea against 1.d4 players as the tempo down makes Black's position slightly worse, but ...a6 is quite useful in most variations. }
2... b5 3. e4
{ Now there is no way to enter a pseudo-French. If Black allows us to take the b5-pawn, we will accept it gladly. }
3... bxc4
{ After  3...Bb7  4.d5  we close the diagonal of the b7-bishop and we strenghten our central control.  4...e6  5.a3  Preventing ...Bb4. Our next moves will be Nc3-Nf3 and Be2. The b7-bishop is fianchettoed against a wall, while our central control gives us a nice space advantage. }
4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nc3 Bb7 6. d5
{ Again leaving a sad bishop on b7 and the space advantage is decisive. } *

