1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... b5
{ The Polish Defense is terrible, as well as the simmetrical Anti-Grob @@StartBracket@@1. e4 g5@@EndBracket@@. Black gives up the center and will also have to waste another tempo defending the b5-pawn. }
2. e4 Bb7
{ Against  2...a6  we can go for the same plan as against 1...b6 but with a healthy extra tempo for us. }
3. Nd2
{ 3.Bd3  if we ignored Black and want to play as against b6 we would give Black an extra option. After  3...Nf6  4.Qe2  c5  Black's threat of ...c4 justifies this move order. }
3... a6 4. a4 b4 5. Bd3 e6 6. Qe2 d5 7. Ngf3
{ I love this position because we have an advantage in development, the center is ours and, besides, Black has eventual weak pawn on b4. In case of ...Nf6 we will continue with e5 and Nb3, hindering Black's reaction with ...c5. }
