[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... b6
{ The Owen's Defense is quite weak. Without playing ...e6, Black is giving up the center to White for free. }
2. e4
{ Although  2.c4  is also a good alternative, against these three Black replies it is important for us to know how to exploit the fact that we dominate the center. }
2... Bb7
{ Attempting now to go back to a French-type of position fails even more clearly.   After  2...e6  3.Bd3  d5  4.Nf3  Bb7  5.e5  Black is much worse. }
3. Bd3
{ The most reasonable development. The setup with Nf3-c3-Qe2 is ideal. If we play Nc3 we could be exposed to ...Bb4 or ...c5-ideas in which we cannot play d5, this way giving up our central control. }
3... f5
{ The typical tricky line that I saw when I was a kid, but now I know that it loses by force.   3...e6  4.c4  transposes to the analysis against the  1...e6 & b6 move order. Here the move 4.Nf3 followed by Qe2-c3 gives us a typical and comfortable advantage that we should know how to play and exploit. }
4. exf5 Bxg2 5. Qh5+ g6 6. fxg6 Bg7
{ Only move to stay in the game.   6...Nf6  loses dramatically after  7.gxh7+  Nxh5  8.Bg6  and here ends the great contribution of our opponent to chess. }
7. gxh7+ Kf8
{ This is Black's main idea: to sac whatever it takes to take our h1-rook. Now it is necessary to be slightly precise. }
8. Nf3 { We want to ckeckmate! Taking the knight would be a mistake. } 8... Nf6
{ 8...Bxh1  9.Ne5  Bxe5  10.dxe5  and Black's king is dead. } 9. Qg6
{ Winning by force against both bishop captures. } 9... Bxf3
{ 9...Bxh1  10.Bh6  Rxh7  11.Ng5  and Black can resign. } 10. Rg1 Rxh7 11. Qg3
{ Double attack on the f3-bishop and h7-rook. } 11... Be4 12. Bxe4 Nxe4 13.
Qf3+ { Getting the piece back with a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Minor Black's first moves"]
[Black "1...e6 - what to be careful about"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... e6
{ This move always caused me headaches. Black remains flexible in regards to their next move and apparently gives up more space in the center.   If you like to play against the French  2.e4  would be very useful to cut the path. I was playing French for a while and with this move order I avoided the most annoying lines against the Dutch. @@StartBracket@@  2.Nc3  or variations without c4@@EndBracket@@.   Besides, Black can play pseudo Queen's-Indians, pseudo Bogo-Indians, and pseudo Benonis, each of them with their own nuances. Taking all this into account, we will not take this move lightly. }
2. c4 { Of course, we go for Queen's Pawn-type of positions. } 2... b6
{ This move order is very dangerous if you don't know very well how to play and it is quite often used as a practical weapon to surprise an inferior or very theoretical opponent. Short, Emilio Cordova and Romain Edouard, among others, have used it with great success. }
3. Nf3 { If we try to transpose to Queen's Indian, we could get into trouble. }
3... Bb7 4. g3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2 Bxf3 6. exf3 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2
{ We usually play a3 in these structures when Black plays ...Bxf3 to prevent piece trades. Without the bishop pair to take advantage of the space generated by White's thematic d5, this position becomes quite delicate in practice.   Objectively White still has better chances by playing 8.d5 followed by Nc3, Be2 and O-O, but it does not have the same glamour. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "27. Minor Black's first moves"]
[Black "1...e6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... e6
{ This move always caused me headaches. Black remains flexible in regards to their next move and apparently gives up more space in the center.   If you like to play against the French  2.e4  would be very useful to cut the path. I was playing French for a while and with this move order I avoided the most annoying lines against the Dutch. @@StartBracket@@  2.Nc3  or variations without c4@@EndBracket@@.   Besides, Black can play pseudo Queen's-Indians, pseudo Bogo-Indians, and pseudo Benonis, each of them with their own nuances. Taking all this into account, we will not take this move lightly. }
2. c4 { Of course, we go for Queen's Pawn-type of positions. } 2... b6
{ This move order is very dangerous if you don't know very well how to play and it is quite often used as a practical weapon to surprise an inferior or very theoretical opponent. Short, Emilio Cordova and Romain Edouard, among others, have used it with great success. }
3. e4
{ The whole expansion in the center entails certain risks that should be kept in mind but, once analyzed, I believe it is worthwhile to go for it. }
3... Bb7 4. Bd3
{ 4.f3  would seem a natural continuation, but after  4...f5!  5.exf5  Nh6!  the complications favor Black and we get into swampy territory. }
4... Nc6
{ This idea has been played in many games and has a very simple goal in mind: attacking d4 and then play ...Nb4 getting the bishop pair. A strong 2600 GM played this once against me and I did not exploit my space advantage, so it could be dangerous.   4...Nf6  5.Nc3  Bb4  6.Qc2  we control the center for free, and we can continue with Nge2 and f4 to consolidate our space advantage. }
5. Ne2
{ Developing the knight to e2 will allow us to eventually support the center with f3. }
5... Nb4 6. O-O Nxd3 7. Qxd3 Ne7
{ Against ...Ne7 we will aim for f4 and f5-push. } 8. Nbc3 d6 9. d5 Qd7
{ The main move, with Short and Ponomariov as main followers, among other GMs. Black waits patiently to adapt to the plan we go for.   9...g6  is a bad attempt to mix variations.  10.Qd4  forcing e5  10...e5  11.Qd3  now f4 will be very strong and the e7-knight will be completely out of the game.   If  9...Ng6  10.f4  we deny the e5-square to Black's knight and we can improve our position with plans like b3-Bb2 or Ng3-Nh5  (this one specially in case Black castles on the kingside quickly.) }
10. a4
{ Apart from h3 I think this is a useful waiting move. We continue placing our pawns on light squares and preventing Black's counterplay. Additionally we can eventually go for the extra option a4-a5. }
10... a5 11. Nb5
{ Spending another tempo wisely, putting pressure on c7. We are still waiting for Black to define where their pieces will go. }
11... g6
{ Against Short's  11...Ng6  we can also continue with the same sequence we are going to see. }
12. Qc3 e5
{ So far we have been following the game Kramnik - Ponomariov. Kramnik played b4 here and he ended up being better. However, as we have seen in this chapter already, there is a better move. }
13. f4
{ Again exploiting the fact that the e5-pawn is pinned and the knight is not doing anything on e7. f5 is unstoppable and we enjoy a powerful knight on b5, which attacks on c7, so Black will not be able to take on f5 without paying a price. }
