[Black "1...e6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... e6
{ This move always caused me headaches. Black remains flexible in regards to their next move and apparently gives up more space in the center.   If you like to play against the French  2.e4  would be very useful to cut the path. I was playing French for a while and with this move order I avoided the most annoying lines against the Dutch. @@StartBracket@@  2.Nc3  or variations without c4@@EndBracket@@.   Besides, Black can play pseudo Queen's-Indians, pseudo Bogo-Indians, and pseudo Benonis, each of them with their own nuances. Taking all this into account, we will not take this move lightly. }
2. c4 { Of course, we go for Queen's Pawn-type of positions. } 2... Bb4+
{ I have faced this 'Accelerated' Bogo-Indian in some gamesand thrives on Black's flexibility and on confusing White with the move orders.   2...f5  will be analyzed in the Dutch chapter. }
3. Nd2
{ I prefer this move to keep my repertoire in the same style as we recommend in the Bogo-Indian, although Bd2 benefits without the moves Nf3 Nf6 being included. }
3... c5
{ Black's best reply.   3...d5  4.Qa4+  again forcing ...Nc6  4...Nc6  5.a3  similarly to what we see in the Bogo-Indian, we will enjoy a very comfortable Queen's Pawn position with the bishop pair and a badly placed knight on c6.   3...b6  4.a3  Bxd2+  5.Qxd2  transposing to what we analyzed in the Bogo-Indian chapter. }
4. a3 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2
{ Unlike what we saw in the Bogo-Indian, not including Nf3 and ...Nf6 means that we have to take with the queen on d2, so we do not have such a fluid piece development. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxd4
{ This seems a very logical decision to my eyes.   In his Catalan Lifetime Repertoire Narayanan recommends  6.Nf3  Nf6  7.Nxd4  d5  8.cxd5  Qxd5  8.Nf3  . This is an interesting practical option, but this move order reduces White's flexibility.   After Qxd4 and Qd2 White has spent the same amount of tempi than after Nxd4 folloewed by Nf3, but the difference is that, in our move order, we are not forced to take the d5-pawn, which gives us some extra options. }
6... Nf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Qd3
{ Each queen retreat has its nuances.   9.Qd2  followed by b4-Bb2 with a comfortable play thanks to the bishop pair is also a good option. }
9... d5 10. cxd5
{ This move would not have been possible with 9. Qd2, as after exd5 we will struggle against ...Ne4 ideas followed by ...Bf5 or ...Na5, exploiting our weak light squares. }
10... Qxd5 11. Qxd5 Nxd5 12. e4
{ After Bd3 and Ke2 we will enjoy a comfortable endgame with the bishop pair. }
