[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
1... d6
{ This move is very well-known for 'forcing' White players who play against the King's Indian without Nf3 to rethink their plan. For this reason, many of them opt for  2.e4  transposing to a Pirc/Modern/Phillidor.   The problem for White is that after  2...Nf6  they should play  3.Nc3  and give up any intention of playing Queen's Pawn positions. In this chapter we will discuss the following reasonable lines by Black without ...g7-g6 @@StartBracket@@which will be covered on the Modern Deefnse chapter@@EndBracket@@. }
2. Nf3
{ Preventing  2...e5  , which is a typical reaction against 2. c4. Usually it would not be advisable to lose the castling as, for example, after  3.dxe5  dxe5  4.Qxd8+  but, in this case, the c4-pawn takes away an ideal square for our f1-bishop and for our b1-knight as well.   We also lose the right to control the squares d4 and b4 as we would do with b3. In fact, it is considered that Black is already better in this endgame. }
2... Bg4
{ The only good attempt in this move order by Black.   2...f5  can also be tried, but will end up in a transposition to Leningrad Dutch positions. }
3. c4
{ While other options are possible, I like this move. The main idea is that we accept that Black will weaken our pawn structure, but then we aim for the d5-push. The reason is that Black's ideal dream would be to build a setup with ...e6-...c6-...d5-...Ne7-...g6-...Bg7 and then go for ...dxc4 and play against our isolated pawn on d4. }
3... Bxf3
{ 3...c6  Black wants to prepare the ...d5-push before taking on f3  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.d5  again restricting BLack's center and wiining the fantastic d4-square for our purposes. Later, we wll conquer the entire center with h3 and e4. }
4. exf3 g6
{ 4...c6  5.Nc3  Nf6  6.d5  again, restricting Black's center and we strenghten our control of the light-squares. Another effect of these positions is the pseudo-chronic weak pawn on e7. Black would like to break with e6, but this would also cause the position to open up further and we have the aces in our hand in the form of a bishop pair. }
5. Nc3 Bg7
{ Here black has not tried to look for d5 and it would be less effective to play this break to boost Black's bishop. }
6. h4
{ The steps we have to remember to calculate effectively are: checks, captures, threats and pushing h4! }
6... Nf6 7. Be3
{ After Qb3 and O-O-O our attack is easy to carry out and Black has little presence on the light squares, so it will be diificult for them to penetrate into our castling. }
*

