[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "The 1...e6 move-order with 4...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ This move order exploits the fact that we go for Queen's Pawn positions and we do not transpose to the French Defense. If any of you also play King's Pawn positions, it is interesting to go for  2.e4  in this position to avoid the numerous sidelines that Black has available after their first move.   Of course, we will cover them all -as this is a Queen's Pawn repertoire-, but I would like to remind you that this course can also be used as a complement at your own discretion. }
2. c4
{ We already covered 2.c4 when we analyzed the English Defence, but I would like to mention that if   2.Nf3  c5!?  and we would enter into radically different positions from those seen in this course. }
2... f5
{ I have myself played this kind of Dutch in numerous games. Black can go for ...Bb4+ ideas, they can play ...b6, the Stonewall with d5 and opt for the 'Classical' Dutch as well. }
3. Nf3
{ We will choose this move order to keep the flexibility characteristic of this course regarding our first 3 moves. }
3... Nf6 4. g3 Be7
{ The Classical Dutch is currently not very frequent, but there are a couple ideas you should know against it. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. b3
{ Again we prefer to deviate from more critical paths and keep the option of playing Nc3 or Nbd2 at our convenience. }
7... Ne4 8. Bb2 Bf6 9. Nbd2 Nc6 10. Ne1
{ The fact that White has scored an 80% in more than 30 games gives us a good review of what is the position about. Black has carried out quite a long setup in order to play ...e6-e5, but will not be able to play this pawn advance. }
10... Nxd2
{ 10...Ng5  11.f4  another problem of the Dutch is that White can play f4. In general, we neutralize each and every attacking plan by Black and we can exploit our space advantage in the center.   10...d5  11.e3  after Nd3 we completely dominate the center of the board. White can go for multiple options; for example, plans with Rc1-Nf3-Nfe5-f3 are very interesting to neutralize Black's counterplay. }
11. Qxd2 e5 12. Bd5+
{ White has won 9 games out of 9 played with this position. All of them tell stories about how sad the bishop on c8 is in all of them. }
12... Kh8 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Nd3 Re8
{ Note that  16...e4?  would be met by the strong in-between move  17.Bxf6  , ruining Black's pawn structure even more. }
17. f4 e4 18. Bxf6 exd3
{ 18...gxf6  19.Nc5  is an ode to White's positional advantage. } 19. Be5 dxe2
20. Rf2
{ Black's pawn structure is miserable and, besides, the light-squared bishop cannot be developed without weakening it even more @@StartBracket@@...c6-c5 has to be played for that purpose@@EndBracket@@. This is a good example to be taken into account: the presence of opposite-colored bishop does not guarantee that the position is a draw. However, White should avoid trading down the rooks in order to prevent drawish scenarios.  A very funny plan is to bring our rooks on e2 and d2 and our king to the queenside —more concretely, to a5.— Black cannot counteract the passivity of their bishop and the weaknesses on dark squares. }
