1. d4 e6
{ This move order exploits the fact that we go for Queen's Pawn positions and we do not transpose to the French Defense. If any of you also play King's Pawn positions, it is interesting to go for  2.e4  in this position to avoid the numerous sidelines that Black has available after their first move.   Of course, we will cover them all -as this is a Queen's Pawn repertoire-, but I would like to remind you that this course can also be used as a complement at your own discretion. }
2. c4
{ We already covered 2.c4 when we analyzed the English Defence, but I would like to mention that if   2.Nf3  c5!?  and we would enter into radically different positions from those seen in this course. }
2... f5
{ I have myself played this kind of Dutch in numerous games. Black can go for ...Bb4+ ideas, they can play ...b6, the Stonewall with d5 and opt for the 'Classical' Dutch as well. }
3. Nf3
{ We will choose this move order to keep the flexibility characteristic of this course regarding our first 3 moves. }
3... Nf6 4. g3 Be7
{ The Classical Dutch is currently not very frequent, but there are a couple ideas you should know against it. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O Ne4
{ I have successfully used the plan ...Ne4-...d5-...Nc6-...a5-...Bf6-...Bd7-...Be8-...Bh5 against extremely passive players @@StartBracket@@for example, against White's b3-Bb2-Qc2-Nbd2 setup@@EndBracket@@. The problem for Black is that I see no reason not to try to challenge the center more vigorously. }
7. Qc2
{ With this play we take advantage of the flexibility to play Nc3 or Nbd2 at our convenience. }
7... d6
{ In case of  7...Bf6  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.bxc3  Black has spent a very valuable tempi in playing ...Bf6 and we benefit from reinforcing the center with bxc3 and nullifying that move. Now we continue with e4 and enjoy total central control. }
8. Nbd2 d5
{ If  8...Nxd2  , we will play  9.Bxd2  and e2-e4 cannot be prevented. } 9. Ne5
{ As we have seen in these Stonewall structures, the knight on d3 is extremely useful. Black should also watch out for plans like Rd1-Nxe4 @@StartBracket@@to develop the dark-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@ and f3, gaining a lot of space in the center. }
