[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "The Stonewall #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ This move order exploits the fact that we go for Queen's Pawn positions and we do not transpose to the French Defense. If any of you also play King's Pawn positions, it is interesting to go for  2.e4  in this position to avoid the numerous sidelines that Black has available after their first move.   Of course, we will cover them all -as this is a Queen's Pawn repertoire-, but I would like to remind you that this course can also be used as a complement at your own discretion. }
2. c4
{ We already covered 2.c4 when we analyzed the English Defence, but I would like to mention that if   2.Nf3  c5!?  and we would enter into radically different positions from those seen in this course. }
2... f5
{ I have myself played this kind of Dutch in numerous games. Black can go for ...Bb4+ ideas, they can play ...b6, the Stonewall with d5 and opt for the 'Classical' Dutch as well. }
3. Nf3
{ We will choose this move order to keep the flexibility characteristic of this course regarding our first 3 moves. }
3... Nf6 4. g3 d5
{ The Stonewall has always been an interesting weapon, like all ideas in which one of the two players goes for a plan without caring what the opponent plays. This wide range of options facilitates the appearance of inaccuracies and doubts. Since we already have the knight on f3, our task will be simpler.   Black gives up the idea of controlling the dark squares in exchange for having a strong point on e4. The first key is that we can always challenge a Black piece on e4 with f2-f3 @@StartBracket@@this is why we will frequently go for Ne1-Nd3-f3 plans@@EndBracket@@ and the second important thing to remember would be to watch out for the ...g5-...g4 plan if we have touched our e2 pawn.     Let's imagine that Black plays ...g5-...g4 and we have already played e2-e3. In this case, we will lose any attempt at a central pawn break @@StartBracket@@after f2-f3, ...gxf3 would come and Black will dominate the e4-square@@EndBracket@@. So, the principle of counterattacking in the center when there is an attack on the wing will be practically impossible to fulfill. It is indeed quite dangerous, since we would be somewhat exposed to simple plans like ...h5-h4 and our control of the dark squares will not be so relevant since our opponent has excellent control of the light squares.    Another long-term plan for Black would be to go ...Bd7-...Be8-...Bh5 and trade their bad light-squared bishop. Again we appreciate the relevance of having or not the pawn on e2. ...Bxf3 will hardly be feasible if we can play exf3, remove the e4 square permanently from Black's knight and be able to exert pressure on the e6-pawn for free.  Finally, Black often opts for ...b7-b6 and develop the bishop to b7. The pawn on f5 is not ideal in Black's setup, but we must be attentive to ideas like taking on c4 and go ...c5, which will leave our c4 pawn isolated, this way justifying Black's pawn structure.    With this compendium of positional ideas I hope you understand a little better the dynamics of the Stonewall; perhaps with these brushstrokes some of you will have enough information. Obviously we now proceed to unravel the moves. }
5. Bg2
{ 5.Nc3  c6  6.Bf4!?  winning presence on the dark squares. I give you this very practical alternative that can surprise your opponents. Our idea is to play e3-Bd3 and pretend that g3 was never played. To keep our f4 bishop safe, we will play h2-h4 and castling will not be so much a priority, as we are interested in having the rook on h1, as ...g7-g5 is Black's only acceptable plan.   Plans such as Rc1-Qb3 or ideas like Kf1-Kg2 will be on the menu. It's a rather odd way to play, but perhaps some of you prefer a greater degree of abstraction and surprise your opponent. }
5... c6 6. Nc3 Be7
{ Black may prefer a more modest development and thus avoid the bishop exchange.   If black ever desires to take on c4 it would basically be a Catalan with a weird pawn on f5, black usually never wants to touch c6-d5-e6-f5 structure.   Ideas like Ne5-Nxc4 or some a4 would be great. I feel that even giving back the pawn straightforward with b3 would be justified, as black pawn structure is laughable. }
7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2 Nbd7
{ A very interesting trick. As we have said when analyzing other variations, Black does want to take on d5 with the c-pawn, as their pawn structure would be horrible in that case. That's why they 'provoke' White to play cxd5.   8...Ne4  9.Bf4  and we will continue with Rad1 and the same plan. }
9. Bf4
{ Not  9.cxd5?!  exd5  10.Qxf5?  Ne4!  11.Qe6+  Kh8  12.Nxe4  Nf6  and we lose the queen! }
9... Ne4 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Ne5 Bf6
{ In case Black trades two pairs of minor pieces with ...Nxe5 y ...Bf6, we will simply have a better bishop and we can continue with Qc3-Rad1-f3, with a comfortable advantage. }
12. Rad1
{ Exploiting the fact that Black cannot play ...Nxe5 due to dxe5 followed by Bxe4. The vital idea of Rad1 is to defend d4 and then we can play Ng4 followed by f3, removing any Black presence in the center and magnifying their poor light-squared bishop. }
*

