1. d4 e6
{ This move order exploits the fact that we go for Queen's Pawn positions and we do not transpose to the French Defense. If any of you also play King's Pawn positions, it is interesting to go for  2.e4  in this position to avoid the numerous sidelines that Black has available after their first move.   Of course, we will cover them all -as this is a Queen's Pawn repertoire-, but I would like to remind you that this course can also be used as a complement at your own discretion. }
2. c4
{ We already covered 2.c4 when we analyzed the English Defence, but I would like to mention that if   2.Nf3  c5!?  and we would enter into radically different positions from those seen in this course. }
2... f5
{ I have myself played this kind of Dutch in numerous games. Black can go for ...Bb4+ ideas, they can play ...b6, the Stonewall with d5 and opt for the 'Classical' Dutch as well. }
3. Nf3
{ We will choose this move order to keep the flexibility characteristic of this course regarding our first 3 moves. }
3... Bb4+
{ I implemented this idea against the strong Argentinian GM Fernando Peralta. It is quite simple: I wanted to develop the kingside pieces and play ...d6-...e5 to gain presence in the center. Once we know the opponent's convenient plan, it is easier to orient our ideas. }
4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Nf6 6. g3
{ Since we'll be playing g3-Bg2, if black tries to go for Ne4-b6-Bb7 we are in time to make use of the pin and play Nfd2 disrupting their hopes, so that option is not a concern. }
6... O-O 7. Bg2 d6 8. Nc3 Qe8
{ We are following my game. My idea is to play ...e5 while avoiding White's knight jump to d5 to attack my queen on e7. }
9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nd5
{ I will use this variation to give several examples of how to deal with minor pieces. I often find that it is quite complex for students to play in relatively fixed pawn structures that depend on accurately moving the minor pieces without having obvious threats in a few moves.   These positions are very good for training our concrete calculation and for paying special attention to Black's defensive possibilities. }
11... Na6 12. Nxf6+ Rxf6 13. e4
{ Important strategic concept. We threaten to isolate the e5-pawn with exf5.   In case of  13...fxe4  14.Ng5!  , we will regain the pawn and put pressure on the exposed e5-pawn.  If Black prefers to keep the position closed with  13...f4  we will see how important it is that Black's knight is on a6 after  14.Qc3!  when Black has nothing better tahn playing  14...Re6  , oppressing the c8-bishop movements. After  15.Rad1  @@StartBracket@@intending to go Rd5!@@EndBracket@@  15...c6  16.c5!  Black's position is very clumsy and we enjoy a practically decisive advantage simply because of our pawn structure and our opponent's exposed center. }
