[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "The 1...e6 move-order with 3...Bb4+ #14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 e6
{ This move order exploits the fact that we go for Queen's Pawn positions and we do not transpose to the French Defense. If any of you also play King's Pawn positions, it is interesting to go for  2.e4  in this position to avoid the numerous sidelines that Black has available after their first move.   Of course, we will cover them all -as this is a Queen's Pawn repertoire-, but I would like to remind you that this course can also be used as a complement at your own discretion. }
2. c4
{ We already covered 2.c4 when we analyzed the English Defence, but I would like to mention that if   2.Nf3  c5!?  and we would enter into radically different positions from those seen in this course. }
2... f5
{ I have myself played this kind of Dutch in numerous games. Black can go for ...Bb4+ ideas, they can play ...b6, the Stonewall with d5 and opt for the 'Classical' Dutch as well. }
3. Nf3
{ We will choose this move order to keep the flexibility characteristic of this course regarding our first 3 moves. }
3... Bb4+
{ I implemented this idea against the strong Argentinian GM Fernando Peralta. It is quite simple: I wanted to develop the kingside pieces and play ...d6-...e5 to gain presence in the center. Once we know the opponent's convenient plan, it is easier to orient our ideas. }
4. Bd2 Bxd2+ 5. Qxd2 Nf6 6. g3
{ Since we'll be playing g3-Bg2, if black tries to go for Ne4-b6-Bb7 we are in time to make use of the pin and play Nfd2 disrupting their hopes, so that option is not a concern. }
6... b6
{ As we will see throughout this course, it is important to see if our opponent can mix ideas. }
7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 Ne4 10. Qc2
{ The pawn on f5 allows us to exchange a couple of pieces, since it closes off the flexibility of Black's position, which is characteristic of the Queen's Indian.   Usually, we would try to pre-empt ...Ne4 or delay Nc3, but with the pawn on f5 we can simply put the rooks on d1 and c1 and then consider Ne1 or c5 —or d5 depending on what Black plays—. The strong center with c4-d4 and the possibility of breaking with c5 or d5 at convenience gives us a good advantage in the long run. Let's look at a couple of examples. }
10... Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Be4
{ 11...d6  12.c5  aiming to open the c-file and then trade the light-squared bishops. We have a somewhat similar position to the Exchange Slav, but with a pawn on f5, which greatly hinders Black's structure. We will become accustomed to seeing ways to punish Black's first move and the weaknesses it implies.   For example, if Black wants to play ...d5 now, the dark squares will be hopelessly weak. If our opponent wants to play ...e6-e5, the center opens dramatically and the lack of development, together with the a2-g8 diagonal, may imply material losses. }
12. d5
{ A good example of how to take advantage of Black's lack of development. }
12... exd5 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Rfd1 Be4 15. Ne5
{ Here we can see the importance of the weakness of the a2-g8 diagonal for Black. The c and d files give us a practically decisive initiative. }
