[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch is a defense that I hold in high esteem. Black apparently plays a 'symmetrical' Sicilian and should not be so special.   The big difference is that it immediately weakens the black king. Having played this variation dozens of times with Black, I have to admit that it has a certain venom and there are usually very specific positions of the variation where most pieces and pawns still remain on the board, which implies a lot of play. }
2. Nc3
{ I am going to recommend the move 2.Nc3 as an alternative. There are quite some options against 1...f5; for example, in 2004 I won a certain person called Wesley So with  2.Bg5  . In this past year 2022 I won three games with  2.Nc3  and I have been playing it for a very long time; I think it gives us very simple positions and can be a reasonable alternative if you prefer to know a few basic ideas against the Dutch.   I think the Leningrad is more consistent to gain advantage and, besides, you can learn more chess along the way. I myself have won some games with Black against 2.Nc3, so I will limit it to a very practical alternative. Our first idea is to play 3.e4; basically it's an Open Sicilian but with colors reversed, so Black's king is somewhat more exposed. }
2... Nf6
{ The most reasonable option. Black controls e4 and it doesn't make his structure much worse. Black cannot allow us to play e2-e4. }
3. Bg5
{ We continue as if we wanted to play the Rossolimo. I will not recommend to take on f6 in the future, but I want to force Black to go ...d5. }
3... g6
{ This development is tremendously unfortunate, but it is punished in a specific way. }
4. h4
{ It is very common for us to seek to burst Black's kingside structure if ...g6 is played. The lack of the f7-pawn changes the situation a lot and weakens enormously the h5-e8 diagonal. }
4... Bg7 5. h5 Nxh5 6. e4
{ This sequence is very often seen. We want to sacrifice the exchange. Unlike the main variation with 2.c4 and 3.Nc3, we have saved the c2-c4 tempo and, in addition, that square can be used by our bishop. }
6... fxe4 7. Rxh5 gxh5 8. Bc4
{ Black always aims for ...Kf8-...Qe8, so this move order avoids this option.   After  8...Kf8  9.Nxe4!  Black can resign in view of Qf3+. }
