[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "1...f5 - the 2.Nc3 alternative #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch is a defense that I hold in high esteem. Black apparently plays a 'symmetrical' Sicilian and should not be so special.   The big difference is that it immediately weakens the black king. Having played this variation dozens of times with Black, I have to admit that it has a certain venom and there are usually very specific positions of the variation where most pieces and pawns still remain on the board, which implies a lot of play. }
2. Nc3
{ I am going to recommend the move 2.Nc3 as an alternative. There are quite some options against 1...f5; for example, in 2004 I won a certain person called Wesley So with  2.Bg5  . In this past year 2022 I won three games with  2.Nc3  and I have been playing it for a very long time; I think it gives us very simple positions and can be a reasonable alternative if you prefer to know a few basic ideas against the Dutch.   I think the Leningrad is more consistent to gain advantage and, besides, you can learn more chess along the way. I myself have won some games with Black against 2.Nc3, so I will limit it to a very practical alternative. Our first idea is to play 3.e4; basically it's an Open Sicilian but with colors reversed, so Black's king is somewhat more exposed. }
2... Nf6
{ The most reasonable option. Black controls e4 and it doesn't make his structure much worse. Black cannot allow us to play e2-e4. }
3. Bg5
{ We continue as if we wanted to play the Rossolimo. I will not recommend to take on f6 in the future, but I want to force Black to go ...d5. }
3... d5
{ Black's main response. Black weakens the dark squares, but in return gains a lot of space in the center. We can see similarities with the Botvinnik variation of the English @@StartBracket@@1.c4 and then play g3 but, in addition, our idea is to to play e2-e4@@EndBracket@@.   Faced with this option, I prefer to recommend redirecting the position to a simpler goal than punishing the doubled pawns on f6. Capture and go for e3-Bd3-Qf3-h3-g4 has always been a plan I have enjoyed and against which I have rarely faced serious resistance. But I think that Black has continuations to prevent us from playing g2-g4 and then we are left with a position with less space and no pawn breaks, which has happened to me 3-4 times and the position becomes annoying. For all these reasons, I propose to limit ourselves to taking advantage of the weak dark squares.   How do we do that? Well, by relocating the bishop on f4 and aiming to play c2-c4, since our knight on c3 has lost its original purpose of providing us support to play e2-e4 and now simply interrupts the possibility of exerting pressure on the center with c2-c4 and supporting a future expansion with a3-b4. To give another simile, we would say that we are looking for a London in which Black has played ...f7-f5, since it is widely considered to be a very good setup for White. }
4. e3 e6
{ Black maybe wants to continue with ...c7-c5. Playing the ...a6-...b6-...Bb7 plan as if we were in a Rossolimo with 3...e5 does not work so well because Black does not want to castle long. }
5. Nf3 { Our plan is Bd3-Ne2 followed by c2-c4. } 5... Nbd7
{ This is the most precise move order to hinder our plan. Lagarde used it against me and I later used it against Pepe Cuenca in the World Rapid Championship 2021. Black intends to play ...c7-c5, but does not yet know where will the f8-bishop will go and prefers to have the option of taking on c5 with the knight right away.   5...a6  6.Ne5  followed by g4 is especially annoying in practice. }
6. Bd3 c5 7. O-O
{ In view of this precise move order @@StartBracket@@3 of the 5 games in the database are played by 2630+ players as Black@@EndBracket@@ I have to give a concrete response or Black's expansion will be extremely annoying for us, as we saw in my game with Pepe. Furthermore, it enables us to play 8. b3 and then continue with Ne2, since we don't have to fear the pin of the c3-knight with moves like ...Bb4 or ...Qa5.   7.dxc5?!  now White cannot continue with the Ne2-c4 plan because Black will take with the knight, hassling our bishop  7...Nxc5  8.Bb5+  Bd7  Black exchanged the 'bad' bishop and ended with a spectacular center and the knight is still misplaced on c3. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Cuenca Jimenez,J @@StartBracket@@2552@@EndBracket@@-Alonso Rosell, A @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2021 }
7... a6
{ The young Ukrainian prodigy Kirill Shevchenko is always very well prepared. The attempt is to expand first with a6-b5 and then play c4 at will, building the house from the foundations. }
8. b3
{ In case of  8.a4  , then Black could follow with ...h6-g5-...Nh5 and the position becomes very murky as a4 does not paint much by itself without Black having committed to playing c5-c4. }
8... b5 9. a4 c4 10. Be2 Bb4 11. Na2 Bd6
{ Black seems to finally be able to enjoy their advanced pawn structure.   Si  11...c3  12.a5  This move is key, as we are fixing two weaknesses in Black's position: the b4-pawn and the a6-pawn. Now our plan will be Nc1-Nd3, our dark-squared bishop will go to f4 and then we can continue with Nfe5 and look for a future expansion on the kingside with g4.   Black has to watch out for two very weak pawns and we have influence on both flanks. The pawn on a5 cannot be captured easily; it requires a lot of effort that can be missed in defending their castling and even if so, Black also has other weaknesses such as the one on e6. }
12. axb5 axb5 13. Nc3 Ba6
{ If  13...Rb8  we would continue  14.Bf4  . All the dark squares are ours and we have the a-file to enter into Black's position. }
14. Rxa6 { 14.Bf4  also gives us a nice advantage. } 14... Rxa6 15. Nxb5 cxb3
16. c4
{ The strong player from Israel finally prevailed with this positional exchange sacrifice. We want to take on d5 and leave the very exposed pawn that we will then put pressure on.   The point is that since there are only pawns on one flank, the extra exchange has less impact, since the long trajectory of the rooks has less influence on a single flank. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Nabaty,T  @@StartBracket@@2638@@EndBracket@@-Shevchenko,K @@StartBracket@@2633@@EndBracket@@ Struga 2021 }
