[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "The Leningrad with 7...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch is a defense that I hold in high esteem. Black apparently plays a 'symmetrical' Sicilian and should not be so special.   The big difference is that it immediately weakens the black king. Having played this variation dozens of times with Black, I have to admit that it has a certain venom and there are usually very specific positions of the variation where most pieces and pawns still remain on the board, which implies a lot of play. }
2. Nf3
{ I will focus on explaining these positions with 2.Nf3 so we will have no move order nuances and Black will be free to play as they please, but nothing is really particularly effective. I prefer that you can go into these positions with 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 without fearing that certain plans are not covered. }
2... Nf6 3. c4 g6
{ The Leningrad Variation is the most common played of all Dutch possible variations. Black plays a pseudo King's-Indian with the pawn on f5. If they manage to play ...e5 favorably, they will be fine, but the move ...f5 also has a strategical drawback that will be seen later. The greatest high-level player who goes for the Leningrad is the Spanish Grandmaster David Antón, who practices it assiduously, as well as the French champion Maxime Lagarde. }
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ Both  6...b6  and  6...Ne4  gave nothing to Black in the past. After  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1ppp1bp/1p3np1/5p2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppppp1bp/6p1/5p2/2PPn3/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  respectively, Black has obtained nothing. }
7. Nc3 { We have reached the first very big tree of options for Black. } 7...
Nc6
{ This variation is famous for reaching quite unique positions in the whole game of chess. }
8. d5 Ne5
{ If  8...Na5  9.b3  c5  10.Bb2  Black will pay a high price for having played f5. We will simply play Rb1-a4-Ba1 and we can continue with our central expansion.   Black usually pays the price of putting the knight on a5 in order to have control of the pawn breaks they can execute and when to go for them  (either ...e6 or ...b5)  . In this position, we have free hands.   If @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1p1bp/3p1np1/n2P1p2/2P5/1PN2NP1/P3PPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Ne4  10.Nxe4  Bxa1  11.Neg5!  (we treat Bd2 and e4)  11...h6  12.Ne6!  Bxe6  13.dxe6  Bg7  14.e4!  and Nh4 is next. Black's pawn structure is completely flawed on the light squares }
9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Qb3
{ This position is tremendously abstract. Black seeks to make progress on the queenside depending on what we play. For example, playing e4 would leave the f4-square vulnerable. The general idea is to look for ...h6-...g5-...Kh8 and perhaps continue with ...Qe8-...Qh5.   Therefore, prophylactic moves such as ...a6 will be common to avoid trouble on c7 after Nb5 ideas. Usually White aims for Rd1 and c5 and gain space. But I really did not understand what that would achieve, so I looked for a more consistent plan. }
10... h6 11. Rd1 g5 12. Bd2
{ We simply aim for developing normally with Rac1 and later bring our bishop to c3 in order for Black to mobilize their center, so that we can go for good pawn breaks for our interests. }
12... Kh8 13. Rac1 a6
{ After  13...f4  14.Ne4  we have control of all the light-squares. It is very typical for us to go Ba5! to force Black to create weaknesses with ...b7-b6. Once done that, we can safely break with c5.   13...e4  14.f3  we will bring the bishop to d4 and then our expansion with c5 will make a lot of sense. }
14. Nb1 Qe8 15. Bc3 e4
{ 15...Nd7  Black can try to keep flexibility in the center.  16.Qa3  now that there are fewer pieces surrounding our king, it is a good time to continue with the c4-c5 expansion. }
16. Be5
{ With Nc3 we can consider our plan being carried out successfully. We would only have to worry about Black's more aggressive variation. }
16... Qh5 17. Nd2
{ 17.f3  f4!?  would lead us to a very unclear position. With the text move being played, we are ready to take on c7. }
17... Ng4
{ If  17...Qxe2  18.Re1!  we take advantage of the fact that the knight is taboo -due to Bc3 and Rcd1, after which Black's queen would be trapped- to calmly take on c7 and Black has lost their initiative.   18.Bxc7  is also good, but this will force you to remember that after  18...b5  you have to play  19.Nf3!! }
18. Bxg7+ Kxg7 19. h3 Nf6 20. f3
{ Black's attack comes to an end and Black will have to deal with their pitiful pawn structure. }
