8. Re1 { We want to play e4; little more needs to be said in this regard. }
8... Qf7
{ Black's most usual reply, attacking our c4-pawn and getting ready to exert some pressure along the f-file in case we insist on playing our e2-e4 break. }
9. e4 { Of course! } 9... fxe4 10. Nxe4 Nc6 11. Neg5
{ This move is the start of a maneuver to force Black's queen out of the defense of the king. }
11... Qxc4 12. b3 Qb5
{ If the queen moves elsewhere, I like to go for a4! to leave Black's queen out of the game on the queenside. }
13. h3 { WE do not want Black's queen to return to the kingside via f5. } 13...
h6 14. a4 { An important intermezzo to remove the queen out of the 5th rank. }
14... Qb6
{ After  14...Qf5  we can see how useful the move h3 is, as it helps us play  15.g4! }
15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. Rxe6
{ Black is left with a weak castling, with a queen that is out of the game, and with holes on the light-squares. Black's position is a complete disaster. WE can get a huge advantage simply by going Qd3 + Bd2, coordinating our minor pieces.   For example, moves like b4 would put Black in some trouble because they do not want to allow us neither to squeeze their queen even more with a5 nor allowing us to open the b-file, as we will have access to the b7-pawn. }
16... Rae8 17. Qd3 Kf7 18. Re1
{ 18.Bd2  leads to a very fantastic sequence of amazing moves, but it is always better not to be forced to remember some rook positional sacrifices unnecessarily :@@EndBracket@@. }
18... e6 19. Bd2
{ Our next move would probably be Rac1 and we also have the Nh4 idea in hand. Black's queen is completely out of the game and it is not very healthy for Black to leave the king alone doing the task of defending the kingside pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "The Leningrad with 7...Qe8 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch is a defense that I hold in high esteem. Black apparently plays a 'symmetrical' Sicilian and should not be so special.   The big difference is that it immediately weakens the black king. Having played this variation dozens of times with Black, I have to admit that it has a certain venom and there are usually very specific positions of the variation where most pieces and pawns still remain on the board, which implies a lot of play. }
2. Nf3
{ I will focus on explaining these positions with 2.Nf3 so we will have no move order nuances and Black will be free to play as they please, but nothing is really particularly effective. I prefer that you can go into these positions with 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 without fearing that certain plans are not covered. }
2... Nf6 3. c4 g6
{ The Leningrad Variation is the most common played of all Dutch possible variations. Black plays a pseudo King's-Indian with the pawn on f5. If they manage to play ...e5 favorably, they will be fine, but the move ...f5 also has a strategical drawback that will be seen later. The greatest high-level player who goes for the Leningrad is the Spanish Grandmaster David Antón, who practices it assiduously, as well as the French champion Maxime Lagarde. }
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ Both  6...b6  and  6...Ne4  gave nothing to Black in the past. After  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1ppp1bp/1p3np1/5p2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppppp1bp/6p1/5p2/2PPn3/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  respectively, Black has obtained nothing. }
7. Nc3 { We have reached the first very big tree of options for Black. } 7...
Qe8
{ The most played move, but not in the last decade as it has some problems. Black wants to play ...e5.   Against  7...c6  , if we continue in the same fashion and play  8.Re1  , eBlack has the extra option  8...Ne4  9.Nxe4  fxe4  10.Ng5  d5!  It is very important that we always pay attention to the ...Ne4 ideas. Black activates his g7 bishop and gains presence in the center. }
8. Re1 { We want to play e4; little more needs to be said in this regard. }
8... Qf7
{ Black's most usual reply, attacking our c4-pawn and getting ready to exert some pressure along the f-file in case we insist on playing our e2-e4 break. }
9. e4 { Of course! } 9... fxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Rxe4 Bf5 12. Ng5 Qf6 13. Rh4
h6 14. Bd5+ e6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Rf4 Qe7 17. Re4
{ After this forced sequence, Black is already considering which Chessable course to buy in order to save this position. }
