7. Nc3 { We have reached the first very big tree of options for Black. } 7...
c6
{ This is the main way to approach the Leningrad. Now Re1-e4 is also decent but It far more complicated as white doesn't usually go for e4 soon. }
8. d5
{ I was looking for many ideas against the Leningrad, but I think this one is based on more general principles and less memorization —which I think may be more necessary in other variations—. We are aiming for Nd4, a plan which we have seen many times where we played d5 to counter Black's b6. In addition, we will have to attack the important e6-square, which has been weakened on move 1. :@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Bd7 9. Nd4
{ Rb1 is a candidate move to be played next, removing the rook from the dark-squared long diagonal and allowing the bishop to develop without any inconveniences. }
9... Qe8
{ A very logical idea. Black wants to continue with ...Na6, but does not want to take on d5. The reason is that the exchange makes it easier for our bishop on g2 to become active with a possible ...Ne6. As long as the c6 pawn remains there, that is not possible. }
10. Qb3
{ It's a 'pity' that Black's last move fails tactically. We put pressure on b7 and sideways we aim at Black's king on g8. }
10... Na6 { After ...Qc8 we play c5! and the house falls. } 11. Qxb7 Nc5 12.
Qb4 Rb8 13. Qa3 Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bxd4 15. Bh6
{ After this semi-forced sequence for Black to get some compensation for the pawn, we will continue with Rad1-b4 and Black's position collapses. The problem often with the Dutch is that Black's pawn on f5 is inconveniently placed :@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28. Dutch Defense"]
[Black "The Leningrad with 7...c6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5
{ The Dutch is a defense that I hold in high esteem. Black apparently plays a 'symmetrical' Sicilian and should not be so special.   The big difference is that it immediately weakens the black king. Having played this variation dozens of times with Black, I have to admit that it has a certain venom and there are usually very specific positions of the variation where most pieces and pawns still remain on the board, which implies a lot of play. }
2. Nf3
{ I will focus on explaining these positions with 2.Nf3 so we will have no move order nuances and Black will be free to play as they please, but nothing is really particularly effective. I prefer that you can go into these positions with 1.c4 or 1.Nf3 without fearing that certain plans are not covered. }
2... Nf6 3. c4 g6
{ The Leningrad Variation is the most common played of all Dutch possible variations. Black plays a pseudo King's-Indian with the pawn on f5. If they manage to play ...e5 favorably, they will be fine, but the move ...f5 also has a strategical drawback that will be seen later. The greatest high-level player who goes for the Leningrad is the Spanish Grandmaster David Antón, who practices it assiduously, as well as the French champion Maxime Lagarde. }
4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ Both  6...b6  and  6...Ne4  gave nothing to Black in the past. After  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1ppp1bp/1p3np1/5p2/2PP4/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Ne5  and  @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/ppppp1bp/6p1/5p2/2PPn3/5NP1/PP2PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 5 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Nc3  respectively, Black has obtained nothing. }
7. Nc3 { We have reached the first very big tree of options for Black. } 7...
c6
{ This is the main way to approach the Leningrad. Now Re1-e4 is also decent but It far more complicated as white doesn't usually go for e4 soon. }
8. d5
{ I was looking for many ideas against the Leningrad, but I think this one is based on more general principles and less memorization —which I think may be more necessary in other variations—. We are aiming for Nd4, a plan which we have seen many times where we played d5 to counter Black's b6. In addition, we will have to attack the important e6-square, which has been weakened on move 1. :@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Bd7 9. Nd4
{ Rb1 is a candidate move to be played next, removing the rook from the dark-squared long diagonal and allowing the bishop to develop without any inconveniences. }
9... cxd5 10. cxd5 Na6 11. Ne6
{ A novelty, but a very logical move in my opinion. We activate the bishop and with 2-3 conditions we will see that the position works. }
11... Bxe6 12. dxe6 Nc5 13. Nd5
{ Black can never take on e6 without losing the b7-pawn. This would be a nice trade for us to be able to enhance our bishops. On the other hand, Black cannot take on e6 without running into possible pins on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
13... Nfe4
{ Now Nxe6 would be a threat since after Bxe4 fxe4 Qb3 Black would have ...Nc5! back, solving all their problems.   13...Kh8  Black disables one of our conditions for our last move to work  14.Nxf6  Rxf6  15.Rb1  and again we are fine. If Black takes on e6 with the rook, we can play Bd5! followed by b4 —this way, the move Ne4 will not block our bishop—. Our threat is Bg5, trapping the rook. Finally, against the immediate ..Ne4 we will play Qd5-Be3 and Black's position becomes unpractical to play. In general, Dutch players —myself included— aim at keeping many pieces on the board to keep the game complex. In this case, we get out of their comfort zone. }
14. Be3
{ Preventing the situation I gave in the last comment. In case Black takes on b2, we could play Rb1 followed by Bxe4 aiming to take on b7. Suddenly, the e6-pawn will be very annoying for our opponent. }
14... Kh8 15. Bxe4 fxe4 { ...Nxe4 does not change our rook's fate. } 16. Rc1
Nxe6 17. Qa4
{ We will take on e4 —no rush; Black cannot defend it!— and Black's three pawn islands are a sign that something is not going so well for them. The knight on e6 is lame as it is ahead of the pawn chain with no support or free squares to pivot. If Black takes the b2-pawn, we will always reply with Rb1 followed by Rxb7, so our opponent is left without resources. }
