11... Bc8 12. Bb2 Qe7 13. Qc2 Bd7 14. Rad1 Rad8
{ We have briefly discussed the idea. I like to approach this position with the following goal: If we manage to play e3 and have both knights on e2 and d2 we can easily expand on the queenside and take advantage of our active bishops on both fianchettos.   Along the way we have to watch out for ideas like ...Ng4 —in this case we can kick the knight away and we are not worried about ...Nxe3@@EndBracket@@ or, if we go for Rfe1, we should prevent any ...Nxf2 ideas. We also have to take into account that we can play the immediate b4 against ...Nc5 by Black, which would be a very reasonable idea for them.   If Black goes for ...h6-...g5, moves like Nf3 or Ne2 are a good reply against it. Since Black has more difficulty in mobilizing their pawn structure, we have a fairly classical advantage. Looking at several correspondence games I am surprised at how much the analysis engines have evolved, since these positions were more difficult to interpret in the past and gave good results. Most errors were made by deviating from the guidelines we have given here. }
