[Black "2...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nf6
{ This move is a relatively frequent mistake in the beginner level and among players that does not know much theory. }
3. cxd5
{ Of course, we take the pawn and we aim to expand our center with e4. } 3...
Nxd5 4. e4
{ 4.Nf3  is a precise move order to prevent one good reply by BLack. Now e4 is unavoidable and White will enjoy a great pawn center. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e5
{ A very frequent theme. White is still a bit better, but the advantage is greatly reduced and Black seriously challenges our central control.   After something like  6.dxe5  Qxd1+  Black can play Ne4 or Ng4 against both captures on d1, reaching an equal position. }
