[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "2...Bf5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5
{ A nice joke that requires a bit of precision from us to counter. } 3. cxd5
Nf6
{ If we play as against the Grünfeld, maybe we would not play an early Nc3, as it will allow Black to go ...Nxd5 and ...Nxc3. But we can wait patiently with our knight on b1. }
4. Nf3 Nxd5 5. Nbd2 Nf6 6. g3
{ White has most of the positive ingredients of a good Catalan. Typical ideas like Qb3 and Nh4 are now on the menu, as Black's bishop is on f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "2...Bf5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5
{ A nice joke that requires a bit of precision from us to counter. } 3. cxd5
Bxb1
{ THis is Black's idea behind ...Bf5: preventing us from comfortably playing Nc3 after ...Qxd5. }
4. Rxb1
{ The typical recommendtaion here is  4.Qa4+  but I wanted to investigate the text move. }
4... Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ Even  5.a3  semms to give White a huge advantage effortlessly, but this one is funnier. Our goal is to play a3 and then g3. }
5... Qxa2
{ If  5...Nc6  6.e3  in this case it is better to strenghten the center to have the Qc2-move available in case of O-O-O  6...Qxa2  7.Bd2  the knight on c6 will be hassled with b4-b5, apart from White's huge advantage in development. }
6. Bd2
{ Preventing eventual ...Bb4+ ideas and threatening the simple e4, after which Black's queen will be left hopeless on a2. }
6... Qd5
{ After  6...Nf6  7.Qc2  both ...Qxc7 and e4 cannot be prevented at the same time. Black's position falls apart due to the lack of development. }
7. Rc1 c6 8. e3
{ Being a lot of tempi up in the opening in exchange for the pawn on a2 seems like a good deal. The plan of Bc4-Qb3 and later on continue with e4 and aim for the d5-break seems quite definitive.   I also like to offer these variations for you to learn to assess the fact that material is relative and that being active is important.   If you like this concept, I encourage you to evaluate  8.e4!  that is even better, but it would already be outstanding. }
