[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "2...c5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5
{ This move is not as bad as it seems. Even Mamedyarov dared to play it on numerous occasions. }
3. cxd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 cxd4 5. Nc3
{ Exploiting the pin to accelerate our development. } 5... Qa5
{ 5...Qd8  6.Qxd4  Qxd4  7.Nxd4  Black cannot prevent Nd5 or Ndb5. The development will cost them dearly. }
6. Nxd4 Nf6
{ 6...e5  this move already seems very bold to my eyes.  7.Nb3  Qc7  8.a3  other moves would perhaps be more accurate but with a3 the advantage in development is obvious and so we don't have to remember any more moves. We simply prevent ...Bb4 and we want to continue with e4-Bg5-Rc1 to put Black in important trouble to be solved over the board. }
7. a3
{ The move a3 is useful to pre-empt Black's plan, which is either playing ...e6 or ...e5 and ...Bb4 next. At the same time, we are able to expand with b4 at the expense of the traveling queen on a5. }
7... g6
{ Si  7...Bd7  8.b4  Qh5  9.g3  again getting a dream Catalan in which BLack has wasted four 4 tempi with the queen.   7...e5  8.Nb3  Qc7  9.Bg5  intending to go Bxf6, Nd5, Rc1. White's play is really easy. I like better the plan with g3 if we take on f6 with the bishop. THe reason is that we can exploit that the black bishop will not play as much on f6. Instead, if black recaptures with the pawn, I would like more going e4-Bc4 taking advantage of the weak light squares. }
8. b4 Qd8 9. Bf4
{ If ...a6 we can continue with Rc1, g3, Bg2, O-O and both bishops are like knives. Black will still have a lot of homework to do in relation to developing the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "Albin's Countergambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ The Albin Counter Gambit had its golden age in the early 2000s thanks to Morozevich, but has fallen out of favor because the engines have improved, making it easier for White to obtain an advantage out of the opening. Black gives up a central pawn to gain space in that area of the board and to hinder the development of our pieces. }
3. dxe5 { The only way for White to obtain an advantage. } 3... d4
{ This is Black's main idea: to gain some space in the center and benefit from simple piece development. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3
{ White has several alternatives to refute the Albin, but 5.a3 seems to me to be the most appropriate, since it is based on the principle that we would like to play 5. e3 to exchange Black's active pawn on d4.    Inserting a3-a5 benefits us enormously by avoiding Black's O-O-O plans. And if they let us, we can expand with b4.   The other important consideration is that the move  5.e3  fails because of  5...Bb4+  followed by dxe3, leaving a very weakened pawn structure. }
5... Nge7
{ Black wants to take quickly on e5 and activate their pieces. Inserting 5.a3 a5 benefits us enormously because in many variations Black would like to play O-O-O and with the move a5 on the board this would be a lot less safe for the black king. }
6. b4 Ng6 7. Bb2 Ncxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. e3
{ We're exploiting the fact that the d4-pawn is pinned to defend c4 and we will take on d4 with the bishop. }
9... Be6 { Threatening our c4-pawn again. } 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. Qc2
{ Black will struggle to castle on the kingside. After simple moves like Bd3, Nc3 and O-O it will be difficult for Black to castle comfortably. }
*

