1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5
{ The Albin Counter Gambit had its golden age in the early 2000s thanks to Morozevich, but has fallen out of favor because the engines have improved, making it easier for White to obtain an advantage out of the opening. Black gives up a central pawn to gain space in that area of the board and to hinder the development of our pieces. }
3. dxe5 { The only way for White to obtain an advantage. } 3... d4
{ This is Black's main idea: to gain some space in the center and benefit from simple piece development. }
4. Nf3 Nc6
{ White has several alternatives to refute the Albin, but 5.a3 seems to me to be the most appropriate, since it is based on the principle that we would like to play 5. e3 to exchange Black's active pawn on d4. }
5. a3
{ Inserting a3-a5 benefits us enormously by avoiding Black's O-O-O plans. And if they let us, we can expand with b4. The other important consideration is that the move 5. e3 fails because of ...Bb4+ followed by dxe3, leaving a very weakened pawn structure. }
5... a5 6. e3
{ With 5.a3 we prevented 5...Bb4, which means that we can now safely put pressure on Black's overextended d-pawn with 6.e3. }
6... Bg4
{ Black can try to take back the e5 pawn, but they will be left with a very deplorable position.   6...dxe3  here would be far worse as black will be forced to take on d8 with the knight losing a lot in development, hence playing Bg4 first makes more sense. }
7. Be2 dxe3 8. Qxd8+ Rxd8 9. Bxe3 Bxf3
{ Nc3-Nd5-0-0-0 was coming, so Black eventually will have take on f3 and there's no other specially useful move. }
10. Bxf3 Nxe5 11. Bxb7 Nxc4 12. Bc6+ Ke7 13. Bf4
{ Black has indeed managed to regain the pawn, but the resulting position is simply lost. Black's king is stuck in the center, his pawns are weak and the black pieces are horribly passive. }
*

