[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "Chigorin Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Chigorin Defense has been played at the top level by Morozevich and recently by Richard Rapport. Black aims to immediately put pressure on our center with minor pieces. This defense slightly resembles the Scandinavian Defense, and requires us to play 3-4 accurate moves. Generally, Black will be struggling with his knight's on c6. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.Nc3  is also an option here, but my aim with this course is to respond with the moves d4, c4 and Nf3 against basically anything to make sure that we can't get surprised if Black uses strange move orders and to make it easier to memorize the lines. }
3... dxc4
{ 3...Nf6?  is bad because of  4.cxd5  moves like e4 and Nc3 force Black's pieces away from the center with tempo, and we'll end up with a nice space advantage. This is a clear example of the problems that can arise when Black is not reinforcing the center with pawns.   3...e5  trying to switch to some Albin doesn't make much sense now to me. After  4.Nxe5  Nxe5  5.dxe5  d4  we will just follow with  6.g3  and f2-f4 makes it really easy to keep the pawn up. }
4. d5 Na5
{ It makes no sense at all to move the knight back to it's starting square. After  4...Nb8  5.e4  our extra tempi compensate for our over expansion in the center. The simple plan Bxc4, Nc3 and O-O will give us a huge advantage. }
5. Qa4+ c6 6. Bd2 { And the game is over after only six moves. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "Chigorin Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Chigorin Defense has been played at the top level by Morozevich and recently by Richard Rapport. Black aims to immediately put pressure on our center with minor pieces. This defense slightly resembles the Scandinavian Defense, and requires us to play 3-4 accurate moves. Generally, Black will be struggling with his knight's on c6. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.Nc3  is also an option here, but my aim with this course is to respond with the moves d4, c4 and Nf3 against basically anything to make sure that we can't get surprised if Black uses strange move orders and to make it easier to memorize the lines. }
3... Bg4
{ Black's only sensible alternative, aiming to continue challenging the center.   3...e6  4.a3  and we draw similar conclusions to those given in the Two-Knight Tango: the knight makes no sense on c6 in this pawn structure. }
4. e3
{ We focus our efforts on the poorly placed knight on c6 by over defending d4. We will often play Qb3 in this variation to put pressure on d5 and b7. }
4... Nf6 5. Qb3
{ A typical move in the Slav when Black's light-squared bishop is developed. With this move we put pressure on b7 and d5. }
5... Bxf3 6. gxf3 Rb8 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bd2
{ With a typical position where we will castle long and push h4-h5. We have the bishop pair and control the center. }
