{ Black's only sensible alternative, aiming to continue challenging the center.   3...e6  4.a3  and we draw similar conclusions to those given in the Two-Knight Tango: the knight makes no sense on c6 in this pawn structure. }
4. e3
{ We focus our efforts on the poorly placed knight on c6 by over defending d4. We will often play Qb3 in this variation to put pressure on d5 and b7. }
4... e5
{ Black continues with his plan to challenge the center.   4...e6  5.a3  This is a practical alternative for those of you who want to enjoy a comfortable position. The plan b4-Be2-Bb2 and Nbd2 seems to me an amazing way of playing against the Chigorin with effortless memorization.   Eventually, a c5-b5 expansion could suffocate Black's army, so their aim is to play ...e5. However, with this piece arrangement it is very difficult to go for the ...e5-break because we firmly control this square and our plan is incredibly simple. The Chigorin Defense is quite rare, so with this variation I would be very satisfied to have a comfortable game with a long-term advantage. }
5. Qb3 { With a little precision, we will get out of this tactical mess. } 5...
Bxf3 6. gxf3 dxc4
{ This move leads to the most complex variation of the Chigorin Defence. } 7.
Bxc4 Qd7 8. dxe5 Na5 { Black should prevent Qxb7. } 9. Bxf7+
{ In this position the tactics favor us. } 9... Qxf7 10. Qb5+ c6
{ After  10...Nc6  11.Qxb7  we're regaining the piece with interest and Black is hopelessly lost. }
11. Qxa5 Qxf3 12. Rg1
{ The only game that made it this far continued with Rf1, but g1 is a much better square for the rook here. }
12... Nh6
{ 12...Ne7  13.Qb4  hinders Black's development quite a lot because if ...O-O-O we will play Qg4+! }
13. Nd2 Qf5 14. e4 Qf4 { Black hinders the development of our knight. } 15. e6
{ White wants to trade BLack's active queen on  f4  . The knight will be completely suffocated on  h6  , since  15...Ng4  is not possible because of  16.Qf5!  . }
15... Rd8 16. Rg3 { Building a shelter for the king on the kingside: Kf1-Kg2. }
16... Qd6 17. Qh5+ g6 18. Qh3
{ After Kf1 and Rb3 followed by Nf3, our pieces will be able to come out. It should be fairly straightforward to find the right moves, while Black will need to continue playing precise moves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "Chigorin Defense #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Chigorin Defense has been played at the top level by Morozevich and recently by Richard Rapport. Black aims to immediately put pressure on our center with minor pieces. This defense slightly resembles the Scandinavian Defense, and requires us to play 3-4 accurate moves. Generally, Black will be struggling with his knight's on c6. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.Nc3  is also an option here, but my aim with this course is to respond with the moves d4, c4 and Nf3 against basically anything to make sure that we can't get surprised if Black uses strange move orders and to make it easier to memorize the lines. }
3... Bg4
{ Black's only sensible alternative, aiming to continue challenging the center.   3...e6  4.a3  and we draw similar conclusions to those given in the Two-Knight Tango: the knight makes no sense on c6 in this pawn structure. }
4. e3
{ We focus our efforts on the poorly placed knight on c6 by over defending d4. We will often play Qb3 in this variation to put pressure on d5 and b7. }
4... e5
{ Black continues with his plan to challenge the center.   4...e6  5.a3  This is a practical alternative for those of you who want to enjoy a comfortable position. The plan b4-Be2-Bb2 and Nbd2 seems to me an amazing way of playing against the Chigorin with effortless memorization.   Eventually, a c5-b5 expansion could suffocate Black's army, so their aim is to play ...e5. However, with this piece arrangement it is very difficult to go for the ...e5-break because we firmly control this square and our plan is incredibly simple. The Chigorin Defense is quite rare, so with this variation I would be very satisfied to have a comfortable game with a long-term advantage. }
5. Qb3 { With a little precision, we will get out of this tactical mess. } 5...
Bxf3 6. gxf3 dxc4
{ This move leads to the most complex variation of the Chigorin Defence. } 7.
Bxc4 Qd7 8. dxe5 O-O-O
{ This funny logical novelty might get us into some trouble if we are not careful. }
9. e6 { The only good continuation. Black cannot take. } 9... Bb4+
{ Makes use of the mate on d1 in case of 10. Qxb4?? } 10. Kf1
{ Almost always we will go for Kf1 anyway later on, so might aswell do it now and have more flexibility. }
10... Qe7 11. exf7 Nh6 12. a3
{ In case of 12. Nc3 Na5! was very annoying, so we better force the bishop to decide his path first. }
12... Ba5
{ 12...Bc5 13.Nc3 Rhf8 14.h4 Again we follow with Be2-Qc2 and an eventual b2-b4. We could just keep up with Be2-Qc2- Bd2-Rd1 in this case, as black doesn't have that much pressure on our knight on c3. }
13. Nc3 Bxc3
{ This doesn't work by some magic you will soon admire.   13...Rhf8 14.h4 We want to go for Be2-Qc2 and look for b4-Bd2 to complete the development and secure the e3 pawn that might get targeted later on. In case of an eventual Bxc3 we would love to access the b file with the rook. Our pawn structure covers our king pretty well, once we finish developing our pieces black will pay the sacrificed pawn and our bishop pair. }
14. bxc3 Na5 15. Qb4 { Taking on c4 and Rd1+ was a winning threat for black. }
15... Rd1+
{ The answer to 15. ... Qxb4 was 16. Be6!+ a key intermediate check. } 16. Ke2
Qxb4 17. Be6+ Kb8 18. cxb4 Rxh1 19. Bb2
{ Black likely will need to sacrifice the h6 knight to stop f7. Then we just retreat our bishops to a2-b2 @@StartBracket@@to say one square@@EndBracket@@ and we push the f and e pawns mercilessly to victory. }
