[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "29. 1...d5, Minor lines"]
[Black "Chigorin Defense #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6
{ The Chigorin Defense has been played at the top level by Morozevich and recently by Richard Rapport. Black aims to immediately put pressure on our center with minor pieces. This defense slightly resembles the Scandinavian Defense, and requires us to play 3-4 accurate moves. Generally, Black will be struggling with his knight's on c6. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.Nc3  is also an option here, but my aim with this course is to respond with the moves d4, c4 and Nf3 against basically anything to make sure that we can't get surprised if Black uses strange move orders and to make it easier to memorize the lines. }
3... Bg4
{ Black's only sensible alternative, aiming to continue challenging the center.   3...e6  4.a3  and we draw similar conclusions to those given in the Two-Knight Tango: the knight makes no sense on c6 in this pawn structure. }
4. e3
{ We focus our efforts on the poorly placed knight on c6 by over defending d4. We will often play Qb3 in this variation to put pressure on d5 and b7. }
4... dxc4
{ Black usually aims to achieve something similar to the Bg4 variation in the QGA. Playing e6 and looking for Bd6-e5 later on. }
5. Bxc4 e6 6. Nbd2 Nf6 7. O-O Bd6 { Black's aim is to break with ...e5. } 8. h3
Bh5 9. a3 a6
{ ...e5 is strongly met by Qb3!, as it is on each try black has on its previous moves, so the text is a waiting move that pre-empts our b4-push, as now it can be met by ...e5. }
10. Be2
{ Here we can see the point of having played h3 and Be2: Black will not be able to play e5, because of Nxe5!. We will follow up with the moves b4 and Bb2 to make sure that Black will never be able to play ...e5 and his position will be very uncomfortable to play. }
10... Qe7 { The only move that insists on playing ...e5. } 11. b4 e5 12. dxe5
{ 12.Nxe5  does not work here:  12...Bxe2  13.Nxc6  Bxd1  14.Nxe7  Bc2!  and the knight is trapped on e7, which means that we lose a piece. }
12... Nxe5 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Nh4
{ Punishing the only drawback of the move ...Qe7. } 14... Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Qe6 16.
f4 Ned7 17. e4
{ White has an amazing position and Black will have a very hard time to hold it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Queen's Gambit Declined - Black avoids the Catalan"]
[Black "3...Bb4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+
{ After  3...dxc4  we have the extra option  4.Qa4+  available, but I still believe that  4.e3  , transposing to the Queen's Gambit Accepted is somewhat better. }
4. Bd2
{ Since Black has already commited to ...d5, losing the inherent flexibility of the Bogo-Indian, it seems more logical to me to play Bd2.   4.Nbd2  gives Black several alternatives that do not convince me. }
4... a5
{ 4...Qe7  5.Qa4+  Nc6  6.Nc3  and both the queen on e7 and the knight on c6 are a bit misplaced in this structure. We will continue with a3, Qc2 and e3 and will enjoy a good version of the Queen's Gambit Declined.   4...Be7  5.g3  transposes to the Catalan. }
5. a3 { Asking Black's bishop what its intentions are. } 5... Be7
{ After  5...Bxd2+  6.Nbxd2  we can continue with g3 with a typical and comfortable Catalan, or we can opt for e3 and Rc1 with a very nice Queen's Pawn position. Usually, when you only have one bishop left, it's preferable to put the pawns on the opposite color to make sure that the bishop isn't being blocked by friendly pawns. With the pawns fixed on the light squares, Black has exchanged his strong bishop for our bad bishop. }
6. Nc3
{ Once again I think it is better to opt for some version of the Queen's Gambit Declined here. The inclusion of a5-a3 benefits us enormously, since Black usually wants to play ...c5 followed by ...Qa5 in these positions. }
6... Nf6 7. Bf4 O-O 8. e3
{ We will play Qc2, take on d5 and develop our bishop to d3 with a very comfortable Queen's Pawn position in which Black cannot go for their usual plans. We should start by taking on d5 to fix Black's pawn structure and continue with moves like Bg3, Ne5 and f4.   In these Queen's Pawn positions all our pieces are on very logical and harmonious squares, it could be said that it is the 'Italian Opening' in the 1.d4 complex  (in terms of concept. Low paced, long term plans, kinda solid and basic for starters)  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Queen's Gambit Declined - Black avoids the Catalan"]
[Black "3...c6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6
{ This is the most common move order to go for the Triangle Variation setup. Black wants to prevent the Exchange Slav and can choose to play a very complex position after  4.Nc3  dxc4  . The triangle variation is a very useful line to build a repertoire around, because Black can play these moves against almost anything. In fact, Sielecki and L'Ami have recently published a Chessable course based on this defense. I prefer to follow the positional lines to avoid some of the sharper variations.   The move order  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  c6  4.e4  leads to one of the sharpest variations of modern chess: The Semi-Slav Marshall Gambit.  4...Bb4  5.Bd2  .   3...c5  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  We already analyzed these positions on the chapters dedicated to the Catalan. After an eventual ...Nf6 it will end up transposing. In general, these pawn structures are very good for us if our knight is on b1. }
4. Nbd2
{ I think this move is very easy to play and we also avoid some annoying sharp lines of the Triangle Variation.   After  4.Nc3  dxc4  5.a4  Bb4!  Black is in time to push ...b5, which results in highly unbalanced positions and this is exactly what Black want here. Our move 4.Nbd2 is a flexible option that avoids those lines. We simply defend c4 and keep our options open. }
4... f5
{ It is usual for the Triangle Slav players to transpose to the Stonewall after 4.e3 or 4.Nbd2, taking advantage of the fact that the g8-knight has not been developed yet. }
5. g3 Nd7
{ Usually black would go Ngf6, this move order is a bit tricky as it doesn't allow us to play with Ne5  (as I explain in move 7)  . You should be aware here that black can go Nh6. }
6. Bg2 Bd6 7. O-O Ngf6
{ Black's ...Nd7 and ...Bd6 prevent us from going Ne5, but it doesn't really change much.   7...Nh6  8.Ne1  following the classical plan of playing Nd3 and, after that, both b3-Bb2 and Ndf3-Ne5-f3 are always safe options to consolidate our center, as Black's plan with Nh6 can be Qf6-Nf7 focusing on the e5 square instead of e4. We can also look for some expansion b4-c5-b5 but it is a bit more specific depending on Black moves. So, i'd rather go for the safer aproach with b3. }
8. Ne1
{ As is often the case in the Stonewall, it's a good idea to move the knight to d3. From there it perfectly controls the center and it allows us to answer ...Ne4 with Qc2, Nd2-Nf3-Nfe5 and f3. }
8... O-O 9. Nd3 { Qc2 and b4 are on the agenda. } 9... b6 10. cxd5
{ Our standard reaction to ...b6 is to take on d5, as you should already know at this point in the course. }
10... exd5 11. Nf3
{ We reach a pseudo-Queen's Indian with a pawn on f5, which guarantees our access to the e5-square and on top of that the c6-pawn will be permanently weak. }
*

