{ At first I was going to recommend  4.Nbd2  , as it leads to positions similar to the Catalan, but after  4...c5  5.g3  dxc4  6.Nxc4  b5  7.Nce5  Bb7  ,  (a line suggested in Max Warmerdam's Chessable course)  , I found no holes for White to exploit and it really seems to me to be very comfortable for black. With 4.Bg5 we take advantage of Black's lack of development to accelerate our own. }
4... Nf6
{ This move is less common, but now the position trnsposes to one with a typical Catalan pawn structure.   The move  4...f6  has been played in some games, but this move makes no sense at all. It hinders Black's development and weakens the kingside. We will play 5.Bd2 and Black will regret moving the pawn. Even Carlsen did not managed to score any points with it. }
5. e3
{ This move order is very annoying for Black.   The most common one would be @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  a6  and here we should play  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  and Black can play ...Be6 straight away, intending to go ...Nbd7 and ...Bd6 next. Instead, in our move order we have not taken on d5 yet and Black's pawn is still on e6, which means that Black can't play ...Be6. }
5... dxc4
{ Black can try to sneak a QGA. The huge difference you might notice is our beloved dark-squared bishop on g5 ready to fight. }
6. Bxc4 c5 7. O-O
{ And having Be2 in mind we can look for the endgames shown on QGA. } 7... cxd4
8. Nxd4 Be7 9. Be2
{ Nothing too crazy is happening but Black cannot play b5-Bb7 easily so requires some deep thinking. We can keep up with Nc3-Bf3 and then our piece flow easily. Next step would be Qb3 and connect the rooks or getting presure on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
