[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 a6
{ The Janowski Variation has only become popular recently despite receiving its name from a 19th century French player. Black wants to take on c4 and defend it with ...b5, while keeping their options open.   However, I find it a bit 'modern' as it requires serious analysis to justify not developing a piece. }
4. Bg5
{ At first I was going to recommend  4.Nbd2  , as it leads to positions similar to the Catalan, but after  4...c5  5.g3  dxc4  6.Nxc4  b5  7.Nce5  Bb7  ,  (a line suggested in Max Warmerdam's Chessable course)  , I found no holes for White to exploit and it really seems to me to be very comfortable for black. With 4.Bg5 we take advantage of Black's lack of development to accelerate our own. }
4... Nf6
{ This move is less common, but now the position trnsposes to one with a typical Catalan pawn structure.   The move  4...f6  has been played in some games, but this move makes no sense at all. It hinders Black's development and weakens the kingside. We will play 5.Bd2 and Black will regret moving the pawn. Even Carlsen did not managed to score any points with it. }
5. e3
{ This move order is very annoying for Black.   The most common one would be @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  d5  4.Nc3  a6  and here we should play  5.cxd5  exd5  6.Bg5  and Black can play ...Be6 straight away, intending to go ...Nbd7 and ...Bd6 next. Instead, in our move order we have not taken on d5 yet and Black's pawn is still on e6, which means that Black can't play ...Be6. }
5... dxc4
{ Black can try to sneak a QGA. The huge difference you might notice is our beloved dark-squared bishop on g5 ready to fight. }
6. Bxc4 b5 { This is the most common way to play for Black but feels off. } 7.
Be2 c5
{ Black can try to play c5 straight away but the bishop on g5 allows us to play quicker on the queenside with Rc1. }
8. O-O Bb7 9. a4 b4 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. Nb3
{ We put some immediate pressure on Black's queenside. } 11... cxd4 12. Nfxd4
{ We'll keep up with Bf3 and black is already into deep trouble when our rooks come to the center and our knights start jumping around. }
