{ The main reply. Black offers a very unusual piece trade so early in the game. }
5. Bxe7 Qxe7 6. Nbd2
{ I think this position is very comfortable for White and we can play in the style of the Catalan. }
6... Nf6 7. g3 O-O
{ The main issue with this move is that it loses a tempo, which means that Black is now no longer in time to play ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7 and ...c5. }
8. Bg2 b6
{ 8...Rd8  Black looks forward to play in the center  9.O-O  Nc6  10.Rc1  dxc4  11.Rxc4  e5  Usually this answer is pretty typical in the Catalan variations, but black is lacking a bishop d6.  12.Rxc6!!  is an amazing exchange sacrifice made by Grischuk. After  12...bxc6  13.Nxe5  and the pawn on c6 will fall.   We are not in a hurry, and we could start with Nb3 first securing the center and threatening Na5-Nc5 ideas. If we manage to get a defended knight on c6, black will not be able to use b nor d columns and both rooks will be very sad.   1-0 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Vallejo Pons,F @@StartBracket@@2704@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019 }
9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 c5 11. Ne5
{ Black doesn't have a comfortable way of dealing with the jump to c6. } 11...
cxd4 12. Nc6 Qd6 13. Nxd4 Bb7 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. e4
{ Now Black has to be careful with the loose b7-Bishop. } 15... N5f6 16. Nc4
Qb8 17. Qe2
{ Our next move will be e5 and after that we can use the d6-square and the the c-file to penetrate Black's position. }
