[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 a6
{ The Janowski Variation has only become popular recently despite receiving its name from a 19th century French player. Black wants to take on c4 and defend it with ...b5, while keeping their options open.   However, I find it a bit 'modern' as it requires serious analysis to justify not developing a piece. }
4. Bg5
{ At first I was going to recommend  4.Nbd2  , as it leads to positions similar to the Catalan, but after  4...c5  5.g3  dxc4  6.Nxc4  b5  7.Nce5  Bb7  ,  (a line suggested in Max Warmerdam's Chessable course)  , I found no holes for White to exploit and it really seems to me to be very comfortable for black. With 4.Bg5 we take advantage of Black's lack of development to accelerate our own. }
4... Be7
{ The main reply. Black offers a very unusual piece trade so early in the game. }
5. Bxe7 Qxe7 6. Nbd2
{ I think this position is very comfortable for White and we can play in the style of the Catalan. }
6... Nf6 7. g3 b6
{ This is Max Warmerdam's recommendation. Black aims to have some presence in the center before castling. }
8. Bg2 Bb7 9. Rc1
{ With this subtle move we force Black to play ...c5 because ...Nbd7 is not possible due to cxd5 and c7 would be hanging. }
9... c5 10. cxd5 exd5 11. dxc5 bxc5
{ Getting a hanging pawns position that is hard for Black to play over the board. The main problem of the hanging pawns is that they are very vulnerable, exposed and, besides, they are not very mobile. After the forcing sequence... }
12. Nb3 Nbd7 13. Na5 Rb8 14. Nxb7 Rxb7 15. b3
{ ...we have removed Black's light-squared bishop from the board, which weakens Black's center even more. }
15... O-O 16. O-O a5 { Black wants to reduce their pawn islands to only two. }
17. Re1
{ Our plan is to play Nd2 and Qc2. Above all, we try to prevent Black from playing the ...a4-break comfortably and also to open the bishop on g2 to threaten an eventual e4. In case Black goes for ...a4 ideas, it would open the door to moves like Nb1!, with the idea of bringing the pony to c3 and put pressure on d5.   Black's idea is to go for this type of set-up to play 'practical' and in this position they must play with extreme precision, so I consider it to be very good for our interests.   Another interesting option is to play  17.Ne1  intending to go Nd3-Nf4. The position is extremely rich and there is quite some room to investigate and test different ideas. }
