[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. Nf3
{ This move order is useful to approach the Queen's Gambit Accepted and the rest of the repertoire. Let's look at the only extra order available to Black for completeness of the repertoire. }
2... c5 3. c4
{ After  3...e6  it is not bad to remember that  4.cxd5  exd5  5.g3  is a very comfortable Tarrasch for White as we have saved the Nc3 tempo. }
3... cxd4
{ Mamedyarov's field of expertise.   3...dxc4  would transpose to  3...c5  which is analyzed in this chapter. }
4. cxd5 Nf6 { 4...Qxd5  transposes to what we analyze on the 1...d5 chapter. }
5. Qxd4 Qxd5 6. Nc3 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 a6 8. g3
{ Our next move will likely be Bg2 with a very comfortable Catalan.   After  8...e5  we retreat the knight with  9.Nb3  and Black will have no satisfactory plan.     A funny alternative that also gives an advantage is @@StartFEN@@rnb1kb1r/1p2pppp/p4n2/8/3N4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KB1R w KQkq - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.f4!  I do not include it as our main recommendation to prevent you from getting confused by it. Its idea is to prevent e5 and comfortably play g3. }
