2. c4
{ The starting position of the famous Queen's Gambit. White offers a pawn and hopes to get it back in a few moves so that we can enjoy a 2vs1 central majority. This is the most common opening inside the 1.d4 d5 complex, and in this chapter we will see what happens if Black decides to accept the gambit. }
2... dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted is an alternative that has always been considered as 'solid', but until recent years it was not played as frequently by top-level players.   The accuracy of today's modern engines have turned around many annoying variations in practice and especially has provided answers against the most critical variation  3.e4  . }
3. Nf3
{ We have chosen these variations for various reasons:    1. It fits well in our repertoire: playing 3. e4 would eliminate the possibility of going 1.Nf3 or 2.Nf3   2. I consider this move to be the most sustainable variation in the long run and fits with the 'Lifetime Repertoire' kind of courses. The alternative 3. e4 could be obsolete for sure in a short period of time, and the massive memorization it requires would be useless.   3. This is the variation I have always played myself and has given me a lot of success. With little knowledge you can play at a high level, and it is also very comfortable to play.   Our idea is to continue with e3 and Bxc4. We play first 3.Nf3 instead of 3.e3 because this way we can avoid Black's extra option 3...e5! }
3... Nf6 4. e3
{ Delaying the capture would only get us into trouble.   The alternative  4.Qa4+  is quite weak as Black is flexible enough to meet the capture with  4...Nc6  followed by Nd7, with a nice position for the second player.  For example, via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  dxc4  this would make more sense, as Black has commited to the move ...e6. Even so, we will go for 4.e3 as the alternative does not completely convince me. }
4... Bg4
{ Black goes into a variation that reminds of one in the Slav Defence. Our opponent aims to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn structure and will play ...e6 next to complete the development. An interesting variation, but if White knows how to counter it, Black will be in trouble quickly. }
5. Bxc4 e6 6. Nc3 { After controlling the center we aim to push h3-g4. } 6...
a6 7. h3 Bh5 8. O-O c5 9. dxc5
{ Reaching a very good endgame for us. The bishop on h5 is totally out of action, we will play with the same idea of Be2-Bd2-Na4-Rac1. Most of the time Black will have no choice other than play ...Bxf3 and part with the bishop pair. }
