11. Qe2 cxd4 12. a5
{ An important intermezzo that guarantees reaching the ideal position for our interests. }
12... O-O 13. exd4 Nc6
{ 13...Nbd7  from here, Black's knight prevents our own knight's jump to b6 but cannot move at all.  14.Rd1  Again, Black will suffer with a6 and the rigidity of his queenside. We want to develop the bishop and again play Qe4 and migrate to the kingside in case of ...Nd5. Against other Black plans, moves like Bd2, Nfe5 and h4 would be interesting to consider. }
14. Rd1 { Now we have to develop the bishop. } 14... Qc7
{ Preventing Bf4.   14...Nd5  15.Qe4  and our kingside attack will be very direct. If ...g6 we will go Bh6-h4. }
15. Be3 Rad8 16. Nce5
{ Here we see Black's main problem. The pawn on a6 will be a permanent nuisance and we can combine attacks on the kingside with pressure on the queenside. }
