3... Nf6 4. e3
{ Delaying the capture would only get us into trouble.   The alternative  4.Qa4+  is quite weak as Black is flexible enough to meet the capture with  4...Nc6  followed by Nd7, with a nice position for the second player.  For example, via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  dxc4  this would make more sense, as Black has commited to the move ...e6. Even so, we will go for 4.e3 as the alternative does not completely convince me. }
4... e6
{ Black's main continuation, clearing the way of the dark-squared bishop to be able to play ...c5 with the idea of challenging our center. }
5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6
{ This move order is not the most precise against our plan of playing the endgame. Black will miss the flexibility to go into the endgame by opting for Nbd7 or Nc6 as appropriate. }
7. Nc3 a6
{ Worse would be  7...Be7  because Black will lose a tempo if we play  8.dxc5  . }
8. dxc5 { I think this move will lead to a good version of the endgame. } 8...
Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. Nd2
{ Our next moves will likely be Nb3-Be2-Bd2.   An alternative move is  10.Bd2  , with the idea of going Rac1-Be2-Be1 and aim for Na4-Nc5, which seems to me to be very comfortable as well. Black pays for having such a clumsy knight and all our pieces are aimed at the queenside. This is another uncomfortable position in which Black has little room for the minor pieces and we have a very simple plan. }
10... O-O 11. Nb3 Be7 12. e4
{ Exploiting this move order to build our ideal setup with Be2-Be3 and f3, which will help us gain some space in the center and Black will have to deal with the b3-knight jumps in a chronically inferior position. Black's f6-knight is hampered by our f3-e4 structure and Black's pieces are in each other's way. }
12... b5 { We will show some examples where Black is too greedy. } 13. Be2 b4
14. Na4 Nxe4 15. Be3 { The bishop on c8 cannot move! } 15... Rb8
{ Black dreams of playing ...Bb7, but after 16. Rac1 would also lose because our rook gets into the seventh rank with Rd7. }
16. Rac1 Ne5 17. Ba7 Ra8
{ 17...Rb7  loses because of  18.Bd4  followed by Na5. } 18. Nb6
{ Black loses material. } *

