{ This move order is aimed at preventing White to go e3-e4 and dxc5, but it is quite weak. }
7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1 { First we develop the rook to the center. } 9...
Nc6
{ Against  9...a6  both  10.d5  and  10.Ne5  would give us a very comfortable initiative. }
10. a3
{ Making room for the bishop on c4 while avoiding the typical ...Nb4-...Nbd5 maneuver. }
10... b6 11. Bf4
{ I spent some time years ago analyzing isolated pawn positions and found that, in general, if we have nothing special with Bg5, it is much better to play Bf4. This way we prevent moves like Nd5 or Nh5, which force the bishop exchange and allow Black to recapture on e7 with the c6-knight with the idea of controlling d5. It is also usual for Black to meet Bg5 with ...h6 and Bf4 with ...Bd6 to trade the dark-squared bishops. }
11... Bb7 12. Ba2
{ In general, our plan will consist of the moves Qd3, Rad1 and likely Bb1, putting pressure on h7 if necessary. This is a very comfortable isolated pawn position for White, while Black will have no easy plans to find. }
12... h6
{ After  12...Nh5  13.Be3  we will continue with Qd3 and Rad1 and, suddenly, ideas like Bb1 and Bg5 are on the agenda. }
13. Qd2
{ We do not want to give Black the opportunity to trade bishops after Bd6. Our possible option of taking on h6 will allow us to avoid Black to free their position by trading pieces.   Our next move will be Rad1 and, after that,it will be feasible to follow the Qd3-Bb1 plan. It is also worth mentioning that the move ...h6 has also weakened Black's castling. }
