Na4
{ Black cannot allow our knight to get to b6, which means accepting the fact that the a3-f8 diagonal will be under our control. }
11... Ba7 12. b3 { Making room for our bishop. } 12... Nbd7 13. Nd4
{ Preventing ...b5.   The king does not want to leave the center, either, so  13.Ba3+  is not necessary. }
13... Ke8 { Black keeps the king active, but far from the paparazzi. } 14. Bb2
{ The bishop on a3 would hit the 'air' and would not help preventing Black's piece development. It is preferable to X-ray the g7-pawn and accumulate pressure on Black's position. }
14... Nd5 15. Nc2
{ The problem with  15.Bf3  was  15...Ne5  . NOw we want to play Bf3 to increase the pressure on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
15... N7f6
{ The move ...b5 was not possible here either. After Nc3, Black would have to deal with indirect threats on g7 and on the h1-a8 diagonal. }
16. Nc3
{ If Bf3 BLack would be able to play the freeing move ...b5, followed by ...Bb7. Even ...Bd7 would be a nice option. Now we are also putting pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal }
16... Kf8 { Defending g7. } 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bf3
{ In case of ...b5, we will continue increasing the pressure with Nb4 followed by Rfc1. Black has to deal with a very annoying pressure. We will activate the king by means of Kf1 and the a2-a4 pawn break could also be a possible option.   Black's coordination is very poor and their king will have to have an eye on the g7-square. Other options would be to play the weakening ...f7-f6 or ...g7-g6 pawn pushes. Basically, we are in a win-win situation. }
18... b5 19. Nb4 Bb7 20. Rfc1 { Black's position experiences a huge pressure. }
