10... Rd8 { A novelty, but it will put BLack in some practical trouble. } 11.
Na4
{ Black cannot allow our knight to get to b6, which means accepting the fact that the a3-f8 diagonal will be under our control. }
11... Ba7 12. b3 { Making room for our bishop. } 12... Nbd7 13. Nd4
{ Preventing ...b5.   The king does not want to leave the center, either, so  13.Ba3+  is not necessary. }
13... Ke8 { Black keeps the king active, but far from the paparazzi. } 14. Bb2
{ The bishop on a3 would hit the 'air' and would not help preventing Black's piece development. It is preferable to X-ray the g7-pawn and accumulate pressure on Black's position. }
14... b5
{ Again, Black's desired move fails. Sometimes I find that simple preparations that require unusual moves from the opponent are very effective. Don't rely so much on the module and, instead, look for more difficult problems for a human to solve! }
15. Bf3 Nd5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Nc3 Bxd4
{ If Black allows us to go Rfd1, consolidating our pressure against the isolani, they will be in serious trouble. The weakening b7-b5 push, together with Black's exposed king, are advantages for us.   Now we can keep on exerting pressure on the d5-pawn. }
18. exd4
{ Our bishop enjoys a ice skating rink and can move back and forth Black's position at will. Ideally, we would like to play Ba3-f3-Ne2-Nf4 and look for access squares to our opponent's camp along the c-file. The pawn on f3 covers the light squares very well and supports a future g4-h4 to generate an imbalance.   Then the knight on f4 puts pressure on d5 and, if it wants, it has access to the d3 square, from which it can have access to all the weak dark squares. It is an extremely annoying position in practice to play for Black. }
18... Nf8
{ Black seeks to regroup quickly to avoid paying a heavy toll for having an exposed king and for being behind in development. }
19. Rae1+ Ne6 20. f4
{ We have to act quickly. Black wanted to play ...f6...Kf7, with good play. }
20... b4 { Only move, preventing Ba3+ in case of ...Kf8. } 21. Na4 Kf8 22. f5
Ng5 23. f6
{ Black's pawn structure is so vulnerable and we can exert pressure for quite a long time against their exposed queenside. The Bc1-Bf4 maneuver is likely to be one of our high-priority plans. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31. Queen's Gambit Accepted"]
[Black "6...a6 with 7...Bxc5 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4
{ The starting position of the famous Queen's Gambit. White offers a pawn and hopes to get it back in a few moves so that we can enjoy a 2vs1 central majority. This is the most common opening inside the 1.d4 d5 complex, and in this chapter we will see what happens if Black decides to accept the gambit. }
2... dxc4
{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted is an alternative that has always been considered as 'solid', but until recent years it was not played as frequently by top-level players.   The accuracy of today's modern engines have turned around many annoying variations in practice and especially has provided answers against the most critical variation  3.e4  . }
3. Nf3
{ We have chosen these variations for various reasons:    1. It fits well in our repertoire: playing 3. e4 would eliminate the possibility of going 1.Nf3 or 2.Nf3   2. I consider this move to be the most sustainable variation in the long run and fits with the 'Lifetime Repertoire' kind of courses. The alternative 3. e4 could be obsolete for sure in a short period of time, and the massive memorization it requires would be useless.   3. This is the variation I have always played myself and has given me a lot of success. With little knowledge you can play at a high level, and it is also very comfortable to play.   Our idea is to continue with e3 and Bxc4. We play first 3.Nf3 instead of 3.e3 because this way we can avoid Black's extra option 3...e5! }
3... Nf6 4. e3
{ Delaying the capture would only get us into trouble.   The alternative  4.Qa4+  is quite weak as Black is flexible enough to meet the capture with  4...Nc6  followed by Nd7, with a nice position for the second player.  For example, via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  dxc4  this would make more sense, as Black has commited to the move ...e6. Even so, we will go for 4.e3 as the alternative does not completely convince me. }
4... e6
{ Black's main continuation, clearing the way of the dark-squared bishop to be able to play ...c5 with the idea of challenging our center. }
5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5
{ When thinking about what to recommend against the QGA, this queenless middlegame came to my mind. I have played it since I was a kid and I have always got nice and almost risk-free positions which, in addition, are hard to play for Black.   Black has quite some options here, which increases the possibility for them to make mistakes, while we have only 2-3 ideas that repeat themselves and are easy to understand.   7.b3  A very practical alternative way of playing these positions. Our light-squared bishop will go to e2 so that the c4-square  (probably after a previous a4 to liberate it in case Black plays ...b5)  and the d4-square will be booked for our knights. Once we reach such a position, we will usually play Bf3 to challenge the important c6-square, which is usually a big issue for Black if they move the b-pawn and trade the c and d-pawns.   I recommend to practice these positions as they can fit your style. THis way, you can analyze the entire variation with minimum effort. Top players use to choose this variation in rapid time controls, which menas that for the rest of us mortals we can play it in classical time controls. :  . }
7... Bxc5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Be2
{ This retreat keeps the maximum flexibility possible and also removes the bishop from an almost useless square. On the one hand, it was vulnerable to the ...b7-b5-push and, on the other hand, there was little he could do on the a2-g8 diagonal.   This move frees the c4-square for one of our knights, the c-file for one of our rooks, and is one move away from getting to f3, from where it will make a higher impact. }
9... Ke7
{ The king looks for shelter here and Black also keeps the flexibility. } 10.
Nc3
{ So, Ding and Giri tried this move in the past The idea is replacing the f3-knight to c4 via d2 or e5 to make an impact on the queenside. The difference between this move and Nfd2 or Ne5 is that the former keeps certain flexibility.   There are some moves that I consider 'unplayable' in practice for Black such as  10...b6  . After  11.Na4  a5!  , both getting an isolated pawn and giving the bishop pair is justified by dynamic means with ...Ba6 ideas.  Against  10...b6  we play  11.Ne5  forcing Black to go  11...b5!  , as after the 'normal'  11...Bb7  12.Na4  Black will indeed suffer.  With this example I want to get out of your head the “engine addiction” that positions like this can encourage; Black is walking on glass floor. }
10... Rd8 { A novelty, but it will put BLack in some practical trouble. } 11.
Na4
{ Black cannot allow our knight to get to b6, which means accepting the fact that the a3-f8 diagonal will be under our control. }
11... Ba7 12. b3 { Making room for our bishop. } 12... Nbd7 13. Nd4
{ Preventing ...b5.   The king does not want to leave the center, either, so  13.Ba3+  is not necessary. }
13... Ke8 { Black keeps the king active, but far from the paparazzi. } 14. Bb2
{ The bishop on a3 would hit the 'air' and would not help preventing Black's piece development. It is preferable to X-ray the g7-pawn and accumulate pressure on Black's position. }
14... b5
{ Again, Black's desired move fails. Sometimes I find that simple preparations that require unusual moves from the opponent are very effective. Don't rely so much on the module and, instead, look for more difficult problems for a human to solve! }
15. Bf3 Rb8
{ The threat on our a4-knight can make Black relax and believe that has time to play ...Bxd4 followed by ...Bb7. }
16. Nc6 bxa4 17. Nxa7 { Threatening a fork on c6. } 17... Bb7 18. Bc6
{ A fantastic move that explains the concept of domination. Black has hardly any moves that do not lose directly, while our bishops cut the position into two.   With  18.Nc6  there would be a simplification on the queenside and that goes against our interests, as we have the bishop pair. }
18... axb3 19. axb3 Ba8 20. Ba4
{ Defending the b3-pawn. Black is practically lost.   20...Kf8  is impossible due to  21.Ba3+  followed by ...Be7, winning an exchange. Apart from that, the g7-pawn would be exposed if Black moves the f6-knight. In any case, our goal is to keep increasing the pressure with Rfc1 to get into c7. }
*

