12. Be5 f6
{ This variation seems to me very complex to play with Black if you do not have a certain level. Ideas like Bxh7 never work, but they are very scary. }
13. Bg3 Rc8 14. O-O { After  14.Bxh7  Nc4!  White is in a lot of trouble. }
14... Nxg3 15. hxg3 Nc4
{ Again,  15...f5  would be useless because it would give us the e5 square, and after  16.Rfc1  looking for ideas like g3-g4 White's play would be good and safe. }
16. Rfc1 Nd6
{ We are following a recent game. The knight on d6 covers some squares of our d3-bishop and Black could soon go for ideas like ...Bxc3 and ...Bb5 to reinforce the control of the light squares. Taking on h7 could lead to a disaster because we have opened a file that Black would use to attack us. }
17. g4
{ Once we have reached this position, we could consider the possibility of turning to the creative mood. With this move we restrain Black's control of some light squares, but we could also end in trouble if Black goes for pawn pushes like ...g5-...h5 and brings the queen to the attack, so we cannot be contemplative forever.   Other interesting alternatives would be  17.e4!?  as the e6-pawn will always be annoying for Black's own pieces and, finally,  17.Qb3  , unpinning and preventing eventual ...Bb5 ideas. }
