9... e6
{ Black accepts that he will not be able to take out the bishop and orients their play on the space he controls on the queenside. }
10. e3 Nh5 11. Bg3
{ I find this retreat veru interesting and could catch Black off-guard. Usually white would force f6 in some way, but we are interested in leaving that square free, as you will see. }
11... Be7
{ 11...Bb4  12.Bh4  and against  @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/4p3/n2p3n/3P4/2N1PNB1/PPQ2PPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 2 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Rc8  we can go for the same idea. Now Black loses the opportunity of winning the bishop pair, and we will have a typical advantage due to the trapped bishop on d7.   11...h6  is a typical waiting move, hoping to take on g3 next and prevent our g4-g5 push.  12.Be5  and here we can see the benefit of not having forced Black's ...f6 move, as in the case of having met ...Nh5 with Be5. Now Black cannot take on g3 anymore nor kicking our e5-bishop back with ...f6. We will continue with Bd3, O-O and an eventual h3 to hide the bishop on h2 if needed.   11...Nxg3  12.hxg3  followed by g4 and then consider either g5, if possible, or Ne5 and f4. Our initiative is very uncomfortable for Black, who will not be able to castle kingside safely. }
12. Ne5
{ Now ...Be7 is not as incisive and we will play Ne5 followed by Be2 and f4. White is quite coordinated, as the pawns are on the opposite color of the light-squared bishop. Besides, our rook on the half-open h file would be always scary in case Black takes our dark-squared bishop. After the above mentioned moves, we could continue with Rc1 and Kf2 to finish our development. }
