10... Bxc3+ { Black should not allow us to ruin their pawn structure. } 11.
bxc3
{ If we take with the queen, we will be vulnerable to eventual ...Ne4 jumps. }
11... Nxe5 12. Bxe5 O-O
{ Black has to be very resourceful or, as we have seen, they would get into big trouble.   12...Qe7  13.Qa4+  and Black has no satisfactory reply here. If ...Qd7 we go Qa3! and it would be impossible for Black to castle kingside.   12...b5  13.Qb4  and Black would only be able to castle in an imaginary world. }
13. Qxb7 Qa5 { The most human move, aiming for pressing our weak c3-pawn. } 14.
Qb2 Rfc8 { Now Black's threat is  15...Ne4  . } 15. f3 Rc6
{ Black aims to take on c3. } 16. Be2 Rac8 17. Qd2
{ After this accurate sequence of moves, we will meet  17...Rxc3  with  18.Kf2  exploiting the pin. The normal reply here would be  18...Qa3  and, after trading everything on c3, Ra1 would lead to a nice endgame for us in which our bishops are very annoying for Black and the f5-bishop slightly out of the action that is taking place on the queenside.  After  17...Rb6  or  17...Nd7  18.c4!  Although we let Black create a passed pawn, in return their light-squared bishop will be trapped on g6 after we play e4 and we also get a nice center. }
