{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Slav I think it is a very good alternative to be able to play every now and then. Some GMs play it all the time, as it avoids a lot of lines with one move and has some venom. Many times it will provoke our opponents to prefer to play other openings and it complements very well with the more aggressive main variations that I recommend.   I have played the Exchange Slav a couple of times, and it has more danger than it seems. The main difficulty of these positions for Black is that all the moves look good and acceptable and it is in that situation that mistakes can happen quickly.   Interestingly, I have a couple of wins against Grandmasters with the Black pieces, so this variation does not come without danger and it is easy for one side to overplay or underestimate the risks of symmetrical positions. }
4... cxd5 5. Nc3
{ There are other options with the move order 2. cxd5 followed by 3. Nc3 and 4. Bf4 next. But the main idea is to play an easier and closed alternative, in which Black has fewer options available.   In addition, from experience, the 4 knight is psychologically difficult for Black to deal with if he wants to play for the win. The reason is that, if White wants to, all the pieces can be exchanged, but this is not our goal. }
5... Nc6 6. Bf4 { Black has several options available at this point. } 6... a6
{ The most usual prophylactic move. Black aims to play ...Bf5 or ...Bg4 and have the reaction ...Na5-...Bd7-...b5 against White's typical maneuver Qb3-Qa4+. }
7. Rc1
{ With this move we do not give an 'easy' solution to Black. After 7. e3 Ag4 can complete the development without any problems and will get rid of the c8-bishop. }
7... Bf5 8. e3 e6 9. Qb3
{ GM Jeoffrey Xiong has won a lot of points with this variation. Again we continue with the usual concept of seeking to punish the queenside once Black has confirmed that his light-squared bishop is not coming back. I love this position because Black can make a lot of mistakes easily. }
9... Bb4
{ Objectively, the best move, developing and, at the same time, defending b7. Now we can pose certain practical problems for Black. }
10. Ne5
{ We want to take on c6 and then go for a2-a3 and capitalize on the c6-weakness while the f5-bishop is a mere spectator of the scene. }
10... Bxc3+ { Black should not allow us to ruin their pawn structure. } 11.
bxc3
{ If we take with the queen, we will be vulnerable to eventual ...Ne4 jumps. }
11... Nxe5 12. Bxe5 O-O
{ Black has to be very resourceful or, as we have seen, they would get into big trouble.   12...Qe7  13.Qa4+  and Black has no satisfactory reply here. If ...Qd7 we go Qa3! and it would be impossible for Black to castle kingside.   12...b5  13.Qb4  and Black would only be able to castle in an imaginary world. }
13. Qxb7 Ne4
{ Black has to go for this novelty and to ascend to the category of God of the active pieces. }
14. f3
{ The move  14.Qb2  would lead to a smooth way towards equality, but it is an alternative I give if you are afraid to enter in this nonsense line I present in the text. I do not know if the theory will ever get here, so I feel as if I have put a flag on an inhospitable planet being the first to arrive. }
14... Qh4+ 15. g3 Qh6
{ Of course, after  9...Bb4  I have to think that our opponent has calculated all this incredible sequence of only moves, which will see next @@StartBracket@@we have had to calculate it too, do not relax yet, please@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Bf4 g5 17. Bc7 g4 18. Bf4 Ng5 19. fxg4 Be4 20. h4 Bxh1 21. Bxg5 Qg6 22. Bf4
{ It is very important to prevent the rooks' access to the b8 square. Now we will continue with Be2 or g5 to defend g4. However, if we lose that pawn, I like c4! a lot @@StartBracket@@taking advantage of the curious pin of the bishop on h1@@EndBracket@@ and we create a very dangerous passed pawn. Our bishop on f4 is God and I find this position to be a complex and interesting one to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33. Slav Defense - Classical Variation"]
[Black "4...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.  After  4.e3  Bf5  Black mages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.   In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.Nbd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently it has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... Bf5
{ This early development of this bishop is again punished with Qb3 ideas. } 5.
cxd5
{ It is important to take first because after  5.Qb3  Qb6  6.cxd5  Qxb3!  Black would be fine. }
5... cxd5
{ 5...Nxd5  6.e3  we will continue with Bd3 and e4 to get a strong center and a very comfortable position. There are other very concrete ways to punish this far-fetched order, but I do not consider it necessary to fill your heads with unnecessary information. }
6. Qb3 Bc8
{ Now we can appreciate the difference: in case of  6...Qb6  7.Nxd5  White would win a healthy pawn. The move  7.Qxb6  would give us a very nice position, too. }
7. Bf4 { Reaching an Exchange Slav position with two very healthy tempi up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33. Slav Defense - Classical Variation"]
[Black "4... Qb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.  After  4.e3  Bf5  Black mages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.   In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.Nbd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently it has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... Qb6
{ This sideline aims to preempt Qb3 to be able to develop the c8-bishop without further problems. The cost in development tempi is very high and the queen on b6 will be somewhat out of play. }
5. e3
{ This is our natural and classical way to develop our pieces. In general terms, we want to play Bd3-e4. Seeing that Qb6 can be punished with natural moves, this one seems to me to be more illustrative. }
5... Bf5
{ 5...Bg4  6.h3  Bxf3  7.Qxf3  e6  these pawn structures are very rock solid for Black. The dark-squared bishop is free to move inside the pawn pyramid c6-d5-e6. The problem, though, is that this kind of play is very passive.   At this point I like a lot going for moves such as Bd3, Qe2, O-O, b3, Bb2 and, later, g4-f4 is very dangerous for Black, as we have both bishops pointing to our opponent's castling and has no effective ways of react on the center to counter our attack on the flank. }
6. Ne5
{ Playing against the f5-bishop works very well. We also see this theme in the Exchange Slav lines. Now we are aiming for g4-h4, trapping the bishop if Black plays  6...e6  . }
6... Nbd7
{ After  6...h6  7.cxd5  cxd5  8.Bd2  the moves Rc1-Na4-Bb5 are coming and Black is simply not it time to turn back all the tempi down. }
7. cxd5 cxd5
{ 7...Nxd5  8.Nxf7  A relatively common trick. We will continue with Qf3-g4 and with our bishop pair and the fact that the black king is on a walk, we should be happy. }
8. Bd2
{ Again we give priority to development. Black will have to play ...e6 at some point and see how after g2-g4 their position collapses. }
