{ I have already mentioned this idea in a variation against the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Usually Bg5 is the  'natural' move, but after ...h6; Bh4 Nh5 Black many times manages to trade our bishop and neutralizes our attack. If h6, ...Bf5 are played, ...Bd6 would be interesting there because Black has the g5-square under their control. That is why I find this way of developing a bit more spicy and interesting. }
11... Nd5
{ I think this is the most accurate move, which is good because Black will usually play ...Nb4 first, aiming for ...Nbd5. However, this plan is less natural here. }
12. Bg3 Bb4 13. Qd3 Nce7
{ Against other moves such as  13...b6  14.Bh4!  Be7  15.Bxd5  exd5  16.Bxe7  we would reach a very annoying simmetrical position for Black as Black's c8-bishop is not the good one in this pawn structure. }
14. Bh4
{ An important move to weaken black's impeccable structure. Anyway, this was our threat. }
14... f6 15. Bg3
{ Now that the e6-pawn is weak, I like the plan Nd2-Nb3@@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@-Nc5. Black's position is much more rigid without having the e6-pawn defended @@StartBracket@@for example, they cannot play ...b6 and ...Bb7 comfortably@@EndBracket@@ . Another approach could be to play Nd2-Nde4 and there we can go to c5 or d6 with the knight or keep on playing waiting moves. Black's pieces are well-placed, but our opponent will have to move them away from those squares at some point. }
