5... e6
{ An alternative, which I have faced in a couple of games. Black goes for a Accepted Queen's Gambit with a tempo down. The question is to evaluate what we gain from having played a2-a4 for free. }
6. e3 c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. exd4
{ We have reached an IQP position, so we have to play energetically. } 8... Be7
9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
{ The most common plan is Qe2-Rd1, but Black will play ...Nc6-...Nb4 and I do not see anything special in going for that move order. Besides, I think that Black has little chances of making significative mistakes there. }
10... Nc6 11. Bf4
{ I have already mentioned this idea in a variation against the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Usually Bg5 is the  'natural' move, but after ...h6; Bh4 Nh5 Black many times manages to trade our bishop and neutralizes our attack. If h6, ...Bf5 are played, ...Bd6 would be interesting there because Black has the g5-square under their control. That is why I find this way of developing a bit more spicy and interesting. }
11... Nb4 12. Ne5
{ As usual in these positions, if Black's knight goes to b4 our knight will jump to e5. }
12... Nfd5
{ If  12...Nbd5  13.Bg3  and now Black cannot play  13...Bd7  due to  14.Bxd5!  followed by Qb3 next. We see the big difference between having the knight on b4 or on f6. It is also worth noting that Black's natural moves are weak.   12...Bd7  Black's usual plan of bringing the bishop to c6 is quite dangerous.  13.Re3  and now we will continue with Rh3, adding one more piece against our opponent's king.   In that case, ideas like Bd3, which we would immediately discard in other variations —as we are giving up the light-squared bishop— are possible. There is no mate attack as such, but after moves like Bf4-Bg5, Qd2, and Bd3 White's attack will become stronger because a rook has also joined the party. }
13. Bg3
{ Aiming for Qb3, hassling Black's weird-placed knights on b4 and d5. In general, a move like ...Nbd5 is more common. }
13... Bd7
{ In case of  13...a5  Black would find out that  14.Qb3!  prevents the c8-bishop's development. We want to continue wkith Qb3 and the move ...a5 allows us to go Ne4-Nc5 in some cases. }
14. a5
{ If our opponent let us, we will gain some space and prevent them from consolidating with ...Bc6 and ...a5. }
14... Rc8 15. Qb3 Bc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Be5
{ We will continue with moves such as Ne4 and we have the option of going Qg3 or look for controlling the c5-square with Rec1 and Bf1. Black has not consolidated their position with ...a7-a5 yet and will have a weakness on c6 for quite some time, so this is enough compensation for the fact that our isolated d4-pawn is blocked. }
