{ The move  5.e4  has become popular recently thanks to the engines, but after  5...b5  it is very complex to get the pawn back and I do not believe that this opening creates chances for Black to make mistakes.  After 5.a4 we prevent Black from consolidating the extra pawn with ...b7-b5 @@StartBracket@@playing ...Be6 is quite counterproductive because it obstructs the natural development of Black's pieces. We would simply continue with e4, Be2, O-O, and the Ng5-threat will force Black to lose more tempi that they can afford@@EndBracket@@ and then we aim to take the c4-pawn and make our central majority count. }
5... a5
{ I like this Black setup against the 'Jobava' Variation. The idea is to prevent the variations in which White goes Ne5and play a very solid position. The main problem here with this set-up is that it gives us the opportunity to take the whole center. }
6. e4 Bg4 7. Bxc4 e6 8. Be3 Bb4 9. Qd3
{ Defending e4 and aiming for Nd2 followed by f3, after which Black's light-squared bishop will be isolated from the rest of the army because of our pawn structure. }
9... Nbd7 10. Nd2 Bh5 11. f3 Bg6 12. Qe2
{ Black's ...Nd5 was not a serious threat, but I want you to be aware of this extra option for Black in other lines. }
12... O-O 13. O-O e5 14. Rad1
{ It is preferable to leave the rook on f1 for future progress in the center. Our idea is Ba2 followed by Nc4. Black has a lot of trouble making sense of the bishop on g6. Moves like Kh1 fit nicely into our setup and plans like Qf2-Qg3 @@StartBracket@@gaining presence on dark squares@@EndBracket@@ could be possible at a later stage. }
