{ The most common move in the past was  8.e4  , but I think it is unnecessary to go into the senseless complications this move involves. After  8...Bxe4  complications is what Black aims for if we go for this variation! }
8... O-O 9. Kf2
{ This recently discovered idea gives White a great advantage.   We avoid the typical bishop sacrifice after  9.e4  Bxe4  and we manage to build a strong center. }
9... c5
{ 9...h6  10.e4  Bh7  11.Be3  and after Be2-Qb3 and Rhd1 we have a formidable development and once again Black's light-squared bishop is relegated to the background. }
10. e4 Bxc3
{ This move has been tried in some games. Black's idea is to trade the sad g6-bishop for some White pawns. }
11. bxc3 Bxe4 12. fxe4 Nxe4+ 13. Kg1
{ Our king is very safe on g1 unlike in the well-known variation with e4 straight away, where it has togo for a walk through c2 and b3. }
13... Nxc3 14. Qe1 cxd4
{ After  15.Ba3  we would get an advantage as Black is practically forced to sacrifice the exchange. Now I like a lot the recommendation of the engine  15.h4!  aiming for h5 to develop the rook via h4 or h3, depending on the situation, thus castling by hand. Black has many pawns for the piece, but their king's position is extremely weak. }
