9... Nfd7 10. Nxd7
{ The great difference between this line and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2pppp/1np2n2/p3Nb2/P2P4/2N5/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq a6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h4!?  h6  10.f3  Nfd7  is that now it is possible for us to play  11.e4!  and after  11...Nxe5  the move  12.exf5!  is interesting as the light squares in Black's camp are weak —especially g6—, and now it is not possible for our opponent to go for ...g6-...Bg7 without ruining their pawn structure. Therefore, Black should meet  11.e4  with  11...Bh7  and, in this position,  12.Nd3  allows us to keep more pieces on the board.   The issue for us though is that our h4-pawn is slightly exposed. Besides, these positions are quite unbalanced to my taste. For example, the engine recommends to go for a 'positional' g2-g4 push: I do not find quite an appealing explanation to this move and we are in danger of making serious mistakes.   For all these reasons, I opt for this more practical variation. }
10... Nxd7 11. e4 Bg6 12. Be2
{ This move order is aimed at minimizing the effect of Black's ...e7-e5 push, since now we are able to meet it with dxe4 and f4-f5.   If  12.Be3  Black would have the extra option of ...Ng4!, against an eventual f4 on our end. }
12... Qb6
{ A rather complex variation that Black has tried to punish our subtle move order. }
13. f4 { We want to prevent the ...e7-e5 push. } 13... e5
{ A very unusual move. Black sacrifices a pawn to make room for the f8 bishop and wants to take advantage of our lack of development and our exposed center to put us in some trouble. }
14. dxe5
{ After  14.fxe5  Rd8  we have no satisfactory ways to maintain our center. }
14... Nc5 { This move leads to a rather forced variation. } 15. Be3 Qxb2 16.
Nb5
{ The knight is taboo. We are threatening, among other things, Nc7+ followed by Bxc5++. }
16... Qb4+ { Otherwise, Black would be helpless after 17.O-O. } 17. Kf1 Rd8
{ If  17...Rc8  18.Nd6+  Bxd6  19.exd6  the f4-f5 push wins a piece. Be careful; against  19...Nd7  we have to play  20.e5  as after  20.f5?  Qxe4!  Black would win the game as the c5-knight is not hanging. }
18. Nc7+ Ke7 19. Nd5+
{ With this elegant maneuver we fix the problem of the weak e4-pawn and we give meaning to our knight. }
19... cxd5 20. exd5
{ Our next moves will likely be d6+ and Bb5. Afterwards, we could play Rc1 and develop the h1-rook via the h-file by playing h4!. Our strong center has practically more value than our opponent's bishop on f8 and there is not much future for their h8 rook either. }
