{ The great difference between this line and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p2pppp/1np2n2/p3Nb2/P2P4/2N5/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq a6 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h4!?  h6  10.f3  Nfd7  is that now it is possible for us to play  11.e4!  and after  11...Nxe5  the move  12.exf5!  is interesting as the light squares in Black's camp are weak —especially g6—, and now it is not possible for our opponent to go for ...g6-...Bg7 without ruining their pawn structure. Therefore, Black should meet  11.e4  with  11...Bh7  and, in this position,  12.Nd3  allows us to keep more pieces on the board.   The issue for us though is that our h4-pawn is slightly exposed. Besides, these positions are quite unbalanced to my taste. For example, the engine recommends to go for a 'positional' g2-g4 push: I do not find quite an appealing explanation to this move and we are in danger of making serious mistakes.   For all these reasons, I opt for this more practical variation. }
10... Bxd7
{ This capture shows that Black prefers to have the bishop closed inside its own pawn structure than to have it on h7 closing by our future e4-pawn. }
11. e4 e6 12. Be2 Bb4 13. Be3 O-O 14. O-O
{ We want to play Qb3-Rac1-Rfc1. It is also common to insert the move Bf2 to keep this bishop safe from eventual ...e5 ideas, followed by ...Bc5. The b6-knight is horrible and the d7-bishop does not do much for Black's army.   Besides, we are threatening Na2 in many situations after Qb3. Let us follow a correspondence game to see what is Black's best defense. }
14... Rc8 15. Rc1 c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Bxc5 Rxc5 18. Qd4 Rc8 19. b3
{ Black is threatening 19......Bxa4!, so we have to play 19.b3 and, afterwards, I like a lot the Qe3-Rfd1 plan and look for relocating the knight with Nb1-Na3 or even via Nd1-Nb2.   The thing is that Black's light-squared bishop only points at our pawn structure and Black's knight is slightly out of play on b6. Our pawn chain f3-e4 is restricting Black's pieces and, besides, we have more space and, in case of reaching a pawn endgame, our king can be easily activated using the f2-e3 road. }
