{ Now we turn the tables and threaten both the bishop on f5 and the pawn on g5 at the same time. Other alternatives such as Nxe5 or Bxe5 fail in the sense that we will be left with a bishop on g2 and a knight on c3 that are both neutralized by Black's c6-pawn, so the strange pawn structure created after the g7-g5 pawn is compensated. }
12... gxf4 13. Nxf5
{ The key move of this variation. The knight on f5 is uncontestable, but Black has a pretty good blockade on the queenside. After ...a7-a5, it will be very difficult for us to break our opponent's wall there and, in addition, the pawn on c6 will hassle the knight on c3 and our f5-knight will hassle the bishop on g7.   Black, however, has a somewhat mediocre queenside structure. @@StartBracket@@f7-g7@@EndBracket@@ nad White can take advantage of this in some situations. Finally, Black will castle queenside and, in many situations, we should be careful with Black's ...fxg3-...h5-...h4 plan , aimed to weaken our beloved king. }
13... O-O-O 14. Qc2
{ Removing the queen from the X-ray of the d8-rook... and aiming to castle queenside ourselves! Black's kingside is quite vulnerable, so due to the fact that we have a same-side castling situation, we will be able to attack it without worrying about our king safety. }
14... fxg3 15. hxg3 Bb4
{ Another option for Black may be to first activate their f8-bishop. Here we would like to castle long anyway; however, as Black has no weakness on h5 and are also putting pressure on our queenside our task will be more difficult than after ...h5.   15...h5  It could be very tempting to prevent us from castling short but here we take the opportunity to go  16.O-O-O  . This is one of the key concepts of this position: if Black allows us to castle long, our king would be safe  (with ...a7-a5 Black would block the queenside, but this blockade could be useful for their attack as well!)  and our h1-rook is already putting total pressure on h5. After Ne4-f4-Bf3 Black's position is extremely unpleasant. }
16. O-O { Intending to go Na2 and b2-b4. } 16... a5 17. Rfd1 h5 18. e3
{ Now we look for Na2 and Rab1-b4 ideas, although Rab1 aiming for Na2 seems reasonable as well. The point of playing e3 first is to have a more active reply to ...Ng4. @@StartBracket@@which is to play Rac1 with knight jumps ideas@@EndBracket@@. }
18... Nf6 19. Na2 Be7
{ Black wants to keep control of the d file. Otherwise we could win the d file and continue with the Nc1-Nd3 maneuver and thus keep all the activity and exchange Black's best piece @@StartBracket@@the f6-knight has no jumps, the f8-bishop is in the way and the rook on h8 is a mere spectator@@EndBracket@@. }
20. b4 axb4 21. a5
{ This nice idea, also recommended by Cheparinov in his book on 1. d4, shakes the foundations of Black's position. The key is that the queen on c7 is defending the bishop on e7 and cannot cover the a5-square.   Now we will continue against practically any move with a5-a6 and Black's position will start to be a sieve as soon as the potential of the bishop on g2 is released. We will attack for free and enjoy a very safe king. }
