{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.  After  4.e3  Bf5  Black mages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.   In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.Nbd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently it has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... dxc4
{ Black accepts the gambit at this point and accepts the fact that they should cede their central pawn majority to White in order to develop their light-squared bishop while our aim is to take on c4.   4...Ne4?!  does not help Black at all to develop the c8-bishop. A good option for us would be, for example,  5.g3 }
5. a4
{ The move  5.e4  has become popular recently thanks to the engines, but after  5...b5  it is very complex to get the pawn back and I do not believe that this opening creates chances for Black to make mistakes.  After 5.a4 we prevent Black from consolidating the extra pawn with ...b7-b5 @@StartBracket@@playing ...Be6 is quite counterproductive because it obstructs the natural development of Black's pieces. We would simply continue with e4, Be2, O-O, and the Ng5-threat will force Black to lose more tempi that they can afford@@EndBracket@@ and then we aim to take the c4-pawn and make our central majority count. }
5... Bf5
{ Black can now develop the bishop without running into our Qb3 usual ideas and also defends against our e4-push. }
6. Ne5
{ The most aggressive variation, that reminds of certain 4....dxc4-Catalan positions. Our aim is to get the c4-pawn back and then start our central expansion, preferably with the f3-e4 plan, and make our opponent light-squared bishop's life difficult. }
6... Nbd7
{ Black should react in the center if it does not want to be crushed by the advance of our central pawns. The idea is to go ...e5. }
7. Nxc4 Qc7 { Black aims to go ...e5 and claim the center again. } 8. g3
{ This move is aimed at enabling our c1-bishop to go to f4 and, at the same time, at being able to develop our f1-bishop.   A funny move that I encountered once is  8.Qd2!?  as after  8...e5  9.dxe5  Nxe5  10.Qf4  Black loses a piece! But Black can play  8...Be6  among other moves and the queen has no future on d2. }
8... e5
{ 8...Rd8?!  another one of Jobava's moves. But after  9.Bf4  Qc8  10.f3  Black is not in time to react with ...e5 and we gain some space for free. }
9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4
{ An important move to avoid giving up the center. Now we pin the knight and we gain one development tempo. }
10... Nfd7 11. Bg2 g5
{ This quite surprising move has been the main line for many years. Black takes advantage of the fact that our bishop has to 'take care' of the knight on c4 and cannot afford to capture on g5, so it will be forced to make a decision. }
12. Ne3
{ Now we turn the tables and threaten both the bishop on f5 and the pawn on g5 at the same time. Other alternatives such as Nxe5 or Bxe5 fail in the sense that we will be left with a bishop on g2 and a knight on c3 that are both neutralized by Black's c6-pawn, so the strange pawn structure created after the g7-g5 pawn is compensated. }
12... gxf4 13. Nxf5
{ The key move of this variation. The knight on f5 is uncontestable, but Black has a pretty good blockade on the queenside. After ...a7-a5, it will be very difficult for us to break our opponent's wall there and, in addition, the pawn on c6 will hassle the knight on c3 and our f5-knight will hassle the bishop on g7.   Black, however, has a somewhat mediocre queenside structure. @@StartBracket@@f7-g7@@EndBracket@@ nad White can take advantage of this in some situations. Finally, Black will castle queenside and, in many situations, we should be careful with Black's ...fxg3-...h5-...h4 plan , aimed to weaken our beloved king. }
13... O-O-O 14. Qc2
{ Removing the queen from the X-ray of the d8-rook... and aiming to castle queenside ourselves! Black's kingside is quite vulnerable, so due to the fact that we have a same-side castling situation, we will be able to attack it without worrying about our king safety. }
14... Nc5
{ A very precise move order aiming at preventing our plan of castling queenside. }
15. O-O
{ 15.gxf4  would be terrible due to  15...Nc4  and we would not be able to prevent the double threat of ...Rd2 and ...Qxf4 at the same time. }
15... fxg3 16. hxg3 a5
{ Black has issues with the f8-bishop's development due to the fact that they have played Nc5. Therefore, winning the fight for the d-file is a reasonable first goal at this point. }
17. Rfd1 h5
{ It seems more appropriate for Black to let White exchange on d8 and then move the queen to f6.   17...Rxd1+  18.Rxd1  h5  19.Ne4  once again we will look to play against the h5 pawn. I really like the fact that after  19...Nxe4  20.Qxe4  we can continue with e3-Bf1-Be2 and Black will pay the price for trying to create counterplay. It is important to emphasize that the black queen does not come into play. }
18. e3
{ This useful waiting move exploits the fact that Black has still a knight on c5 and, therefore, the f8-bishop cannot be developed. }
18... Kb8 19. Ne4 { An already very familiar move in this kind of positions. }
19... Nxe4 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Bxe4
{ We want to free the g2-square for our king and put pressure on the h5-pawn with Rh1. }
21... Qf6 22. Kg2 Ng6 23. Qc3
{ With this move we are preventing ...h5-h4 which would be a little more annoying without trading queens.   For example,  23.Rh1  h4  24.g4  and continue there with Kh3 could be interesting if you love imbalances. However, with the queens on the board and taking into account that we cannot take the h-pawn, I am less attracted to thhis idea.   Now f2-f4 would not be the same as we have a rook on a1 and, besides, Black has exchanged a pair of pieces and has more space than before. }
23... Qxc3 24. bxc3 h4 25. g4
{ Of course, we do not want to fix Black's pawn structure. } 25... h3+
{ Black cannot allow us to create blockades on the light squares, as their pieces cannot access to this color complex. }
26. Kh2
{ We reach an endgame in which I see it quite likely that we will eventually take the h3 pawn and that Black will have to suffer enormously @@StartBracket@@plus taking into account that our opponent has already suffered a lot to get to this position without losing the thread of the game@@EndBracket@@ to hold this endgame with 3vs1 pawns on the kingside.   For example, after  26...Ne5  27.g5!  we will continue with f2-f4 and ...Ng4+ is always strongly met with Kg3, after which we are fine. Besides, we fix the f7-pawn on a light square in order to attack it later. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34. Slav Defense - Chebanenko Variation"]
[Black "Why we don't go for the fianchetto"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.  After  4.e3  Bf5  Black mages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.   In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.Nbd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently it has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... a6
{ The Chebanenko Variation usually leads to unique positions that require some caution. Black makes a usual waiting move to develop the c8-bishop without so many problems.   The main issue of the text move is that it weakens the b6-square considerably. Incidentally, Black also has the option of taking on c4 and further reinforcing that capture with ...b7-b5. Kamsky and Malakhov are among its greatest exponents. }
5. g3
{ This is the variation that is often recommended, but from my own experience I find Black's play so telegraphed. After the following variation you will see my approach. }
5... dxc4 6. a4
{ We want to prevent Black from playing ...b7-b5.   After  6.Bg2  b5  7.Ne5  e6!  Black is in time to defend their expansion, as  8.Nxc6  Qb6!  followed by ...Bb7! is a nice tactical shot with which I myself won a game. }
6... e6
{ In typical Slav fashion, Black changes the strategy and looks for c6-c5 once he has managed to force us play a2-a4 and make our queenside less flexible. }
7. Bg2 c5 8. dxc5
{ Otherwise, it will cost us an awful lot to get the pawn back after  8...cxd4  as we cannot go for jumps like Ne5 to take it back. }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxc5 10. Ne5
{ If  10.Ne3  Black dries the position completely after ...Bd7!. } 10... Nd5
{ Otherwise Black could not develop the queenside. I met this variation when I was only 14 years old and since then I had the feeling that Black does not have much room for error. }
11. Ne3
{ Against  11.Nxc4  Black can play  11...Nc6  and complete the development without any issues. Having the pawn on a4 would mean that we lose any possibility of going a3-b4, so Black has the b4-square for themselves and that would be a great improvement for the second player.  If  11.Bd2  Black continues with  11...Nc6  and Black dominates the b-file and has some initiative that compensates their worse pawn structure. }
11... Nxe3 12. Bxe3 Bxe3 13. fxe3 c3
{ This endgame seems to be very drawish and easy to play with Black after ...Nd7 and ...Ra7 —Black has few other legal moves—. This is the reason why I did not want to recommend 5. g3. }
*

