5. c5
{ Friendly reminder that here we can play  5.cxd5  transposing to what we saw in the Exchange Slav section. For example, I would recommend you to learn the Exchange Slav first 'just in case' as in the Chebanenko we cannot play 'random' moves. I have suffered two or three defeats because of this, which I think it justifies what I just wrote. I would even see no harm if you chose to say something along the lines of 'then against the Chebanenko I take on d5 to simplify my opening repertoire'.   After 5.c5 White gains some space on the queenside and exploits Black's lack of development. This reminds me of what I analyze after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  a6!?  4.Nc3  d5  5.c5!?  in another section of the course.   The big difference now is that Black holds out hope of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain I recently beat a Grandmaster with this variation and then saw that I already won another game 4-5 years ago. Our plan is to move the bishop from c1 to f4 and look for a fairly natural development with h3-e3-Bd3.   Black on the other hand seeks to hinder this development and also go for the e5-break, which can annoy us a lot since the c5-pawn is somewhat exposed in case he loses its mate on d4. }
5... Bf5 6. Qb3 { In the Slav we usually meet ...Bf5 automatically with Qb3. }
6... Ra7 7. Nh4 Bc8
{ This peculiar idea requires a little attention on our end.   7...Bg6  8.Nxg6  hxg6  9.e3  and we simply aim for Bd2-Be2, O-O-O, and then expand on the kingside with h4-g4. Black is close to losing, as they will have to open the position to create some counterplay and we can take advantage of that by using our bishop pair.  The retreat  7...Be6  is somewhat weak because of h3-Bf4 or Qc2-e3-Bd3, which prevent Black's light-squared bishop to see the light via f5 or g4. }
8. Bf4 Nbd7 9. Nf3
{ If we leave the knight on h4, we will struggle against ...e5! } 9... Nh5 10.
Bd2
{ The e2-e4 push is on our radar again, so Black is not happy enough although they have kicked our bishop away from the h2-b8 diagonal. }
10... e5 { What else? } 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5
{ After  12...Bxc5  13.e4!  works, and if  12...Qe7  we will castle and aim for Be3-Bd4, consolidating our pieces in good positions. }
