8... dxe4 9. Nxe4
{ Aiming to comfortably develop our light-squared bishop to c4. } 9... Ndf6
{ This peculiar move is quite accurate. Black aims to take with the e-pawn and relocate the knight via g7. The doubled f6-pawn controls our f3-knight and makes it difficult for our dark-squared bishop to get into play. }
10. Nc3
{ After the most common  10.Nxf6+  exf6!  I think our play will have to be very precise. We start from the logical deduction that if Black executes this peculiar knightly maneuver he knows what he is doing, one cannot go for this position by accident.   Cheparinov recommends some playable lines here, but one mistake on our end could be decisive due to the hole on d5 and our worse pawn structure, especially our exposed d4-pawn. I am not convinced by the practical problems we have to face after  11.Bc4  Qe7+!  .  After  10.Nc3  my aim is to look for more dynamic positions and to exploit the awkward position of Black's knight on h5. }
10... Be6
{ 10...Ng7  this maneuver to activate the knight also leaves the f4-square unprotected.  In case of 11.Na4 Nd5  , after  12.h3  Black will struggle to find a square for the c8-bishop. If they allow us to go Nb6 it will be annoying for Black, especially if they have to go Ra7 to defend from the threat of losing an exchange after Bf4.   10...Bg7  11.Bc4  and now Black cannot comfortably develop the c8-bishop and after h3 or Qb3 our position would be completely winning. }
11. Be2 { We continue our development. } 11... Nd5 12. O-O Nhf4
{ Black seeks to give meaning to their knights. } 13. Re1
{ With the idea of going Bf1 and the simple h2-h3. Even if Black plays ...Bg4-...Bxf3, his knights are not stable and taking on c3 in order to relocate the f4-knight to d5 would run into the unpleasant bxc3! This would solve all our problems; we have the bishop pair and there is a weakness on b7 to put pressure on. }
13... Nxe2+ 14. Rxe2 Bg7
{ After  14...Bg4  15.Qb3!  Black has the typical problem of how to defend d5 and b7. Taking on d5 would give us a 3vs2 pawn majority on the queenside. }
15. h3
{ Now Black runs into our nasty Qc1! idea in order to play Bh6 and leave the dark squares very weak. In case Black is looking for h6, we have a thematic idea in Rxe6! which is very annoying in practice and takes advantage of the weak pawn on g6.   Simply doubling rooks on the e file would also give us a good advantage after something like Na4 @@StartBracket@@although we should take care of ...Nb4! jumps@@EndBracket@@, Qc2 and Rae1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34. Slav Defense - Chebanenko Variation"]
[Black "5...Nbd7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3
{ Going for a more ambitious line.   I have played  4.e3  in most of my games, but I consider that it requires a lot of technique and until I reached the Grandmaster level I used to play 4.Nc3, as it generates more complex and ambitious positions.  After  4.e3  Bf5  Black mages to develop the light-squared bishop without any issues and solidifies the position.   In case of  4.e3  e6  , that was considered to be bad because White could play the flexible  5.Nbd2  instead of Nc3 @@StartBracket@@its main virtue lies in the fact that Black's reaction with ...dxc4, ...b5, ...b4 is not possible when the knight is on d2 and also the knight is also supporting the e4-square to play Bd3 and e4@@EndBracket@@, but recently it has become fashionable again, especially thanks to Chessable courses such as Shankland's. Besides, this variation is also very solid. }
4... a6
{ The Chebanenko Variation usually leads to unique positions that require some caution. Black makes a usual waiting move to develop the c8-bishop without so many problems.   The main issue of the text move is that it weakens the b6-square considerably. Incidentally, Black also has the option of taking on c4 and further reinforcing that capture with ...b7-b5. Kamsky and Malakhov are among its greatest exponents. }
5. c5
{ Friendly reminder that here we can play  5.cxd5  transposing to what we saw in the Exchange Slav section. For example, I would recommend you to learn the Exchange Slav first 'just in case' as in the Chebanenko we cannot play 'random' moves. I have suffered two or three defeats because of this, which I think it justifies what I just wrote. I would even see no harm if you chose to say something along the lines of 'then against the Chebanenko I take on d5 to simplify my opening repertoire'.   After 5.c5 White gains some space on the queenside and exploits Black's lack of development. This reminds me of what I analyze after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  a6!?  4.Nc3  d5  5.c5!?  in another section of the course.   The big difference now is that Black holds out hope of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain I recently beat a Grandmaster with this variation and then saw that I already won another game 4-5 years ago. Our plan is to move the bishop from c1 to f4 and look for a fairly natural development with h3-e3-Bd3.   Black on the other hand seeks to hinder this development and also go for the e5-break, which can annoy us a lot since the c5-pawn is somewhat exposed in case he loses its mate on d4. }
5... Nbd7
{ The main line. It is somewhat strange to block the development of the c8-bishop, but in return it will be seen that it is useful against Bf4. Also, Black is threatening ...e7-e5.   In general, our response to ...e7-e5 is to take on e5 and then defend the c5-pawn with Na4, keeping the squares on d4 and b6 under our control. }
6. Bf4 Nh5 7. Bd2
{ Now we are threatening e2-e4, gaining space and highlighting Black's lack of reaction on the queenside, so they should react adequately. }
7... e5 { Now this maneuver does not work. } 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5
{ Since the knight is on h5 we are threatening e2-e4, breaking the opponent's center and exposing the lousy knight on h5. }
9... Qc7
{ Now after  10.e4  Qxe5  Black would have problems because of the pin.   9...Qe7  is more of the same. }
10. Na4 Qxe5 11. e3
{ We will continue with Bc3-Qb3 and O-O-O. Thanks to both Black's weak pawn structure and our strong knight on a4 and pawn on c5 Black will not be able to attack us. However, we can continue with pawn pushes such as h4. }
*

