8... Qc7 { Black aims to immediately go for the e5 pawn break. } 9. Bg5
{ I find this move much more strategic and interesting. } 9... e5
{ The move  9...b6  would not have independent value, as we can go for  10.cxb6  and Na4-Rac1 in the hypothetical case of ...Qxb6. }
10. e3 Be7 11. Bh4
{ After  11.Be2  Ng8!?  White obtained 3 wins in correspondence chess. Black loses all counterplay as the dark squares in their camp are chronically weak.   However, I want to bring a new extra idea for you to understand other variations in chess and compare them with this one. This novelty is aimed at playing Bg3 to come back to familiar territory in the 5...g6 lines. }
11... e4 12. Nd2
{ White has a dream pawn structure. It is like one of the variations against the Advance French, but WITH THE BISHOP OUT OF THE PAWN CHAIN. }
12... O-O
{ Against  12...b6  13.cxb6  Nxb6  14.Bg3  and we can continue with Be2 and O-O likely followed by Na4 and take advantage of our incredible dark-squared bishop and Black's exposed pawn structure. }
13. Be2 Qd8 14. Bg3
{ After  14.O-O  Ne8  Black's attack with f5-g5-f4 is somewhat dangerous. }
14... Ne8 15. Na4
{ Our intention is to continue with Nb3 and O-O-O, as is typically played in the French. Black usually has the bishop on a5 @@StartBracket@@a4@@EndBracket@@ and dreams to bring it to c7 @@StartBracket@@c2@@EndBracket@@ or to g3 @@StartBracket@@g6@@EndBracket@@.   We will hide the king with a3-Kb1 and we can play Nb6! in many situations. When Black takes, after cxb6 we can continue with Nb3-c5. Black will not know very well how to attack on the kingside and having the bishop on the outside is a guarantee of a much healthier position. }
