{ Once g3 is played, Black's ...e5 is even more relevant. We cannot be satisfied with capturing on e5 and go for Na4; now the pawn on g3 takes away our flexibility and will leave a nice hole on f3 if we play the thematic Bc3-e3 after Na4. }
10. dxe5 { Taking first with the knight disables our idea of pushing e5-e6. }
10... Ng4 11. e6
{ Weakening Black's pawn structure and exploiting our piece coordination by playing g3-fxe6-Bh3. }
11... fxe6 { Black improves their pawn structure, but has dynamic issues. } 12.
Bh3
{ Taking advantage of the fact that the e6-pawn is vulnerable.   After  12...Ngf6  13.Ng5  , followed by e4 and  eventually b4 against ...Nxc5 practically ensure our victory. }
12... Ndf6 13. Bxg4 Nxg4 14. Na4
{ Black's dark squares are incredibly weak.   After  14...Bg7  15.Nb6  Rb8  16.h3  Ne5  17.Nxe5  Bxe5  18.Bh6!  we will continue with O-O-O and e4. The fact that Black cannot play ...e6-e5 to unblock their pitiful queenside will be decisive. }
