8... g6 9. g3
{ Now e2-e4 would be unsuccessful after taking everything on e4 as Black would continue with ...Nf6-...Be6-...Bd5. With g3 we seek to maintain an active development and keep the option to play e2-e4 in the future and have a powerful bishop on the long diagonal.   From now on the moves become very precise and that is why I take this opportunity to remember that 5. cxd5 is a recommended alternative —or even a main option— to avoid dealing with the Chebanenko. }
9... e5
{ Once g3 is played, Black's ...e5 is even more relevant. We cannot be satisfied with capturing on e5 and go for Na4; now the pawn on g3 takes away our flexibility and will leave a nice hole on f3 if we play the thematic Bc3-e3 after Na4. }
10. dxe5 { Taking first with the knight disables our idea of pushing e5-e6. }
10... Ng4 11. e6
{ Weakening Black's pawn structure and exploiting our piece coordination by playing g3-fxe6-Bh3. }
11... Nxc5
{ This variation is very popular in correspondence and was popular a decade ago with level +2600. Black has several problems having a weak king, but he enjoys a very strong center if he gets out alive. }
12. exf7+ Kxf7 13. Bg2
{ Continuing our development and waiting for what Black may throw at us. }
13... Bf5
{ Against  13...Bd6  14.e4!  works very well. We do not go 13.e4 because after ...Bg7! Black could take advantage of the fact that we are still two moves away from castling.   13...Bg7  loses to  14.Nxd5!  as Maxime Vachier-Lagrave showed in a game. }
14. Qc1 Bd6
{ Now that Black has prevented e2-e4, they develop the dark-squared bishop.   After  14...d4  15.Na4!  helps us to trade a couple of pieces and then we will take advantage of the fact that Black's pawn center is not so strong anymore. }
15. O-O
{ We want to go e2-e4 and, after the check on g5, take back on e4 with an open and winning position. }
15... Re8 16. Ng5+ Kg7
{ Against  16...Kg8  both  17.Nxd5!  and  17.e4!  fantastically take advantage of the weak a2-g8 diagonal. }
17. b4 { The e4-square is key. } 17... Ne6
{ Against  17...Nd7  our plan would be e2-e4 and, after recapturing with the c-knight, go for Qc4! to gain a decisive tempo thanks to the Qf7+ threat to be able to bring the a-rook to d1.   Against  17...Ne4  18.Ncxe4  dxe4  , the move  19.Qc4!  works, with the same idea in mind. }
18. e4
{ Technically better is  18.h3  as Cheparinov correctly states, but it is true that the game becomes quite complex for both sides and I rather prefer you to use the same idea time and time again for your memory to correctly work when learning and facing long variations. }
18... dxe4 19. Ncxe4 Be5 20. Nxe6+ Bxe6 21. Bc3
{ We will bring the rook to d1 and, after h3 Black has to do a million of accurate moves to get to an incredibly unpleasant endgame. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Kund,W @@StartBracket@@2253@@EndBracket@@-Godat,T @@StartBracket@@2305@@EndBracket@@ LSS email 2009 }
