[White "34. Slav Defense - Chebanenko Variation"]
[Black "Schlechter Slav #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6
{ The Slav is a very well considered defense by the theory of chess. It has a reputation for being very solid and easy to master in a short period of time.   It has obvious similarities with the Caro-Kann @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  and  2.--  ...d5  @@EndBracket@@, whose definition I like to give is the following: 'I want to develop the light--squared bishop, let me do it, please!'   Again, in the Slav most of the conflicts in the position are generated by this simple sequence of Black's ideas:   1. Stabilizing the center.   2. Developing the c8-bishop   3. Closing the pawn structure with e7-e6 while you defend against threats on the light-squared bishop.   4. Enjoying a London... with colors reversed!    Surprise, surprise! The Slav Defense has a lot of similarities with the London System that can be extrapolated, especially if we consider the 4.e3 Bf5 variation —which I played myself a lot, but it is not covered in this course—. It is a very cool exercise to see the similarities and differences in other openings or with colors reversed. Also, it is very common for White variations that simply consist of playing a 'black' position with extra time to become fashionable.  Usually, White can play an annoying Qb3 move when Black's light-squared bishop goes for a walk, and the double pressure on d5 and b7 has the aim to hassle Black. This is why Black often assumes that we will 'win' his bishop in exchange for a knight or that he will have to give up space in the center @@StartBracket@@ I am talking about the variation that I will cover here with 4...dxc4@@EndBracket@@ to develop it without any issues. }
3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 g6
{ The Schlechter Slav; but I believe the fianchetto works very badly when the center is closed. Now we will put our dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and simply go e3-h3-Bd3 and will look for a way to penetrate Black's position on the queenside. The g7-bishop will have little to no role in the action. }
5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Bf4
{ I claimed that this position was just bad. We get a far better version of the slav exchange, as black will have issues with both bishops and our play is far easier. Which I felt it was enough @@StartBracket@@I checked now and the stats prove my point: 67% winrate over 1500 classical games@@EndBracket@@, but a course on chessable appeared with black so let's dig a bit deeper. }
6... Nc6
{ Black needs to do something quickly, otherwise we get e3-h3-Bd3 and the suffering would start. }
7. e3 Nh5 { Black wants to annoy our beloved bishop. } 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4
{ This 'tension' is hard to break. Black doesn't want to play g6-g5 as we always have Nd2! as an answer. }
9... Bg7 10. Bb5
{ Careful here, if we put the bishop on e2 g5! was possible. 10. Be2 g5 11. Nd2 and here 11. ... e5 and 11. ... Nf4! are both good. Now we just want to develop and create some pressure on the queenside. If we take on c6 black will suffer to defend it and we also gain a really good square on c5 for our knight. }
10... O-O
{ In case of 10. ... g5 11. Ne5! would be a better version of our theme with Nd2. }
11. O-O Qd6
{ Black has the chance to "wait". This move is required to properly develop the c8 bishop. This was the last chance to play g5. Now white has too much development to justify the ideas. }
12. h3 Bd7 { 12. ... g5 just 13. Ne1 and black cannot make it work. } 13. Rc1
{ And now it becomes a waiting game. Black cannot move anything else than the rooks and the pawns on the queenside. In case of e7-e6 ever happening we have the strong g4-Ne5-f4 plan as a reaction. For instance 13. ... e6 14. g4! Nf6 15. Bd3! first we stop the jump on e4 and we will proceed with Bg3-Ne5-f4 with great attacking prospects. In the meantime we have plenty useful moves like Bd3 back, a3, Re1. Later on we could even go for Nd2-Nb3 if black also has this course :@@EndBracket@@. }
