{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 g6
{ The Schlechter Slav; but I believe the fianchetto works very badly when the center is closed. Now we will put our dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain and simply go e3-h3-Bd3 and will look for a way to penetrate Black's position on the queenside. The g7-bishop will have little to no role in the action. }
5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Bf4
{ I claimed that this position was just bad. We get a far better version of the slav exchange, as black will have issues with both bishops and our play is far easier. Which I felt it was enough @@StartBracket@@I checked now and the stats prove my point: 67% winrate over 1500 classical games@@EndBracket@@, but a course on chessable appeared with black so let's dig a bit deeper. }
6... Nc6
{ Black needs to do something quickly, otherwise we get e3-h3-Bd3 and the suffering would start. }
7. e3 Nh5 { Black wants to annoy our beloved bishop. } 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4
{ This 'tension' is hard to break. Black doesn't want to play g6-g5 as we always have Nd2! as an answer. }
9... Bg7 10. Bb5
{ Careful here, if we put the bishop on e2 g5! was possible. 10. Be2 g5 11. Nd2 and here 11. ... e5 and 11. ... Nf4! are both good. Now we just want to develop and create some pressure on the queenside. If we take on c6 black will suffer to defend it and we also gain a really good square on c5 for our knight. }
10... O-O
{ In case of 10. ... g5 11. Ne5! would be a better version of our theme with Nd2. }
11. O-O g5 12. Bxc6
{ In case of Ne1 or Nd2 black wants to play e5! and claim with dynamics that the position is holdable. This way we just make black suffer for a while. }
12... bxc6 13. Ne5 Bxe5 { Only move. } 14. Qxh5 Bg7 15. Bg3
{ Likely our queen goes back to d1 and we have easy play with Rac1-Na4-Nc5 and invading the queenside with Qa4 and some plans like Rc3-Rb3. Black has a bishop pair but barely any activity and we have a very solid and easy position to play on. }
