[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35. Slav Defense - The Semi-Slav"]
[Black "5...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... b6 6. cxd5
{ In Queen's Pawn structures, as usual, we meet Black's ...b6-push with cxd5. Now the option of playing exd5 is less attractive for Black since the c6 pawn will always be somewhat weak and our option of playing e2-e4 in the future will no longer imply having an isolated pawn on d4 without any counterplay in return for it. }
6... cxd5
{ After  6...exd5  7.g3  this pawn structure is very reminiscent of the Queen's Indian one. Depending on Black's piece arrangement we can look for Bg5-e4  (after castling)  , Nh4-Nf5, or even Ne5 followed by f4. }
7. Bf4
{ Again we get a very comfortable version of the Exchange Slav where the bishop on c8 does not come out. }
7... Bd6
{ Black will receive a severe punishment for playing this natural move.   7...Be7  8.Qc2  we facilitate the natural development with e2-e3 and prevent ...Ba6.  8...O-O  9.e3  after Bd3-a3 we will look for bringing pieces to the c-file  (for example, by going for the Rac1-Qb3-Rc2-Rfc1 plan.)  Reaching this kind of position for free is very unpleasant for Black in practice and definitely is not to the liking of Semi-Slav players. }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Nb5 Qb4+ 10. Nd2 Na6 11. a3 Qe7 12. g4
{ We again find a moment to go for this interesting maneuver. We will likely continue with moves such as g5-h4-Nf3, gaining a lot of space on dark squares. Future maneuvers that work very well in this structure are Bd3-Rg1 and look for Ne5-f4 next. The bishop on c8 does not come into play. }
*

