{ This move is quite venomous.   Now  6.g4  is not so good as Black has a lot more flexibility. }
6. e4
{ 6.g3  A world in which each and every position could be 'catalanized' would be wonderful.  6...b6  7.Bg2  going into symmetrical Exchange Slav structures with g3 already inserted is not a good thing.   Our bishop wants to go to g2, and hitting Black's pawn wall on d5-c6 is not pleasant for it. In addition, g3 only makes the c1-bishop's development really difficult.  7...Ba6  8.b3  b5!  if it were not for this precise maneuver, which forces us to give up a lot of space, g3 would be interesting enough to be our main idea.   We could still go for  9.cxb5  cxb5  10.Qe3  with the idea of going for Bb2-Rfc1. I really think that Black is fine, but if you find this small price reasonable  (which is new for Black)  the g3 idea is very interesting and combines very well with what has already been explained in the Catalan part of this Lifetime Repertoire. }
6... dxc4 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qd3
{ If we were allowed to play e5 and Ne4, we would be very happy. Black has to go ...b4. }
8... b4 9. Na4 Ba6
{ We want to play Qc2 to control the c5-square and Bd3 next, developing and threatening e4-e5. Again, Black has to react quickly.   Against  9...Bb7  we continue with  10.Be3  and with typical plans like Nd2 next to cover e4. }
10. Qc2 Bxf1 11. Kxf1
{ We lose the right to castle, but Black has compromised their pawn structure. }
11... Qa5
{ Otherwise we go g3-Kg2 and Black has a hard time not being able to play c5 on good terms. 11...Qa5 threatens ...Nxe4 so we should waste an important tempo on b3. }
12. e5 Nd5 13. Bg5
{ This move is aimed at controlling the c5-square. g3-Kg2 will come next. If Black were to waste a tempo checking our king, we can also go for the interesting plan h4-Rh3-Rg3 and we would magically castle by hand! :@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35. Slav Defense - The Semi-Slav"]
[Black "5...Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... Be7
{ This move is quite venomous.   Now  6.g4  is not so good as Black has a lot more flexibility. }
6. e4
{ 6.g3  A world in which each and every position could be 'catalanized' would be wonderful.  6...b6  7.Bg2  going into symmetrical Exchange Slav structures with g3 already inserted is not a good thing.   Our bishop wants to go to g2, and hitting Black's pawn wall on d5-c6 is not pleasant for it. In addition, g3 only makes the c1-bishop's development really difficult.  7...Ba6  8.b3  b5!  if it were not for this precise maneuver, which forces us to give up a lot of space, g3 would be interesting enough to be our main idea.   We could still go for  9.cxb5  cxb5  10.Qe3  with the idea of going for Bb2-Rfc1. I really think that Black is fine, but if you find this small price reasonable  (which is new for Black)  the g3 idea is very interesting and combines very well with what has already been explained in the Catalan part of this Lifetime Repertoire. }
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 8. Qxe4 Nd7
{ The most common continuation. Black delays castling to take advantage of the ...Bb4+ move  at their convenience.   Against  8...O-O  we could play  9.Bd2  and O-O-O.   Against  8...c5  I like  9.Be3  and O-O-O. Do you see the pattern?   8...Bb4+  9.Bd2  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2  and we will continue with O-O-O and Bd3 and meet an eventual...Nf6 with Qh4. This natural continuation for Black is quite lame. We will have a simple and uncompromising attack. We see how Black has a lot of work to do to fix their sad queenside. }
9. Bd3 c5
{ If  9...Nf6  we go  10.Qe2  building the perfect setup to castle next, bring our dark-squared bishop to f4 and the rooks on the d and e files. White has a very classical advantage. }
10. O-O cxd4
{ If  10...Nf6  , we play  11.Qe2  cxd4  12.Rd1  and we will get the pawn back after Bc2. Our rook will also be activated and soon you will have to look for a mate combination. }
11. Qxd4 Nc5
{ If Black lets us keep the queens on the board, we will play Bc2 and, if we manage all the space we have, we will be better. }
12. Qxd8+ Bxd8 13. Bc2
{ After Be3-Rad1 and Ne5 or Nd4 Black's position is very uncomfortable and you will appreciate how difficult it is for our opponent to develop their pieces. In general, this 3 vs 2 queenside majority gives us very good chances in the long run. The fact that our pieces are active give us a nice position. }
