10... Qxd5
{ 10...cxd5  11.Bf4  is a very good version of the Exchange Slav. Apart from the fact that the b7-bishop is poorly placed, Black should pay close attention to our simple plan h4-h5. White has won the two GM-level games that have been played with this position. }
11. Bg2
{ Black will have to play ...c5, but the way we want. In a complex position, it is better to be guided by which of the versions of their natural plan are better from our point of view. }
11... c5
{ The only justifiable move. Be3 and obstructing the entire black position would end in drama. }
12. O-O
{ This novelty seems more sensible than Rg1, as our king would be misplaced in that case.  Remember that Ne1!, is a strong threat. After exchanging the light-squared bishops and take on c5, Black will see after recapturing how Qc3!, forces to play the sad retreat ...Bf8. }
12... Nc6
{ Against  12...c4  we could continue with  13.Qe3  and then go b3, creating a lot of tension in Black's position. }
13. e4 Qd6 { Not an evident retreat, but the correct one. } 14. d5 exd5 15.
exd5 Nb4 { The only reasonable jump. } 16. Qe4+ Be7
{ Covering the check with the queen would be suicidal, as after Qh4! our attack will start to flow. }
17. Nh4 { Forcing matters a bit. } 17... Bxd5
{ Bf4 is coming and Black has no time to lose if they want to survive. } 18.
Nf5 Qd7 19. Qe5 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 f6
{ Against  20...Nd3  we would play  21.Nxg7+  Kd8  and here  22.Qe4!  would make Black's life difficult. }
21. gxf6 gxf6 22. Qe4
{ Again we should keep in mind ideas with a2-a4 after playing Re1. Black should be quite afraid of our knight on f5. }
