1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 a6 8. g4
{ This surprising move, which has recently become fashionable, will be our main idea against this variation.   The idea is to sacrifice the g pawn in the purest Shirov style, getting permanent pressure against the g7 pawn and Black's upcoming castled king. It is a rather unlikely scenario that our opponent will castle long with such a queenside pawn structure. }
8... Bb7
{ Black has several interesting move orders to pose us problems. Now ...c5 will be very strong and the pawn on g4 may be exposed.   8...h6  9.Ne5  the Queen will go to g3 and the bishop will be developed via g2. Black will not have an easy way to react with ...c6-c5 and at the same time I see it unlikely that they can castle short against our attack. Black is already in enormous practical trouble. }
9. g5 Nd5 10. Nxd5
{ This variation is a little spicier, but I consider it very important to prevent Black from having easy play.   Against  10.Bg2  Black will play the move they want, ...c5, leading to an equal position in more than one way. }
10... Qxd5
{ 10...cxd5  11.Bf4  is a very good version of the Exchange Slav. Apart from the fact that the b7-bishop is poorly placed, Black should pay close attention to our simple plan h4-h5. White has won the two GM-level games that have been played with this position. }
11. Bg2
{ Black will have to play ...c5, but the way we want. In a complex position, it is better to be guided by which of the versions of their natural plan are better from our point of view. }
11... c5
{ The only justifiable move. Be3 and obstructing the entire black position would end in drama. }
12. O-O
{ This novelty seems more sensible than Rg1, as our king would be misplaced in that case.  Remember that Ne1!, is a strong threat. After exchanging the light-squared bishops and take on c5, Black will see after recapturing how Qc3!, forces to play the sad retreat ...Bf8. }
12... Nc6
{ Against  12...c4  we could continue with  13.Qe3  and then go b3, creating a lot of tension in Black's position. }
13. e4 Qd6 { Not an evident retreat, but the correct one. } 14. d5 exd5 15.
exd5 Nb4 { The only reasonable jump. } 16. Qe4+ Be7
{ Covering the check with the queen would be suicidal, as after Qh4! our attack will start to flow. }
17. Nh4 { Forcing matters a bit. } 17... Bxd5
{ Bf4 is coming and Black has no time to lose if they want to survive. } 18.
Nf5 Bxe4 19. Nxd6+ Bxd6 20. Bxe4 Rc8 21. Rd1 Be7 22. Bf4
{ The bishop pair guarantees us sufficient play. Themes such as a2-a4, the rook entering on d7 and our powerful bishops are enough compensation. }
