18... Bxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Nxe5 20. Qxe5 f6
{ Only move to avoid ending up with a rook on g7 whose only task is to defend h7. }
21. Qxf5 exf5 22. Bf4
{ Again, I consider this endgame somewhat uncomfortable for Black to play. We have both central pawns still on the board and we are exerting pressure on both flanks  (with Rh6 on the kingside and with a2-a4 on the queenside)  so it is easier for us to coordinate our pieces.  Black has a huge amount of possible moves here, however; their piece coordination is poor as they have to defend several weak spots. Additionally they do not have a clear way of improving their pawn structure. }
