18... Qd1+ 19. Kh2 Bd6+ 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. dxe5 Bxg2 22. exd6
{ This seems dangerous for us, but Black is the one that is completely lost here. We have total control of the dark squares, we want to continue with f3 and I do not see where Black's king can be safe enough. }
22... Qh1+ 23. Kg3 Qg1 24. f3 { And Black's bishop will fall. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35. Slav Defense - The Semi-Slav"]
[Black "Main Line with 7...a6 #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 a6 8. g4
{ This surprising move, which has recently become fashionable, will be our main idea against this variation.   The idea is to sacrifice the g pawn in the purest Shirov style, getting permanent pressure against the g7 pawn and Black's upcoming castled king. It is a rather unlikely scenario that our opponent will castle long with such a queenside pawn structure. }
8... c5 { Black's main reaction. } 9. g5 c4 10. Qe3
{ Pinning the e-pawn, so Black will not be able to take on d5 with a pawn. We will take Black's knight as soon as it gets there to fix the pawn structure. }
10... Nd5
{ If  10...Nfd7  we will simply play Bg2-O-O-Rd1 and, after that, we will aim for Ne4-Ne5 or for the d4-d5 push. The g5 pawn greatly hinders the development of the black pieces that are piling up on the queenside. }
11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Bg2 Bb4+
{ Black eliminates our castling rights, but keeps on delaying the development of the queenside pieces. }
13. Kf1 Bb7 { The only move that makes sense here. } 14. h4
{ Once again, Black has trouble developing the b8 knight and we take advantage of this to generate pressure on the kingside. }
14... Qf5
{ The main move, and the one recommended by Sethuraman. In my database there are already 2 games that have reached this position. Black's simple aim is to develop the b8-knight.   14...Ra7  Defending b7 would be very difficult for Black otherwise. Losing the right to castle long when the king will not be safe on the kingsisde is not a good thing. }
15. h5
{ Enabling quite some options such as Rh4 and Nh4 and threatening both ...h6 and ...g6 pushes. The a8-h1 diagonal is very tasty for our interests. }
15... Nd7 { Black can now develop the knight without being afraid of Nh4. } 16.
h6
{ Now Black has to face the unpleasant reality of the pressure on g7 and not being able to play a desirable move like ...g6. }
16... gxh6 17. Rxh6 { Threatening Bh3 to break Black's defense through e6. }
17... Qc2
{ 17...O-O-O  18.b3  Our kingside is very safe with the pawn wedge on g5 and our rook on h6. We want to play bxc4 and complicate Black's life. If  18...Nb6  we could play  19.Ne5!  followed by f4. The idea is to consolidate our advanced pawn on g5 and I think Black will struggle to deal with some natural moves such as Qf3  (invading the diagonal)  followed by Be3 and put pressure on the c-file. }
18. Kg1
{ Deviating from Sethuraman's analysis in his Semi-Slav Chessable course for Black. We simply want to exchange the light-squared bishops in order to challenge the long diagonal with an eventual Qf3. However, we first need to prevent ...Qd1 followed by mate. }
18... Qd1+ 19. Kh2 Bd6+ 20. Ne5 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 Nxe5 22. Rh1
{ Be careful and do not play  22.dxe5  , as after  22...Qd5+  we would lose a pawn. With this intermezzo we avoid this issue. }
22... Qc2
{ If  22...Ng4  please go to f3 with the queen, as going to e4 has a drawback :@@EndBracket@@. }
23. dxe5 Be7 24. Qf3
{ Dominating the long diagonal and giving some room for the c1-bishop to develop comfortably. From here on Black has to play incredibly accurate. }
24... Rd8
{ After  24...Rc8  we would go for the same line:  25.Be3  Rg8  26.Rac1  Qg6  and after  27.Kf1  Black would not be able to play 27...Rd5!. The reason is that we can enter on b7 and h6 and, besides, we can eventually go a2-a4 breaking the position wide open. All these are enough reasons to show that we are close to winning. }
25. Be3 { A move like b3 is very annoying for Black. } 25... Rg8 26. Rac1 Qg6
27. Kf1 Rd5 28. b3
{ Black will have to continue finding precise moves and we have a notable presence on both flanks. It seems very unlikely to me that anyone would make it this far without collapsing. }
*

