10. b3 c5 11. Ne5 { Exploiting Black's lack of development. } 11... cxd4
{ If  11...Nc6  12.Nc4!  followed by Nxc5. After playing f3 we will have a healthy bishop pair and a huge advantage thanks to the f3-e4 structure in the center, that overrides the f6-knight and the b7-bishop. }
12. Qb5+ Qxb5 13. Bxb5+ Ke7 14. Nc5 Bxe4 { The only move. } 15. Bb2 Bxg2 16.
Rg1 Bc6
{ The only move to stay in the game.   If  16...Bd5  17.Bxd4  Ne8  we play  18.Ncd3  to meet ...Nd6 with Bc5!. Black's position is incredibly passive and our next move  (Rc1)  is quite obvious. We could even win the game in a few moves! }
17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. Nxc6+ Kd6 19. Rc1 Kxc6 20. Nxe6+ Kd7 21. Nxf8+ Rhxf8 22. Bxd4
{ After finding such accurate moves, Black still has to play a very uncomfortable endgame due to their exposed pawn structure and White's active pieces. The b4-pawn is still quite exposed.   In the only game that reached this position, Anand played  22...Rac8  and, after  23.Rd1!  Andreikin could have put the "Tiger from Madras" in serious trouble. }
