{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 Bb7
{ This is a good alternative for Black. Now g2-g4 does not work so well, so it is preferable to gain space in the center. }
8. e4 b4 9. Na4 Qa5
{ If Black does not fight for the center, we will have a very healthy position.   9...Ba6  10.Qc2  Bxf1  11.Kxf1  Preventing us from castling may look nice, but now there is no way for Black to play the necessary pawn break ...c6-c5, so after g3-Rg2 we will have a clear advantage. }
10. b3 c5 11. Ne5 { Exploiting Black's lack of development. } 11... cxd4
{ If  11...Nc6  12.Nc4!  followed by Nxc5. After playing f3 we will have a healthy bishop pair and a huge advantage thanks to the f3-e4 structure in the center, that overrides the f6-knight and the b7-bishop. }
12. Qb5+ Qxb5 13. Bxb5+ Nfd7 { 13...Nbd7  loses an exchange after  14.Bg5! }
14. Bb2 f6 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Bxd4 Bxe4 17. O-O
{ Black has won a pawn, but they are way behind in development. Now Bc5 is a very serious threat. }
17... Bd6
{ After ...Rb8, we will get the pawn back with Bxd7 or Bc4 while keeping our initiative alive. }
18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Bxc5 Rb8 20. Ba4 Rb7
{ This rook maneuver is the only move that keeps everything defended. } 21.
Rac1
{ We are threatening things like Bxa7 or Bxb4.   After  21...Kd8  we simply go  22.Be3  and it seems to me that White has reasonable compensation and Black's play is somewhat complex. We will continue by doubling rooks on the c-file and then perhaps go for a plan like h4-f3-Kf2 to gain space on the kingside.   I see it quite plausible to pull the handbrake on many situations and drift into a drawish opposite-colored bishop endgame when we want to.   In the meantime, we can play what seems to me an unpleasant position for Black because they must play passively. The pawns on a7 and b4 are very vulnerable. }
*

