[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35. Slav Defense - The Semi-Slav"]
[Black "Main Line with 7...Bb7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 Bb7
{ This is a good alternative for Black. Now g2-g4 does not work so well, so it is preferable to gain space in the center. }
8. e4 b4 9. Na4 Qa5
{ If Black does not fight for the center, we will have a very healthy position.   9...Ba6  10.Qc2  Bxf1  11.Kxf1  Preventing us from castling may look nice, but now there is no way for Black to play the necessary pawn break ...c6-c5, so after g3-Rg2 we will have a clear advantage. }
10. b3 c5 11. Ne5 { Exploiting Black's lack of development. } 11... cxd4
{ If  11...Nc6  12.Nc4!  followed by Nxc5. After playing f3 we will have a healthy bishop pair and a huge advantage thanks to the f3-e4 structure in the center, that overrides the f6-knight and the b7-bishop. }
12. Qb5+ Qxb5 13. Bxb5+ Nfd7 { 13...Nbd7  loses an exchange after  14.Bg5! }
14. Bb2 Bd6 15. Bxd4 Bxe4 16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Bxc5
{ Again, we have a nice compensation for the sacrificed pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35. Slav Defense - The Semi-Slav"]
[Black "Main Line with 7...Bb7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
{ 3...Bf5  4.cxd5  cxd5  5.Qb3  taking the bishop for a walk so blithely is bad enough. Black will already be close to losing. We will continue with Nc3 and simple development suffocates Black. In case of trying  5...b6  they will be very vulnerable to  6.Nc3  e6  7.e4!  and Bb5+ ideas. }
4. Nc3 e6 5. Qd3
{ This will be my peculiar recommendation for the course. I have played multiple times both  5.Bg5  and  5.e3  , and, to a lesser extent,  5.g3  . These are highly analyzed moves that require extensive memorization.   With 5.Qd3 I hope that, at least, you get interesting positions and have the surprise factor in your favor.   5...Bd6  gives nothing special compared to ...Be7 and we will meet it the same way.  5...Bb4  would be an inferior version of the Nimzo-Indian, as Black has commited to the move ...c6. After  6.a3  Bxc3+  7.Qxc3  we will continue with Bf4-e3-Bd3. Black will miss presence on the dark squares while we enoy a comfortable development advantage, the bishop pair, and a nice pawn center. }
5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qd3 Bb7
{ This is a good alternative for Black. Now g2-g4 does not work so well, so it is preferable to gain space in the center. }
8. e4 b4 9. Na4 Qa5
{ If Black does not fight for the center, we will have a very healthy position.   9...Ba6  10.Qc2  Bxf1  11.Kxf1  Preventing us from castling may look nice, but now there is no way for Black to play the necessary pawn break ...c6-c5, so after g3-Rg2 we will have a clear advantage. }
10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bf4
{ Nd2-Nc4 and reinforce the center with f3, nullifying the b7-bishop, is the key of this variation. }
11... c5 12. Ne5 Bxe4
{ Taking the pawn now means bad news for Black.   12...Nxe5  13.dxe5  and the key strategic concept is that after  13...Nd7  we will play Nb2-Nc4 and all Black pieces would like to be able to use the c5-square or the c-file. The doubled pawns also prevent Black from enjoying the d5 square. Our queen can also do a lot of damage from g3 and I find it very difficult for Black to defend. }
13. Qb5 Qxb5 14. Bxb5 cxd4
{ Black cannot easily get rid of the pin and must play accurately. We were threatening to take on c5 and complicate things even more for Black. }
15. Rc1 { White's advantage in develoopment is huge. } 15... Rd8 16. f3 Bd5 17.
Bg5 Ke7 18. Nxd7 Rxd7 19. Bxd7 Kxd7 20. Nc5+
{ Misplacing Black's king. Our opponent's dream is to play ...Bd6 and Ke7, but after the text move the endgame is very uncomfortable for Black to play. We will aim for Bf4 to limit Black's e-pawn advance and, besides, we could look for penetrating into Black's camp with Rc7. }
