[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alonso Rosell, Àlvar vs. Dourerassou, Jonathan"]
[Result "*"]

{ When I started playing chess, I was passionate about solving puzzles and I often wondered about the names I saw written. Gligoric will sound familiar to some of you. He was a strong Yugoslav grandmaster that I have never seen a full game of, but I became an absolute fan seeing him 'winning' chess problems so many times. If he appeared often, he must be very good, right? Since then there has always been a dream as a child, will I ever deserve to belong to that list of players chosen to impress us in tactics books? In the game that I will show you below, after they confirmed that it was 'correct', I immediately remembered that childhood dream. So without further ado I hope you enjoy this dose of tactical dopamine. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 { The Catalan. What else? } 4... Be7 5. Bg2
O-O 6. Qc2 Nc6
{ An unusual move. In general Black prefers to have c6 or c5 in this type of structure. Black looks for Nb4 and c5 to get play. }
7. a3
{ It seemed the most logical answer to me, asking the meaning of the Knight in c6. Although with hindsight I verified that 7. 0-0 is technically somewhat better. }
7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 Qd5
{ A well-known plan for Black, pressing d4 quickly with Rd8 is the main idea. The main problem for my interests is that usually White has saved the move a3. }
9. Nbd2
{ We defend the  of c4 and seek to make it difficult for Black to advance e5. }
9... Rd8 10. e3 Qh5
{ 10...e5  It was perfectly possible even if it was 'scary' and in the 3 games that I have found in the database it has not been played. }
11. h3 { We hinder ...e5 by making g4 available. } 11... Bd6 12. Qe2
{ I can't really explain why I didn't play e4. } 12... Bd7
{ This gives me a second chance. } 13. e4 Bf8 { 13...e5  was met with 14.g4. }
14. O-O Qa5 15. Rd1 Qa4
{ This was annoying to meet. d4 is under attack and b3 is 'touched' too. } 16.
e5
{ Sad necessity as I'd rather leave the pawn structure as it was, but I´m still better anyway. }
16... Nd5 17. Ne4 Na5 { This gets too many pieces too far from Black's King. }
18. Nfg5 { Making way for my pieces. } 18... h6
{ I was hoping for this mistake. } 19. Nxf7 { Opening it up! } 19... Kxf7 20.
Bxh6 { 'Developing' the Bishop! } 20... Be8
{ 20...Kg8  21.Bg5  Re8  22.Nf6+  gxf6  23.exf6  Nxf6  24.Bxf6  Kf7  25.Be5  Ke7  26.d5+-  And we just need to open the position. }
21. Bg5 Kg8 { 21...Rd7 22.b4 Nc6 23.Qg4 } 22. Bxd8 Rxd8 23. b4
{ Cutting Black's Queen from the defense. } 23... Nb3
{ 23...Nc6  24.Ng5  Bf7  25.Qe4  g6  26.Qh4  Bg7  27.Rd3 } 24. Rab1 Nxd4 25.
Rxd4 Nf4 26. Nf6+ gxf6 27. Qg4+ Ng6 28. Rxd8 f5 29. Qg5 Kh7 30. b5
{ Again, cutting the Queen from joining the defense. } 30... Bxb5 31. Rxf8 Nxf8
32. Rb4 Qd1+ 33. Kh2 Ng6 34. Rxb5 *

