[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alonso Rosell, Alvar vs. Galaviz Medina, Sion Radamantys"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ 1...e5  The Englund gambit is a nice joke. Hopefully you did not get mated on c1 yet :  .   I want to propose a less direct way to win but more instructive general way to approach the position.  2.dxe5  Nc6  3.Nf3  Qe7  4.Nc3  I love this move. We negate all trickery related to taking the bishop from c1 and just focus on developing and threatening Nd5.  4...Nxe5  5.Bf4!  With 5. Nd5 we might force our opponent to play Nxf3+ and then Qd8, which is also good, but let's let black make mistakes.  5...Nxf3+  6.gxf3  c6  7.Qd2+-  We keep up with long castle, e4 and Rg1 and black is a zillion times behind on development, and we have everything in place to strike the death blow. }
2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. Ne5 c5 7. Be3 Nd5 8. O-O Nd7 9.
Nxc4 Nxe3 10. Nxe3 Be7 11. d5
{ Up to this point, we follow what was explained in the course, and we will see the punishment for Black to have tried to make the 'natural' moves. }
11... exd5 12. Nxd5 O-O 13. Nbc3
{ Finishing the development of the minor pieces. Now my idea is to move the queen away and put a rook on d1. Black would want to have the c5-pawn either on c7 or c6, but as it stands, the weaknesses on light squares are notorious. As we will see, it is more serious than it seems. }
13... Ne5
{ Black should have tried to soften our stronghold on d5. Nf6 followed by Rb8 would have given better chances for Black. }
14. Qa4
{ I enable the f4 or e4 squares for my queen and prepare the entry of a rook on d1. }
14... Bd7 15. Qf4
{ My main idea was that Ng6 was very attractive for my opponent and, apart from being somewhat out of the game, it could be a target of some h4-h5 or f4-f5 pushes. }
15... Ng6 16. Qe3
{ The natural Re8 loses a pawn in view of Nxe7+, so the discomfort continues. }
16... Bd6 17. Rfd1
{ Black has not made much progress and we continue accumulating pieces. Now Ne4 is a very serious threat. }
17... Re8 18. Ne4 Re6
{ 18...f5  The key is that this reaction did not work.  19.Qb3!  Black's king is exposed to a discovered attack.  19...fxe4  20.Ne7+  Kh8   20...Kf8  21.Qg8+  Kxe7  22.Qxg7+  Ke6  23.Bh3  This would have been a very  beautiful way of finishing off the game.  21.Nxg6+  hxg6  22.Rxd6+-  Black's structure falls apart. }
19. Qb3
{ I get out of the pin of the rook on e6 and we create new problems on b7. }
19... Bb5 20. Ndc3
{ Apart from Nxc5 and Nxb5, Black realizes that Bh3 is another new threat. Here we can clearly see my idea of leaving the knight on g6 and its uselessness. }
20... c4 21. Qc2 Qf8 22. Bh3 f5 23. Ng5
{ Nxd6 would have won material, but I prefer to attack the rook, and we use the threats of Qd2-Qd5+ and the weak pawn on f5. }
23... Re5 24. f4
{ We deflect the defender of f5 and Black will have to give up the pawn. }
24... Bc5+ 25. Kf1 Ree8 26. Bxf5 Ba7
{ Here my opponent lost on time, but after  27.Bxg6  , there will not be many moves left in the game anyway. }
