[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Santos Ruiz, Miguel vs. Barbot, Pierre"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 O-O 5. a3 Be7 6. e4 d6 7. Be2 Nfd7 8. b4 e5 9. d5
a5 10. Bb2 c5 11. b5
{ Up to this point, the game has followed the course. In this game, we will see how the young Spanish talent develops the attack. }
11... Nf6 12. Qc2
{ The first key point of this move order is that we keep the option of castling long open. }
12... g6
{ A very typical plan in these structures with pawns on c5-d6-e5 against c4-d5-e4. It reminds me of my game against Durarbayli, which I highly recommend you to have a look at. }
13. O-O-O Nh5 14. Ne1
{ Miguel clears the way for the advance of our pawns on the kingside. } 14...
Ng7 15. f4
{ Starting the attack directly. Black still has the entire queenside without taking part in the position, and we don't want Black to gain space on the kingside with f5-f4. }
15... Nd7
{ 15...exf4  16.Qc3  f6  17.Nd3+-  Recovering the pawn on f4. We will continue with g4-h4. The strength of the a1-h8 diagonal will be apparent in a few moves. }
16. f5
{ The player from Utrera suffocates his opponent with f5. As we will see in a few moves, he has foreseen a plan in case Black tries to close the kingside. }
16... h5 { Black pre-empts g4 and hopes to close the position with g4. } 17. g4
h4 18. Ndf3
{ Miguel accepts the bet that he will be able to open the kingside in case of g5. }
18... g5 19. Kb1 { A key move, freeing the c1 square for the bishop. } 19... f6
20. Ng2
{ The end of the plan that start with 15. f4!. White will sacrifice on h4 and will subsequently aim to open up Black's position with the h and g pawns. Black's lack of space prevents the transfer of reinforcements from the queenside to the kingside and also prevents the king from escaping safely to the queenside. }
20... Kf7 21. Ngxh4 gxh4 22. Nxh4 Rh8 23. Ng6 Rh3
{ Black tries to free some space for his pieces and hopes to play Nf8 and exchange pieces. }
24. Rd3
{ A very nice concept. Exchanging Black's best piece will only clear the way towards the enemy king. Black is still far from mobilizing the queenside. }
24... Rxd3 25. Qxd3 Nf8 26. Nxe7 Qxe7 27. h4
{ Black's knights are extremely clumsy and a plan like g5-g6-h5-h6 seems practically unstoppable. }
27... Nh7 28. Bc1 { Reinforcing g5. } 28... Bd7 29. g5
{ Black was one move away from being able to play Rh8 and have some coordination, but Miguel succeeds and sacrifices a pawn to finish exposing Black's position. }
29... fxg5 30. hxg5 Nxg5 31. Qg3 Nxf5
{ 31...Nxe4  Lead to a forced checkmate.  32.Qg6+  Kg8  33.Qh7+  Kf8  34.Qh8+  Kf7  35.Bh5+  Nxh5  36.Qxh5+  Kf8  37.Qh8+  Kf7  38.Rh7 }
32. Bh5+
{ With this in-between check, Miguel makes sure that the rook on a8 does not come into play. }
32... Kf8 33. exf5 Nf7 34. Qg6
{ The threat f6 decides the game. We have been able to appreciate how skillfully he has developed the attack to Black's kingside without his opponent being able to do anything. }
