[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alonso Rosell, Alvar vs. Bulmaga, Irina"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 Na6 8. h4 c5 9. d5
exd5 10. Nh2
{ So far, the game has followed the course. Remember that the pin on d5 and the threat of cxd5-e4-f4 is very intimidating. }
10... Ne4 { Black aims to gain presence in the center with f5. } 11. cxd5 f5
12. Nc3
{ We exchange Black's best piece, and then we go for e4. The knight on a6 and the bishop on b7 are somewhat out of the game. }
12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Bf6 14. Qc2
{ We want to play Bf4 and e4. The only drawback to watch out for is that, in case of the direct e4, Black has Nb4 and c4 ideas, taking advantage of the vulnerable rook on a1. }
14... c4
{ Black wants to give sense to his knight on a3 and gain the d3 square in case of e4. }
15. e4
{ Ba3 seemed more logical, first preventing the move Nc5. However, it was a problem for me to meet the move f4 when I wanted to play e4. }
15... Nc5 16. Ba3 { We take advantage of the pin on the c5-knight. } 16... Nd3
{ The only move that makes sense. Suddenly, the knight on d3 is very strong and the pawn on c3 will be Black's target. }
17. Bxf8 Qxf8 18. exf5
{ Black's best piece is his knight on d3. Trying to keep the extra exchange with a move like 18. Re2, could lead to problems after f4! }
18... Nxe1
{ 18...Qa3!?  seemed to be slightly better, taking advantage of the strong knight on d3.  19.Re2  Bxc3  20.Rd1+-  White is still in control and after Ng4 a strong attack with h5 can be mobilized. }
19. Rxe1
{ The bishop on b7 is still terrible and our knight on g2 will come into play shortly. }
19... Re8 20. Rc1
{ I prefer the more practical option. I pre-empt Qa3 and aim to activate the knight on h2.   20.Rxe8  Qxe8  21.Qa4  This move was somewhat stronger. We want to take the dangerous pawn on c4 and the b7 bishop will continue to suffer its confinement.  21...Bxc3  22.Qxc4  Qe1+  23.Nf1 }
20... Qc5 21. Qd2 h5 { Black prevents Ng4, so we take the alternative way. }
22. Nf1 b5 23. Ne3 Bd8
{ Seen that c3 is very well defended, Black wants to put pressure on the a7-g1 diagonal. }
24. Kh2
{ Intending Qd1 and attacking the weakness that Black has created. The problem of Bd8 is that leaves the kingside vulnerable and does not solve the life of the b7 bishop. }
24... Bb6 25. Qd1 Qa3 26. Qxh5
{ Black's king is too exposed. This piece sacrifice decides the game. } 26...
Rxe3 27. fxe3 Qxc1 28. Qe8+ Kh7 29. Qg6+ Kh8 30. f6 gxf6 31. Be4
{ Black will not be able to prevent Qh7+ and we have a good shelter on h3 for our king. Black resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Cheparinov, Ivan vs. Santos Latasa, Jaime"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6 6. Ne5 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nd5 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne4
c3 10. bxc3 Nxc3 11. Qc2
{ Up to this point, the moves were covered in the course. The main move is Qxd4, but the young Spanish talent opts to insert two moves first. }
11... Nxe4 12. Bxe4 f5
{ Black weakens his position to be able to defend h7 and take advantage of the threat against the bishop on e4 so he can take on d4. }
13. Bg2 Qxd4 14. Rb1
{ We answer a threat creating one ourselves. The bishop on b4 is hanging and we have reserved the option of developing the bishop on c1 to b2 or f4.   14.Bf4!?  This would transpose to what we analyzed in the course. It seems to me a very good example of the versatility of these positions with material deficit in exchange for development and the different ways to fight for the initiative. }
14... Qc3
{ Black wants to simplify material to help the queenside development. } 15. Qa4
{ We refuse the queen exchange offer and, at the same time, we threaten the bishop on b4 and the move Bb2, so Black's reply is now forced. }
15... Qxe5 16. Qxb4 Qb5
{ A very logical idea. Black sacrifices a pawn, to free the rook on a8 and put pressure on a2. If White's queen avoid the trade, the rook on b1 would be undefended. It seemed that Black would equalize by means of trading queens, but Jaime missed a brilliant move.   16...Nc6  seemed slightly better, but we still have some initiative after  17.Qc4  Qd4  18.Qb3=∞  Black still struggle a lot to develop his queenside and the a1-g7 diagonal is very vulnerable. }
17. Qc3
{ Cheparinov sacrifices the rook on b1 taking advantage of the mate on g7. Usually exchanging two rooks for a queen would be a success, but we are in a position where Black still has a lot of unfinished business regarding development. }
17... Qxb1 18. Bb2
{ The key. There are two threats: checkmate on g7 and the queen on b1. } 18...
Qxf1+ 19. Kxf1 { We want to keep the bishop on the long diagonal. } 19... Rf7
20. f4
{ Cheparinov has a nice control on the dark squares, and now he will harass the rook on f7 with moves like Bf3-Bh5. Maybe the direct 20. Bf3 was objectively stronger, but it is not clear how to justify it. }
20... a5 { Jaime prioritize the activation of his a8-rook. } 21. Bf3 Ra6
{ 21 ...Nc6 first was necessary due to a tactical motif that we will see later. }
22. Bh5 Rd7 23. Be8
{ We are still taking advantage of the fact that the rook on d7 should remain on the 7th rank to defend c7 and g7. }
23... Re7 24. Bb5
{ This bishop maneuver is one of the most surprising ones I have seen. Thanks to the fact that the a6-rook is under attack, Black cannot stop Ba3 and Be8 back, punishing the rook on f7 for not being able to leave the 7th rank. }
24... Rb6 25. Ba3 Rxb5
{ Jaime gives up and gives an exchange back. Now Black's position is very precarious because of the weak dark squares. If the f5 pawn were on f6 it would radically change the position. }
26. Bxe7 Nc6 27. Bd8
{ A finish worthy of a great game. The c7 pawn is undefended and the d8 bishop is taboo due to Qxc7, threatening both of the black pieces. }
27... Bd7 28. Bxc7 Rd5
{ Black wants to create a 'fortress' defending both the pawn on g7 and the one on b7, the weakest points of his construction, with the rook. We cannot relax yet. }
29. Bb6 Kf7 30. Kf2 Kf8 31. g4
{ h3 could be met by h5, trading one more pawn. Cheparinov takes advantage of the fact that Black cannot take as White would expell the rook from the d-file after e4, so we would enter Black's position. Remember that one of the conditions to defend adequately was to place a rook on the 7th. }
31... Be8 32. h3
{ Cheparinov consolidates his progress. Now he wants to give a purpose to the bishop on b6. }
32... Bf7 33. Kg3 Kg8 34. Be3
{ Having gained space on the kingside, we look to place the bishop on the long diagonal and press g7. Consulting the metal oracle, a4 and Ba3 was much stronger, since we have two threats, Qc5 looking for Qf8 and Bb2 looking for Qxg7. As always, consulting the computer gives us an answer that is logical after the fact, but very difficult to assess. }
34... h5 35. gxf5
{ Rxf5 with the idea of Rf6-e5! @@StartBracket@@fxe5@@EndBracket@@-Re6, getting a very good block, seemed like a good practical option. }
35... exf5 36. Bc1 Rd7 37. a3 Kh7 38. Bb2 Bg6
{ Black has reached the type of strength we talked about before. Now it will be necessary to tighten the position until generating a break with the important pawn on e4 that destabilizes the position. }
39. Kh4 Re7 40. e3 Kh6 41. Qc5 Rf7 42. Qd6 Re7
{ Black wants to prevent the entry with Kg5. } 43. Qc5 Rf7 44. Qd5
{ Now black is forced to move the rook to f8, he can't let us play Qg8. It's sad to see how the c6-knight has zero relevance, and its only function is to defend the a5-pawn. }
44... Rf8 45. Qd7 Rf7 46. Qc8
{ With this we have already gained access to the eighth rank and Black will not be able to avoid both Qh8+ and the g5 entry. }
46... Bh7 47. Qe8 Bg6 48. e4 { The key moment. } 48... Kh7
{ 48...fxe4  49.f5+-  and Black is defenseless against Qh8+ and Bc1++, so he will have to sacrifice material. }
49. e5 Rc7 50. Qf8 Bf7 51. Kg5 Re7 52. a4
{ With this move, we again reach a position where Black hardly has any moves. The king on g5 neutralizes much of Black's defense. }
52... Rd7 53. Qc8 Be6 54. Qe8 { The h5-pawn falls and then the game. } 54...
Re7 55. Qxh5+ Kg8 56. Ba3 Rd7
{ Jaime left Qe8+ losing the a6-bishop and preferred to end his agony. Great mix between technique, very good calculation and understanding of Cheparinov's activity. }
