[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Cheparinov, Ivan vs. Bacrot, Etienne"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ An advantage of the move order  1...d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nf3  is that we can transpose to the Catalan unless the opponent plays the typical queen pawn variations 3...c5, 3....dxc4, 3....c6 3.....a6.  After I finished the course, I began to choose 3. Nf3 against certain opponents. }
2. c4
{ The move order  2.Nf3  e6  3.g3  d5  4.Bg2  allows us to avoid certain Catalan variations with 4. ... dxc4 and also the annoying 4. ... Bb4+. However, we allow 3 ... b5 and 4 ... b5, that lead to very different positions, but very interesting and useful to know, as these setups can be played with both colors.   Another problem of this move order is that Black is not forced to play 2. ... e6 and, usually plays 2. ... d5 immediately, keeping the option of developing the bishop on c8 outside the pawn chain or playing a quick c5 before e6.   I would recommend this move order if you play against someone with a very fixed repertoire and who always wants to vary within the Catalan. This way, you can limit the scope of the preparation a lot. }
2... e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 Na6 8. h4 d5 9. cxd5
exd5 10. Nc3
{ This game follows the course until this point. This game is a practical example of the most talked-about pawn structure in the course, played between two strong Grandmasters. Again, Cheparinov shows us how to play the Catalan. }
10... c5 11. Bf4 Nc7 12. e3 Ne6 13. Rc1
{ As we have mentioned before, it does not bother White that Black takes on f4. Another option could have been 13. Be5, to increase the pressure on d5. }
13... Nxf4 14. exf4
{ We gain the e-file for our rook and the e5-square is very well protected and ready for our knight on f3. The most important detail is the efficient blockade and the versatility that it provides. }
14... Re8
{ cxd5 followed by Bc5 was slightly better for Black. Now, White knight can access to e5. }
15. Ne5
{ Rc2 intending Rce2 or Rd2 is an infrequent, but very classy plan to continue putting pressure on Black's position. }
15... cxd4 16. Qxd4 Bc5
{ The strong French GM tries to activate somehow, but the pawn on d5 cannot be moved as the bishop on b7 is hanging. }
17. Qd3 Rc8 18. a3 { We prevent Bb4 first, and we also avoid trading pieces. }
18... a5 19. Rcd1 Bf8
{ Bacrot is ready to sacrifice the pawn on d5 and look for counterplay after the trades with Rc2. }
20. g4
{ We have to stop for a moment to admire White's position. Every piece and pawn is on the ideal square, and only the pawn on g3 had no role! By deflecting the knight from f6, we can capture on d5 without having to exchange queens. }
20... Ne4 21. Nxd5
{ The weakness on f7 and the opposite-colored bishops puts Black in serious trouble. }
21... Bxd5 22. Qxd5 Qxd5 23. Rxd5 Nf6 24. Rdd1
{ g5 y Bd5 is unstoppable. We can even play Bf3 first to prevent the jump to h5. }
24... Rc2 25. g5
{ Bacrot resigned due to the threat of Bd5 and maybe f5 next, enabling g6!. A very instructive game about this pawn structure. It is surprising to see strong GM's today not playing as precise as it is required. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Baenziger, Fabian vs. Ammar, Sedrani"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. d4 Nf6 4. g3 Be7
{ 4...c5  A very dangerous variation if we do not know much, but the idea is that we do not develop the knight to c3 until the end. The variation is very easy to remember.   4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  Although I mention Nc3 and Nbd2 as alternatives, I consider the move Bd2 as the main line. This is one of the best variations for Black in my opinion, so it would also be useful for you to consider the more dynamic alternatives I give. It is very important that after  5...a5  6.Bg2  keep in mind the option of  6...dxc4  , which transposes to chapter 15.   4...dxc4  In the list of variations that start with this move, I recommend being especially aware of 5...a6 and 5...c6. Apart from being very popular, they require us to be more mindful of the issues that arise after 6.Ne5 as they are both quite critical.   By having many shared ideas, you will also find that it is more pleasant to learn them at the same time.   5...c5 and 5...Nc6 are more solid, and you have more practical alternatives if you find yourself playing them without being fully prepared.   Finally, 5...Bb4+ is one of the most common variations in fairly high average ratings, as it has many nuances in the order that justify it, so I would analyze it last. The rest of the sub-variations are relatively simple to meet and will not take you long to master them. What I like most about these variations is that they encourage imbalances from the start and generate a lot of winning options. }
5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O Nbd7 7. Qc2 c6 8. Rd1 b6 9. b3 Ba6 10. Nbd2 Rc8 11. e4 c5 12.
exd5 exd5 13. Nf1 cxd4
{ 13...dxc4  14.d5  this position is well known in correspondence and in human-to-human games. We get the c4-pawn back. In case of cxb3, after axb3, Black will be forced to play Bxf1. Our plan then could be Ra4-Bd3 and the attack on the black castling is outlined while we enjoy the light squares and the passed pawn on d5. }
14. Nxd4 b5 15. Ne3 bxc4 16. Ndf5
{ The game follows the course up to this point. This game seems to me to be a great example of the danger that these positions entail and how Black can receive an exemplary punishment. }
16... cxb3
{ This seems a reasonable option. After Qxb3 we could follow with Bc5 and Black would continue in the game. }
17. Qb2
{ The queen coordinates perfectly with the knight on f5 and "pins" the knight on f6. Our next move is Nxd5, increasing the pressure via the d-file. }
17... Re8 { bxa2 could be met with Nxd5 followed by Bg5. } 18. axb3
{ Another of the well-known issues and problems of playing Ba6 in the Catalan without having played a5 before. Black is practically lost. Nxd5 still allowed Bc5! And Black was still in the game. }
18... Bb7 19. Rxa7 Bc6 20. Bxd5 Bxd5
{ Bf8 would continue the fight for a little bit. } 21. Nxd5 Bf8 22. Bg5
{ Above all, I have chosen this game because of the final position. It represents very well what the Catalan is, constantly looking for the best square for our pieces. Black is helpless against Nxf6+, losing material. }
